They kept the same four shapes — skull, ribs, bone and hand/foot — and loaded lots of the dark red Flamin' Hot onto it.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Pretty mild. Can't really smell this particular heat.

snack_name: Cheetos Bag of Bones White Cheddar
snack_taste_test: Taste test: On the heels of Cheetos Mix-Ups, which combined four different shapes (and flavors) of Cheetos in one bag, Chester Cheetah is back with four new shapes, this time shaped like skeletal parts as part of a Halloween theme. The shapes were a skull, rib cage, bone (apparently a generic one) and hand/foot (again, multipurpose/generic). The front of the bag showed how you could build (most of) a body using just these four pieces. Unlike the Mix-Ups, which were each a different flavor, all four of these had the same light yellow color of puffs, covered with white cheddar powder. The white-on-yellow look was kind of ghostly!
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice white cheddar smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This Japanese version of Cheetos had the usual Cheetos Crunchy texture and shape, but unlike typical Cheetos, there was no cheese (which seems to be a bit of a paradox for something named Cheetos).
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells sort of like pancakes. Sweet.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: We've reviewed a number of varieties of Bugles, plus even more kinds of Cheetos, but this was the first time that we've seen a bag that was branded with both of them.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mild shrimp smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: The signature slogan of Cheetos is "Dangerously Cheesy," so when I saw that Frito-Lay was selling a companion line of crackers with Chester Cheetah's picture on the package, I had high hopes.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: These smell just like Cheetos. Good!

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These roughly spherical snacks were a dull orange in color, not nearly as bright of an orange as some Cheetos varieties we've tried. They weren't quite ball-shaped, as they were more like stubby tubes with rounded ends.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong smoky cheese smell, but not really like bacon.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Cheetos from Korea had a six-spoked wheel shape, far different from any of the typical Cheetos shapes, with a beige color.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Kind of remotely like a cheeseburger. Mostly like spicy beef, or steak sauce.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These taste pretty much the same as regular Cheetos.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: A mild cheesy smell

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These Cheetos-shaped snacks had a light orange color with some darker orange spots, and they had a very tasty hot and sweet pepper flavor that was quite a bit different than any other snacks we've tried.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very tangy spicy smell, reminded me of Thai food.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Cheetos had the same irregular shapes as the cheese-loaded Crunchy Cheetos, but with a light yellow color, plus a very, very sparse application of some small, dark seasoning bits (just a few bits per piece, at most).
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Sweet smell, indeed a whole lot like corn soup.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This new snack from Chester Cheetah's kitchen appeared to be Frito-Lay's attempt to compete against the popular Cheez-Its line of snack crackers. Each piece was shaped like Chester's paw print, with one large hole for the paw and four smaller holes for his fingertips. The whole exterior was coated with a bright orange cheese seasoning.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Pretty good cheese smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: What does a Cheeto taste like? If you don't know, go out and buy some. It's the taste against which all other crunchy cheese flavored snacks are compared. Always look for the big Cheeto, (a.k.a. the Cheeto de Milo), the one with the extra big head that makes it extra crunchy. It seem like the percentage of really huge Cheetos in the can was lower than you would typically find in a bag. But you do get a more even distribution of sizes throughout the package than you would with a bag, where the little ones all settle to the bottom.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: No particular smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This small bag of Cheetos came in a bucket multi-pack as part of a Halloween promotion. It's been many years since we wrote our review of Crunchy Cheetos, so we decided to review these to confirm those impressions, while checking out what sounded to be an exciting package.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice mix of cheese and corn.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Cheetos had the same range of irregular shapes as the original crunchy curls, with a less-fluorescent light orange color and lots of powder on the surfaces.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Kund of a weird cheese smell. Not good.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This new variety of Cheetos looked a lot like the Cheetos Crunchy, with the addition of some tiny green spots.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Wow, a really nice cheddar jalapeño smell. Great. Made my mouth water.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These cheese curls had the same general shapes as the standard Crunchy Cheetos, but the color was a bit darker because of some dark spots of flavor powder.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Wow, very nice! Sort of a mix of honey barbecue and the standard Cheetos smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This latest variety of Cheetos was an excellent addition to the Cheetos lineup.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice, it does smell like enchilada sauce.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These had the same general shape as the crunchy version of Cheetos, but they looked quite different, as they were reddish with dark red seasoning visible in all of the crevices, for a very dark overall color.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Some lime smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These were a lot like regular Cheetos Crunchy but with lots more bright orange "cheese" powder on them, as if they've doubled the amount of cheese that they put on the Cheeto.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: I couldn't tell whether the smell was doubly cheesy, but it smelled like a normal bag of Cheetos, that "corn chip" type smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This ambitious flavor of Cheetos (released along with an identically named Doritos flavor) looked mostly the same as the regular Cheetos, though maybe the orange was a little less bright-orange and more red.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mostly just like regular Cheetos. Maybe some extra spices, but not heat.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are good hot crunchy snacks, with the same shapes as the regular Crunchy Cheetos but a more intense look.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: A nice but not overpowering hot and spicy cheesy smell.

snack_name: Cheetos Crunchy Flamin' Hot Chipotle Ranch
snack_taste_test: Taste test: With 87 varieties of Cheetos reviewed so far, this one stood out for being a rare one that tried to alter the basic Flamin' Hot flavor, and also for having such a long flavor name.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Not particularly hot, but I could notice a hint of ranch among the cheese and peppers.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These were a bit strange.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Just slightly limey smell, not strong.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Mozzarella cheese is not among the types of cheeses that I expect to go well on a snack.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Not a great smell, but after a few whiffs it smelled like a plate of spaghetti.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This new Cheetos form factor was similar to the original (puffed) twisted, with a spiral or helix shape, but a bit thinner.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good typical cheese puffs smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of crunchy Cheetos had some additional dark seasoning beyond the usual Cheetos color, giving them a somewhat darker appearance.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong smell, really some kick to it.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This is a fascinating new creation.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good ranch smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These cheese curls had the same sorts of irregular shapes as the original fluorescent orange Cheetos Crunch, but with a pale yellow overall color.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice toasted corn smell, just slghtly cheesy.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These Cheetos from Taiwan looked a lot like the standard American "Dangerously Cheesy" Crunchy Cheetos, with irregular shapes, a wide range of sizes and an uneven coating of bright orange powder on the otherwise yellow surfaces. The amount of orange was a little less than I'm used to, but still, it was a bright orange look overall.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice mild cheddar cheese smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Cheetos adopted the shape of the Cheetos Sweetos, which were supposed to look like Easter eggs with two stripes across the middle, but instead of the Sweetos Cinnamon or  Caramel flavors, they stuck to what Cheetos are known best for, along with the usual Cheetos fluorescent orange color.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice strong cheddar smell.

snack_name: Cheetos Flamin' Hot Brand Flavor Filling on Cheese Flavored Crackers
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This package contained six square cracker sandwiches, orange crackers with a red filling.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very strong Cheez Whiz sort of smell, but not really any heat.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This new version of Cheetos piled on some major hype for its heat level, claiming to be not just the hottest type of Cheetos ever, but the hottest of any Frito-Lay product in the United States. The puffs had a very bright, intense red seasoning on their surfaces, and they were shaped like some sort of short, stubby chili peppers — though neither the bag's marketing copy nor the Ingredients identified which particular pepper(s) powered the heat.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Cheesy smell, but not hot at all, didn't make my mouth water.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Flamin' Hot Cheetos from China had similar shapes to the American Flamin' Hot Crunchy Cheetos but a much lighter color, with a light orange overall look punctuated by some sparse darker seasoning bits.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Just mildly tangy.

snack_name: Cheetos Flavor Shots Cheddar Jalapeño Asteroids
snack_taste_test: Taste test: After considerable hype surrounding the  Flamin' Hot Asteroids Flavor Shots (and then months of searching just to find a bag to review), this jalapeño variation managed to fly under the radar. I hadn't heard a peep about it when I spotted this bag in the snack aisle.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Pretty intense spicy cheese smell.

snack_name: Cheetos Flavor Shots Flamin' Hot Asteroids
snack_taste_test: Taste test: Years ago, Frito-Lay had a whole line of Go Snacks in cans, designed to fit in your car's cup holder and then be poured directly into your mouth, including a Flamin' Hot Cheetos version. They stopped selling all of them. Now the Cheetos ones are back, but in a narrow, vertical bag instead of a can.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Not much at all. Definitely nothing hot.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These cassava-based chips from China contained actual shrimp, though we couldn't see it, with the pieces formed into off-white (not really yellowish as pictured), styrofoam-looking pieces that were generally flat or slightly scoop-shaped. Despite their Cheetos name, they didn't seem to contain any cheese among the long list of Ingredients, but the dancing Chester Cheetah pictured on the bag didn't seem to mind. (We base this on pointing Google Translate at the Chinese, as the import label appeared to be quite wrong, listing Potatoes first on a very short Ingredients list.)
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mild, sweet smell with some spices, but not fishy.

snack_name: Cheetos Fresh Shrimp Thai Hot & Spicy
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These shrimp chips from Chester Cheetah looked much like the original flavor, with flat, slightly scooped shapes that slightly resembled melba toast, they but had a bit of orange seasoning in this case.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Pretty intense on the first whiff

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These cheese curls looked generally like the American Crunchy Cheetos that I know and love, but the brightly colored curls were more yellow and less orange.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very mild cheese smell.

snack_name: Cheetos Futebolas Com Sabor A Queijo
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These Cheetos are shaped like soccer balls, complete with some soccer-ball like shapes drawn on them.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Sort of a bacony cheese smell, nice.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These snacks had the same basic shape as the standard Crunchy Cheetos.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very tangy seasoned shrimp small.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This Cheetos flavor from Taiwan had a particularly odd version of the Chester Cheetah mascot on the front of the bag, as Chester had a very humanlike appearance and was wearing sneakers and pants.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very mld cheese smell, but sweet too.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These Cheetos looked a lot like the regular Crunchy Cheetos in terms of shapes, but they had a light yellow-orange color rather than then fluorescent that Cheetos is best known for. The front of the bag showed some honey being drizzled onto a big wedge of cheese, so the expectation was some combination of honey and cheese.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice sweet smell, kind of like corn and honey.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These cheese balls from Colombia had shapes that were a bit lumpy on the outside but still mostly resembled spheres, and they were fairly large at just under an inch in diameter. They had a bright orange color typical of Cheetos, much brighter than the balls depicted on the bag.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice strong cheddar smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This Mexican version of Cheetos was supposed to be shaped like vampire fangs, but they didn't off-hand look like fangs because they were very dark red in color, which is quite different from the white (or something close) fangs that you tend to see on any vampire who sees his dentist twice a year. The shape was reasonably fang-like, and the size was about an inch long, which was reasonable to use as fangs to hold up to your mouth. Some of our tasters saw the shape and instead though that they looked like some body part other than fangs (which we won't mention). We crunched in to find that the puffs were crisp and soft, with lots of very hot and spicy seasoning.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very zesty.

snack_name: Cheetos Horneados Colmillos Queso y Chile
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This Mexican version of Cheetos was shaped like Chester Cheetah's four-finger paw (but oddly, with a hold in the middle of the palm) and had a very dark orange-brown color.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good spicy chili pepper and lime smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These puffed Cheetos were thinner than the typical puffs we've come to expect from Cheetos or Jax, and they were also shaped differently, as they were nearly straight sticks (with some minor wiggles) rather than being quite curved.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice mild cheese smell.

snack_name: Cheetos Kadurim Onion Flavored Corn Snack
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This variety of Cheetos had a spherical shape and the same sweet onion taste that we've come to expect from Funyuns.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very sweet onion smell.

snack_name: Cheetos Kafa Ketchup Flavored Corn Snack
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These cheese puff-like creations were shaped like Chester Cheetah's paw, with four fingers (or toes?) and a hole in the middle of the paw.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very tomatoey ketchup smell. Nice.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These were one of the more controversial snacks we've tried in a while.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Kind of odd, but maybe a little like soy sauce.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Cheetos brought a whole new shape to the brand, as the pieces were shaped like 5-pointed throwing stars, with a light orange color and some bits of darker red seasoning.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Kind of strange, but there was also a hint of hot peppers.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Cheetos had the standard Crunchy Cheetos shape but a light orange color (not the typical Cheetos fluorescent orange) with darker seasoning in the crevices.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very hard to place, but kind of a mildly tangy peppers smell.

snack_name: Cheetos Mighty Zingers Crazy Cheddar & Wicked Picante
snack_taste_test: Taste test: After viewing this bag and even reading the marketing copy on the bag, I was unsure whether this was just a change in the colors of the snacks from the Sharp Cheddar & Salsa Picante version of Mighty Zingers, or a spicier version. (Frito-Lay gave us a similar mystery when they sold Ragin' Cajun & Tangy Ranch Zingers in dragon and non-dragon versions.) This time, the colors were green and orange instead of light orange and dark red, with the same small nugget shapes as the original.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice toasted corn and cheese smell, but no heat.

snack_name: Cheetos Mighty Zingers Ragin' Cajun & Tangy Ranch
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Zingers combined a some orange-colored hot cajun pieces with pale yellow ranch ones. This gives the snacker the option of going for the hot or cool flavor, or a combination, on any given mouthful.  As with the Sharp Cheddar & Salsa Picante flavor, the pieces were small, randomly shaped nuggets with a very nice crunch.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mostly ranch, not cajun, but really quite good.

snack_name: Cheetos Mighty Zingers Ragin' Cajun & Tangy Ranch Dragon Edition
snack_taste_test: Taste test: Having already reviewed two kinds of Cheetos Mighty Zingers, I found this bag confusing, as it claimed the same Ragin' Cajun & Tangy Ranch flavor that we had already  tried, but with the added label of "Dragon Edition." Did this mean it was hotter (the Ragin' Cajun ones were already quite hot) or was it just a different bag featuring a fire-breathing Chester Cheetah on front? I had to buy it and eat some  to find out.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Same as the non-Dragon version: More ranch than cajun.

snack_name: Cheetos Mighty Zingers Sharp Cheddar & Salsa Picante
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This bag contained miniaturized versions of Cheetos, more of a nugget shape than the Crunchy Cheetos irregular sticks, with a mix of light orange pieces and dark red ones. Both colors were impressively bright. The Zingers came in all sorts of shapes and sizes, but on average they were about half an inch in their longest dimension. The orange Sharp Cheddar pieces seemed to outnumber the red Salsa Picante ones.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice. Mostly toasted corn rather than the spices, but I really liked it.

snack_name: Cheetos Mini Crunch Onion Flavored Wheat Snack
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These snacks were extruded into four different shapes: a soccer player, soccer ball, a trophy and a bicyclist.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very mild onion smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This spicy variation of the Xtra Cheezy Mix followed the same path of having four different shapes in the bag (the same four shapes) and four different flavors, with three of the four flavors being spicy ones in this case. It also provided a wider range of colors than the Cheezy version, offering a rare green Cheeto. As far as colors go, this was a very attractive mix, with a nice contrast between the four kinds: light orange, round and grid-filled Chipotle Cheddar pieces; bright orange Cheddar puffs; green Jalapeno Cheddar mini puffs; and dark red Salsa Picante crunchy curls.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Kind of zesty, definitely some good hints of hot peppers.

snack_name: Cheetos Mix-Ups Flamin' Hot & Cheezy Mix
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This latest addition the the Cheetos Mix-Ups line had the same four shapes of Cheetos as the Cheezy Salsa and Xtra Cheezy versions, with a different lineup of flavors. Two of the four were standard-issue Cheetos that can be purchased separately — Flamin' Hot Curls and Cheddar Puffs — while the other two were newly created flavor/shape combinations just for this mix: Double Cheddar Mini Puffs and Jalapeño Cheddar Grids.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good cheddar smell, but not much in the way of heat.

snack_name: Cheetos Mix-Ups PX41 Limited Edition Cheezy Mix
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This special version of Cheetos boasted the novelty of turning your tongue purple by eating cheese puffs. The bag contained the same four kinds of Cheetos as the Xtra Cheezy Mix-Ups: standard crunchy ones and puffy ones (known as "Double Cheddar Puffs"), plus stubby parmesan puffs and nacho cheese grids. The colors were also the same, at least out of the bag, with no purple in evidence. The PX41 name first brought to mind the long-gone limited-edition X-13D Doritos, but it turned out that PX41 is a reference to a character in Despicable Me, not just some intentionally obscure-sounding code.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong cheese smell. Borderline too strong.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This new creation from Cheetos broke the longstanding practice of including just one shape of Cheeto per bag, as they included an unprecedented four different shapes of Cheetos, each with a different flavor.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very strong cheese smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These didn't seem to taste any different than the regular X's & O's Cheetos. The big deal about them was that any given Cheeto in this bag was supposed to change your tongue to either green or blue. They did just that, but the blue or green wasn't nearly as bright as it showed in the example with Chester Cheetah's tongue on the bag.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells the same as the Cheetos that don't change colors when you eat them.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are shaped differently from the regular Cheetos Puffs, as the puffs are both narrower and less curvy, and they're a pale yellow in color.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice cheddar aroma, more like real cheese than the usual fluorescent orange cheese puffs.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: We've seen paw-shaped Cheetos several times before, including in a Mexican version, an Israeli version and in the defunct Cracker Trax varieties, but this one marked the first time that Paws were found in the flagship American Cheetos bag.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Not really all that cheesy.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: The name confusion on Frito-Lay products continues with this one, as we've seen something called Cheetos Popcorn before, but it was not the same thing as this — it was freshly popped cheddar popcorn mixed with Crunchy Cheetos, sold at the ballpark. We've also seen Chester Cheetah's face on bags of popcorn before, but it was labeled as Chester's Popcorn, with no mention of Cheetos anywhere on the bag. This seemed to be the practice (until now) for things that weren't Cheetos but had enough cheese to satisfy the notorious cheesaholic Chester.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong cheddar popcorn smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This popcorn, much like the cheddar flavor of Cheetos Popcorn, seemed to signal a transition of non-cheese puff cheese products from the Chester's brand to the Cheetos brand, which also happens to have Chester Cheetah as its mascot.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice cheese smell, but couldn't really smell the heat.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are your standard thick cheese puffs.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good cheese smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These puffs were noticeably redder in color than the standard Cheetos.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Definitely different from regular Cheetos. You can smell Italian spices and some tomato, nice.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Cheetos Puffs had the usual shape but a much different color, as the seasoning was a deep, bright shade of dark red.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Not really cheesy, but not hot either. sneers sort of like tomato sauce.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This new flavor of Cheetos had the same thick, puffy shape as the regular Cheetos puffs but looked different, as the orange was slightly darker and didn't have the bright glow that we've come to expect from Cheetos.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice,

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These cheese puffs were as thick as the normal Cheetos Puffs and had sort of a very pale yellow (though not quite white) color. It looked like the cheese powder was closer to being white than the slightly-yellower underlying puffs.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Pretty good cheese smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: All thumbs are up on these delicious snacks.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: These smell like Smartfood popcorn.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Crunchy Cheetos had a much less bright color of orange, and there were also some bits of green scattered over the surfaces of the curls. The illustration on the bag depicted Chester Cheetah tossing a tomato, a lime and a jalapeno into a bowl of queso sauce, so I was expecting some strong flavor and heat.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice slightly spicy cheese smell. Reminds me of a Chinese restaurant for some reason.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: After selling Giant Cheetos Snowballs in some previous years, which were notable more for their size than shape, Chester Cheetah decided to try some special shapes for this year's winter edition. There were four different shapes in the bag, but only one of them had the six-way symmetry that makes up an actual snowflake. The surfaces had a light yellow color, with a fairly even, light coating of off-white cheese powder. They looked wintery.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice strong white cheddar smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This new shape from Cheetos consisted of small, five-pointed stars with a bright yellow base and lots of smallish green and orange seasoning bits on the surfaces.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong creamy ranch smell, like ranch dressing.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: When the original cinnamon flavor of Sweetos was announced, it was big news, earning headlines as the first-ever sweet version of Cheetos. They were quite good, but they didn't exactly change the world as much as some expected. As a Chief Snacks Officer, I have a pretty good memory for snacks, but when I saw this new flavor on the snack shelf of my 5th-favorite supermarket, I was only about 70% sure it was a new flavor ... until I noticed the bag of cinnamon ones right next to it.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice buttery caramel smell. Sweet!

snack_taste_test: Taste test: We've eaten many different varieties of Cheetos over the years, and although the 78 kinds that we reviewed before this one varied quite a bit in size, texture, color, shape and flavor, the one thing that they all had in common as members of the Cheetos brand was cheese. This bag of Sweetos marked the major departure of being officially branded Cheetos that didn't have any cheese.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like cinnamon toast. Nice.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This Mexican version of Crunchy Cheetos looked mostly like the American version, except in color, as the curls were overall medium-orange in color (not quite as bright as we've come to expect) with some very small, much darker spots on them.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good cheese smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are giant cheese puffs (or curls) that are twisted around like a spring.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like a bag of Cheetos.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These spiral-shaped Cheetos had a nice texture, slightly more dense than Cheetos Puffs, but without the crunch you get from Cheetos Crunchy.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice mild cheese smell.

snack_name: Cheetos Twisted Star Wars Episode III
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These spiral-shaped cheese puffs were fairly dense but crisp and a had a good cheese taste with a mild crunch.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Not much.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: The latest shape of the popular Cheetos snacks looks kind of like a throwing star.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mildly cheesy smell

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Cheetos featured tater tot-like shapes, except a bit smaller. They had a pale yellow color on the outside, thanks to the evenly applied, off-white cheese powder on an already pale yellow corn puff.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very strong white cheddar smell. Nice.

snack_name: Cheetos X e O Sabor A Cheeseburger
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These have sort of a slight pickle taste to them, and they also taste cheesy, but they don't really taste like a cheeseburger.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Sort of a mild pickle-like smell, not bad.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: The Xs are better than the Os.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Cheese.

snack_name: Cheetos X&O Pizza Flavored Corn Snack
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These were shaped like X's and O's, similar to other Cheetos varieties, but these had a very mild pizza flavor.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like pizza sauce.

snack_name: Cheetos Xtra Flamin' Hot Cheese and Chili
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Cheetos had lots of intense red-orange seasoning powder on the irregularly shaped corn curls, and the bag had an unusually high proportion of extra-thick pieces (something that we refer to as the "Cheeto de Milo" around the Taquitos.net offices).
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Some sharp chili pepper spices.

snack_name: Cheetos Xxtra Flamin' Hot Asteroids Go Snacks
snack_taste_test: Taste test: We've reviewed more than 80 kinds of Cheetos, but for this one, Chester Cheetah went to a new level of danger, adding something "Xxtra" to the previous generation of Flamin' Hot Asteroids. (There's also a corresponding crunchy curl with the same Xxtra Hot flavor.)
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Not much, and definitely no heat in the smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These crunchy cheese curls should not be confused with the regular Cheetos Flamin' Hot, as they lived up to their name by being a scarier color (deep red, rather than orange-red) and impressively hotter. The curls were tasty and pretty hot upon biting in, and they kept getting hotter as I ate more, which I kept doing in between sips of lemonade. The lemonade was able to temper the heat only temporarily, so the increasingly hot aftertaste quickly came back in full force.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Kind of tangy but not actually hot.

snack_name: Doritos Dinamita Chile Limón/Cheetos Flamin' Hot
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This was a groundbreaking snack, as it was the first attempt we've seen to package Cheetos and Doritos together exclusively in the same bag. (They've been together before, along with other snacks, in bags of Munchies.)
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Not much.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Each piece in this bag of Cheetos was quite large, as you would expect from the Giant Cheetos name, with a tube-like shape, kind of like a marshmallow, though somewhat irregular, with rounded-off ends. Each tube was about an inch and a half in diameter and about an inch and a half long.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Pretty good cheese smell, not that string.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This new shape of Cheetos bag (about 3 inches high by 8 inches wide, with openings at the sides) brought the shape of the regular Giant Cheetos (the world's largest Cheetos) and combined it with the spices from Flamin' Hot Crunchy Cheetos.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Barely any.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This latest Giant Cheetos followed in the tradition of the original Giant Cheetos and Flamin' Hot version with the same size and shape — about the same as a typical marshmallow.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mild cheddar cheese smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are miniature cheese balls, very small in fact. They remind me of the Planters Cheez Balls. These are smaller, with a good cheese taste, but you'll still get orange residue on your fingers. Be careful out there!
snack_smell_test: Smell test: The Cheetos smell we all love and adore.

snack_name: Go Snacks Cheetos Asteroids Flamin' Hot
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These hot cheese balls used to be sold in cans like this, and Frito-Lay has announced they're coming back in bags under the Flavor Shots brand.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Not much.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are the Korean version of Cheetos.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Not a bag smell, but they definitely don't smell like Cheetos.

snack_name: Matutano Cheetos Pandilla/Fantasmas Sabor a Queso/Queijo
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are different from any Cheetos I've ever seen, in several notable ways.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: OK cheese smell, kind of sharp.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Cheetos took on the irregular shapes of the original flagship Crunchy Cheetos but with a light yellow color rather than fluorescent orange.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice toasted corn smell with a hint of cheese.

snack_name: Simply Cheetos Puffed Corn White Cheddar
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Cheetos consisted of small, C-shaped twists with a very pale yellow color.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: A bit strange. Not really like cheese, not like corn either, but not really bad.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Cheetos Puffs was narrower than the standard ones, and rather than being orange, had a light yellow color. Most of the puffs were fairly straight, with just a slight curvature in most cases.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice white cheddar smell.

snack_name: Simply Cheetos Puffs White Cheddar Jalapeño
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Cheetos consisted of puffs that were much thinner than the standard Cheetos puffs (but the same thickness as the non-Jalapeño white cheddar Simply version), with generally just a small curvature, a strong yellow color and a smattering of small dark seasoning bits.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong cheese flavor, not really a good one. Couldn't really notice any of the jalapeno, but maybe just because the cheese smelled bad.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Cheetos from Taiwan had generally the same types of wiggly shapes as other Crunchy Cheetos, with a pale yellow color and some whitish areas, much like other white cheddar snacks.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: More toasted corn than cheese, but nice.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are the Israeli version of Cheetos.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Cheesy, sort of buttery smell. Mild.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: As someone who has reviewed more than 300 kinds of cheese puffs, I've gotta say that new extension of the venerable Cheez Doodles line this was an odd one — at least the way that it was marketed.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong spicy cheese smell. Very unexpected!

snack_name: Cheez Doodles Extra Crunchy Queso Habanero
snack_taste_test: Taste test: We've enjoyed many very tasty hot cheese curls — as well as some that were hot but not particularly tasty — so the promise of a Queso Habanero flavor had us very eager to try this new one from Wise. It boasted the same "Extra Crunchy" claim as the Extreme flavor. The curls had a light orange color with some darker seasoning spots too.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice cheese and toasted corn smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Four years ago, we saw cheese puff behemoth Cheetos (Chester Cheetah, CEO) bring innovation to the category by putting four different shapes of puffs/curls in the same bag, with mixes flavored as Cheezy Salsa,  Flamin' Hot,  Xtra Cheezy and  P41. Cheez Doodles from Wise might be four years late, including only two shapes — the previously reviewed crunchy curls and new-to-us Puffed Balls — rather than four, having just one flavor, and doing it only as a limited edition, but at least they have finally joined the multiple-kinds-of-puffs game!
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very strong cheese smell. Way above your typical cheese puffs.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This bag was filled less than halfway with smallish, remotely crocodile-shaped cheese puffs, each about an inch long but curved. I guess the shape was supposed to be the torso of the crocodile with two legs jutting out on each side, but if not for the crocodile-themed name and illustration on the bag, I would have never have guessed that it was a crocodile shape.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong cheese smell. Too strong. Ick.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These cheese puffs are disc-shaped, with two eyes and a smiley mouth carved out to form a face.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mild cheese aroma.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are moderately crunchy cheese puffs — not as crunchy as a crunchy cheese curl, such as Crunchy Cheetos, but crunchier than a cheese puff, such as Jax.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mild cheesy smell

snack_name: Wise Cheez Doodles Cheese Flavored Potato Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: One of the great trends in potato chips has been flavors that authentically imitate the tastes of various kinds of food.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Wow, it really does smell like Cheez Doodles.

snack_name: Wise Cheez Doodles Crunchy Hot & Tangy
snack_taste_test: Taste test: One of the many nice things about Chicago is that there are several snack companies selling hot cheese curls.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Not hot, definitely tangy, but still mild.

snack_name: Wise Cheez Doodles Crunchy Jalapeño Cheddar
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This flavor of Cheez Doodles had the standard shapes of crunchy cheese curls, with a fairly light orange color overall, as the intense orange seasoning covered just a portion of the curls while the remaining exposed corn area was more yellowish orange.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice jalapeno kick. Could feel the heat in the air as soon as we opened the bag.

snack_name: Wise Cheez Doodles Honey BBQ & Cheese Flavored
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These cheese puffs looked pretty much like the standard Cheez Doodles in terms of shape and color.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very mild, and nothing like I expected. Kind of like celery.

snack_name: Wise Cheez Doodles Jalapeño Cheddar Poppers
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These fairly large, roundish cheese puffs had a good helping of bright orange seasoning, but unlike many similar snacks boasting both jalapeño and cheddar, there was no green to be found when we opened the bag. A much closer look at the puffs revealed some very tiny dark spots, but not many of them, and they were so small that it was hard to tell that the were green.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: A lot of jalapeño. Wow.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are cheese puffs shaped sort of like macaroni, complete with a hole that stretches the full length of the puff down the center.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: A weak cheese smell, and I suppose it could be remotely like macaroni and cheese, though it might just be the regular cheese puffs smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are like Cheez Doodles, but instead of a fluorescent orange cheese coating, it's a pale while.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very strong cheese aroma. Sharp and good.

snack_name: Wise Cheez Doodles White Cheddar Crunchy
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These cheese curls were crisp and very crunchy, and they had a nice white cheddar taste.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice cheese and tasted corn smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are very good cheese thingies, with a good crunch and a nice cheese flavor.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: These smell really good. There's a toasted corn smell to go along with the cheese smell that dominates most cheese curls.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are good cheese puffs.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very, very cheesy, just on the edge of too cheesy.

snack_name: Wise Reduced Fat Cheez Doodles Crunchy
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These cheese curls were crunchy with a bright fluorescent orange color, and they tasted just like a Kraft macaroni and cheese dinner.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Weak, not much of an aroma at all.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are basically white cheese puffs with many tiny red and blue specks on them, but the overall color of each puff from a distance is still pretty much white.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mild but good white cheddar aroma.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This snack mix included Chex-like cereal, wiggly bread sticks (called "Tater Twists" on the bag), "Bread Bites" that looked like mini-bagel chips, Cheez-Its and small knotted pretzels.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very mild, but kind of like the Worcestershire sauce that that they use in Chex Mix.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This box said that each of the Cheez-Its inside was twice the volume of original Cheez-Its, so before opening it, I paused to think about what that meant. Drawing on my many years of studying geometry some decades ago, I did some quick calculations and determined (based on the assumption that these crackers weren't any thicker) that the height and width should each be about 1.4 times the normal Cheez-It dimensions. This didn't seem like that dramatic of a change, so I was expecting to be disappointed that the pieces weren't all that big.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: The usual Cheez-Its smell. Good.

snack_name: Cheez-It Big Crunch Baked Snack Mix
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This is a really good snack mix.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like Doritos.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This new flavor of Cheez-Its didn't look notably different from the original, with the same orange color generally, with some darker spots on some of the pieces.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mostly like Cheez-Its, but a hint of hot sauce in there.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These crackers had the same general look and shape as the original Cheez-Its, but some of the crackers seemed to have an additional light coating of flavor powder.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Definitely different from regular Cheez-Its, but I couldn't really recogize any Jack cheese.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This Cheez-Its flavor was pitted up against fellow limited editions Pizza and Cheeseburger in a contest to choose a permanent flavor. The crackers had the usual orange Cheez-Its orange color on their surfaces, plus a generous smattering of very dark seasoning powder, with the amount of dark stuff varying a lot from one piece to the next.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Not really that much like nachos, but some kick of taco powder.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Much like the Cheeseburger flavor of Cheez-Its, the pieces in this box generally looked pretty similar to the original, but the looks varied a lot from piece to piece, as some of the pieces had a noticeable smattering of darker seasoning.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Can smell some tomato, but it didn't smell really like pizza.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This special Cheeseberger version of Cheez-Its didn't look much different from the original, as there wasn't even any noticeable difference in the orange color, but it did look like there was some extra powder on parts of the surfaces.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Kind of like a cheeseburger with lots of condiments, particularly pickle.

snack_name: Cheez-It Cheesy Sour Cream & Onion Baked Snack Crackers
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These were like regular Cheez-Its, but much less orange in color, and with a thin coating of a green flavor powder.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very mild sour cream and onion smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This variation of Cheez-Its had the same appearance as the original flavor, but it took just one bite to find that they tasted quite different.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice!

snack_taste_test: Taste test: We've eaten and reviewed many kinds of Cheez-Its, with all manners of shapes and flavors, but this is the very first time they've combined two of them into a sandwich.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very strong cheese smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: When we spotted this bag on the snack aisle shelf, what immediately came to mind was a relatively recent product innovation from Goldfish.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Not much.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: After bring quite disappointed with the taste cheddar flavor of Cheez-It Crunch'd, we were cautiously optimistic that this spicy version would be better. Other than the different flavor and a slightly darker color, these seemed to be the same in just about every way — which is also to say, different from what you probably think of as Cheez-Its in most ways. They were not crackers at all, but square cheese puffs made from wheat and corn, with a small hole in the middle of each piece.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice zesty, spicy cheese smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of the two-flavor Cheez-It Duoz featured regular cheddar pieces, with the typical orange Cheez-Its color, plus bacon-flavored ones with a less-bright yellow color that also included some tiny bits of dark seasoning. It was easy enough to tell the two kinds apart by look, but it wasn't a huge contrast.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Kind of bacony, but not the typical bacon smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: When we first encountered the Cheez-It Duoz sub-brand, the innovation was that they figured out a way to combine two different flavors of Cheez-Its in one box. They've sold at least four such flavor combinations: Bacon & Cheddar, Jalapeño & Cheddar Jack, Sharp Cheddar Parmesan and Zesty Queso Cheddar Blanco. (For those paying attention in case there's a pop quiz, you surely noticed that the one thing that they all have in common is cheddar!)
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Definitely can smell both the cheddar and caramel corn.

snack_name: Cheez-It Duoz Cheddar Jack & Sharp Cheddar Pretzel
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Cheez-It's Duoz followed on the path of the Caramel Popcorn & Cheddar ones by providing one kind of Cheez-Its and something else, rather than two flavors of Cheez-Its.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong cheddar smell, nice.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of the two-flavors-one-box Cheez-It Duoz provided a good color contrast between the yellow Jalapeno ones and the orange Cheddar Jack ones. Other than the base color, there not much colored seasoning on either one, as the yellow ones had some green stuff, but less of it than it showed in the picture on the box.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Not strongly jalapeno-like nor cheddary. Kind of muddled.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This brand-new concept took two different kinds of Cheez-Its and combined them in one box.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: I think I can smell both cheddar and parmesan. Pretty good.

snack_name: Cheez-It Duoz Zesty Queso Cheddar Blanco
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This box contained two kinds of Cheez-Its, with a good contrast of colors between the pale yellow Cheddar Blanco ones and the orange Zesty Queso ones.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Wow, it does have the kick of a queso dip. Nice.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This Extra Cheesy version of Cheez-Its isn't the first time that Cheez-It has gone the extra mile, as they previously brought us Extra Toasty and Extra Big ones. But since Cheez-Its are really all about the cheese, this seemed like a particularly important development.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good strong cheese smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Several weeks before we found this box in the cracker aisle, we had heard some buzz about how the folks behind Cheez-Its were planning to sell a "burnt" version of the popular square snack crackers, featuring just the rare overcooked ones that certain people crave in an ordinary box of Cheez-Its.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice mild cheese smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These Cheez-Its tasted really taco-y, like the powdered taco seasoning mix you add to browned burger to make tacos.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: The box of Cheez It Fiesta Cheesy Taco smelled exactly like the packet of taco seasoning you add to ground beef when you make your own taco.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These Cheese-Its were shapled like large equilateral triangles, a bit over an inch on each side.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Like Cheez-Its with a little taco powder.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Cheez-Its came in an easily opened packet, filled with tiny hexagonal pieces.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Regular Cheez-Its smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This new flavor of Grooves expanded on the original Sharp White Cheddar version by promising some spices in addition to that cheddar, with the same Grooves form factor — larger and thinner than standard Cheez-Its, with some subtle ripples and a series of holes on one side. The crackers had a dark orange color with a smattering of green seasoning bits and some fine powdery stuff.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Not particularly spicy or hit, but a tangy and nice cheese smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These snacks had a dull orange color with a smattering of dark seasoning bits, on the same rectangular, rippled chips with a pattern of holes as the White Cheddar and Hot Cheddar Grooves varieties.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong taco powder smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Cheez-Its boasted "grooves" to set it apart from the original, but that wasn't the only change, nor even the most noticeable one.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mild white cheddar smell, but also like Cheez-Its.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: I remember eating Cheez-Itz way back in high school, but I don't think I've ever eaten any since.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Slight jalapeno aroma

snack_taste_test: Taste test: One weird thing about "three cheese" and "four cheese" snacks is that sometimes the snack companies make little effort to actually identify the cheeses. Such was the case here, as they put "Four Cheese" in very big letters on the front of the box, but nowhere in any of the marketing copy did they specify what any of the four cheese were (though there was a picture of some cheeses). I checked the government-mandated ingredients list to look for clues, and although it did answer the question, there were actually five cheese listed: Monterey Jack, Romano, Parmesan, Mozzarella and Asiago. So why not call it Five Cheese? Which one were they trying to hide from?
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong cheese smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This is an unimpressive snack mix.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Not much, slightly oily.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This extension to the popular Cheez-It line of snack products takes the Cheez-It concept to the world of spreadable cheese served from an aerosol can.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good cheddar smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These Cheez-Its had a much yellower color than the orange original flavor, with various shades of light yellow, plus some areas of browning on most pieces. Their shapes were the same as the original, with their sort of postage stamp-like edges, a hole in the center and generally a slightly puffy appearance. We crunched in to find a fairly mild provolone cheese flavor with some nice smokiness as well.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Fairly strong provolone-like smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Cheez-Its had a color much different from the original ones, with various shades of beige rather than orange, while retaining the original shape. Most of the pieces had a light smattering of fine green and red seasoning bits.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: A bit zesty, noticeably different from regular Cheez-Its.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: With the other two flavors of Cheez-It sandwiches, Italian 4 Cheese and Spicy Queso, they tried to get fancy. But with this Cheddar one, the Cheez-It folks kept it pretty basic, and the result was still good.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong sharp cheddar smell, like Cheez Wiz

snack_taste_test: Taste test: When Cheez-Its got into the sandwich business, they jumped in with both feet, as there were actually three flavors, the previously reviewed Italian 4 Cheese, this Spicy Queso one and a Classic Cheddar. They all followed the same formula, with six square sandwiches per pack and six packs inside the package.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Kind of a rancid cheese smell. Ick.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: It's a new kind of Cheez-It — not just a new flavor, but a whole new shape, and atypically for Cheez-Its, this one comes in a bag instead of a box. The pieces were much larger than regular Cheez-Its, with the shape of a parallelograms but not quite a rhombus, as two of the sides were slightly shorter than other two. The surfaces were generally wavy and far from flat. There generally was a hole near the center, then additional ones near each of the four corners, but in many cases, some of the holes seemed to have disappeared during the cooking process. They had a fairly bright orange color.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good cheese smell, fairly mild.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This flavor of Cheez-Its took the same shape as the other Snap'd versions, such as Double Cheese, parallelograms with wavy surfaces, but this one looked quite different. It had a strong yellow color instead of the usual Cheez-It orange, with some green seasoning bits on the surfaces adding to the expectation of some jalapeño heat.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice Jack cheese smell, but couldn't really notice any jalapeño.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Snap'd had the same shapes as the Jalapeño Jack and Double Cheese flavors, with a yellow color and a smattering of green seasoning bits on the surfaces.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Kind of bacony at first, then an odd cheese smell.

snack_name: Cheez-It SpongeBob SquarePants Baked Mild Cheddar Crackers
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Cheez-Its had a generally trapezoidal shape, with wiggly SpongeBob-style edges and Spongebob's face stamped into one side of the Cheez-It.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very mild Cheez-Its smell.

snack_name: Cheez-It Star Wars Episode III Limited Edition
snack_taste_test: Taste test: The crackers in this box were just regular square Cheez-Its, as all that Star Wars stuff on the box turned out to be nothing more than movie promotion. I was hoping for crackers in Star Wars shapes, such as Darth Vader, Yoda, C3PO, Emperor Palpatine or General Grievous.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very, very mild cheese smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: When we last reviewed a Star Wars edition of Cheez-Its, we were not impressed. For that one, released in conjunction with Episode III of the popular movie series, they designed a special Star Wars box and proceeded to fill it with a bag of entirely ordinary Cheez-Its — nothing Star Wars about them. So after spending $113 million to make the movie, they got cheap when it came to designing a respectable licensed Cheez-It? Lame.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Regular Cheez-Its smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This new style of Cheez-Its was a big disappointment.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Really weak smell, not much like Cheez-Its at all.

snack_name: Cheez-It Twisterz Baked Cheese Snacks Hot Wings & Cheesy Blue
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are made from roughly the same raw material as conventional Cheez-Its, but they're shaped sort of like elongated nuggets with a twist in them from combining two separate strands of dough.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice, it really does smell like blue cheese.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These inch-long sticks had sort of a double helix design to them, with one helix being a dull yellow color and the other a dull orange.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Surprisingly mild cheddar smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Tastes a little bit like normal Smartfood white cheddar popcorn, though not as sticky on your fingers.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like white cheddar popcorn.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These Cheez-Its had the same extra-large size as the Big Cheez-Its and generally a light yellow color, with many bits of green, red and whitish seasoning on the surfaces.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice zesty cheese smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This popcorn tastes quite buttery.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mild, very nice butter aroma.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This creation from the kitchen of Chester Cheetah didn't claim to be Cheetos and followed a formula we've seen from Canadian snack companies before, with Corn Puffs from Yum Yum and Jardi Cheese Puffs.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Slightly buttery.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are pretty hot and taste good.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Not too strong — a pleasant, cheesy aroma.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This is good, crisp popcorn with a tasty and pretty hot flavoring.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These fries had a nice bright orange color and were generally fairly long, with some measuring as much as 3 inches. I crunched in to find a soft crunch and a fairly dense feel, with a good taste that was more cheddar than bacon. There was a hint of bacon smokiness, but it was pretty subtle as bacon snacks go.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice smoky bacon smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Chester's Fries consisted of bright orange fries with some dark spots on them, in a variety of lengths up to about 3 inches.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mild chili smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: I bought this bag figuring it was going to be a fairly ordinary cheese popcorn — marked to sell for $1.50 but actually priced at $1, like everything else at Dollar Tree. Then I checked out the back of the bag and read some old-school, over-the-top Chester Cheetah hype marketing copy, which raised my expectations considerably.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good mix of sharp cheese and popcorn.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These spiral-shaped potato snacks had a light beige color on their surfaces, brightened up by a light coating of reddish barbecue seasoning. Each piece was about half an inch wide and an inch and a half long.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Sweet barbecue sauce smell, but mild.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Chester Cheetah's latest entry in the crowded market for fries in a bag consisted of hollow, square-profile sticks about two inches long, with the ends cut at an angle. They were potato-based, and the surfaces had a beige potato color, along with a good helping of orange seasoning. We crunched in to find that the mix of processed potato and cheddar was pretty bland. There was a soft crunch and a fairly ordinary potato-and-cheese flavor.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Pretty good cheddar del, like Cheez Wiz.

snack_name: Chester's Poppers Cheese Pizza Waffle Rounds
snack_taste_test: Taste test: When we saw this bag, the close-up picture on the front highly resembled one of the four Cheetos shapes in the Cheetos Cheezy Mix-Ups, which is made from corn meal. Since the other two kinds of Chester's Poppers that we'd already reviewed (BBQ Spirals and Cheddar Crunch Fries) were potato-based, it seemed strange that they would use this new Poppers brand for a corn snack, so we checked the ingredients and found that this too was potato-based (with wheat also). We opened the bag and were surprised that the snacks didn't quite match the picture. They had the same general circle-with-grid-inside shapes, but everything looked thinner and lighter, with smoother surfaces.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good pizza smell. Tomatoey.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This is the Frito-Lay version of Puffcorn, which is basically a cheese puff shaped sort of like an oversized popcorn kernel.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very strong cheese smell, similar to Cheetos, but just on the border of being too cheesy.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These corn puffs had sort of a popcorn-like shape (except bigger than any actual popcorn kernels) and were mostly covered with a seriously red seasoning powder.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Sort of buttery or cheddary. Not hot.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This bag marked a major departure in the way Frito-Lay markets their party mixes, as they've gone beyond the longtime Munchies brand name and let Chester Cheetah (of Cheetos fame) join the party.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like taco powder.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This latest variation of Chex-in-a-snack-bag did away with the Mix part and made the Chex quite a bit bigger than what we've come to know as Chex from the cereal. Each one was about an inch square and shaped like a pillow, with a hollow interior and a pattern of small holes running diagonally across the surface.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Definitely some jalapeño.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Much like the Cheddar Jalapeño flavor of Chex Chips, this snack seemed to be more themed on Chex than based on Chex. The "chips" looked like oversized Chex, but they were made from different materials, had a different texture, were multigrain rather than single-grain, and generally were really nothing like Chex.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mildly zesty spices, but only a bit of it seemed to be wasabi.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These bars combined Chex cereal with peanuts, M&M's (or possibly imitation M&M's) and pretzels, with lots of caramel to hold everything together.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mostly like caramel.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This is an excellent snack mix.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells good, vaguely garlicy.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This mix included small round and knottled pretzels, isosceles triangular cheddar cheese crackers, and Corn and Wheat Chex, some fairly plain and some infused with lots of cheese powder.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong cheese smell. OK.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Chex Mix is like party mix where you have several different tastes going on — Pretzels, kind of standard taste, but you have two different shapes (round and square); Chex cereal, two kinds — both the regular Corn Chex and Wheat Chex pieces; and peanuts, although if you eat them out of the bag you usually don't get to the peanuts until the end.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Standard oil-type smell with those aluminum foil-type inside bags.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Chex Mix had the same assortment of snack types as the original, with Corn Chex, Wheat Chex, small pretzel rings, 2x2 grid pretzels, squiggly bread sticks and thin triangular cheese crackers.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Definitely can smell the hot peppers.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Chex Mix included Corn and Wheat Chex with a light chocolate coating; tiny knotted, chocolate-covered mini pretzels; something similar to mini red M&M's; tiny chocolate cookies; and some sort of yogurt-covered Chex.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mild chocolate smell, like hot chocolate but weak.

snack_name: Chex Mix for Kids Castle Adventure Pizza Flavor
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This snack mix had crackers and pretzels shaped like different things, including faces, a tic-tac-toe board, magic scepter and a "crown" that looked like a giant E.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: It smells like a Chuck E. Cheese! Oh, wait, it smells like a pizza parlor.

snack_name: Chex Mix For Kids Crazy Creatures Cheddar
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This snack mix included crackers in three different shapes (squarish with a diagonal line across the center, sort of like a horn, and sort of like a crown), pretzels in three shapes (sort of like the letters S, D and L), and Corn Chex.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice cheddar smell, sort of like Cheez Wiz.

snack_name: Chex Mix For Kids Funny Faces Triple Cheese Flavor
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This mix contained pretzels in three shapes (wiggly sticks, rounded triangles, and the letter C), isosceles triangle crackers, mouth-shaped crackers, oval crackers that have circles in the middle and look sort of like eyes, and Corn Chex.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good cheddar cheese smell (regular cheddar, not sharp cheddar).

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Individual pieces include: Honey Nut Chex, Honey Nut Clusters, Vanilla breadsticks, Wheat Chex, Round Pretzels, Corn Chex.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: No particular strong smell one way or another.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: I like these.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like Chinese hoisin sauce

snack_name: Chex Mix Hot & Spicy Ghost Pepper
snack_taste_test: Taste test: Having eaten the tiniest bit of an actual Ghost Pepper, I know that the heat bar should be pretty high when evaluating a snack that claims a Ghost Pepper taste. We've had some notable failures in that regard.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nothing great, it seemed almost like the Melba toast with the dominant smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Chex Mix promised hot and spicy Buffalo-flavored Chex, along with ranch-flavored everything else, which consisted of more Chex, plus pretzel rings, 2x2 grid pretzels and melba toast. The Buffalo pieces really stood out visually from the rest with a very bright orange color.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: A hint of the Buffalo wings flavor, but not in a spicy way.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Hot pickles are hot! (As in, popular in snacks lately, with the Lay's Flamin' Hot Dill Pickle Remix turning into quite a hit.) But also, they're just plain hot! (As in, spicy.) This version of Chex Mix combined round and 2x2 grid pretzels, triangular cheese crackers and two kinds of Chex — one with a light helping of cheese applied, and another caked heavily with pickle seasoning. Heavily!
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Fairly mild, but still like you just opened a pickle jar.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Usually Chex Mix contains Chex cereal and various salty snacks seasoned with some flavoring, but this one was just the Chex, though enhanced with a special sweet recipe.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Really nice peanut butter and chocolate smell. Wow.

snack_name: Chex Mix Muddy Buddies Peppermint Bark
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This variety of Chex Mix wasn't really a mix like most kinds, in that it contained only one element, but that didn't matter much to our tasters, as they enjoyed the taste immensely.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Great! Smells like Mint Oreo ice cream.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: We opened this edition of Muddy Buddies to find that the Chex pieces had a very thin white powder coating, but also an evenly applied one, as they had consistent grid-like surfaces, with white areas in the pattern of crevices and yellow in between.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mild sweet cinnamon smell (but different from cinnamon sugar). Nice!

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This mix contained six different snacks — honey-roasted peanuts, plain-roasted peanuts (hence the name), Corn Chex, Wheat Chex, Peanut-shaped pretzels and "bread sticks." Because this was Peanut Lovers' Chex Mix, I was expecting a ton of peanuts, but like all Chex Mix bags, they end up on the bottom of the bag because of their weight. So the best way to eat this snack is to pour the entire bag into a bowl, and then dig your hand into the bottom of the bowl to grab the peanuts. Just be sure that your friends don't see you doing this, or make sure your hands are clean when you do this.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like a jar of peanut butter.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Chex Mix was supposed to combine some of the usual elements of Chex Mix with popcorn, so we were quite surprised when we opened the bag and looked inside that there was just a whole lot of popcorn staring back.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like white cheddar popcorn. Nice.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This mix consisted of Corn Chex, Wheat Chex, small round tortilla chips, round and peanut-shaped pretzels, and cheese crackers shaped like peppers.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Fairly strong salsa smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Chex mix consisted of Corn Chex and Wheat Chex with lots of seasoning on them, seasoned melba toast, wiggly bread sticks, round pretzels and 2x2 grid pretzels.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Not really sour creamy or oniony. Well, maybe oniony, but not really good or anything.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Chex Mix consisted of Corn Chex heavily seasoned with an orange-red seasoning, plus assorted shapes of Japanese rice crackers and some dried green peas.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice spicy smell.

snack_name: Chex Mix Sweet 'n Salty Caramel Crunch
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This is a great mix of snacks.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice caramel smell.

snack_name: Chex Mix Sweet Peanut Butter Crunch
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Chex Mix had just four elements: Corn Chex, Wheat Chex, peanuts and peanut butter-filled pretzel nuggets.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like a jar of peanut butter. Sweet too.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Chex Mix had the same mix of pieces as the Spicy Szechuan version, with Corn Chex, Japanese rice crackers and peas — and it even had the same picture of those pieces on the front of the bag.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like ginger (the tuber, not the Gilligan's Island character).

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This mix contains various snacks including Corn Chex, Wheat Chex, various pretzels, toast and some other strange-shaped items.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: It's hard to place the smell. Kind of strange, but not that bad.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This mix consists of sweetened corn and wheat Chex, small round pretzels, 2x2 grid pretzels (called "Window Pretzels" on the bag), peanuts, raisins and "candy coated chocolatey pieces" (also known as imitation M&Ms).
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like Peanut M&Ms.

snack_name: Chex Mix Xtreme Sweet & Spicy Sriracha
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This flavor of Chex Mix promised to be "Xtreme" so we figured that it would be quite a bit bolder than your typical Chex Mix flavors by virtue of being Sriracha flavor.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: A lot like the Worcestershire smell of the standard Chex Mix.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This snack mix included peanut-shaped pretzels (they looked kind of like a figure 8 or hourglass), peanut butter Chex cereal and chocolate peanut butter Chex cereal (I didn't even know they made that style), along with honey roasted peanuts and milk chocolate candies.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: A chocolate, and somewhat peanut-buttery smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Chex Mix included caramel popcorn, Caramel Chex cereal, Chocolate Chex cereal, honey roasted peanuts, round pretzels and milk chocolate candies.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like chocolate.

snack_name: Osem Chex Mix Natural Flavored Cocktail Snack
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This is a good snack mix, with a good variety of snacks in it, including 3 different kinds of Chex, plus two kinds of pretzles, a couple of kinds of melba toast, and some squiggly sticks.
snack_smell_test: From the package:  “Osem does its best to give you full satisfaction from its products. However, some natural circumstances are beyond the company's control. Should the product be deficient, please return it to ... stating exact deficiency, when and where you bought it. Osem will replace it.”

snack_name: Osem Chex Mix Piquante Cocktail Snack
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This is a good snack mix.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: It seems that the good folks at Chex have finally figured out that lots of people buy bags of Chex Mix not for the "Mix" part but for the "Chex" part.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good cheddar smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This mix included pretzels shaped like cars, ranch-flavored twisted breadsticks, ranch bagel chips, sun-shaped pretzels, Corn Chex and Wheat Chex.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Not really a ranch smell, but OK.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This mix included pretzels shaped like stockings, snowflakes, sleighs, snowmen and Christmas trees (moronically described on the bag as "holiday trees" so as not to offend); mini marshmallows, the kind they include with hot chocolate mix; vanilla bread sticks; Corn Chex; and Frosted Mini Chex.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like any of those chocolate cereals such as Cocoa Puffs.

snack_name: Chewy Chips Ahoy! Brownie Filled King Size!
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This smallish package promised brownie-filled Chips Ahoy cookies, with something about the cookies being "King Size!" so we had reason to be optimistic ... but given our past experiences with special flavors of Chips Ahoy, particularly the Chewy versions, we were skeptical.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mild chocolate/cookie dough smell. Nothing great.

snack_name: Chewy Chips Ahoy! Ice Cream Creations Mint Chocolate Chip
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These ice cream-themed cookies were dark brown in color overall, with some similarly colored chocolate chunks, plus some very light green mint chunks.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mild, but it does smell a lot like mint chip ice cream.

snack_name: Chewy Chips Ahoy! Ice Cream Creations Root Beer Float
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This new version of Chips Ahoy created quite a stir among our snackers, as many people anticipated bad things and some weren't even willing to try them. We opened the package to find that the cookies looked mostly like the ones pictured on the package, with two flavors of chips (root beer and vanilla) on top, but the vanilla chips were a definite beige in color, not white as shown, and the root beer chips weren't as perfectly shaped or as shiny as shown.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like a root beer. But not strong.

snack_name: Chewy Chips Ahoy! made with Reese's
snack_taste_test: Taste test: Just when I decided that I wouldn't bother to try any more new variations of Chips Ahoy (after the lackluster Chewy Gooey Caramel, American Summer and Soft with Chocolate Chunks), they had to come out with a Reese's version that I could not resist buying.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Doesn't smell like Reese's at all. JUst a weak chocolate chip cookie smell.

snack_name: Chewy Chips Ahoy! Oreo Crème Filled
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Chips Ahoy promised a layer of Oreo creme filling within the chocolate chip cookie. After not resisting the temptation for a similar product promising a caramel layer and being disappointed, plus getting a friend's tip about these not having enough creme, I very reluctantly bought some.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Way more like Chips Ahoy than Oreos.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Chips Ahoy expanded on the original recipe by adding chips coated in red, white and blue, in additional to the usual chocolate chips.
snack_smell_test: From the package:  “Real Chocolate Chip Cookies” ... “Crammed with real chocolate chips & candy coated fudge pieces” ... “Crammed with joy”

snack_name: Chips Ahoy Chewy Granola Bars 100 Calorie Packs
snack_taste_test: Taste test: Mmmmm chocolate chip cookies! Who doesn't love chocolate chip cookies? Even a mass-market brand like Chips Ahoy is usually a very good thing.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Not very good. Definitely didn't smell like chocolate chip cookies.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This thin version of Chips Ahoy really wasn't super-thin, but I suppose it was thinner than the original Chips Ahoy. "Double Chocolate" means chocolate chips within chocolate dough, and it sure did look chocolatey. The picture on the package showed some minor contrast between the chips and the cookie dough, but in reality they were just about the same color.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Wow, a lot of chocolate. Kind of like a brownie.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: So, Chips Ahoy took chocolate chip cookies and added a layer of gooey caramel somewhere inside. Wow, that sounded pretty awesome to me, and the picture of the cookies with the oozing caramel looked tempting, so I bought a package. I opened it and grabbed a few cookies, finding that they were very, very soft, with almost more the feel of cookie dough than cookies.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Fairly ordinary caramel and chocolate smell. Nothing great.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These cookies had chocolate chunks and some sort of yellowish chips or chunks jutting out from their top surfaces, with quite a bit of variation in shades of beige for the rest of the dough. The yellow things were presumably the banana component of the cookies, but they looked a lot like macadamia nuts.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like banana candy (not like real banana).

snack_name: Chips Ahoy! Soft Baked Real Chocolate Chunk Cookies
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These chocolate chip cookies were indeed soft as it said on the bag, and they were perfectly OK, but nothing special.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: An OK chocolate chip cookie smell, with a lot of chocolate.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: I gave up on trying to taste every new kind of Chips Ahoy years ago, because so many turned out to be disappointments. (I focused instead on trying every kind of Oreo.) However, this was one that I could not resist, not so much because it sounded incredibly awful, though it did, but mostly because it was different from anything else we've ever reviewed.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like Sour Patch.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These tiny cookies had a small rectangular shape, meant for dipping obviously.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smell like Chips Ahoy! cookies.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: While the original flavor of Chips Ahoy! Thins was a thinner version of a well-established product, this cinnamon sugar one followed the same form factor but had a formula that was all new to the Chips Ahoy brand, as far as we're aware.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: More sugar than cinnamon (by far) but it turns out that it's a great combination.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This thin version of Chips Ahoy surprised me when I went to go eat it. I looked at the picture on the package and said hey, those look like chocolate chips, not raisins. And indeed it turned out that they were. I had assumed incorrectly that with oatmeal cookies come raisins — without thinking about the obvious reality that these were labeled as Chips Ahoy, and raisins are not chips. So chocolate with oatmeal made this a relatively rare combination.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: More chocolate than oats, but kind of an odd mix of both.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: It seems that the five flavors of Oreo Thins introduced by Nabisco during the past year might be just the beginning, as they've followed up by adding two "Thins" versions of Chips Ahoy to the cookie aisle — this one plus a Cinnamon Sugar version.
