snack_smell_test: Smell test: Same as regular Chips Ahoy. Pretty good.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: I've become very skeptical over the years of the various limited-edition versions of Chips Ahoy, particularly chewy varieties, but the lure of a cinnamon donut was just too much to prevent me from buying this one.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Yes, a lot like a cinnamon donut.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These tiny cookies were just under an inch in diameter, but about the same thickness as a regular Chips Ahoy.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like regular Chips Ahoy cookies.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Chips Ahoy added some small pieces of fudge candy with an orange-colored coating to the regular Chips Ahoy chocolate chip cookies.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Same as non-haunted Chips Ahoy. Really good.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This special edition of Chips Ahoy tempted me by promising the taste of my favorite hot beverage, so I went against my best instincts (not to buy limited-edition Chips Ahoy, based on past experiences) and got them. I opened the package to find that the cookies were brownie-colored, with some small, white, marshmallow-looking things embedded inside. The cookies were even darker than the one pictured on the package, and I didn't even notice the chocolate chips until I saw the ones pictured, which were much more distinct and nicely formed than the real ones.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like marshmallows and brownies. Not like hot chocolate.

snack_name: Lunchables Fun Snacks Chips Ahoy! Soft Cookie 'n Frosting
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This snack was a definite disappointment. The packaging is an impressive-looking plastic contraption with three individual compartments and a brighly colored peel-off cover, containing all that you need to construct a special snack. But upon opening it, I realized that the package contains exactly one (count it, one) cookie. It seems like way too big of a production for it to contain just one cookie. (In fairness, it does say on the package that there's one cookie inside, but other than those words, it definitely looks like the kind of package that should contain more cookies.)
snack_smell_test: Smell test: The cookie smells like a chocolate chip cookie, and the frosting smells like frosting.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This large chocolate bar had the same 5x3 grid as the Oreo Milka, with a filling that in this case tried to bring the taste of a Chips Ahoy cookie in between the milk chocolate top and bottom. The center looked kind of like cookie dough, with some cookie bits or chocolate chips visible, but not a lot of them.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: There is a hint of chocolate chip cookie amid the milk chocolate smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Chips Ahoy was made from a brownish red dough that really did look like Red Velvet cake (though it was more brown and less red than shown on the package), with some white chips (described as "cream cheese flavored chips") embedded inside.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like Red Velvet cake!

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Everyone's making s'mores flavors of everything these days, so Chips Ahoy has joined the s'mores party too. They did this by adding marshmallow chips to the usual chocolate ones. In addition to the white and brown chips near the top (which didn't look like the huge ones shown on the package, as they were generally just slightly poking through the dough), there was also a chocolate layer within the cookie.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Maybe a hint of marshmallow, but not really much like s'mores.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: A quick glance at this bag had me expecting that the chips inside would taste like Cinnabon cinnamon rolls. A more careful reading of the bag only reinforced this expectation, as it promised to deliver sliced-up and toasted Cinnabon rolls.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells kind of like cinnamon taste, but not like a Cinnabon,

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This irregularly shaped candy bar had a whitish nougat center, covered by a very thin caramel layer, and then a thicker layer of cinnamon sugar-drenched pecans.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like a coffee cake. Pretty good.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This popcorn had fairly large kernels with a fairly consistent application of light brownish seasoning.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Yeah, smells a lot like a cinnamon roll.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These short bars were made from a pastry sort of base, with a cinnamon sugar filling and a sprinkling of white frosting on top.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Sweet cinnamon smell.

snack_name: Mrs. Freshley's Cinnamon Twirls Sweet Rolls made with Cinnabon
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This package contained six cinnamon rolls, each fairly large at about an inch thick and 2-1/2 inches in diameter. All for just $1, so quite a deal. They truly were rolls, with dark cinnamon sugar layers between the cake layers, about five revolutions of spiral in each one.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good cinnamon roll smell. Sweet and cinnamony.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of the tortilla Combos promised seven different flavors from the seven layers of dip. We couldn't find anywhere on the package where they specified what those seven layers were, but it still seemed pretty ambitious. Even the picture showed a bowl of dip with only four layers (two of them the same dark red) plus a bunch of stuff on top.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like taco powder. Mildly so.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This special flavor of Combos looked pretty much like the other flavors, as it consisted of darkish pretzel tubes filled with an orange cheese filling.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: I could smell a hint of blue cheese.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are the cracker version of Combos Cheddar Cheese Pretzel.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong (but not bad) spreadable cheddar cheese smell

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Combos are hollowed-out thick pretzel tubes with stuff inside them. It doesn't really matter what's in a particular combo, because all of the different flavors taste pretty much the same.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like Cheez-Its, sort of a Nacho cheese aroma.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Like all Combos, these tube-shaped snacks had a crunchy outside and cheese-flavored filling.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like the pickles on a hamburger.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Combos had a dark pretzel exterior on the tubes and a light orange-colored filling coming out of each end, so they didn't look much different from the other Combos flavors.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: More like a sweet chili sauce than a hot sriracha (which might actually make sense, given that it was supposed to be honey sriracha).

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Combos had the same shape as usual, a hollow tube filled with cheese, but this time the tube was made from corn, with some salt visible on the exterior.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good jalapeno cheddar smell. Lots of jalapeno.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are OK.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like Cheez-Its, sort of a Nacho cheese aroma.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These pretzel-based snacks have sort of a cheese and tomato taste to them.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like pepperoni pizza. Really.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Tastes like a pretzel dipped in tomato sauce.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like pizza sauce with oregano

snack_name: Combos Spicy Honey Mustard Baked Pretzel
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This new flavor of Combos looked much like other pretzel-based Combos, with the exteriors of the tubes definitely looking pretzel-like and a pale orange filling showing at the center of each end.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: More spice for the smell than the taste. A bit more kick than standard honey mustard.

snack_name: Combos Sweet & Salty Caramel Crème Pretzel
snack_taste_test: Taste test: Combos is known for various cheesy and savory fillings to go with their various pretzel, cracker and tortilla tubes, but this snack marked their first-ever crossover into sweet territory.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice caramel smell. Pretty strong.

snack_name: Combos Sweet & Salty Chocolate Fudge Pretzel
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This additional sweet flavor of Combos (following up Caramel Crème) was the first time I've seen chocolate in the middle of a Combos tube, so I was eager to see what happened when chocolate and pretzel collided.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Barely any. Just the slightest hint of chocolate.

snack_name: Combos Sweet & Salty Vanilla Frosting Pretzel
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of the sweet-filled Combos had a light pretzel color on the outside of the tubes, with an off-white (slightly yellow) filling at each end, plus many bits of salt attached to parts of the sides. The frosting wasn't quite so perfectly clean around the ends of the tubes, so there was a bit of a messy appearance.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like vanilla frosting.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These snacks had the same basic shape and concept as previous Combos formulations, with a tube-shape outside filled with a soft inner filling.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Wow, a very seriously sharp, strong hot sauce smell. Cleared out my sinuses instantly.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: When we saw this bland package with the words "Cheddar Cheese Pretzels," visions of knot-shaped pretzels with cheese seasoning came to mind. We've reviewed more than 400 pretzels, but precious few of them have met that description — just this one from Rold Gold and this "Special" edition from Utz, neither seen in stores in recent years. (Why the bland package? It was part of an MRE. What's an MRE? Glad you asked!)
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good mildly tangy cheese smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Cracker Jacks are the standard by which all carmel-coated popcorn and peanut snacks are judged.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: The smell is so familar, what can I say? It smells like Cracker Jacks.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This box of Cracker Jacks tried to resurrect the old look of a Cracker Jacks box, and it succeeded perhaps a little too well at that.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good caramel and peanuts smell.

snack_name: Cracker Jack Butter Crunch Candy-Coated Peanuts
snack_taste_test: Taste test: It's hard to go wrong with butter toffee-coated peanuts, and Cracker Jack has not disappointed.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice, sugary roasted peanut smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are a lot like regular Cracker Jacks, but as the name implies, they have a coating of butter toffee, rather than ordinary caramel.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells the same as regular Cracker Jacks.

snack_name: Cracker Jack Holiday Sugar Cookie Popcorn
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This popcorn had a thick off-white sugary-looking coating over most of the popcorn surfaces, with smallish bits of green and red embedded into the coating.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells a lot like popcorn, but definitely some cookie sweetness too.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These tasted just like the peanuts inside regular Cracker Jacks, which happens to be a pretty good taste. The formula for these is not entirely unlike McDonald's "Sausage Biscuit With Egg, No Egg" — it's "Cracker Jack Peanuts and Popcorn Snack, No Popcorn."
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells just like Cracker Jacks.

snack_name: Cracker Jack Nothing But Nuts Butter Toffee Peanuts
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are good honey-roasted peanuts, but I don't know why they're labeled as "butter toffee" since they don't really have a toffee shell.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells mostly like roasted peanuts, but a bit sugary.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This peanut bittle had kind of a weird, musty taste to it.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Not too good.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This popcorn's surfaces were a mix of white and yellow with brownish spots, as the areas with and without sugar could easily be distinguished. The vast majority of the surface area did have the sugar. Most of the kernels were fairly large and quite round.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Kind of sort of burnt.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This bag contained mostly large, roundish kernels with a dark coating on most of the surfaces (but certainly the entire surface like the ones pictured on the front of the bag). It seemed a single coating of a hybrid chocolate/caramel, not separate coatings of chocolate over caramel. Most of the pieces were individual kernels, but there were some small stuck-together clusters.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mild chocolate smell. Noticed the caramel too on the second whiff.

snack_name: Cracker Jack Popcorn Chocolate Peanut Butter
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This chocolate-coated version of Cracker Jacks had less coating than it showed in the picture on the bag, as those ones had no white showing through, while the actual kernels had a less-even coating with many areas of white showing. Many of the coated areas were a darker brown than what was shown on the bag. The smallish bag was filled just about halfway, but it did include a Cracker Jack prize, which was nice.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong peanut and chocolate smell. More peanuts than chocolate.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: We've reviewed many kinds of kettle corn (including quite a few that claimed to be kettle corn but weren't) but this bag was a major discovery, as Cracker Jack remains one of the biggest names in popcorn but had never before entered the kettle corn arena. Most of the kernels were smallish and roundish, with generally an off-white color, except for the yellower sugary areas and darker exposed kernel exterior (or pericarp). I crunched in to find that the kernels had a nice light feel, good crispness and a mid-level sweetness. It did seem to be actual kettle corn (rather than sugar-coated popcorn) but the salt level was on the very low end of the spectrum as kettle corns go. More salt would have made this even better, as the sweet-and-salty combination is what makes many kettle corns so appealing. But this was still solid first effort by Cracker Jack.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Just mildly sweet. None of the usual popcorn smell, nor any burnt popcorn smell, as some kettle corns have.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This mix consists of banana chips (OK, considering they're banana chips, but I'd much rather just eat a real banana), honey-roasted peanuts (good), cashews (OK, but bland), sugarized pineapple chunks (OK, considering), and sugarized papaya chunks (not as bad as I thought they'd be).
snack_smell_test: Smell test: The cashews seem to be the dominant smell.

snack_name: Cracker Jack'D Hearty Mix Cheddar BBQ
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This Jack'D mix followed a similar formula to the  peanut butter and chocolate version, with flavored oat clusters and two kinds of nuts — in this case, cheddar and barbecue clusters, salted peanuts and smoked almonds.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: More link honey-roasted peanuts than cheddar or barbecue on the first whiff. Could some some hot BBQ powder after that.

snack_name: Cracker Jack'D Hearty Mix PB & Chocolate
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This "jacked" version of Cracker Jacks broke partially from the Cracker Jacks formula, in that it was based on clusters of oats, rather than popcorn, but it did include some peanuts.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong peanut butter smell.

snack_name: Cracker Jack'D Intense Mix Spicy Pizzeria
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This snack mix combined just three elements, but it did it quite well.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good cheesy pizza smell.

snack_name: Dale Jr. Foods Carolina Barbecue Potato Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips were fairly flat, with a very light orange color overall and just a very sparse amount of dark seasoning. The edges of the chips were virtually skin-free.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Sweet and sort of creamy barbecue smell. Different. And nice.

snack_name: Dale Jr. Foods Creole & Green Onion Potato Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips had lots of dark orange seasoning, with some small black spots as well.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Kind of a mildly spicy cheese smell.

snack_name: Dale Jr. Foods Crispy Original Potato Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips had a pale yellow color generally, with just a few darker spots and lots of skin around the edges.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong potato smell. God.

snack_name: Dale Jr. Foods Zesty Jalapeno Potato Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips had generally fairly flat shapes, with a light yellow color and large areas of skin along some edges. The actual chips had much less seasoning visible than the ones pictured on the bag, and the seasoning that there was had an orange color for the most part, vs. the largely green seasoning pictured. Some of the chips were quite large, which was nice.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice spicy jalapeño smell, mildly hot.

snack_name: Dale Jr.'s BigMo' Milk Chocolate with Creamy Caramel
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This thin candy bar had 10 sections in a 5x2 grid, and each section was primarily chocolate with a small pocket of liquidly caramel in the middle.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Pretty good chocolate and caramel smell, definitely more chocolate than caramel.

snack_name: Dale Jr.'s BigMo' Milk Chocolate with Peanut Butter
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This very large candy bar had a 5x2 grid of detachable sections, with alternate sections bearing either the BigMo logo or Dale Jr.'s signature.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good chocolatey peanut butter smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of the hockey puck-shaped Ding Dongs snack cakes looked like like the original ones from the outside, with an all-chocolate exterior, but inside, the cake had a light orange color, and the creme filling, a very light beige color.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice, creamy, more caramel than chocolate.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: As a longtime resident of New England, Ding Dongs have always been sort of a legendary snack that I could rarely find, but I have had occasional encounters while traveling. Around here, our circular Devil's Food cakes had always been Ring Dings from Drake's. Even after Drake's and Hostess became part of the same company, Ding Dongs were not to be seen. (I did come across an entirely unrelated snack from the Philippines that also used the Ding Dong name, though not in the plural.)
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Sweet, creamy milk chocolate and creme. Nice.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of the hockey puck-shaped Ding Dongs not only incorporated peanut butter into the famous Devil's Food snack cakes, but made a surprising change in the formula while doing so. A regular Ding Dong has a white creme filling surrounded by chocolate cake and coated in milk chocolate. I expected the white filling to be replaced by peanut butter, and it was. The wiggles of peanut butter-colored stuff atop the chocolate coating also seemed within the range of expectations. But I didn't expect that chocolate cake to be replaced by a yellow cake!
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice creamy PB and chocolate smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These Ding Dogs took a heart shape instead of the usual round one, while attaching small white, pink and red heart candies to the chocolate coating, retaining the chocolate cake interior and white creme center.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good Devil's Food smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These small, circular cakes took the same form factor as the conventional Ding Dongs, but they subbed out two of the three elements. The milk chocolate coating became a white fudge coating, and the Devil's Food interior became a yellow cake. The original creme filling remained. With the chocolate ones, I've never noticed any hint of the interior visible through the coating, but in this case, the fudge coating looked transparent in places, with hints of the yellow cake showing through. There were 10 pieces in the box, each individually wrapped in clear cellophane with the Hostess logo all over it.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Fairly mild, but a good sweet cake-and-frosting smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of the hockey puck-shaped Ding Dongs cakes had a white chocolate-looking exterior, with teal blue sprinkles attached to the top and some frosting-like stuff of the same color on parts of the bottom, plus some of the inner yellow cake almost jutting through the frosting in places.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Just slightly minty, nice.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips were generally fairly small, with a thick cut, wiggly shapes and a glowing orange-yellow color.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice mix of vinegar and maybe a sweet barbecue smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are different from most kettle chips, kind of lighter than Cape Cod chips.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smell like kettle chips.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are good kettle-cooked jalapeno chips, with a decent amount of heat and lots of crunch.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very strong jalapeno smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are pretty good chips.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Potatoey

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are pretty good chips.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Really nice barbecue aroma.

snack_name: Dirty Potato Chips Roasted Garlic & Herb
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are very good potato chips, with tons of garlic and herb flavor and the nice crunch of a kettle-cooked chip.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: A nice garlicy, herby smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: The "dirty" chips look darker, but they are not burned, it's only because they have been cooked in peanut oil.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: A very strong, nasal-stinger, vinegar smell awaits you when you open the bag.

snack_name: Dirty Potato Chips Sour Cream & Onion
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are pretty good chips.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: These have a really nice, strong sour cream and sweet onion flavor.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are good chips.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: These have a nice, spicy smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This Doritos flavor was one of three in the "Burn" series of escalating heat levels (along with Buffalo sauce 2nd Degree Burn and Habanero 3rd Degree). We tried them one at a time, in escalating order of degree, to evaluate the relative heat levels.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice sweet and tangy version of the usual Doritos smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Doritos Burn didn't look much different than the standard Doritos, but the seasoning was a tad more orange/red and less yellow.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good, but mostly like cheese, not really like Buffalo wings.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: You get a cheese taste at first, but after about three-quarters of a bite, the jalapeño taste kicks in.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: They smell like cheddar.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: They taste like Doritos.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: They smell like Cheese-Its.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: I like these.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: They smell like paprika, a bit barbecuey.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These taste just like the earlier, Cooler Ranch variety, but with the snazzy new packaging.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: A ranchy type of smell, typical Doritos.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Doritos followed up on the 1st Degree Burn and 2nd Degree Burn versions by cranking up the heat even higher. In terms of bag design, they stepped the color up from yellow (1st) to orange (2nd) to red for this maximum-heat one while also increasing the intensity of flames on the burning bag pictured.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mostly like Doritos, but with maybe some peppers added, though not really a "hot" smell.

snack_name: Doritos After Dark Last Call Kebab
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These Doritos from Australia closely resembled the American Tacos at Midnight Doritos in bag design, but they promised a somewhat different flavor in kebab.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice mix of creamy and some tangy seasonings.

snack_name: Doritos After Dark Southern Fried Chicken
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Doritos from New Zealand had a yellow color with a slight hint of orange, and there seemed to be a lot of seasoning on the surfaces.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice tangy, even citrusy smell, but not really like chicken.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: I really don't get the point of these.
snack_smell_test: From the package:  “Open the bag for a LOUD taste. Baja Picante flavor tortilla chips have the BOLD taste of picante, LOADED with tomatoes, onions and spices, combined with IRRESISTIBLE cheddar cheese.” Lies, lies, lies.

snack_name: Doritos Baked! Cooler Ranch Tortilla Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are baked tortilla chips, which means they are slightly better for you than regular tortilla chips.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: A slightly aromatic flavor of cooler ranch.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Just like Classic Doritos, but lighter and less oily.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Classic Doritos cheesiness.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This variation on the Doritos brand was not tortilla chips at all, but rather small rings with more of a Fritos consistency than Doritos.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mild paprika smell.

snack_name: Doritos Black Pepper Jack Tortilla Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: For once, biting into a Dorito doesn't actually taste like every other flavor of Dorito we've had.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: They smell like corn-flavored Doritos, nothing like pepper at all.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This was the shortest and simplest name for a Doritos flavor that we've seen in a while, maybe ever. After seeing the name and the heat hype on the back of the bag, I wondered whether this might approach the heat of the Carolina Reaper Pepper-based One Chip Challenge and then gasped as I realized that this is a big bag with lots of chips — 120 of them based on the estimates in the Nutrition Facts.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Kind of a toasted corn hot pepper kick, not the usual Doritos smell.

snack_name: Doritos Blazin' Buffalo & Ranch Tortilla Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These nuclear orange-colored tortilla chips looked had a flavor powdering more red and less orange than the usual Nacho Cheese Doritos.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like every other bag of Doritos I've ever opened.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: We've reviewed lots of different kinds of Doritos, but for all of those wide-ranging flavors, hasn't been much variation in color, as it generally runs from yellowish orange to orangish yellow. So this blue version definitely stood out.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Kind of like a seasoned steak, heavy on the seasoning and a bit sweet.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These chips looked almost exactly the same as the standard Nacho Cheese Doritos in terms of color and texture.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Kind of a tangy take on the usual Doritos smell. Not really cheesy.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This British version of Doritos had the same shape, texture and color as the normal Nacho Cheese Doritos, and the bag resembled the old American Nacho Cheesier flavor before the bag was redesigned when the flavor got renamed back to Nacho Cheese.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Kind of like the regular Doritos smell, but with some sweet pepper added.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: It's been a long while since we've seen a new variety of Doritos Collisions, the sub-brand where they take two contrasting flavors and mix them into the same bag. This time, it was the heat of Blaze (a very recent flavor from earlier this year), and the cheesy goodness of something new called Ultimate Cheddar. They even provided separate Ingredients lists for the two flavors.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Wow, the heat from this one really kicked me in the face, a really nice smell too.

snack_name: Doritos Collisions Cheesy Enchilada Sour Cream
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This bag contained two entirely different flavors of Doritos, intermixed. Despite Frito-Lay's valiant effort to brand the bag as "Collisions" and explain the two flavors, most of our tasters either couldn't grasp the concept or ignored the details on bag and just crunched in — in both cases blissfully unaware of the intent of the flavor designers.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice mix of tomato ad spices, kind of like an enchilada.

snack_name: Doritos Collisions Chicken Sizzler Zesty Salsa
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This bag contained two different flavors of Doritos, with a slight color difference between the two kinds. The Chicken Sizzler-flavored ones had kind of  a yellowish color, and the Zesty Salsa ones were more of a typical Doritos color, with a mix of yellow and orange. Still, I wish they had tried harder to make a stronger contrast of colors in this combination.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice. It did smell sort of like a spicy chicken fajita, with a lots of spicy tomato mixed in there as well.

snack_name: Doritos Collisions Hot Wings Blue Cheese Tortilla Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This new variety of Doritos combined two different flavors of chips in the same bag.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: We expected a much stronger aroma. The bag smells like a corn-flavored Doritos rather than hot sauce or blue cheese.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This bag combined two different Doritos flavors, with roughly half of the chips being each flavor.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mostly the typical Doritos smell, maybe a bit of ranch or pizza, but not dominant.

snack_name: Doritos Collisions Zesty Taco Chipotle Ranch
snack_taste_test: Taste test: The new Collisions style of Doritos puts two different flavors of chips in one bag. The hope is that the two flavors create yet a third a taste sensation when eaten together, as with the  Hot Wings and Blue Cheese Collisions.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like taco powder. Mmmmmmmm.

snack_name: Doritos Cool Ranch 100 Calorie Mini Bites
snack_taste_test: Taste test: Frito-Lay has joined the 100-calorie snack revolution by taking a bunch of Doritos and putting them in individually sized snack packs.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: These didn't smell like ranch, just smelled like regular Doritos.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Cooler Ranch Doritos are a true classic.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Pleasant ranch chip aroma.

snack_name: Doritos Cooler Ranch Mini Go Snacks
snack_taste_test: Taste test: Recently called 'The Mack Daddy of all Snacks' by our friends at the Phantom Gourmet, Cooler Ranch Doritos recently shrunk in size to fit into a can! Even though they're smaller, you can't tell the difference, and you can use the top as a cup can.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: They smell like every other bag of Doritos on the planet.

snack_name: Doritos Corn Chips Cool Original Flavour
snack_taste_test: Taste test: Just like Cooler Ranch Doritos in the U.S., but with quite a bit less flavoring.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Really nice smell. Smell sort of like tacos but sort of like Doritos.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This snack mix from Doritos expanded on their Crunch Nuts coated peanuts product by adding four additional items — "pretzel bites" that were basically broken-up big pretzels, like the ones from Snyder's of Hanover; miniature cheese puffs; "3-D triangles" and "corn sticks." The various things seemed to be present in roughly equal amounts.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mostly like roasted peanuts.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These coated peanuts, much like the Nacho Cheese flavor of them, consisted of peanuts with a corn-based coating and then coated again with seasoning based upon a Doritos flavor.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good peanut smell, couldn't notice any ranch.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This snack's existence surprised the heck out of me — the package said "Doritos" but it was much farther from my understanding of what constitutes Doritos than any of the 125 kinds previously reviewed. These were starch-coated peanuts, a type of snack with which we're quite familiar, but one entirely unlike a flavored tortilla chip. The other ones have been coated in a number of different starches (often wheat or potato), so I crossed my fingers as I checked the ingredients, hoping that it would at least be corn this time. Good news, it was!
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Definitely different from Doritos. Could smell something like peanuts but not any nacho cheese.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This new flavor and shape from Doritos packed some intense flavor into a tube made from a rolled-up tortilla chip.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong chili and lime smell.

snack_name: Doritos Dinamita Chile Limón/Cheetos Flamin' Hot
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This was a groundbreaking snack, as it was the first attempt we've seen to package Cheetos and Doritos together exclusively in the same bag. (They've been together before, along with other snacks, in bags of Munchies.)
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Not much.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This edition of Doritos Dinamita promised to be even hotter than the other flavors, Chile Limón and Nacho Picoso, as habanero tends to be one very hot pepper. We've seen the same flavor name from Doritos before, as their more conventional triangular tortilla chips came in a Fiery Habanero flavor several years back. Much like those triangular ones, these had a light orange color with some reddish accents, like the Nacho Cheese ones. This didn't quite match the red on the bag, as the actual snacks looked quite different from other hot flavors like Takis Nitro that have scary, intense shades of red.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice mix of spices and toasted corn, but mild, no heat.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This new flavor had the same shape and size as the other flavors of Doritos Dinamita, which are similar to the popular Takis and other rolled tortillas, but in this case, without the intense seasoning color that some of the other flavors have. The color was a pretty standard yellow tortilla chip, with a minimal amount of seasoning on the surfaces.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Zesty kick of spices, including some lime.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Years ago, Frito-Lay rolled out Rollitos, a tubular version of Doritos, but they didn't last. Now, perhaps driven by the popularity of Mexico-produced Taquis, they've brought back the Rollitos shape — but with a twist. Instead of mimicking the of triangular Doritos flavors, as Rollitos did with Nacho Cheesier, Cooler Ranch and Zesty Taco, they've given bolder flavors (again, a nod to Taquis) to the Dynamita line.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mostly like regular Doritos, but make a hint of jalapeño.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: If you've been suckered into trying the low-carb lifestyle as a way to lose weight (eat less and exercise more!), then you deserve to be fooled into thinking that these snacks will help you attain that lifestyle.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: They don't smell like regular Doritos, that's for sure. Kind of a dry, cheesy smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: It's always exciting when they come out with a new Doritos flavor, so I was looking forward to trying these.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like taco powder.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are kind of like regular Doritos, except that they're bigger and thicker, and rather than having a uniform flavor throughout the eating experience, these start out extremely mild — not spicy at all — and then in the aftertaste, you get the spice.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong, good spicy cheese smell. Mmmmm. On second whiff, kind of like Doritos, only stronger.

snack_name: Doritos Extreme Zesty Sour Cream & Cheddar
snack_taste_test: Taste test: I was quite excited when I heard that there was a whole new kind of Doritos, and that they were supposed to be more "extreme" than ever.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: About the same as regular Doritos.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This new Doritos flavor appeared at the same time as a identically named Cheetos flavor, and that's a rarity in Frito-Lay's world. It also came on the heels of a similar Lay's Kettle Cooked flavor, Spicy Cayenne & Cheese (as the Doritos and Cheetos were both subtitled "Sizzlin' Cayenne & Cheese" underneath the Fiery Fusion brand).
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Lots of hot peppers. Made my mouth water.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These looked pretty much the same as the Nacho Cheesier flavor Doritos, with the same size, shape, color and texture, but it took just one bite to see that they packed a nice kick of habanero heat.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Maybe a slight variation on the usual Doritos smell, but not really hot.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This flavor of Doritos had a seasoning powder more intensely red than any Doritos flavor we've tried. It was pretty much the same color as the Sabritas Turbos Flamas, though obviously in a Doritos shape this time.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Kind of a sweet tangy smell, though definitely some peppers in there too.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: A year after adding Flamin' Hot Nacho to the vast array of Doritos flavors, we found this generally similar-looking bag. The Dorito pictured on front was still very much on fire, but the majority of the bag changed from red to green, and there was a slice of lime next to that burning Dorito.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong kick of hot spices, just a little lime.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Doritos had the same intensely red seasoning powder that we've seen in other Flamin' Hot flavors from Frito-Lay, definitely more red and less orange than Nacho Cheese Doritos.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice cheese and corn smell, but not actually hot.

snack_name: Doritos Flavor Shots Atomic Chile Limón
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Doritos Flavor Shots included a bag of Nacho Cheese Doritos and a packet of Atomic Chile Limón flavor for spicing up the chips.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: After I mixed in the packet, a fairly typical chile a lime chips smell.

snack_name: Doritos Flavor Shots Blazin' Buffalo Rush
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This creation from the Snack Strong Productions division at Doritos had the same chips as Nacho Cheese Doritos but included a Blazin' Buffalo Rush flavor packet to let snackers spice things up.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Regular Doritos smell when I opened the bag (but not the flavor packet).

snack_name: Doritos Flavor Shots Fiery Habanero Triangles
snack_taste_test: Taste test: We've seen the name Doritos Flavor Shots before — twice, in fact, in the form of tortilla chips bearing the usual Doritos shapes, with an extra packet of add-your-own flavoring powder of the Blazin' Buffalo Rush or Atomic Chile Limon  variety — but these were not like those at all.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mostly like Fritos, with some mild spices, but not notably hot or zesty.

snack_name: Doritos Flavor Shots Flamin' Hot Nacho
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This bag had corn starch-coated peanuts, much like the Nacho Cheese Nuts Flavor Shots, but this time they promised a flavoring that corresponded to these Doritos chips.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mostly like peanuts, the hot stuff did not dominate.

snack_name: Doritos Flavor Shots Nacho Cheese Nuts
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This latest in the Flavor Shots line was basically corn starch-coated peanuts with nacho cheese seasoning, so not tortilla chips, despite the Doritos name. It sounded a lot like Doritos Crunch Nuts, except in a narrow bag instead of a weird box.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mostly like peanuts, but I could detect some tangy cheese seasoning.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These taste pretty much exactly the same as Nacho Cheesier Doritos.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Slight cheese aroma

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These were the first Doritos that we've tried that had a rectangular shape, and the only snack of any kind that we've found that claimed a duck flavor.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong aroma, maybe like miso soup.

snack_name: Doritos Gourmet Fried Chicken and Green Onion Sauce
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This variety of Doritos had a light, Cool Ranch-like color and a modified wedge shape, with a very rounded corner at on most acute of the three corners.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells mostly like soy sauce, with some other flavors as well.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These tortilla chips were shaped sort of like pizza slices, except the pointy end of the pizza was very rounded off.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Some strong spices, not specifically sausage-like, but pretty good.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This flavor is just one of 115 kinds of Doritos that we've reviewed. At first, they tasted sort of like regular Nacho Cheese Doritos and sort of like guacamole, but in the aftertaste there was a definite guacamole taste, slightly hot.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells slightly like guac.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Like the companion Heat Wave flavor Chipotle Cream, this Doritos flavor promised a two-stage taste, in this case a sweet and smoky barbecue followed by a massive wave of heat.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice sweet, tangy and especially smoky barbecue smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These chips were the first we've found (along with a concurrently discovered BBQ version) that promised a two-stage taste, starting "cool and tangy" and then super-hot. We've actually noticed just this pattern in many snacks we've reviewed, but in this case it was actually the stated point of the snack.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good zesty smell, but not too different from the Cool Ranch ones.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This flavor of Doritos from Korea looked much like ordinary Doritos, with a mix of yellow and orange plus some dark spots.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Definitely a chili kick, with a sweetness that wasn't the usual. Odd but good. Honey could explain it.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Slightly cheesy, these kind of remind you of the old Doritos before they changed them to "Nacho cheesier." Not great cheese taste, but not awful either
snack_smell_test: Smell test: A spicy sort of smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Way back when in the '70s or early '80s, Doritos made regular tortilla chips.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: No discernable aroma to speak of

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Doritos from Mexico had a light red color, not really a scary red color as we've come to expect from many hot Mexican snacks, but in fairness, the color was similar to the flaming Doritos logo on the bag (the red parts of it, anyway). Speaking of which, we really liked the inferno of a Doritos logo on the bag. Putting the color aside, the "Inferno" name had us expecting some serious heat.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Kind of a vinegar-like sting on first whiff. But not really like hot sauce or anything after that.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are another new addition to the Australian Doritos line, and once again Doritos has created a good flavor.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: A cheesey, tomato aroma.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: The revival of the Doritos 3D brand continues, as after a decade of being dormant, we've seen in the span of four months first a Jalapeño Pepper Jack version and now this Bacon Cheddar Ranch one. The snacks had the same shape as the other recent one, not pillow-like like the old days, but instead in some sort of triangular pattern.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: A lot going on. There was something in addition to the taste corn smell, but with bacon, cheddar and ranch all (in theory) crammed in there, I couldn't really smell any of them.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: For years, Doritos 3D's have been one of those snacks that lots of people wanted to eat, but nobody could find them. Over a decade ago, we reviewed Zesty Ranch, Jalapeño Cheddar and Nacho Cheesier versions from the USA and a Texas Paprika flavor from the UK. Since then, we've had numerous folks reading those reviews and trying to find them, with no success.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Kind of like ranch flavor, with maybe a bit of heat too.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These Doritos from Taiwan took their enormous triangular shapes from the American "Jacked" Doritos flavor Ranch Dipped Hot Wings that we first found six years ago. They had a mustardy orange color with lots of dark spots and not much powder on the surfaces.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Wow, really does smell like grilled shrimp. Nice!

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This new size/flavor of Doritos, introduced along with the Jacked Smoky Chipotle BBQ variety, claimed to have "jacked" things to a new level of intensity.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like a mix of taco powder and regular Doritos. But more taco powder.

snack_name: Doritos Jacked Ranch Dipped Hot Wings
snack_taste_test: Taste test: It seems this new Doritos flavor was a big enough deal that Frito-Lay graced the bag with an entirely new Doritos logo, never before seen on any other flavors, nor on the Doritos website or Super Bowl ads. It didn't look like the new logo was for the entire "Jacked" sub-brand, as the two other Jacked flavors, Enchilada Supreme and Smoky Chipotle BBQ, were next to this on the shelf, with the old logo. This turned out to be a new logo for the whole Doritos brand.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good tangy ranch smell, but no heat at all.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This new one from Doritos brought not just the promise of a bold new flavor, but a new recipe for the underlying chip, as they claimed to have "Jacked" things up with a bigger and a thicker version of Doritos.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong sweet and spicy barbecue smell, very aromatic. Made my mouth water.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This new product from Doritos wasn't really a new flavor, as it was just a new name for a flavor previously sold as Test Flavor: 855. For those of us evaluating the chips, the difference was that with the previous package, we had no idea what to expect, but now we knew that these were supposed to taste like tacos, or more specifically, street tacos (whatever that means).
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong spicy taco powder seasoning.

snack_name: Doritos Jacked Test Flavor: 2653 (Chocolate Chipotle Bacon)
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This limited-edition Doritos bag hid its true flavor behind a code number, in conjunction with some contest. It was introduced alongside mystery flavors 855 (red bag) and 404 (yellow bag), bringing our Doritos review total to 106 varieties. The chips had the same oversized triangular shapes as the other Jacked flavors (Ranch Dipped Hot Wings, Smoky Chipotle BBQ and Enchilada Supreme), and the surfaces had generally a dull orange color, with some areas very dark orange. The chips had a rough texture, including some curvature and bubbles embedded inside most chips. We crunched in to find a strong, crisp crunch, with a surprisingly mild flavor. The initial taste was somewhat sweet, like maybe a mild cheese with some sweet pepper, but it was certainly not a "Jacked" level of flavoring. After that, we could taste mostly the toasted corn, which again seemed to be less than "Jacked" in flavor intensity. There was just a mild heat in the aftertaste, not much to speak of. Reasonably tasty, but there was nothing extreme here other than the very large size of the chips.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Fairly intense, like a mix of taco powder and barbecue sauce.

snack_name: Doritos Jacked Test Flavor: 404 (Caribbean Citrus Jerk)
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This mystery Doritos flavor got a number instead of a descriptive name (as did 855 with a red label and 2653 with a blue one). The choice of the number 404 was a curious one, because it immediately brought to mind the Interweb's "Not Found" error. Flavor Not Found? Snack Not Found? We don't know. What we do know is that most of our snackers found these Doritos to be quite spicy and tasty. The chips had a dull orange color generally, with some areas more of a dull-and-dark orange thanks to lots of darker seasoning powder clumped on. They were also extra-extra large as triangular tortilla chips go. We crunched in to find a strong, solid crunch with a good crispness, plus a sweet, citrusy tropical fruit taste mixed into a chili pepper flavor. The lime in particular became even more noticeable in the aftertaste, as did the heat. A reasonably hot but not scary-hot flavor, quite tasty, a great mix of spices, sweetness and lime.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mildly spicy, but also kind of citrusy.

snack_name: Doritos Jacked Test Flavor: 855 (Spicy Street Taco)
snack_taste_test: Taste test: The red label on this bag was kind of distracting, because it brought to mind the red Nacho Cheese Doritos bag every time I looked at it. But that was a red herring, because Test Flavor: 855 was supposed to be a mystery whose flavor would remain unknown until eating commenced. (The yellow 404 and blue 2653 bags didn't distract like this, as those colors aren't so closely tied to famous Doritos flavors.)
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Kind of like chili & lime chips, but with a bit of the typical Doritos smell mixed in.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Doritos from Taiwan had the same extra-large triangular shapes as the other Jacked ones, with a fairly typical Doritos light orange color.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice mild barbecue smell. Not particularly bold or spicy.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are a pretty good new flavor of Doritos.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: These smell sort of like regular Doritos, but with a bit of Jalapeño too.

snack_name: Doritos Jalapeno Cheese! Golden Toast Crackers
snack_taste_test: Taste test: When you first bite into the first cracker that you take out of the package, you get a hint of jalapeno taste, but not really jalapeno heat.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Slight jalapeno smell, to go along with cheese smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: The chips in this old-style bag from Doritos looked a lot like the Cool Ranch ones, with a light yellow color and some seasoning on the surfaces, though a close look revealed many tiny bits of black and red/orange seasoning too.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mild cheese smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: As a fan of ketchup-flavored chips, I was thrilled to see that Doritos was offering a ketchup flavor. The color of the chips was a lot like the Nacho Cheesier flavor, but maybe a bit more red, rather than orange.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells mostly like spicy, vinegary ketchup, with just a bit of corn chip smell in there too.

snack_name: Doritos Late Night All Nighter Cheeseburger
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This night-themed version of Doritos followed up the earlier Last Call Jalapeno Popper and Tacos at Midnight flavors.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like a fast-food cheeseburger, heavy on the pickle.

snack_name: Doritos Late Night Last Call Jalapeno Popper
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This bag was filled nearly to the top with lots of unbroken triangular Doritos, most with a lot of wiggle in their form. The color was generally the typical Doritos color, but there were some areas of the chips that appeared to be even oranger than usual (more of a Cheetos shade of orange than the usual Doritos orange), and there were also some tiny green spots scattered all over the surfaces.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good jalapeno smell.

snack_name: Doritos Late Night Tacos at Midnight
snack_taste_test: Taste test: I'm not sure what the Doritos folks were thinking when they named this flavor (which is just one of more than 100 flavors that we've reviewed).
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Wow, it really does smell like heavily seasoned tacos from a good taco place.

snack_name: Doritos Locos Tacos Cool Ranch Crunchy Taco
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This Taco Bell-themed flavor of Doritos (released along with a Nacho Cheese version) purported to split the bag between Cool Ranch chips and the a new "Crunchy Taco" flavor.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong taco powder smell. Couldn't notice the Cool Ranch at all.

snack_name: Doritos Locos Tacos Nacho Cheese Crunchy Taco
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This new Doritos flavor and its companion Cool Ranch version have gotten more buzz than any Doritos flavor in recent memory, much of it mocking how circularly derivative it is: A Doritos flavor based on a Taco Bell item based on a Doritos flavor. But really, it was even more derivative than that. Half of the chips in this bag were just the regular Nacho Cheese flavor, which is the most popular, most readily available of all Doritos flavors, so it seems strange to make such a big deal out of it. Two flavors in one bag isn't even a new thing for Doritos, as they were selling "Collisions" flavors that do just that for several years until recently. In fact, one of those Collisions had taco in it: Zesty Taco Chipotle Ranch. Although half of the chips in this bag featured a new "Crunchy Taco" seasoning, recent years have seen a virtual parade of other taco flavors: Late Night Tacos at Midnight, Original Taco, (Un-original?) Taco, Taco (in retro bag) and Rollitos Zesty Taco. They even previously sold Taco Bell-flavored Doritos way back around 1994 (which was unfortunately before we started reviewing Doritos flavors).
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very strong taco powder smell. Can hardly smell the nacho cheese.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Fantastic! I love them! They are just cheesy enough and just spicy enough.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong cheesy/salsa aroma.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These corn chips were pretty good but sadly paled next to the Doritos Chilli Cheese variety.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Not overpowering tomato aroma.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Not very hot at all.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Spicy hot aroma, with a hint of taco flavor smell. Kind of smells like cheese sauce that has jalepenos in it.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are a new addition to the Australian Doritos line, and they're pretty nice.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: A cheesey, salsa aroma.

snack_name: Doritos Mini 3D's Zesty Ranch Go Snacks
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are smaller triangular versions of 3D's with the same kind of ranch flavor as seen in the larger snack.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Pretty strong ranchy Dorito smell. Tingled the nose when I took a big whiff.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Much like the Taco Explosion and Cheese Explosion versions, this Doritos mix combined four different shapes of corn-based snacks, each bearing a different flavor. (And apparently, any time you devise a flavor of Doritos Mix, it has to involve something exploding!)
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice spicy spin on the standard Doritos smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This flavor of the Doritos Mix offered the same four shapes as the Taco Explosion version, but with less variety of color, as all of them were very close to the standard Doritos orange.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Seemed like more toasted corn and less cheese than the standard bag of Doritos (but still plenty of cheese).

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Frito-Lay has previously sold mixes that included Doritos, but they were under the Munchies brand, so this was the first Doritos-branded mix that we're aware of. But the fact that it promised a "Taco Explosion" was what really got me excited about it.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Cheese and mild taco smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This much-anticipated new flavor of Doritos was supposed to have a hot wasabi taste, so between the promised wasabi and the fire-breathing dragon on the bag, we were very eager to try it. The chips had a yellow-green overall color (similar to the coloration of the bag) as the yellow tortilla chips had an uneven coating of a wasabi-like green powder.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: A slightly zesty mix of spices, but no hint of heat or wasabi.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Everything that's old is new again. Maybe. After years of pushing ever-cheesier versions of Doritos under the brand name of Nacho Cheesier, there's a redesigned Doritos bag that returns to its roots as "Nacho Cheese" flavor. Does this mean we get less cheese? The bag says it's just a packaging redesign.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Somewhat cheesy tortilla chips smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: A classic corn chip brought to Australia.
snack_smell_test: Smell test:  A cheesy, tangy aroma.

snack_name: Doritos Nacho Cheese 100 Calorie Mini Bites
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are miniature versions of Doritos Nacho Cheese, the grand-daddy of all nacho cheese tortilla chips.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Each individual bag smells like a bag of Doritos, but only 100 calories worth.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: The nacho cheese chip by which all other tortilla chips are judged.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very cheesy.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: A review of this bag of Doritos from Taiwan requires some discussion of the history of the flavor.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Not the expected smell. More corn, less cheese.

snack_name: Doritos Nacho Cheesier Mini Go Snacks
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are Doritos that seem to have been shrunk down in some sort of magical shrinking machine ("Honey, I shrunk the Doritos!") Same Dorito nacho cheese taste, only in a smaller form factor.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like a bag of Doritos.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are one of the stranger snacking concepts to come along recently.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like pizza or garlic bread.

snack_name: Doritos Natural White Nacho Cheese Tortilla Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are white tortilla chips with the usual Doritos nacho cheese flavor powder on them.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: They smell like plain tortilla chips or taco shells when you open the box.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This flavor of Doritos, not to be confused with (un-original) Taco, had a slightly darker coloration than the standard Doritos, with less of the bright orange/yellow powder and a slight brownishness instead.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice mild and cheesy taco smell. Could definitely smell some sour cream in there too.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This Japanese edition of Doritos broke just about all of the rules of Doritos, as these chips came in a can rather than a bag; were squares and not triangles; were rippled; and seemed to be made from whatever substance it is that they use to make Fritos.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Not bacony in the usual sense, but bacon in its own way, thanks to the pepper. Really nice.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This variety of Doritos didn't look a whole lot different from the ordinary Nacho Cheese version, so the big issue for our tasters was definitely going to be whether the chips actually tasted like pizza.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Kind of like the spices from a pizza, but also a lot of the regular Doritos smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These tortilla looked generally like regular Doritos, with a color similar to Cool Ranch Doritos, but the shape was slightly different, as one of the three edges was rounded, giving each chip the shape of a slice of pizza.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong tangy smell, maybe like curry, but not like pizza.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Of all the many flavors of Doritos we've tried (we're talking more than 140), this one from Mexico was one of the only pizza-related ones, which include Pizza Supreme, Collisions Pizza Cravers/Ranch and Pizza-La Curry Monterey. It wasn't the first Frito-Lay tortilla chip with "Pizzerola" in the name — they had a round tortilla chip simply named Pizzerolas.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good pizza spices smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These Doritos (one of more than 100 Doritos flavors we've reviewed) had about the same color as the regular Nacho Cheese Doritos, a fairly bright shade of orange, with the addition of some tiny green specks on them. There was a definite jalapeno edge to the cheese taste, though not really much heat at first. Without even thinking about it, I ended up eating several of these Doritos in succession, and when I did that, the heat definitely grew stronger. It was not an intense, run-for-some-water type of heat, but it was still strong and did enhance the cheese flavor. The good crispness and high level of cheese was typical Doritos.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Some of the regular Doritos smell, but there was definitely some fresh jalapeno mixed in, and it made my mouth water.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These tasted like Nacho Cheesier Doritos.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: These smelled like Nacho Cheesier Doritos.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are shaped like regular Doritos, but they've got a flavor powder on them that gives the chips a darker color.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: A good, strong smell of chili, not really hot, though.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These ring-shaped snacks looked kind of like Ringolos or Hula Hoops, but they were much, much smaller.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice sweet, spicy barbecue smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Take a regular Dorito chip, roll it up (preferably when they're not hard) to make it look like a taquito, and you've pretty much got a "Rollito." As is typical with a Doritos snack, there's a ton of flavoring powder, and the Ranch is no exception.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: The always-pleasing aroma of Doritos Ranch flavoring...

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These were basically Doritos rolled up into tiny taquito-like shapes.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Kind of weak but OK.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are Doritos tortilla chips rolled up to look like a taquito (yay!).
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Slight smell of taco powder.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This "Roulette" version of Doritos from Canada added a game of chance to the act of eating the popular brand of tortilla chips. Each chip was either a regular Nacho Cheese one or a special hot and spicy flavor.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Pretty much the same as Nacho Cheese Doritos. Maybe a hint of hot peppers.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This flavor of Doritos looked mostly like the regular Nacho Cheese version, but maybe slightly redder, though not as red as the chips pictured on the bag.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: A mix of the usual Doritos smell and a bit of seta salsa. Nice.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are (or at least were) the best Doritos ever.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Not too hot, just smells like toasted corn chips.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: We've been down on Doritos before for having the "same old taste" no matter what the actual flavor.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: They still smell like every other bag of Doritos that I've ever smelled.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Doritos promised to be screamin' some major sriracha heat, a first for Doritos, but not their first recent heat attempt, as Doritos introduced both Blaze and Flamin' Hot Nacho versions earlier this year. The chips had lots of reddish brown seasoning, giving them a different look from the generally bright orange color that most Doritos flavors have.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Some spices to go along with the toasted corn, but not hot ones.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Doritos looked pretty much like the original Nacho Cheese flavor, with just about the same color of cheese spices.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like corn chips, with some extra spices.

snack_name: Doritos Smokin' Cheddar BBQ Tortilla Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: I'm a big critic of Frito-Lay for making all of their Doritos flavors taste nearly the same, with just different combinations of ingredients.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells a little like taco powder for some odd reason.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: There's no discernible difference between these and Cooler Ranch Doritos.
snack_smell_test: From the package:  “The tortilla chips so LOUD they'll break through the sound barrier! The COOL tang of sour cream blends with nacho cheese, tomato and SPICES for a creamy taste that'll send you into ORBIT!” Yeah, whatever.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This throwback flavor (and packaging) from Doritos tried to recreate a popular flavor from the early years of Doritos.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mostly the regular Doritos smell. Maybe a little oniony.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These Doritos looked much different than any others we've tried, as they had a purplish red flavor powder covering large areas of the otherwise orangeish chips.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Not really much.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: The name of these chips threw me off a bit. Spicier Nacho? Spicier than what? The good news is that they were spicier than some things, but the bad news was that the things that they were spicier than are barely spicy at all.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: There's a nice spicy kick to the cheese smell of these.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Doritos from Taiwan came in a very shiny bag with the same logo as the recent American versions (but a very different look from the Spicier Nacho! version that we reviewed many years back).
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Slightly weird cheese smell, not hot.

snack_name: Doritos Spicy Sweet Chili Tortilla Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These chips had the same shape and pretty much the same color as the ordinary Nacho Cheese Doritos.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mostly the regular Doritos smell, with something else mixed it, but whatever it was didn't smell sweet or like chili.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Wow, this snack was quite a change for Doritos.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Kind of like barbecue sauce powder.

snack_name: Doritos Stadium Nacho Inspired by EA Sports Madden NFL 11
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Doritos looked a lot like the Cool Ranch flavor in terms of color, as there was definitely less orange than we've come to expect from the Nacho Cheese flavor. But the Stadium Nacho name immediately raised the question of how these would be different from the regular Nacho Cheese — does cheese taste different just because you eat it at a stadium?
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mild cheese sauce smell, pretty good.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: We rarely buy Doritos at Costco, for two reasons. First, as with many product lines at Costco, the selection is limited — usually they have just Nacho Cheese. Been there, done that. Second, Costco only sells Doritos in monstrously ginormous bags. This one weighed 30 ounces and was almost 18 inches tall. Huge! We like Doritos just fine, but that's just way too many Doritos.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice mix of cheddar and spices, with maybe some sour cream too?

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This bag was quite a find, as it has been years since I've been able to buy a bag of taco-flavored Doritos. (Most recently, I remember eating a Taco Bell flavor of Doritos in the mid-90s.)
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Just a mild taco powder smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Having previously reviewed a confusing array of of taco-related Doritos flavors including Taco, Tacos at Midnight and Original Taco, I was glad to discover this kind in Japan. I opened the bag to find the usual Doritos look, with mostly a yellow color in this case, with none of the bright orange typical of some flavors.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Some very mild tangy smell. Not at all like the usual Doritos smell.

snack_name: Doritos Tailgater BBQ Inspired by EA Sports Madden NFL 11
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These chips (a pregame partner with the Stadium Nacho flavor in this Madden promotion) had the same color as the Nacho Cheese Doritos, and the Doritos folks were generous enough to pack a lot of chips into this smallish bag.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: On first whiff, seemed like normal Doritos, but after that I did detect some barbecue seasoning.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Having eaten countless bags of Nacho Cheese Doritos in the USA over years, we were glad to get our hands on this one from England for a chip-to-chip comparison. The end result was that there was not much of a difference.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very close to the typical Nacho Cheese Doritos smell. We did a side-by-side comparison and could smell a little less corn and more cheese with this one.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This new Doritos flavor had a light yellow color generally, with just occasional seasoning scattered on the surfaces, some of it light in color, some black.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Tangy, but less of an intense pickle smell than many other pickle snacks we've reviewed.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This new take on Doritos (released along with Tapatio versions of Fritos and Ruffles) had a slightly darker shade of orange than the ordinary Nacho Cheese Doritos but otherwise looked fairly similar. On close examination, there were some tiny dark specks of seasoning unevenly distributed over the surfaces, which seemed to account for most of the difference in color.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Kind of like regular Doritos except way more intense. On second whiff, I could smell some strong taco powder.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This Doritos flavor from Taiwan had an almost entirely yellow color, with only a hint of seasoning in places, with the usual bends in the shapes and bumps on the surfaces.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice kick of Thai spices. Zing!

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This was another "guess the mystery flavor" contest that Frito-Lay held in 2008, a follow-up to 2007's Doritos X-13D, and it's just one of the 110 kinds of Doritos that we've reviewed.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: They smell more like Fritos than Doritos.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Long before Doritos started to add flavor powder to every tortilla chip they produce, they had a tortilla chip that was just plain.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like a box of taco shells.

snack_name: Doritos Tortilla Chips Taco Flavor (retro bag)
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This was certainly the most confusing bag of Doritos ever. It was a retro bag using a design from the 1960s or 70s — that much makes sense to me — but beyond that, things get very hazy.
snack_smell_test: From the package:  “Celebrate Legends Then & Now”

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These Doritos had a dirty yellow color generally, with the usual corn-related black spots, plus a light smattering of dark seasoning bits of various colors (but mostly green).
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Definitely some lime kick, like lime and hot sauce.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This new Doritos flavor jumped out as an oddity, because we've seen (and indeed eaten) it before. The story begins with the Blaze flavor that appeared in early 2018. This hot flavor was followed late in the same year by a Collisions version that combined Blaze with Ultimate Cheddar. That's where it got weird — at the time, there was no such flavor as Ultimate Cheddar, at least as a stand-alone flavor. It's hard to judge individual flavors in bags of Collisions, because some of the flavor rubs off on the other chips. But now — for a "Limited Time Only" — they're selling the Ultimate Cheddar in its own bag. Beyond the words Ultimate Cheddar, there was no marketing copy to explain what it meant.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice tangy cheese smell. Not all that different from Nacho Cheese.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This mysterious new Doritos flavor from Canada was hard to categorize.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells kind of like the usual Doritos, but with the addition of some sweet pepper or pickle or something I can't quite place.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This wasn't the first wasabi version of Doritos we've tried (that distinction goes to Mr. Dragon's Fire Chips) but it was a standout in several ways.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Kind of like ranch chips.

snack_name: Doritos Wild White Nacho Tortilla Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This snack helps prove my theory that all Doritos pretty much taste the same.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: smells like corn

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This new Doritos variety is part of a Frito-Lay promotion that lets customers come up with a name for the flavor.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: They smell a bit like dill pickles, oddly enough.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These Doritos from Canada had the usual Doritos shape and a light orange/yellow color, with a promise of "Zesty Cheese" as distinct from the more standard Nacho Cheese. The surfaces had more bubbles embedded inside than we're accustomed to from Doritos.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Like Nacho Cheese Doritos, but even stronger.

snack_name: Go Snacks Doritos Mini 3D's Nacho Cheesier
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are miniature versions of the 3D Nacho Cheesier snacks, there's a good amount of nacho cheese on each piece (very triangular, in fact), but not enough where you're going to get a lot of residue on your fingers.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: A slight cheese odor/aroma.

snack_name: Munchies Sandwich Crackers Jalapeño Cheddar Doritos
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These crackers followed the standard formula for six square cracker sandwiches in a cellophane wrapper. The crackers had a very pale beige color, and the filling looked like Cheese Whiz, with a very strong orange color.
snack_smell_test: Smell test:  Can smell a bit of the zesty cheddar.

snack_name: Simply Organic Doritos Spicy White Cheddar
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Doritos looked much like the numerous non-organic flavors, with large, triangular shapes that included lots of bumps, bends and bubbles, and they had a light orange color generally, with quite a few dark spots on each piece, plus a light smattering of generally orange seasoning powder.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice kick to this cheese smell, really zippy!

snack_name: Simply Organic Doritos White Cheddar Tortilla Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: Normally I wouldn't seek out a new chip just simply because it's organic, but when I heard that there was an organic version of Doritos, I did just that. The bag itself was a bit confusing, as it claimed a White Cheddar flavor, but the chips pictured on it were quite orange. I opened it to find that the actual color was much more yellow and less orange color in the picture. Still, they didn't look white or close to it. I could see that slightest amount of red powder on some of the chips, but nothing in terms of very pale yellow or close to white seasoning. There were many black spots on the chips. They had the usual triangular Doritos shapes.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: More like tortilla chips than the usual very cheesy Doritos, but some cheese in there too.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This is one of those snacks that I used to eat all the time as a kid but hadn't eaten in years. It was actually a bit different, as it used to be a Drake's product (not "Drake's by Hostess") and it was a two-pack of Coffee Cake Jr. rather than one larger Coffee Cake.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Wow, really nice.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: I've never been a huge fan of Devil Dogs. That's not to say that I wouldn't eat one if given the opportunity, but they're just a bit on the dry side as snack cakes go. That's why this new product intrigued me: It appeared they took a standard Devil Dog (which consists of a creme filling between two dry-ish pieces of chocolate cake) and coated it in chocolate. And that's pretty much just what they did.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good chocolate smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These snacks were shaped kind of like Twinkies, but they were smaller, had chocolate cake instead of yellow cake, had peanut butter creme filling instead of white filling and were coated in milk chocolate. They came two to a pack, with five packs in the box.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: More peanut butter than chocolate, really good.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This new knockoff of Twinkies from Drake's weighed in at 1.5 oz per piece, slightly more than the revived Twinkies brand with its 1.358-oz. cakes. Our first impression of these was based on the excellent "Zoinks!" name alone, which we assume they took from the favorite expression of Shaggy Rogers from Scooby Doo (despite the lack of anything Scooby or Shaggy-related on the box). The taste was pretty much the same as Twinkies, quite good. The texture was nice too, spongy and soft with a good amount of creme. The balance of creme filling to cake seemed to be a bit more on the cake side with Zoinks vs. Twinkies, but it was still just fine with us.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice, sweet and creamy without being too sweet.

snack_name: Dunkin' Donuts Coffee Thins Original Blend
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This small, square, thin chocolate bar had a flat bottom, a ridge around the top edges and some diagonal lines running across the flat top. I bit in to find a soft feel and a nice mix of milk chocolate and coffee. Very smooth and creamy, I liked this one a lot.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mild coffee smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Not long after Pop-Tarts rolled out two Dunkin' Donuts flavors (Frosted Chocolate Mocha and Vanilla Latte), these coffee-themed Oreos promised to deliver the flavor of a mocha beverage from Dunkin' Donuts in Oreo form. Each sandwich appeared to have the same chocolate cookies as the regular Oreos, but their filling was a very light brown rather than the usual white. The cookies had standard Oreo markings — no Dunkin' Donuts logo or anything.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like regular Oreos. Couldn't notice any coffee.

snack_name: Pop-Tarts Dunkin' Donuts Frosted Chocolate Mocha
snack_taste_test: Taste test: I'm reviewing this Dunkin' Donuts co-branded version of Pop-Tarts (as well as the Vanilla Latte flavor) from the point of view of someone who loves the smell of coffee and enjoys various coffee-related foods such as coffee ice cream — but doesn't actually drink coffee. For the review, I tried one Pop-Tart right out of the package, then a second one toasted.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Fairly mild mocha smell.

snack_name: Pop-Tarts Dunkin' Donuts Frosted Vanilla Latte
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This Dunkin' Donuts-themed version of Pop-Tarts was released alongside a Chocolate Mocha one. Keep in mind when reading this review, I don't drink coffee, but I do like the taste of many coffee-flavored non-coffee things.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good coffee smell, slightly creamy.

snack_name: Famous Amos Bite Size Chocolate Chip Cookies
