snack_taste_test: Taste test: These small cookies were just about perfectly round and about an inch and a half in diameter.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very good chocolate chip cookie smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These Cheetos had an impressively bright glow from the red flavor powder on them.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Not much. Not like a cheese puff or hot sauce.

snack_name: Cheetos Bag of Bones Flamin' Hot
snack_taste_test: Taste test: It's that time of year when many snacks appear on store shelves with special features for Halloween, and we're glad that Cheetos chief Chester Cheetah is playing the game. This one took the white cheddar version of Bag of Bones that we've seen in past years and swapped out the seasoning for the Flamin' Hot stuff. They kept the same four shapes — skull, ribs, bone and hand/foot — and loaded lots of the dark red Flamin' Hot onto it.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Pretty mild. Can't really smell this particular heat.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are good hot crunchy snacks, with the same shapes as the regular Crunchy Cheetos but a more intense look.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: A nice but not overpowering hot and spicy cheesy smell.

snack_name: Cheetos Crunchy Flamin' Hot Chipotle Ranch
snack_taste_test: Taste test: With 87 varieties of Cheetos reviewed so far, this one stood out for being a rare one that tried to alter the basic Flamin' Hot flavor, and also for having such a long flavor name.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Not particularly hot, but I could notice a hint of ranch among the cheese and peppers.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These were a bit strange.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Just slightly limey smell, not strong.

snack_name: Cheetos Flamin' Hot Brand Flavor Filling on Cheese Flavored Crackers
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This package contained six square cracker sandwiches, orange crackers with a red filling.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very strong Cheez Whiz sort of smell, but not really any heat.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This new version of Cheetos piled on some major hype for its heat level, claiming to be not just the hottest type of Cheetos ever, but the hottest of any Frito-Lay product in the United States. The puffs had a very bright, intense red seasoning on their surfaces, and they were shaped like some sort of short, stubby chili peppers — though neither the bag's marketing copy nor the Ingredients identified which particular pepper(s) powered the heat.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Cheesy smell, but not hot at all, didn't make my mouth water.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Flamin' Hot Cheetos from China had similar shapes to the American Flamin' Hot Crunchy Cheetos but a much lighter color, with a light orange overall look punctuated by some sparse darker seasoning bits.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Just mildly tangy.

snack_name: Cheetos Flavor Shots Flamin' Hot Asteroids
snack_taste_test: Taste test: Years ago, Frito-Lay had a whole line of Go Snacks in cans, designed to fit in your car's cup holder and then be poured directly into your mouth, including a Flamin' Hot Cheetos version. They stopped selling all of them. Now the Cheetos ones are back, but in a narrow, vertical bag instead of a can.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Not much at all. Definitely nothing hot.

snack_name: Cheetos Mix-Ups Flamin' Hot & Cheezy Mix
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This latest addition the the Cheetos Mix-Ups line had the same four shapes of Cheetos as the Cheezy Salsa and Xtra Cheezy versions, with a different lineup of flavors. Two of the four were standard-issue Cheetos that can be purchased separately — Flamin' Hot Curls and Cheddar Puffs — while the other two were newly created flavor/shape combinations just for this mix: Double Cheddar Mini Puffs and Jalapeño Cheddar Grids.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good cheddar smell, but not much in the way of heat.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This popcorn, much like the cheddar flavor of Cheetos Popcorn, seemed to signal a transition of non-cheese puff cheese products from the Chester's brand to the Cheetos brand, which also happens to have Chester Cheetah as its mascot.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice cheese smell, but couldn't really smell the heat.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Cheetos Puffs had the usual shape but a much different color, as the seasoning was a deep, bright shade of dark red.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Not really cheesy, but not hot either. sneers sort of like tomato sauce.

snack_name: Cheetos Xxtra Flamin' Hot Asteroids Go Snacks
snack_taste_test: Taste test: We've reviewed more than 80 kinds of Cheetos, but for this one, Chester Cheetah went to a new level of danger, adding something "Xxtra" to the previous generation of Flamin' Hot Asteroids. (There's also a corresponding crunchy curl with the same Xxtra Hot flavor.)
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Not much, and definitely no heat in the smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These crunchy cheese curls should not be confused with the regular Cheetos Flamin' Hot, as they lived up to their name by being a scarier color (deep red, rather than orange-red) and impressively hotter. The curls were tasty and pretty hot upon biting in, and they kept getting hotter as I ate more, which I kept doing in between sips of lemonade. The lemonade was able to temper the heat only temporarily, so the increasingly hot aftertaste quickly came back in full force.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Kind of tangy but not actually hot.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are pretty hot and taste good.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Not too strong — a pleasant, cheesy aroma.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This is good, crisp popcorn with a tasty and pretty hot flavoring.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These corn puffs had sort of a popcorn-like shape (except bigger than any actual popcorn kernels) and were mostly covered with a seriously red seasoning powder.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Sort of buttery or cheddary. Not hot.

snack_name: Doritos Dinamita Chile Limón/Cheetos Flamin' Hot
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This was a groundbreaking snack, as it was the first attempt we've seen to package Cheetos and Doritos together exclusively in the same bag. (They've been together before, along with other snacks, in bags of Munchies.)
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Not much.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: A year after adding Flamin' Hot Nacho to the vast array of Doritos flavors, we found this generally similar-looking bag. The Dorito pictured on front was still very much on fire, but the majority of the bag changed from red to green, and there was a slice of lime next to that burning Dorito.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong kick of hot spices, just a little lime.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Doritos had the same intensely red seasoning powder that we've seen in other Flamin' Hot flavors from Frito-Lay, definitely more red and less orange than Nacho Cheese Doritos.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice cheese and corn smell, but not actually hot.

snack_name: Doritos Flavor Shots Flamin' Hot Nacho
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This bag had corn starch-coated peanuts, much like the Nacho Cheese Nuts Flavor Shots, but this time they promised a flavoring that corresponded to these Doritos chips.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mostly like peanuts, the hot stuff did not dominate.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These Fritos had a very nearly uniform dark red color, much redder than the Fritos pictured on the bag.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Different from regular Fritos, as you could smell some hot sauce.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Funyuns had lots of dark red seasoning on the otherwise yellow rings, and though some rings were redder than others, all had a pretty good helping of the special flavor powder.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Sweet onion smell, not actually hot.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This new shape of Cheetos bag (about 3 inches high by 8 inches wide, with openings at the sides) brought the shape of the regular Giant Cheetos (the world's largest Cheetos) and combined it with the spices from Flamin' Hot Crunchy Cheetos.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Barely any.

snack_name: Go Snacks Cheetos Asteroids Flamin' Hot
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These hot cheese balls used to be sold in cans like this, and Frito-Lay has announced they're coming back in bags under the Flavor Shots brand.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Not much.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These were pretty hot potato chips.
snack_smell_test: From the package:  “Get ready for a sizzle of a flavor that will set your mouth on fire. Dive into a red hot blaze of fiery crunch with LAYS® brand Flamin'® Hot Flavor Potato Chips”

snack_name: Lay's Flamin' Hot Dill Pickle Remix
snack_taste_test: Taste test: We've reviewed lots of hot pepper chips as well as a whole bunch of pickle-flavored ones, but ones that combine both flavors are pretty rare — and usually confined to Chicago-area potato chip brands such as Jays. Now Lay's has brought the idea national.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Wow, lots of intense pickle! Couldn't really notice the Flamin' Hot aspect.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: For years, on and off, there was a Flamin' Hot version of Lay's, and now they've brought the flavor to the crunchier Kettle Cooked chips. The chips had wiggly shapes with lots of bubbles embedded inside, with various levels of reddish orange seasoning, allowing select areas of the paler yellow chip surfaces to show through.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Just mildly hot, can smell the potato too.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This flavor of Stax promised to bring an extra-big hit of heat to the Pringles-like crisps from Lay's — not just Flamin' Hot, but Xtra Flamin' Hot! It seems like they skipped a step here, because although we've seen over a dozen Flamin' Hot varieties from Frito-Lay, we never tried a (not Xtra) Flamin' Hot Stax. (We have reviewed a Flamin' Hot Lay's, non-Stax, non-Xtra. We've also seen the "Xtra" flavor in two kinds of Cheetos, but they spelled it "Xxtra" in those cases: Crunchy Curls and Asteroids.)
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Slightly tangy, but nothing at all hot about it.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These corn (maize) snacks, molded into the shape of a monster's foot, had a pickle flavor with some spicy heat.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Sort of a pickled onion smell.

snack_name: Munchies Baked Snack Crackers Flamin' Hot
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This flavor of the Munchies crackers had the same odd shapes as the two other flavors (one sort of triangular and two not quite rectangular) with what looked like a light coating of Frito-Lay's standard dark red Flamin' Hot seasoning. The crackers weren't as red as they looked in the picture, as there was more of a mix of light orange from the cracker and red from the seasoning.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Kind of a hot sauce-like smell, but not actually hot.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This mix combined four different Frito-Lay snacks (Mini Doritos, Cheetos, Rold Gold pretzels and Sun Chips) with various hot seasonings, and the result was quite good.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: A good hot sauce smell, makes your mouth water.

snack_name: Rold Gold Thin Crisps Flamin' Hot
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Rold Gold Thin Crisps brought the same thin, double knot-shaped pretzels as the other flavors, but with the Flamin' Hot flavor that's been featured frequently on many other Frito-Lay brands but never before on a pretzel. The surfaces had a whole lot of intense red powder, somewhat unevenly distributed.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: A bit of a tangy smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Frito-Lay has sporadically offered the Flamin' Hot flavor across many of its brands for as long as we've been reviewing snacks — including Lay's, Fritos, Chester's Fries, Munchies, Fritos, Stax Xtra Hot, Funyuns and Chester's Puffcorn, plus a whole array of Cheetos variations: Crunchy, Xxtra Flamin' Hot Crunchy, Puffs,  Giant, Baked, Asteroids, Xxtra Hot Asteroids, Bag of Bones, Crunchy with Limón and Cracker Sandwiches — but this is the first time we've seen the flavor under the Ruffles banner.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: No heat or anything really that I could smell from the hot sauce. Just potato mainly.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips had lots of intense red seasoning (much more red and much more intense than the two chips pictured on the front of the bag) so they really looked hot.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice spicy cheese smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips from Mexico promised to go behind merely Flamin' Hot, to an Xtra level. They certainly looked the part, as there was lots of intense orange-red seasoning all over the surfaces, with just occasional glimpses of the pale yellow potato showing through.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Really hit me in the face on first whiff, then reminded me of Louisiana Hot Sauce.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: When it comes to Flamin' Hot-branded stuff, the first thing that comes to mind is Cheetos, which after years of offering Flamin' Hot expanded the line to include Xxtra Flamin' Hot, available in their spiciest markets.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice tangy smell, not noticeably hot, though.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: I liked these a lot.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Just slightly tangy.

snack_name: Flat Earth Baked Veggie Crisps Farmland Cheddar
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These square crisps had a bright yellow-orange color, with very thin ripples running diagonally across each crisp.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good, sort of sweet cheddar smell.

snack_name: Flat Earth Baked Veggie Crisps Peach Mango Paradise
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These square crisps had lots of seasoning on them, and unfortunately, the seasoning tasted very strongly of peach and mango.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong smell of peach and mango, almost as strong as the actual fruits.

snack_name: Flat Earth Baked Veggie Crisps Tangy Tomato Ranch
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These square, wiggly crisps had very narrow diagonal ripples and a bright orange color, with lots of flavor seasoning visible, including some green bits of parsley.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice creamy tomato smell, like a tomato bisque soup.

snack_name: Flat Earth Baked Veggie Crisps Wild Berry Patch
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These crisps were square in shape with a light purplish color, and most had some curve to them.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong smell of berries, pretty good.

snack_name: Cheetos Flavor Shots Cheddar Jalapeño Asteroids
snack_taste_test: Taste test: After considerable hype surrounding the  Flamin' Hot Asteroids Flavor Shots (and then months of searching just to find a bag to review), this jalapeño variation managed to fly under the radar. I hadn't heard a peep about it when I spotted this bag in the snack aisle.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Pretty intense spicy cheese smell.

snack_name: Cheetos Flavor Shots Flamin' Hot Asteroids
snack_taste_test: Taste test: Years ago, Frito-Lay had a whole line of Go Snacks in cans, designed to fit in your car's cup holder and then be poured directly into your mouth, including a Flamin' Hot Cheetos version. They stopped selling all of them. Now the Cheetos ones are back, but in a narrow, vertical bag instead of a can.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Not much at all. Definitely nothing hot.

snack_name: Doritos Flavor Shots Atomic Chile Limón
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Doritos Flavor Shots included a bag of Nacho Cheese Doritos and a packet of Atomic Chile Limón flavor for spicing up the chips.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: After I mixed in the packet, a fairly typical chile a lime chips smell.

snack_name: Doritos Flavor Shots Blazin' Buffalo Rush
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This creation from the Snack Strong Productions division at Doritos had the same chips as Nacho Cheese Doritos but included a Blazin' Buffalo Rush flavor packet to let snackers spice things up.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Regular Doritos smell when I opened the bag (but not the flavor packet).

snack_name: Doritos Flavor Shots Fiery Habanero Triangles
snack_taste_test: Taste test: We've seen the name Doritos Flavor Shots before — twice, in fact, in the form of tortilla chips bearing the usual Doritos shapes, with an extra packet of add-your-own flavoring powder of the Blazin' Buffalo Rush or Atomic Chile Limon  variety — but these were not like those at all.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mostly like Fritos, with some mild spices, but not notably hot or zesty.

snack_name: Doritos Flavor Shots Flamin' Hot Nacho
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This bag had corn starch-coated peanuts, much like the Nacho Cheese Nuts Flavor Shots, but this time they promised a flavoring that corresponded to these Doritos chips.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mostly like peanuts, the hot stuff did not dominate.

snack_name: Doritos Flavor Shots Nacho Cheese Nuts
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This latest in the Flavor Shots line was basically corn starch-coated peanuts with nacho cheese seasoning, so not tortilla chips, despite the Doritos name. It sounded a lot like Doritos Crunch Nuts, except in a narrow bag instead of a weird box.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mostly like peanuts, but I could detect some tangy cheese seasoning.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Frit-os from Mexico had not just an extra hyphen in the middle of the name, but also lots of extra dark seasoning powder all over the surfaces. The shapes were a bit different from regular Fritos, with a similar type of curviness but more variation in widths and lengths.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mildly spicy, nice. Way different from regular Fritos.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These Fritos from Mexico were a bit wider and generally shorter than the conventional Fritos but had similar curly shapes, plus much darker surfaces, thanks to a good helping of dark orange seasoning. The colors of the actual Frit-os were much darker than the ones pictured on the bag.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice rich chile pepper smell with a hint of lime, but not really hot.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These Frit-os from Mexico had the shape wide shapes as the other Mexican flavors, with a color much like the familiar American ones.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Different from regular Fritos, but I couldn't really smell the lime.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This special edition bag of Fritos had the same Fritos as the regular bags, which is to say they were salty, a little greasy, and quite tasty.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong corn chips smell.

snack_name: Fritos Chili Cheese Flavored Corn Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are pretty good, but nothing spectacular.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like chili powder. Not bad.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: It's rare to get a new flavor from Fritos, so I was pretty excited when I spotted this one in the chip aisle. I opened the bag to find that the chips had the expected Fritos shapes, but also noticeable was a light smattering of small green and red seasoning bits.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mostly like regular Fritos. Just a slight hit of ranch seasoning.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These Fritos had a very nearly uniform dark red color, much redder than the Fritos pictured on the bag.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Different from regular Fritos, as you could smell some hot sauce.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Formula: Take Twisty Fritos corn chips, add the flavoring from Nacho Cheese Doritos and Cooler Ranch Doritos.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: They smell like either Doritos or Fritos, depending on your nose that day.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are pretty good.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: A little bit of cheddar, barely any jalepeno smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: For a company that has cranked out over 100 varieties each of Doritos and Lay's, Frito-Lay has been much more reserved in making different kinds of Fritos (just 17 as of this writing), so we were really thrilled when one of our teams of chip hunters returned from Canada with this bag in hand.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very mild barbecue smell mixed into the usual Fritos, but pretty good.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These flavored Fritos were OK, as they had a mild enough level of lime and chile flavoring that you could still taste the Fritos, and far less of that flavoring than some other lime and chile-flavored snacks.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mostly like regular Fritos, but there is a very slight lime and chile smell too. These smell better than regular Fritos.

snack_name: Fritos Matutano Tiras de Maíz Barbacoa
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are the Spanish version of everybody's favorite all-American corn chip, Fritos.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: A different aroma than the usual Fritos aroma, not really barbecue-like, but not bad.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: The chips in special version of Fritos didn't look a whole lot different from regular Fritos, as the jalapeno seasoning wasn't visually evident on the surface of the chips and the color was standard Fritos. But when I bit in, I was thrilled with how tasty they were. The jalapeno flavor mixed extremely well with the taste of the Fritos and gave these a fairly hot and extremely delicious flavor. Wow. Just great.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: You can smell the regular Fritos, but there is definitely a spicy jalapeno kick as well.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Fritos are the standard by which all corn chips are judged.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: The standard Fritos smell: greasy, corny, salty.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Pretty gross.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Pretty good barbecue smell, but still corn chippy. We smelled the bag again almost two years later (we got the bag in 1998), and now it smells really like bad paint.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: They're more lime-ey than chile-ey.
snack_smell_test: From the package:  “Introducing Fritos® brand Lime & Chile Flavored Corn Chips. We took the familiar hearty corn crunch of Fritos® brand and added an aromatic combination of the flavors of pepper and a bit of lime to give you an explosive blend your mouth just can't get enough of!”

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are just like regular Fritos, except that they're bigger and come in a can.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Regular corn chips aroma

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This new version of Fritos promised the extra-large shapes of the longstanding Fritos Scoops and the flavor of the more recent Jalapeño Fritos. (Speaking of recent, we found this bag in 2019 and don't remember seeing these before, but oddly, it had a 2004 copyright on the back.)
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Kind of sweet, but not really spicy or jalapeño-like.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These Fritos had a light orange-colored seasoning on them that tasted like a very mild barbecue flavor at first, and then tasted very distinctly of lime in the afteratste.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like regular Fritos with a hint of barbecue seasoning.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This hot sauce-branded version Fritos had the spiral shapes of Fritos Flavor Twists and some orange Tapatío hot sauce flavor powder.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mostly like Fritos, but a hint of hot sauce.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These corn chips are about twice as wide as your standard Fritos, and they're generally less curvy in shape.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice barbecue aroma.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are thicker-cut Fritos with a wavy design.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: No particular aroma.

snack_name: Go Snacks Fritos Flavor Twists Honey BBQ
snack_taste_test: Taste test: I've never been a big fan of putting flavor onto a corn chip, because you have to have a lot of flavor on the chip to overpower the taste of the corn chip.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like some barbecue sauce.

snack_name: Go Snacks Fritos Hoops Honey BBQ Flavored
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are made from the same basic materials as Fritos chips, except that they're shaped like rings instead of chips — sort of like the potato-based Ringolos or Hula Hoops, except that these are rougher around the edges than those, and these have more irregular shapes.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: More of a hot barbecue-type smell than honey barbecue, but not actually a hot smell (it won't make your mouth water).

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This snack mix combined Rancheritos, Sabritones, Cheetos cheese balls and four different kinds of Frit-os in one bag.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very mild chili-lime smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This bar was basically a whole lot of Froot Loops glued together by something sugary and formed into a bar, with a white sugary coating on the bottom of the bar.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Not really like Froot Loops.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This variation of the delicious Froot Loops cereal transforms them into a whole new shape, as they're shaped like straws that are both drinkable and edible. So you can drink some milk through the straw, in theory flavoring the milk as you drink, and then eat the actual straws.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like Froot Loops.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Taquitos.net is not in the cereal review business because, frankly, keeping track of the latest snacks keeps us busy enough. But we've reviewed lots of snacks made with cereal, and this version of Froot Loops was very explicitly formulated and packaged as a snacking version of the delicious cereal.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Same great smell as regular Froot Loops. Love it.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: After deeply disappointing us with a weird use of the treasured Froot Loops brand by creating Froot Loops Numbers, Toucan Sam is back for more gummies with these Letters. As with the others, they were not shaped like Froot Loops. Instead, they were shaped like capital letters of the alphabet. And the overall shapes of the gummies were not even really like those letters; they were shaped like blocks of gummy with the actually letters on top. The holes and other openings did not all the way through. So in many cases you had to look carefully to even identify the letters. (Even the letter O didn't look anything like a Froot Loop.)
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Typical fruit gummy smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: As someone capable of eating vast quantities of Froot Loops cereal in one sitting, I was excited to see that Froot Loops (which has also made cereal straws and cereal bars) has gotten into the gummy game. The box contained 10 individually wrapped packets, and each contained an assortment of about nine gummies shaped liked three-dimensional versions of various Arabic numerals. That was the odd part here: Branded as Froot Loops, but not shaped like loops. The digit shapes did distinguish them from all of the other gummy candies we've tried, but giving the Froot Loops gummies shapes that had nothing to do with Froot Loops was the biggest miss in gummy design since The Simpsons Fruit Snacks, which were shaped like various fruits rather than various Simpsons.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Pretty typical fruit gummy smell. Kind of like grape juice.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These's something about the taste of Froot Loops that has always been irresistible to me. I don't stock much cereal in my kitchen, but on the rare occasions when I buy some Froot Loops, the box gets emptied very quickly, with bowls consumed at many meals that aren't breakfast (not to mention snacktime). Thus, I couldn't resist trying a Froot Loops-flavored Pop-Tart.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Yes, smells like Froot Loops! (But mild.)

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These taste just like Froot Loops.
snack_smell_test: From the package:  “Super Sized Bites with Deliciously Intense Natural Fruit Flavors” ... “Flavor Bursting!”

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Robust onion flavor, but not overpowering.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very weak onion smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This new flavor of Funyuns was quite an important discovery, because we don't come across new Funyuns flavors every day, or even every year. For Frito-Lay's other major brands, new flavors are a bit more routine — we've reviewed more than 100 kinds of Doritos and 70+ Cheetos — but Funyuns had to this point been limited to just original, Flamin' Hot and wasabi.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mild chile and lime smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Funyuns had lots of dark red seasoning on the otherwise yellow rings, and though some rings were redder than others, all had a pretty good helping of the special flavor powder.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Sweet onion smell, not actually hot.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: More than a year after our last new Funyuns flavor discovery, finally another ... for a grand total of five. Still the lowest total of all major Frito-Lay brands.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Sweet onion smell, definitely different than standard Funyuns.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This new variation on the old standby Funyns indeed had some wasabi flavor, but it was more like a hint of wasabi. The taste was not as vinegary as the smell. The overall taste was less oniony than a regular Funyun, with a little bit of a bite, but not something where your head will explode.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Vinegary smell, not like wasabi.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are miniature Funyuns in a smaller ring-sized shape.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: A not too strong onion aroma.

snack_name: Cheetos Xxtra Flamin' Hot Asteroids Go Snacks
snack_taste_test: Taste test: We've reviewed more than 80 kinds of Cheetos, but for this one, Chester Cheetah went to a new level of danger, adding something "Xxtra" to the previous generation of Flamin' Hot Asteroids. (There's also a corresponding crunchy curl with the same Xxtra Hot flavor.)
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Not much, and definitely no heat in the smell.

snack_name: Doritos Cooler Ranch Mini Go Snacks
snack_taste_test: Taste test: Recently called 'The Mack Daddy of all Snacks' by our friends at the Phantom Gourmet, Cooler Ranch Doritos recently shrunk in size to fit into a can! Even though they're smaller, you can't tell the difference, and you can use the top as a cup can.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: They smell like every other bag of Doritos on the planet.

snack_name: Doritos Mini 3D's Zesty Ranch Go Snacks
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are smaller triangular versions of 3D's with the same kind of ranch flavor as seen in the larger snack.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Pretty strong ranchy Dorito smell. Tingled the nose when I took a big whiff.

snack_name: Doritos Nacho Cheesier Mini Go Snacks
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are Doritos that seem to have been shrunk down in some sort of magical shrinking machine ("Honey, I shrunk the Doritos!") Same Dorito nacho cheese taste, only in a smaller form factor.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like a bag of Doritos.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are miniature cheese balls, very small in fact. They remind me of the Planters Cheez Balls. These are smaller, with a good cheese taste, but you'll still get orange residue on your fingers. Be careful out there!
snack_smell_test: Smell test: The Cheetos smell we all love and adore.

snack_name: Go Snacks Cheetos Asteroids Flamin' Hot
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These hot cheese balls used to be sold in cans like this, and Frito-Lay has announced they're coming back in bags under the Flavor Shots brand.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Not much.

snack_name: Go Snacks Doritos Mini 3D's Nacho Cheesier
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are miniature versions of the 3D Nacho Cheesier snacks, there's a good amount of nacho cheese on each piece (very triangular, in fact), but not enough where you're going to get a lot of residue on your fingers.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: A slight cheese odor/aroma.

snack_name: Go Snacks Fritos Flavor Twists Honey BBQ
snack_taste_test: Taste test: I've never been a big fan of putting flavor onto a corn chip, because you have to have a lot of flavor on the chip to overpower the taste of the corn chip.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like some barbecue sauce.

snack_name: Go Snacks Fritos Hoops Honey BBQ Flavored
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are made from the same basic materials as Fritos chips, except that they're shaped like rings instead of chips — sort of like the potato-based Ringolos or Hula Hoops, except that these are rougher around the edges than those, and these have more irregular shapes.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: More of a hot barbecue-type smell than honey barbecue, but not actually a hot smell (it won't make your mouth water).

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are miniature Funyuns in a smaller ring-sized shape.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: A not too strong onion aroma.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are all mini versions of a party mix favorite, including mini Cheetos, Funyuns, Doritos and Pretzels.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like Doritos.

snack_name: Go Snacks Tostitos Mini Size Rounds Hint Of Lime
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are small, round, thin tortilla chips that come in a can.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like tortilla chips.

snack_name: Lay's Go Snacks Crisps Sour Cream & Onion
snack_taste_test: Taste test: Oh my God these are incredible! These are crisp-like snacks with a great Sour Cream & Onion flavor.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: A pretty good aroma that kind of smelled like sour cream.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are like Jax, but they're less curly.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like corn, only mildly cheesy.

snack_name: Golden Flake Cheeseburger Flavored Potato Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These things taste just like a McDonald's cheeseburger.
snack_smell_test: From the package:  “Taste the Fun!” ... “Golden Flake products are made fresh daily in our plants located in Birmingham, Alabama, Ocala, Florida and Nashville, Tennessee.” ... “Open a package of Golden Flake Potato Chips and you get the light, fresh, crisp flavor that makes Golden Flake the choice of people all over the South. Our commitment to quality and our use of only the purest, lightest, freshest ingredients are our promise of satisfaction in any Golden Flake product you try.”

snack_name: Golden Flake Crisp & Crunchy Cheese Curls
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are good cheese curls, with a lot of crunch and a decent amount of cheese flavor.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice, cheesy but not too cheesy.

snack_name: Golden Flake Dill Pickle Thin & Crispy Potato Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are good pickle chips.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Vinegary, medium strength

snack_name: Golden Flake Dip Style Cheddar & Sour Cream Potato Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These narrow-rippled potato chips had a light orange color overall, and we could see lots of orange seasoning in between the ripples, with a good helping of potato skin around the edges of some chips.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Fairly strong cheddar smell.

snack_name: Golden Flake Dip Style Southern Heat Potato Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These narrow-rippled potato chips had just a bit of orange seasoning with some small black specks too, plus some bits of potato skin around the edges. They looked quite different from the heavily orange chips pictured on the bag.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Wow, definitely smells like hot sauce.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are pretty good hot chips, with a nice taste.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: A mildly hot smell.

snack_name: Golden Flake Sweet Heat Barbecue Thick & Crispy  Potato Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are good sweet barbecue chips.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: A mild, sweet barbecue aroma.

snack_name: Golden Fluff Potato Stix Honey BBQ Flavor
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These Passover-certified potato sticks had the standard range of shapes, with a light orange seasoning that was applied evenly across the surfaces.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Couldn't really smell the BBQ, just the potato.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These triangular tortilla chips were similar to Doritos, but the chips were generally flatter than Doritos, with very little or no curl in most of the chips.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very mild nacho cheese smell.

snack_name: Mrs. B's Southern Style Cajun Hot Potato Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These wide-rippled chips have a bright orange seasoning on them and a tasty, hot flavor that grows on you as you eat more chips.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice cajun spicy aroma.

snack_name: Mrs. B's Southern Style Deli Ranch Potato Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are good wide-rippled ranch chips.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells mostly like potato chips, with a very mild ranch aroma.

snack_name: Mrs. B's Southern Style Potato Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are wide-rippled potato chips.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Regular potato chips smell, a bit salty and oily.

snack_name: Tortiyahs! Superior Dipping Chips Sea Salt
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These large, quarter-circle tortilla chips had a pale beige color and somewhat curvy shapes, so they looked like fairly typical tortilla chips But I found this appearance surprising, given the emphasis on dipping in the marketing copy on the bag. They didn't have scoop shapes like Tostitos Dippers or other dipping-optimized chips.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong corn tortilla smell. Intense.

snack_name: Flavor Blasted Goldfish Blazin' Buffalo Wing
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Goldfish had the same orange shape and same base color as regular goldflish, but most of the pieces had some isolated splotches of a darker red.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Sort of a creamy, maybe just slightly spicy cheese smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are a good variation on the standard goldfish, with taco powder added to the taste.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Sort of like Tabasco, but weak.

snack_name: Flavor Blasted Goldfish Wild White Cheddar
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are a lot like the Goldfish that come in those bags, except that these come in a milk carton.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Not too strong (but it's hard to tell when you're trying to take a whiff through the top of a milk carton).

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Every time I hear the name of these, I just think "exploding pizza!" and wonder what it would be like if there actually were exploding pizzas, whether that could be a dangerous thing, and how messy it would be to clean all of the cheese and tomato sauce off my shirt if I ever got hit by an exploding pizza.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Sort of like regular goldfish, but with some tomato sauce aroma mixed in.

snack_name: Flavor Blasted Goldfish Xtra Cheddar Cheese
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are kind of like your standard Goldfish, except that they have a slightly more tangy cheddar cheese taste.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Not much, really.

snack_name: Flavor Blasted Goldfish Xtreme Cheddar & Sour Cream
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These have more cheddar flavor than regular Goldfish, along with a noticeable sour cream taste.
snack_smell_test: From the package:  Ingredients include Hydrolyzed Wheat Gluten, Enzyme Modified Cheese, Autolyzed Wheat Extract, and Disodium Guanylate

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Goldfish was just what we expected — a smaller version of the original. The crackers had the same pale yellow color and typical Goldfish shapes, complete with eyes and mouth, except the fish was smaller.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mild cheddar smell, typical Goldfish.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of goldfish wasn't actually crackers like the original, but rather graham cracker-like cookies, with a similar fish shape.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice mild graham cracker smell.

snack_name: Goldfish Cheddar Made with Organic Wheat
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This new version of Goldfish came in the same zipper-resealable bag as the carrot and cheesy tomato types, but this promised a standard Goldfish flavor made using organic ingredients.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mild cheddar smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Goldfish promised to be crunchier and bigger than the standard Goldfish, with the major change in composition being that they were made primarily from corn instead of wheat. Each piece had a similar shape to regular Goldfish, but was about 50% bigger and quite noticeably thicker, with a yellowish beige surface featuring some orange seasoning.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good zesty nacho cheese smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Goldfish had the same slightly-larger fish shapes as the Nacho version, with a light beige color and a light smattering of colorful seasoning.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong smell of something, but not really much like ranch.

snack_name: Goldfish Flavor Blasted Grahams Xtra Chocolatey
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Goldfish was very dark brown and had the same general shape that you would expect, but one side of each fish was flat while the other (the one featuring the eyes and mouth) was curved like normal goldfish cheese crackers.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Pretty good chocolate graham cracker smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These goldfish were cookies instead of crackers, and they were chocolate-flavored rather than cheesy.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good chocolate cookies smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Goldfish caught our attention because what makes more sense than French toast shaped like fish? The fish had a graham cracker color, just like the ones pictured on the bag (the ones at the bottom, not the one wearing the sunglasses), but they had lots of white sugary stuff on the surfaces, unlike the ones on the bag.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Wow, really smells like French toast!

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These dark brown Goldfish had some lighter specks of something sugary-looking on the surfaces, with the fish's eye and mouth on the rounded side of the cookie, and just a flat surface with no facial features on the other side.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Just remotely like chocolate. Not like a brownie.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These small, fish-shaped cookies didn't look like they should contain strawberry, as there was nothing pink about them. Each piece had one side flat, the other curved and featuring an eye and mouth, and a smattering of white powder on the surface.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very mild, but yes, smells like strawberry shortcake.

snack_name: Goldfish Mix-Up Adventures Pretzel & Flavor Blasted Xtra Cheddar
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Goldfish combined fairly conventional Goldfish crackers (though the kind with extra cheddar) with a special kind that wasn't a cracker at all, but rather a pretzel. The really nice thing about the pretzels was that some of the cheese rubbed off the crackers onto them, so we got the texture and taste of a pretzel with just a mild kick of cheese — and that made them taste quite good.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Not much.

snack_name: Goldfish Mix-Up Adventures Xtra Cheesy Pizza
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This bag combined some light-colored parmesan cheese goldfish with some more orangey Xplosive Pizza pieces, and both kinds appeared to have a light coating of additional pizza seasoning powder on their exteriors.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice tomatoey pizza smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Having had much experience eating Goldfish, I was quite intrigued when I spotted Goldfish Puffs at my local supermarket. Puffs? Did that means they'd be really big? That they were more like cheese puffs? The large bag dwarfed the standard Goldfish bags, so I was thinking big as I opened the bag. I peered inside to find that they were actually about the same size as the cracker fish and had a similar orange color, but they looked quite different. Most pieces were thicker, the fishes' mouths were more pronounced (cut away rather than just indented into the snack) and the tails had a different shape. But the really important difference was the ingredients, as these were made from corn meal instead of wheat.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Like a Buffalo wing sauce, but pretty ,ild.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These puffed Goldfish had the same bright color and remotely fish-like shape as the other flavors of the corn-based puffs, but they promised to contain a bacon and cheddar flavor. Why a fish would be flavored like bacon is a whole other question that we won't attempt to answer, so we just crunched right in to see how they tasted.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice mild bacony smell with a bit of cheddar too. Not like greasy bacon, just the smoky part.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These corn-based Goldfish were basically small cheese puffs that were slightly larger than the usual wheat-based Goldfish crackers, with a different but similar shape.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong cheese smell. Kind of bad.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This corn-based version of Goldfish had shapes that looked less like fish than the original wheat versions, with some weird variations in shape that looked like things other than fish. (It was kind of like looking at clouds to identify shapes.)
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Kind of like a spicy queso dip.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This new version of Goldfish brought several innovations to the whole Goldfish concept, and some these concepts boggled the minds of our snackers.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Kind of like graham crackers.

snack_name: Goldfish Special Edition Cheddar Toy Story 4
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Goldfish expanded on the original by adding three new kinds of pieces to the orange fish-shaped crackers. First, they made a black version of the fish pieces, with the same shape and even the same eye and smile. I have no idea what this one has to do with Toy Story 4 (but then again, the movie is over a month from being released, plus I never saw Toy Story 3). Then they made yellow ones shaped like Buzz Lightyear and Woody. These pieces were thinner and flat on the bottom, with some details of the characters on top. I know what these two have to do with the Toy Story franchise in general, but they don't seem to have anything particular to the movie mentioned on the bag.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: The usual Golfish cheddar smell, but it seemed milder.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Goldfish followed much the same concept as the Sweet Carrot ones, with half of the pieces taking on a tomato shape (complete with face, though it actually looked more like a pumpkin than a tomato), while the rest kept the usual fish shape. This time they included cheese instead of omitting it as they did with the carrot ones.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Slight hint of tomato in the usual cheddar Goldfish smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This new version of Goldfish promised to include actual carrot among its ingredients, but the crackers looked mostly like the regular ones, with an orange color and familiar shape — the fish-shaped ones, anyway. The others were shaped like carrots, though with eyes and a smiling mouth that I've never seen on the actual vegetable.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Just a mild cheese smell. Couldn't notice the carrots.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This bag contained mostly Goldfish in the usual goldfish shape, but about a fifth of the pieces had the same color and cheddar flavor but very different shapes — specifically they were supposed to resemble, the Leaning Tower of Pisa, the Taj Mahal, the Arc de Triomphe and the Clock Tower at the Palace of Westminster (sometimes called Big Ben, though technically that's just the clock).
snack_smell_test: Smell test: The usual cheddar Goldfish smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This special edition of Goldfish contained special red, Mickey-shaped crackers, along with the original orange, fish-shaped ones.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Really nice! Whatever spices they used in addition to the cheddar made for a great combination.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This package contained two large chocolate chip cookies, each about 3 inches in diameter and fairly thick, with a generous helping of fairly large chips visible on the surfaces.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: An OK chocolate smell, but nothing like a fresh-baked cookie.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: The cookies in this single-serve pack were fairly large and thick (same size as Grandma's Chocolate Chip Cookies) with an unusual pattern on the tops. It was like a grid, but instead of straight lines, they were wavy lines in both dimensions.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong peanut butter cookie smell. Nice.

snack_name: Guinness Luxury Milk Chocolate Solid Bar
snack_taste_test: Taste test: We were quite surprised a few years back to find potato chips bearing the Guinness logo, and this candy bar was equally unexpected.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mild milk chocolate smell, with a hint of beer.

snack_name: Guinness Rich Chili Thick Cut Hand Cooked Potato Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These chips had a similar brown-and-yellow appearance to the non-Chili version of the Guinness chips, with a thick cut, wiggly shapes and bubbles embedded inside.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice kick of spices with some nice heat.

snack_name: Guinness Thick Cut Hand Cooked Potato Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips had an unusual appearance, with a mix of yellow and brown on their fairly flat surfaces. The big appeal here was the huge word "Guinness" on the bag, so we were eager to share them with some snackers who enjoy a good pint of Guinness (though they were drinking various beers at the time).
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Not like Guinness. Not like beer. Kind of a sweet mix of spices and potato.

snack_name: Guinness Toasted Cheddar Thick Cut Hand Cooked Potato Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: Following up on the original and Chili flavors of Guinness potato chips from Burts, this one promised to combine cheddar with the flavor of a Guinness stout. The chips had wiggly shapes and various shades of yellow to brown, much like the other flavors.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good potato smell, with a hint of cheese.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: After reviewing several variations of the original Hot Tamales, I finally got my hands on a box of the original (or at least the first box I remember) to do a formal review and fill a gaping hole in the confusing lineup.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Not much.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: I've noticed in some of the other Hot Tamales varieties that the level of "hot" in the cinnamon candies varies a lot from one piece to the next, but with this box, they've actually touted the fact that the pieces have different heat levels, while color-coding the pieces.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Not much.

snack_name: Hot Tamales Chewy Cinnamon Flavored Candies (retro box)
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This retro box contained what appeared to be original version of Hot Tamales, amid a confusing lineup of different heat levels that includes Fire and Fierce Cinnamon versions.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Not much there.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This special version of Hot Tamales had two different flavors mixed in the same box, with light green ones promising Apple flavor and bright red ones being Spicy Cinnamon.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Just the slightest, slightest sweet cinnamon smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: As a major fan of the intense cinnamon flavor of Hot Tamales candy, I couldn't resist buying this cotton candy, as it would be great if they could duplicate that same taste in cotton candy form.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Kind of strange, only a bit like the cinnamon candy.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: After many years of eating Hot Tamales and then discovering the Fire version (which was maybe slightly hotter than the regular version), I found this "Fierce Cinnamon" flavor confusing.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Not much.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This was supposed to be a hotter version of the well-established and excellent Hot Tamales candy.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good cinnamony smell, same as the regular Hot Tamales.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This box intermixed two different kinds of Hot Tamales (each of which we've reviewed separately) in one box, with red pieces being the fire and blue ones being the ice. But there was some weird stuff going on here.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Not much.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: I've long enjoyed eating the cinnamon Hot Tamales (as well as the nearly indistinguishable Fire version). Once you've eaten one piece, it just hard to stop grabbing more and more until the box is empty.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Not much.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Hot Tamales did away with the usual medicine capsule shape, instead looking like half-inch sections of braided licorice — though noticeably thicker than a typical Twizzler.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: The usual intense spicy cinnamon smell of Hot Tamales. Nice.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This mix of of Hot Tamales was quite a departure from previous versions, as it offered three very different flavors, each in an entirely different colors, in the same box. Hot Tamales are best known for the original kind, which offers just one type of hot cinnamon candy. This wasn't the first kind with 3 varieties in the same box, as 3 alarm used different shades of red to reflect different heat levels, but they were all cinnamon-flavored.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Not much.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato-based rings had a good ring shape, with a pale yellow color and a very light seasoning powder.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: They smell kind of like the beef-flavored powder that comes with beef-flavored ramen soup.

snack_name: Hula Hoops Cheese & Onion Flavour Potato Rings
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These thick, ring-shaped snacks made from processed potato flakes have a nice cheese and onion flavor.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good, very mild cheese and onion smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are ring-shaped snacks made from dried potato.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Bland potatoey smell, like Pringles.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are small ring-shaped snacks made from processed dried potatoes.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Potatoey.

snack_name: Hula Hoops Prawn Cocktail Flavour Potato Rings
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are ring-shaped snacks made from processed potatoes.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like prawn cocktail, not bad.

snack_name: Hula Hoops Salt & Vinegar Flavour Potato Rings
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These rings made from dried, processed potatoes are cunchy and have a very mild vinegar flavor.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very mild vinegar smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These tubular potato snacks had a sharp cheese flavor, and they tasted quite good.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: A somewhat bad cheese smell.

snack_name: Hula Hoops Sizzling Bacon Flavour Potato Rings
snack_taste_test: Taste test: The ring-shaped snacks made from processed potatoes have a bacon-like flavor, but it isn't a strong flavor.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very, very subtle bacon aroma.

snack_name: Hula Hoops XL Beef & Mustard Flavour Potato Rings
snack_taste_test: Taste test: A subtle hot mustard flavor, but what you taste of the mustard isn't the mustard but the hot.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: A beefy aroma, kind of like bullion cubes.

snack_name: Hula Hoops XL Cool Chilli Flavour Tortilla Rings
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are really good.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like a bowl of chili. Excellent.

snack_name: Hula Hoops XL Curry Flavor Potato Rings
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato-based rings are somewhat irregular in shape, as they've deviated from the rounder standard Hula Hoops.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Light curry aroma.

snack_name: Hula Hoops XL Nacho Cheese Flavour Tortilla Rings
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These tubular, corn-based snacks taste sort of like Doritos, but the cheese taste is much, much weaker.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very weak cheese smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Bachman redesigned their crunchy cheese puffs bag and made a slight name change.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Doesn't smell like cheese, but does smell like a bag of crunchy cheese puffs.

snack_name: Jax Crunchy Cheddar Cheese Corn Twists
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are quite a bit like Crunchy Cheetos, but most people who tried them thought that these were clearly superior in taste.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: A somewhat pungent cheese smell ... not the most pleasant aroma out there.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are small cheese puffs that come in a wide variety of shapes.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Wow, very, very, very cheesy smell.

snack_name: Jax MultiGrain Real Cheddar Cheese Puffs
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Jax posed quite a challenge for our Jax-loving Cheese Puff Wizard, as the original Jax set a high standard for cheesiness and great texture, while "multigrain" varieties of some snacks tend not to be particularly tasty. These appeared to be "multigrain" by virtue of including not just corn but also rice, but there probably wasn't a whole lot of rice, as it was the very last ingredients listed. We opened the bag to find that these were thinner than the original Jax, as well as less bright in their intensity of orange. They also had somewhat irregular edges, versus the usual perfect curves.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good cheese smell, but much less intense than the incredibly strong smell of the regular Jax.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This bag contained small, soft, irregularly shaped cheese puffs, with bright orange areas where the cheese powder was and bright yellow where it wasn't.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good cheddar cheese puffs smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Ignore the crazy writing on the bag. These are the cheese puffs by which all other cheese puffs are judged. Cheetos may be golden on the crunchy side, but they've never been able to come close to Jax when it comes to the "puffed" variety. Even others cannot duplicate the correct combination of cheese and corn puff. Most other brands tend to put too much cheese on their curl.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong cheese smell when you open the bag.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These soft spheres of candy had caramel on the inside and a thin, shiny chocolate coating.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Not much.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These Junior Mints had soft shells colored yellow and powder blue, rather than the usual chocolate-colored coating.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Not really very minty.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This special version of Junior Mints was shaped like hearts, and the pieces seemed to be a bit larger than the regular Junior Mints.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: The usual Junior Mints smell, mildly mint and quite nice.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This new version of Junior Mints was white on the outside and dark on the inside.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice mild minty taste. Like Tic-Tacs.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These candies looked almost the same as Junior Mints, but there were some tiny pink and red spots in the shiny chocolate surfaces.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Surprisingly, not the same as Junior Mints. Weaker,

snack_taste_test: Taste test: The orange and black fillings in this edition of Junior Mints seemed like a fun variation on the classic. However, as soon as I was ready to eat some to do this review, I realized that changing the internal color of a Junior Mint is sort of an impractical change to even notice. They're a single-bite snack, so there's normally no opportunity to see the filling.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice minty smell, as usual.

snack_name: Keebler Bite Size Snackin' Grahams Cinnamon
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are small graham crackers, coated with cinnamon sugar on one side.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice cinnamon sugar smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Each of these five snack packs contained six chocolate chip cookie sticks and a tub of chocolate dip.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice chocolatey smell.

snack_name: Keebler Club Cornbread Cracker Bites Jalapeño
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These crackers were smallish, at about an inch and half long and one inch wide, with a 2x4 grid of fairly large holes that went all the way through. They were fairly thick as crackers go.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Not much, really could smell any cornbread or jalapeño.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Deluxe Grahams are one of Keebler's classic recipes, but somehow we neglected to review them until now. Oops!
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Surprisingly mild. Just a bit of graham and chocolate.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This package contained 22 large sandwich cookies, each shaped like a Keebler elf, with details of various elves on the top cookie exterior and slogans on the bottom cookie. The weird thing was that although they used different elf characters, they looked only very slightly different — the overall shape was the same, and it took some close analysis to notice the differences. All of the characters had nametags just below their necks, including Ernie, Elwood and Fast Eddie, but some of the names were hard to read. The slogans included "From the Hollow Tree," "Dunk head first," "Uncommonly Made" and "Uncommonly Good!"
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very mild, but kind of like an Oreo.

snack_name: Keebler Filled Pretzel Bites Peanut Butter and White Fudge
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This box contained five small bags, each containing six or seven pretzel nuggets.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mild peanut butter smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These cookies had the same ring shapes as Keebler's Jif peanut butter-filled cookies, but the similar external appearance hid a very different interior — nobody could ever confuse peanut butter with coconut in any way.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong coconut smell, definitely dominates the chocolate.

snack_name: Keebler Fudge Shoppe Grasshopper Fudge Mint Cookies
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These thin chocolate cookies were round with regularly spaced bumps along the edges and a fudge mint coating over the entire outside of the cookie.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Awesome chocolate mint smell. Wow.

snack_name: Keebler Fudge Shoppe Jumbo Fudge Sticks
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These bars were kind of like the various "nutty bars" (from Mrs.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice creamy fudge smell. Great.

snack_name: Keebler Fudge Shoppe Merry Mint Patties
snack_taste_test: Taste test: I'm figuring that when the Keebler elves convened inside their tree to plan this product, their goal was to produce the finest cookies ever, bar none.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice chocolatey mint smell.

snack_name: Keebler Fudge Shoppe Mint Creme Filled
snack_taste_test: Taste test: To make these, the Keebler elves took round chocolate cookies with a ridge around the top, filled the top area with mint creme, and then coated the whole thing in fudge.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Great chocolate mint smell. Awesome.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Having been surprised by the deliciousness of Keebler's peanut butter and chocolate Jumbo Fudge Sticks, I jumped at the chance to buy these as soon as I spotted them, as I'm a big fan of mint chocolate.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Really nice minty chocolate smell. Wow.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This special version of Fudge Stripes swapped out the standard butter cookies for chocolate ones and replaced the chocolate frosting stripes with caramel ones.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good mix of chocolate and caramel, but very different from a chocolate and caramel candy bar.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This special version of Fudge Stripes had the same round cookie with a hole in the middle and a pattern on the surface as the original, but they replaced the fudge with a cinnamon frosting covering the same areas: the whole bottoms and stripes of the tops.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong cinnamon sugar smell, a lot like a cinnamon roll.

snack_name: Keebler Fudge Stripes Lemon Cream Pie
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Fudge Stripes had off-white frosting stripes on round, light beige, hole-in-the-center cookies, with fully coated bottom sides.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong, smells like a lemon cream pie.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Fudge Stripes cookies have long been a favorite way to satisfy a chocolate craving, with a nice cookie crunch and a whole lot of chocolate fudge, but this was the first time we've seen the Keebler elves even attempt them with any other flavor.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice sweet gingery pumpkin spice smell. Great!

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of fudge stripes used pink cookies instead of butter cookies like the original, with off-white frosting in all of the places where the chocolate fudge gets used.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong, very sweet strawberry smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Fudge Stripes (not to be confused with the Strawberry Cheesecake ones) had pink stripes of frosting on top and a full pink coating on the bottom of each cookie. The cookies were the standard Fudge Stripe kind, round butter cookies with a hole in the middle.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong sweet strawberry smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This is a very sweet snack mix, so if you're not in a mood for some sugar, seek snacks elsewhere.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Great. More apple than cinnamon. It smells like an apple crisp.

snack_name: Keebler Graham-n-Go Mix With Real Peanut Butter
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This is an  excellent snack mix.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Kind of peanutty and kind of grapham crackery, but not great.

snack_name: Keebler Grahams Bites The Amazing Spider-Man
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This box contained Spider-man-themed, graham-cracker flavored cookies, with an assortment of six different kinds included.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice graham cracker smell.

snack_name: Keebler Jif Fudge, Peanut Butter & Crunchy Nuts
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These cookies were round and had a hole in the center of each one, with milk chocolate exteriors that included many small bits of crushed peanuts embedded in the surfaces.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice fudge and peanut butter smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This Keebler creation consisted of round chocolate cookies with a lip around the edge, with the bottom of the cookie coated in fudge, the area inside the lip filled with green mint creme, and then three or four thin stripes of fudge across the whole top.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Really nice mint chocolate smell. Great!

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This was one of those snacks that we bought strictly because we liked the name. "Pitter Patter" sounded like they were trying to copy Nutter Butter, and indeed these were also peanut butter cookie sandwiches. The major difference at first glance was that these sandwiches were round, unlike the peanut shell-shaped Nutter Butters. (Fun fact: The portable version of Nutter Butter that we've actually reviewed was round.)
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong peanut butter cookie smell. Nice.

snack_name: Keebler Right Bites Fudge Shoppe Mini Fudge Stripes cookies
snack_taste_test: Taste test: Right Bites? Try Wrong Bites.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Somewhat chocolatey.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: After reviewing the peanut butter version of Keebler's S'mores and finding that they didn't taste like s'mores (but still were quite good) we figured it was time to try the original; if they didn't taste like s'mores, there's a problem in the Keebler tree.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Really nice! Smells like a melted marshmallow being toasted on the campfire!

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This package contained a tray holding 10 fairly thick cookies, each in its own compartment of a plastic tray so that none of them stuck together or scuffed each other up.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mostly like sweet peanut butter.

snack_name: Keebler Simply Made Chocolate Sandwich Cookies
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These round sandwich cookies appeared to be Keebler's version of Oreos. They had a similar overall appearance to Oreos, but each sandwich looked a tad smaller, so I got some Oreos and measured both to find out. Turned out they were indeed smaller, measuring 1-5/8" in in diameter, vs. a bit over 1-3/4" for Oreos. Side-by-side, these looked quite noticeably smaller. And the Oreos were thicker too. Besides being smaller, the package also had fewer cookies, at 30 here vs. 36 for the standard-size Oreos.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Not the same as Oreos. Nothing bad, but not as good, a much less intense chocolate smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are wiggly stick-shaped crackers.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like wheat crackers.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Each of the five single-serving packs in this included six cookie sticks and a small vat of creamy, sugary, pale pink-orange dipping sauce (not really the bright pink pictured on the label).
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very sweet and good.

snack_name: Keebler Town House Flatbread Crisps Italian Herb
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These rectangular crackers had wavy edges and a geometric pattern of holes, with lots of seasoning visible on the surface, almost all of it was confined to one side of any given cracker.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice mix of herbs and spices.

snack_name: Keebler Town House Flipsides Pretzel Crackers Original
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These smallish crackers promised to be a hybrid between a pretzel and a cracker, which was unusual, as those are two universes that don't usually meet. Each one had rounded ends and much different appearances on the top vs. bottom surfaces. The bottom was kind of a golden color with some browning in places, while the top had a brown pretzel type of color, with lots of smallish bits of salt.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells mostly like Ritz Crackers. Maybe a hint of pretzel too.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: For years, I've been comparing some snacks to Vienna Fingers in my reviews, based on memories of a cookie sandwich that I used to enjoy many years ago. However, despite reviewing more than 400 kinds of cookies, I'd never actually reviewed Vienna Fingers. When I spotted this package on sale for just $1.88 (along with lots of other Keebler varieties at the same price), it seemed like the perfect opportunity to finally do a review.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice mildly sweet smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Fudge Stripe cookies have long been a favorite, known for years as round cookies with a hole in the middle, a full coating of fudge on the bottom and stripes of fudge on top. They've even come out with Cinnamon Roll, Pumpkin Spice, Strawberry Cheesecake, and Lemon Cream Pie versions — all keeping those signature stripes. Now we're told that the Keebler Elves messed up the striping process, resulting in these cookies. The story sounds fishy, but it seems like everyone who eats cookies could stand to benefit, so we won't dwell on it.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good chocolate smell, on the mild side.

snack_name: Keebler Whoopsy! Fudge Stripes #FullyFudged Fudge Mint
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These cookies took the same idea driving the original Whoopsy! Fudge Stripes — that one of the Keebler elves screwed up and coated the whole cookie instead of just stripes of it — and brought mint into the mix. The result was a round, bright green cookie with a hole in the middle and the whole outside coated in milk chocolate.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Oh wow, great chocolate mint smell!

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This snack followed very closely the example of Froot Loops Jumbo Snax, taking a popular cereal concept and just making the pieces bigger for snacking purposes. The resulting Apple Jacks were slightly bigger than the Froot Loops, closer to a quarter than a nickel in diameter, bearing the same pinkish surfaces and red things embedded inside as regular Apple Jacks.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice spiced apple smell.

snack_name: Corn Pops Jumbo Snax Caramel Crunch
snack_taste_test: Taste test: Our introduction to the Jumbo Snax line was the Froot Loops version, which kept the concept simple — they were just larger Froot Loops. It wasn't so simple with this Corn Pops version.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Slight caramel smell, OK.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Taquitos.net is not in the cereal review business because, frankly, keeping track of the latest snacks keeps us busy enough. But we've reviewed lots of snacks made with cereal, and this version of Froot Loops was very explicitly formulated and packaged as a snacking version of the delicious cereal.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Same great smell as regular Froot Loops. Love it.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Tony the Tiger is well known as the mascot for Frosted Flakes (for which he has repeatedly, though accurately, proclaimed, "They're great!") and this member of Kellogg's line of Jumbo Snax was based on his four-finger paw. Tony is a bit of a copycat in this regard, as fellow mascot Chester Cheetah has previously sold us cheese-based snacks Cracker Trax and Paws based on his hand.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Kind of weird. Sweet, but me no like.

snack_name: Kettle 40% Reduced Fat Krinkle Cut Potato Chips Sea Salt & Vinegar
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These salt and vinegar chips were cut thick and had a golden yellow color, with many shades of browning, lots of skin around the edges, some irregular shapes and some folded-over chips.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mild vinegar and potato smell. Nice.

snack_name: Kettle 40% Reduced Fat Potato Chips Salt & Fresh Ground Pepper
snack_taste_test: Taste test: The (non-reduced-fat) salt and pepper chips from Kettle have always been a big hit among our tasters, especially the Krinkle Cut ones, so the challenge with these was whether the 40% Reduced Fat version would be as good.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good strong peppery smell.

snack_name: Kettle Baked Potato Chips Hickory Honey Barbeque
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips were very crunchy when I bit in, and on first bite I was briefly convinced that they were quite a bit better than the other varieties of Kettle Baked Potato Chips (which were all really bland and not potato chip-like).
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very mild, just a slight barbecue-like seasoning.

snack_name: Kettle Baked Potato Chips Lightly Salted
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips were shaped less irregularly than the standard (non-baked) Kettle Chips, with not much wiggle in the chips and no folded-over chips.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Definitely different from the regular Kettle Chips. Sort of a potatoey smell, not bad, but nothing like the great baked potato smell of Kettle Chips. Ironic, since these are "baked" potato chips.

snack_name: Kettle Baked Potato Chips Salt & Fresh Ground Pepper
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips were smallish and nearly round, with skin around nearly the entire edge of most chips, plus just a handful of fairly large pieces of black pepper on each chip.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice fresh black pepper smell.

snack_name: Kettle Baked Potato Chips Sea Salt & Vinegar
snack_taste_test: Taste test: After being very disappointed by the Lightly Salted version of Kettle's new line of low fat potato potato chips, I wasn't optimistic about this salt and vinegar version being good. When I opened the bag, they looked like potato chips, with skin around the edges and a somewhat wiggly shape, though far less wiggly than regular (non-baked) Kettle Chips. There was some color variation within each chip, with some browning of the generally yellow chips, but not as much color variation as the non-baked ones.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Seemed like a mild vinegar smell at first, but then it was like punching me in my sinuses.

snack_name: Kettle Bakes Hickory Honey Barbeque Potato Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: It was almost impossible to open this bag, but once I got it open, I found small, baked potato chips with a flat shape, unlike the curves of chips cooked in oil.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like a bag of potatoes — no smell of honey, hickory or barbecue.

snack_name: Kettle Bakes Potato Chips Lightly Salted
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips were cut fairly thick but had a light feel to them, as their taste and texture were quite a bit different than just about any other potato chips that we've tried.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Fried potato smell, maybe even like a slightly burnt potato.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Chocolate-flavored potato chips are a rarity, so when Kettle Chips included these among the five varieties in the People's Choice 2007 promotion, I was eager to try them.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very mildly cinnamony, even milder chocolatey smell, but nice.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These chips were wide-rippled, but with very dull ripples, and the chips generally had very irregular shapes, including a few holes in the chips here and there.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mostly the usual Kettle Chips smell, which is of course good, but no Buffalo sauce or blue cheese.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Like all Kettle Chips, these were thick, crisp and had a great crunch.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mostly the good smell of Kettle Chips. A little cheddar, no beer.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This bag contained large, unbroken chips, with colors varying within each chip from yellow to brownish yellow.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice. Something vert sweet about the aroma, a bit of ginger with other spices.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips had a dull yellow color, with wiggly shapes that included lots of bubbles embedded inside, some skin and other dark areas along the edges, plus a smattering of green seasoning bits on the surfaces.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Some peppers, nice, but subdued. Not hot.

snack_name: Kettle Chips Classic Barbeque Hand Cooked Potato Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are very good chips, combining a mild, sweet barbecue flavor with the excellent taste and great crunch of the underling thick-cut, dark, irregularly shape Kettle Chips.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice baked potato-type smell. No noticeable barbecue smell.

snack_name: Kettle Chips Cooked in 100% Almond Oil Fiery Thai
