snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips had bumpy shapes and lots of bubbles embedded inside, plus some folded-over chips, with a strong yellow color and many bits of green on the surfaces.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Pretty mild, but does smell like peppers and lemongrass.

snack_name: Kettle Chips Cooked in 100% Almond Oil Wood Smoked Sea Salt
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips introduced two new ingredients that we don't normally encounter, namely Almond Oil and Wood Smoked Sea Salt. (We've seen plenty of Sea Salt snacks, but the "Wood Smoked" is brand new.) We opened the bag to find that the chips look mostly like other Kettle Chips, with wiggly, bumpy surfaces with lots of bubbles embedded inside. Many of the chips had no visible seasoning powder at all, while others had just the lightest smattering of smallish black bits.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Maybe slightly smoky.

snack_name: Kettle Chips Cooked in 100% Avocado Oil Himalayan Salt
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips broke from the usual (and very successful) Kettle Chips formula by switching to avocado oil (which we've seen in a few chips, but not a lot) and using Himalayan salt (also relatively rare in snacks, but definitely on a rapid rise in recent years). We found them on a shelf alongside a BBQ flavor also cooked in avocado oil.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good rich potato smell.

snack_name: Kettle Chips Cooked in 100% Avocado Oil Tropical Salsa with Mango Infused Salt
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These chips looked a lot like another Avocado Oil flavor from Kettle, Hawaiian BBQ, with wiggly shapes, a golden color and not much seasoning powder.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice, and not a typical salsa smell at all, as it was tangy in a different way.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This flavor was part of the Kettle Chips People's Choice promotion, and the chips had a sort of a deep orange appearance, with a good supply of dark seasoning on the chips.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like chile peppers and lime. Very strong, a hint of heat.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This bag (one of the five varieties in Kettle's People's Choice 2007 promotion) contained lots of wide-rippled, kettle-cooked chips, including some borerline ginormous ones.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice mix of spices, the ginger is what stands out the most.

snack_name: Kettle Chips Fully Loaded Baked Potato
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips had sort of an orangey glow to them, with some green bits of seasonings on the surface.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice, smells like a potato with chives, sour cream and maybe bacon bits.

snack_name: Kettle Chips Habañero Chili with Ginger
snack_taste_test: Taste test: Just describing the taste of these chips is quite a task.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Gingery, with some habañero kick.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These chips tasted like KFC Crispy Strips dipped in honey dijon sauce.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Kind of mustardy, but sweet

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These wide-rippled, golden yellow potato chips (one of the five varieties in Kettle's People's Choice 2007 promotion) were thick cut and very crisp, with a great kettle-cooked crunch.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very strong, very sharp, very sweet jerk barbecue flavor.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips were thick cut, irregularly shaped and very crunchy, with a variety of shades of orange and brown.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Not much.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips had a medium yellow color, with wiggly shapes including many folded-over chips, lots of skin around their edges and many small bubbles embedded inside. These was a light coating of some multi-colored seasoning.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice jack cheese smell. Couldn't really notice any jalapeño, but the cheese was great.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These chips had a golden orange overall color, with a light orange tint to the underlying chips and a dark orange seasoning.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells mostly like lime, couldn't notice any jalapeno. Pretty good.

snack_name: Kettle Chips Jalapeño with Tequila & Lime Hand Cooked Potato Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are awesome chips.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like tequila.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips had fairly flat shapes as Kettle Chips go, with a dark orange color generally, plus many bits of dark seasoning scattered over the surfaces.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Ni e sweet and tangy smell. Great!

snack_name: Kettle Chips Krinkle Cut Classic Barbeque Hand Cooked Potato Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: The wide-ripped, thick-cut chips had a decent sweet barbecue flavoring and a good potato taste.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice, mild barbecuey potato smell.

snack_name: Kettle Chips Krinkle Cut Dill & Sour Cream Natural Gourmet Potato Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are big, thick, crisp, wide-rippled, sort of kettle-cooked chips with lots of flavor.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice baked potatoey dill smell.

snack_name: Kettle Chips Krinkle Cut Jalapeno Cheddar
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are top-notch chips.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very, very nice baked potato sort of smell, but no hint of jalapeño or cheddar.

snack_name: Kettle Chips Krinkle Cut Salt & Fresh Ground Pepper
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are AWESOME chips! Like salt & vinegar, I wasn't a big fan of salt & pepper chips when I first tasted them.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Pretty big peppery smell.

snack_name: Kettle Chips Krinkle Cut Sour Cream & Onion Hand Cooked Potato Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These chips were wide-rippled and thick-cut, and they had a pretty good crunch.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Wow, just an awesome baked potato with sour cream smell. Great!

snack_name: Kettle Chips Krinkle Cut Spicy Queso
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips had wide ripples and a light orange color, with somewhat wiggly shapes, bubbles embedded inside and tons of seasoning powder of various colors on the surfaces.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice tangy pepper and cheese smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: The funny thing about these chips is that a common reaction to them is, "They need more salt." Yet it's hard to really make that complaint, considering that "lightly salted" is right there in the name of the chip.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like a baked potato.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These chips, part of the Kettle Chips Fire & Spice People's Choice promotion for 2007, were a big hit around the chip bowl.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice sweet and tangy smell, with a slight kick. Pretty good.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips didn't look all that different from ordinary Kettle Chips, but when we crunched in, we found quite a distinctive flavor.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice ginger and potato smell.

snack_name: Kettle Chips New York Cheddar with Herbs
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These taste kind of like Doritos.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: They smell a little bit cheesy, but also kind of oily.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: If I had to pick three flavors to combine on one potato chip, orange, ginger and wasabi are not the first three that would come to mind.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice mild smell with a little cirtus noticeable, and even a hint of ginger.

snack_name: Kettle Chips Organic Chipotle Chili Barbeque Hand Cooked Potato Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These chips were a major hit around the chip bowl, ranked by some among the best chips ever.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice, but very mild, baked potato smell.

snack_name: Kettle Chips Organic Sweet Summer Herb Hand Cooked Potato Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are very tasty chips.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice spicy aroma.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips had generally a medium yellow color, with wiggly shapes, some skin on parts of the edges and a good helping of multi-colored seasoning spread fairly evenly over the surfaces. Even before crunching in, the chips looked like they were particularly thick.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice mix of sweet peppers and potato.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips had wiggly shapes and dark, golden yellow surfaces with a fine orange seasoning and some larger green bits. Most of the chips were on the small side.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong sweet curry smell. Smells like a restaurant curry dish. Nice!

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips had a light yellow color, with many bubbles embedded inside and areas of browning and darker skin on parts of the edges. There was a light coating of fine seasoning, with colors that included green, brown and black.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice sweet garlic smell.

snack_name: Kettle Chips Roasted Red Pepper with Goat Cheese Hand Cooked Potato Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This was one of the more unusual flavors to come along in a while.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Definitely unusual, kind of cheesy, but not really bad.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These wide-rippled, kettle-cooked chips (one of the five varieties in Kettle's People's Choice 2007 promotion) were thick and ranged from very crunchy to quite crunchy, with good crispness, for an excellent overall texture.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good fresh curry smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are really good.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good rich barbecue chips smell, heavy on the mesquite.

snack_name: Kettle Chips Salt & Fresh Ground Pepper Hand Cooked Potato Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These chips were pretty good, but they were far from being the best salt and pepper chips.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mild peppery smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are the vinegariest vinegar chips I've ever tasted.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Wow, these smell vinegary. A whiff of the bag will give you quite a jolt, possibly knocking your right off the sofa!

snack_name: Kettle Chips Sour Cream & Onion All Natural Hand Cooked Potato Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These chips were excellent, with a tasty sour cream and onion seasoning and a great potato taste.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice potatoey smell, with a slight sweet onion smell mixed in.

snack_name: Kettle Chips Sour Cream Onion & Chive
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This flavor of Kettle Chips had the same large, irregularly shaped pieces as most other flavors, but some of these chips seemed less crisp upon biting in.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice sweet onion and sour cream smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips were spectacular, with great crispness, excellent crunch and an awesome spicy and hot flavor.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Lots of spicy aroma, like you're inhaling of a galicy dish at a good Thai restaurant.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips were generally smallish, with wiggly shapes featuring many bubbles of all sort of sizes embedded inside, with a dark orange glow overall plus a sparse coating of fairly large, very dark bits of seasoning powder.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good Sriracha smell. Milder than the sauce, but really quite nice anyway.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: We've reviewed quite a few flavors of Kettle Foods' potato chips, as well as many other brands, and mixing sweet and salty in a potato chip is relatively rare. (Many barbecue chips and some other flavors do include sugar among the ingredients, so it's far from unheard of, but just salt and sugar without any real spices is quite unusual.)
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong potato smell, a bit oily, reminds me more of other brands of potato chips than Kettle Chips (which usually have a richer nicer potato smell).

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips had generally the same look and texture that we've come to expect from Kettle Chips, with a variety of shapes, some wiggly chips and some folder over, as well as some intact chips that were narrow and long.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good potato smell with lots of sweet onion mixed in.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: It was very tough to get this bag open.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mostly the great potato smell of plain Kettle Chips. Some cheese too

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These wide-rippled, kettle-cooked chips were thick cut and quite crunchy, and they were quite loaded with chili lime seasoning.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Kind of a zippy chile and lime smell, pretty good.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: As someone who looks for any opportunity to add hot sauce to my food, I was excited to see this flavor in the Kettle Foods People's Choice box this year.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Regular Kettle chips smell with maybe some spices, but not really any heat.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Yogurt and green onion seems to be the health food generation's answer to sour cream and onion.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very potatoey, somewhat oniony aroma.

snack_name: Kettle Discoveries Yorkshire Wensleydale & Cox Apple Chutney
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips from England had a strong yellow color and fairly flat shapes, with many small bubbles embedded inside and lots of skin around the edges. There wasn't much visible seasoning powder.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice tangy mix of cheese and maybe something fruity.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips had wide ripples and came in irregular shapes, with mostly a nice gold yellow color and many areas of browning, plus some skin on the edges and assorted green bits on the surfaces.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice! Not your typical BBQ smell at all, kind of like Thousand Island dressing.

snack_name: Kettle Krinkle Cut Potato Chips Cheddar & Sour Cream
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These wide-rippled potato chips were cut thick and had a golden yellow color, with most of the chips being fairly small, most having some skin visible, and a few chips folded over.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice mix of baked potato and sour cream and cheddar smell.

snack_name: Kettle Krinkle Cut Potato Chips Dill Pickle
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips had a light yellow color and wide ripples, with many small bits of dill clinging to various parts of the surfaces.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like a jar of pickles, heavy on the dill. Nice.

snack_name: Kettle Krinkle Cut Potato Chips Organic Sweet Chili Garlic
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips were cut that had wide, shallow ripples, with a range of colors from yellow to golden orange, plus some dark bits of seasoning. Even with barely any broken chips, be bag was filled less than halfway.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice mild garlic and chili smell. Great!

snack_name: Kettle Krinkle Cut Potato Chips Zesty Ranch
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These wide-rippled chips were cut thick and a had a fair helping of green and reddish orange seasoning powder on their yellow surfaces.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Kind of garlicy. The smell didn't say "ranch" to me at all.

snack_name: Kettle Krisps Baked Potato Chips French Onion
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are not baked crisp-like chips, but rather they look like potatoes that have been thinly sliced and then baked instead of fried in oil.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: A potato-like aroma.

snack_name: Kettle Krisps Gourmet Baked Potato Chips Mustard & Honey
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are small chips that look like normal potato chips but are actually baked, still kind of crunchy but without the greasy taste of a normal potato chip.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very slight mustardy aroma.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This bag contained generally large kernels with an off-off-white color and some light brown specks scattered about.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice mix of smokiness and a subtle maple smell.

snack_name: Kettle Popcorn Salt + Fresh Ground Pepper
snack_taste_test: Taste test: The popcorn kernels in this bag were generally large and had just a smattering of large black pepper bits on their surfaces, a change from the numerous smaller bits we've seen in some other pepper popcorns.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice fresh black pepper smell, but kind of mellow compared with some other salt & pepper snacks.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This bag was filled nearly to the top with large kernels covered in light orange-colored seasoning, plus some black spots here and there. The seasoning was remarkably even from kernel to kernel.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like the space, but way, way, way milder.

snack_name: Kettle Potato Chips Cooked in 100% Avocado Oil Hawaiian Barbecue with Ginger Infused Sea Salt
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips had a golden yellow color, somewhat wiggly shapes, with many small bubbles embedded inside, some folded-over chips, and just the sparsest hint of seasoning powder on the surfaces.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very mild. A hint of ginger but not really a barbecue smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This flavor of potato chips from Kettle was highly anticipated by our bacon-loving snackers, who would all be thrilled to dip their precious bacon into some maple syrup. We've reviewed quite a few bacon snacks and a handful of maple snacks, but aside from a granola mix, there haven't been many snacks offering those two particular flavors together. The chips had wiggly shapes with some bubbles embedded inside, plus some skin around the edges, with just a bit of seasoning powder and a golden yellow overall color.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Sweet bacon smell. Very nice!

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Of the four flavors of Tias that we tried (including Zesty Ranch and Nacho Cheddar), all shared a texture and crunch a bit different than Doritos, but this flavor stood out from the crowd of Tias and earned the most praise from our tasters.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Not a strong one, but some salsa spices.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These triangular tortilla chips were almost the same shade of yellow as the bag, and I crunched in to find that they were among the best "plain" (unflavored) tortilla chips we've ever had.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mild corn tortilla chips smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These tortilla chips were clearly based on the Cool Ranch Doritos concept, but they were also quite different, with a good result.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong spicy ranch smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These chips appeared to be the Kettle Chips adaptation of Doritos-style tortilla chips.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mild cheese and corn smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These round tortilla chips had a very good black bean taste.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice strong black bean smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These triangular tortilla chips had a very dark blue color to them, and they were crisp and somewhat brittle (with many small broken pieces in the bag).
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mild but good corn tortilla smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These round tortilla chips were thick with a somewhat rough texture, and there was generally not much curve to the chips.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mild lime and chili smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These round tortilla chips were disappointing, because they were very lacking in crispness.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong, very nice tortilla chips smell, very rich.

snack_name: Kettle Tortilla Chips Organic Fire Roasted Chili
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These tortilla chips had a somewhat unusual shape, like pizza slices that someone had taken a first bite out of.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice chili powder aroma. Made my mouth water.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These tortilla chips were large and quarter-circle shaped, with a rough texture and many curved or broken pieces.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong, very nice tortilla chips smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Hershey's Kisses have come a long way since they only came in one flavor, so we probably shouldn't have been surprised by this flavor based on the Hershey's Gold Peanuts & Pretzels bar (but we were anyway). In addition to the new the Kisses shape, it didn't follow quite the same formula as the bar, retaining the pretzels within the caramel creme base while skipping the peanuts.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong caramel smell, even before unwrapping a piece, and even stronger after. Mmmm!

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These miniature Hershey's Kisses each had a colorful candy coating, with orange, yellow, red, green and blue pieces.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Same smell as Hershey's Kisses, but weak.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This snack followed the usual Kissables formula, with a miniarturized Kiss shape and an M&M's type of candy coating, but in this case the colors of the coating were four different pastels: green, blue, yellow and purple.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: A sweet smell, kind of odd, but kind of remotely like M&M's.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This dark chocolate version of Kissables came in four odd colors, all tough to describe: dark brown, very light lavender, reddish brown and a sort of dark purplish color.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Kind of like M&M's.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Ever since Hershey's introduced Kissables (their version of M&M's, shaped like Hershey's Kisses), I have figured that they would have all sorts of special editions of them, substituting special color combinations for the original rainbow of colors.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Kind of odd, kind of a chemically chocolate smell. Maybe the colors affected the smell of the chocolate.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This aerated chocolate version of Kisses came with each Kiss in a silver foil wrapper bearing a pattern of various sized brown circles, with the words "Air Delight" in red on the paper pull tab.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: The usual Hershey's chocolate smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: The flavors of Kisses keep on coming (most recently, Hershey's Gold), so with the ever-growing popularity of Oreos, why not a Cookies 'n' Creme version?
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very sweet white chocolate smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Hershey's Kisses had the usual Kisses shape, as each piece a silver wrapper bearing the words "Mint Truffle" in a variety of sizes, with a paper pull tab also labeled "Mint Truffle" jutting out of each wrapper.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice chocolate mint smell. Great.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Kisses came in orange and brown patterned foil wrappers, with the usual paper tag (in this case, as "Caramel" label) protruding from each piece. Unwrapping that stuff, the exterior of the Kiss was revealed to be all milk chocolate.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Great caramel and milk chocolate smell. Mmmm!

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Kit Kat took on a rabbit shape, with smooth surfaces and some nice detailing. What it lacked as a member of the Kit Kat brand was actual wafers inside; instead, there were crunchy-ish bits that the label referred to as "crunchy wafer pieces."
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good chocolate smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This was very similar to the American Kit Kat, but we found quite a few differences.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good milk chocolate smell, but slightly different from the American Kit Kat bar. Reminded me of the Yorkie.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Kit Kat has always been a favorite.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Great, rich milk chocolate smell. Excellent.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Kit Kat had the original four-finger format, with the coated wafers showing an external color that was off-white, similar to many white chocolate bars, but the surface color was somewhat textured, with many tiny chunks of stuff (perhaps apple) inside it.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Sweet and sort of remotely apple-like.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This special version of the Kit Kat bar had the usual four sticks, but with some special touches.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: The usual Kit Kat chocolate smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This four-finger bar had an off-white exterior, with tiny candy sprinkles in lots of colors embedded inside the top, and on the bottom, the wafers inside showing through the coating looked vaguely reddish.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mostly like white chocolate, but kind of like birthday cake frosting.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This Easter edition of Kit Kat followed the model of some other seasonal versions, modifying the traditional detachable four-finger structure by having a fancy design span multiple fingers.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: The usual Kit Kit milk chocolate smell. Very Nice,

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of the Kit Kat bar was kind of like the Big Kat or Kit Kat Chunky, in that it was like they took one of the four bars of a regular Kit Kat and made it huge. In this case, they also left an area inside the wafers and filled it with caramel.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice chocolate and caramel smell. Great.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of the Kit Kat bar had the same shape and color as a normal Kit Kat, but there was a definite mocha taste upon biting in.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice mocha smell, heavy on the coffee.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Kit Kats normally come as four thin bars stuck together, and you can break them apart and eat one at a time (but usually this happens in rapid succession).
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good chocolate smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This oversized version of a single Kit Kat bar had three Kit Kat logos on top, with very slight dividers in between that made it sort of detachable into three sections.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Chocolate and, just mildly, caramel. Good.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This variation of the oversize Kit Kat bar had three layers of wafers inside, with a hazelnut cream layer on top of them, then the whole thing was coated with a nice thick exterior of milk chocolate.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice chocolate and hazelnut smell.

snack_name: Kit Kat Chunky New York Cheesecake
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of the large, 1-finger Kit Kat Chunky bar had three wafer layers inside, topped with a bunch of cheesecake stuff, then it was all coated in milk chocolate.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Great milk chocolate smell. Maybe a hint of cheesecake.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This large, one-finger Kit Kat bar had the usual wafers inside, with a thin layer of peanut butter near the top.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Pretty good peanut butter and chocolate smell.

snack_name: Kit Kat Chunky Salted Caramel Fudge
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of the large, one-finger Kit Kat had the standard wafers filling most of the interior, with the top consisting of a salted caramel fudge, then the whole exterior had a thick milk chocolate coating.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Can definitely smell the caramel more than the chocolate — even though it's on the inside!

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This white chocolate version of the giganticized single-bar Kit Kat had wafers in the middle and a thick white chocolate coating around them.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice white chocolate smell. Perfect, not too sweet.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This bar had the same shape as the standard Kit Kat, with four thin wafer bars stuck together by their chocolate coating.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like coffee on first whiff. More like mocha on second whiff.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Kit Kat (a Hershey/Reese's product not to be confused with the British Nestle Kit Kat Fine Dark bar) was like a regular Kit Kat in terms of size, shape and internal wafers, but obviously dark chocolate was substituted for the usual milk chocolate.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice, very good dark chocolate smell.

snack_name: Kit Kat Duos Mint + Dark Chocolate
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This huge package contained two separate four-finger Kit Kat bars, the first ones we've seen under the Duos line, which meant that the bar itself had two different exteriors, with chocolate on the bottom half and mint on top. Inside, the usual crunchy wafers. I opened the package to find that the dark chocolate was indeed quite dark, quite a contrast to the very light green mint portion. The delineation between the two colors was much less well defined in reality than it was in the pictures, as the chocolate reached higher or lower in different areas, and there was a small area where the two mixed.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Great chocolate mint smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This bar was shaped like a giganticized version of one of the four individual bars in a regular Kit Kat.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Great chocolate and caramel smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: From the outside, this bar looked like a Kit Kat Chunky, but it was quite a bit different upon biting in.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Rich mocha-like smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This had the same shape as the standard Kit Kat, with four detachable thin bars and a slightly crunchy wafer inside each one.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good chocolate smell, same as regular Kit Kat.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This was a giganticized version of one of the four bars in a standard Kit Kit, with thicker chocolate and bigger wafers, similar to the Big Cat or Kit Kat Chunky.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: The regular Kit Kit chocolate smell, very nice,

snack_name: Kit Kat Extra Crispy Triple Chocolate
snack_taste_test: Taste test: If you're in the mood for some chocolate overload, this might be the bar for you.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good Kit Kat chocolate smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This 4-finger bar had the same general look as a regular Kit Kat bar, with the Kit Kat logo on each of the detachable sections, and a typical dark chocolate color.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good, mild dark chocolate smell.

snack_name: Kit Kat Flavor of California Strawberry
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This state-themed version of Kit Kat (released alongside a Georgia Reese's and Texas Pay Day) came in the usual detachable four-finger Kit Kat configuration, with the Kit Kat logo in the center of each section, but the light pink color gave it a very different look.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice sweet strawberry smell. Like fresh strawberries and cream.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This box from Japan contained three individually wrapped packs, each containing a smallish two-finger light green Kit Kat bar.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: On first whiff, I smelled a bit of white chocolate, but after that, definitely tea.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This was kind of a gimicky idea, but it was a decent candy bar, especially if you like white chocolate.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like hot cocoa.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This candy bar had the same four-stick shape as the standard Kit Kat bar, and the chocolate was the same color, so once the wrapper was removed, it looked the same.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very malty chocolate smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This bag contained lots of small packs of two-finger Kit Kat bars, with a very light orange color and the Kit Kat logo atop each finger.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like a Creamsicle.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This bag of Kit Kats contained individually wrapped single-finger bars, each a bit under 2-1/2 inches long and slightly wider than a single finger of a four-finger bar. There was a shallow section divider halfway along the length, with an encircled Kit Kat logo for each of the two sections.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good chocolatey cookies and cream smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: There are few flavor combinations as perfect as mint and chocolate, but America's mass-market candy industy has generally done an poor job bringing chocolate mint products to market.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Great chocolate mint aroma.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This bar had the same shape as a normal Kit Kat, with the trademark four parallel sections, but it had a pale orange color.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells exactly like a Creamsicle. Mmmmm.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This bag from Japan contained small, individually wrapped two-finger Kit Kat bars with a very light orange color.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Kind of a sugary pumpkin smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Kit Kat was shaped kind of a like they took a single finger from a four-finger Kit Kat bar, lengthened it, and then added five turrets on top, each containing hazelnut filling.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong hazelnut smell, more hazelnut than chocolate. Nice.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This candy bar followed up the original hazelnut version of Kit Kat Senses by substituting caramel for the hazelnut while retaining the same overall shape.
snack_smell_test: From the package:  “Crisp Wafer with a Creamy Caramel Topping”

snack_taste_test: Taste test: I bought this candy bar not specifically because I was hungry for a Kit Kat, but more because I saw Homer J.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Great chocolate smell. Sweet and creamy. Mmmm.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This special Halloween version of Kit Kat broke with the usual bar design by not just adding some Halloween-themed elements (a ghost emerging from the moon and the words "Happy Hauntings") to the design — they also had those design elements span multiple sections of the four-finger bar, thus challenging the integrity of the traditional four sections.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: The usual Kit Kat milk chocolate smell, very nice.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This variation on the standard Kit Bar bar had chocolate wafers separated by chocolate creme, coated in milk chocolate.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good chocolate smell, like a regular Kit Kat.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: The Kit Kat bars in this package from Japan came in smallish 2-finger form, with a light green color on the outside. Having reviewed quite a few wasabi and horseradish snacks over the years, we still had no idea what to expect from this one, as wasabi in a candy bar seemed like a whole other thing.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Kind of like white chocolate

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This package contained the standard Kit Kat shape of four detachable, wafer-filled bars, but with a much different appearance thanks to the white chocolate's creamy off-white color.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice mild white chocolate smell. Not overly sweet, quite good.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These crunchy curls had a light orange color with some darker spots, but not really any of the red like the ones shown on the bag.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Spicy, smells like an Indian food store.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This flavor of Kurkure had the same types of shapes as your typical crunchy cheese curls, with a light orange, sort of beige-like color over pall, plus some slightly darker spots and a smattering of bits of green seasoning. Despite the "Green" in their flavor name, the overall look really wasn't green at all. And they weren't cheese puffs, as they featured some Indian spices instead of cheese.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mild. Kind of sweet and a bit fruity but mildly spicy.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These snacks looked like Crunchy Cheetos, but with a dull light orange color in most areas and some darker orange in the crevices.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Kind a sweet curry smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These snacks were shaped like crunchy cheese curls, and they were even orange, though it was darker orange, not the fluorescent orange that you get from Cheetos.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice mild spicy and tangy smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These snacks had the irregular shapes typical of crunchy cheese curls, with generally a light orange color, plus some darker orange seasoning.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Tangy ketchup smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These snacks had irregular shapes, kind of like cheese puffs except not as curvy and with knobby bumps on them. The ones pictured on the bag had more Y-like shapes, similar to the faux-popcorn shapes of Chester's Puffcorn, but most of the ones in the bag did not.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice mildly tangy cheese smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These were shaped kind of like crunchy cheese curls, though the individual pieces were generally less irregularly shaped than crunchy curls such as Cheetos.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice, fresh Indian food smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This snack consisted of midsize triangles, much smaller than Doritos-style snacks, with an orange color generally and a light smattering of dark seasoning bits.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Some mild Indian spices, but not really any lime or pickle.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: The snacks in this bag looked a lot like Crunchy Cheetos, with the same types of wiggly-shaped sticks and a light orange color (not as bright as Cheetos) with some darker orange spots.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Kind of remotely like chicken soup, but with some other spices.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This snack from Nepal was just the second one from that country that we've reviewed, and the concept was a lot like Kurkure, which isn't from Nepal but from neighboring India.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mild mix of spices with tomato.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This package contained six square cracker sandwiches, and I like cream cheese with chives, so the flavor sounded very tempting.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Not much. Maybe I could smell the crackers themselves, but no cream cheese or chives.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This pack contained six cracker sandwiches, each with two square Captain's Wafers surrounding a thin cheese filling.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice cheez whiz and crackers smell, but not particularly like grilled cheese.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Each of the sandwiches in this six-sandwich cracker package had a thin layer of peanut butter between two square Captain's Wafers crackers.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong peanut butter smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This package contained six cracker sandwiches, each consisting of two square Captain's Wafers crackers and a thin, dark orange-colored filling.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice smoky cheddar smell.

snack_name: Chip Thunder Boomin' Barbecue Rumble Potato Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are good barbecue chips.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good barbecue smell

snack_name: Chip Thunder Buffalo Wing & Blue Cheese Rumble Cut Potato Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: Chip thunder, indeed! These rippled chips are extremely crunchy and also very flavorful.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very hot and spicy aroma, sort of like Buffalo wings.

snack_name: Chip Thunder Chargin' Cheddar & Sour Cream Rumble Potato Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are possibly the best cheddar potato chips out there.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice cheddar and sour cream aroma

snack_name: Chip Thunder Original Rumble Potato Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are very good plain ripple chips.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Potatoey

snack_name: Chip Thunder Stormy Salt & Vinegar Rumble Potato Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are really good vinegar chips.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong vinegar smell.

snack_name: Chip Thunder Wild Sour Cream & Onion Rumble Potato Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are top-notch sour cream and onion chips — thick, wide-rippled and heavily flavored with a sharp but sweet onion taste.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good sour cream and onion smell.

snack_name: Choc-o Poppers Bite-Size Creme Filled Chocolate Cookies
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These were pretty much mini versions of Oreos.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like Oreos.

snack_name: Lance 100 Calorie Nip Chee Cheddar Cheese
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This 100-calorie pack contained sandwiches made with two tiny round crackers held together by a thin layer of cheese.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Barely any.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These 100-calorie bags contained small round cracker sandwiches with peanut butter in the middle.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Just mildly peanut buttery.

snack_name: Lance Bolds Cracker Sandwiches Bacon Cheddar
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This box contained six 6-packs of square cracker sandwiches, each promising the tempting combination of bacon and cheddar. There was also a first-of-their-kind twist: Unlike pretty much every other bacon-flavored snack we've tried, the crackers appeared to have small chunks of bacon embedded inside. We didn't see anything in the ingredients that indicated that Lance used actual bacon, but still, it looked a lot like it. Besides that, the crackers had generally a light beige color, with some darker shades in a few places, plus a bright orange cheddar filling.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice smoky bacon smell. Great!

snack_name: Lance Bolds Cracker Sandwiches Buffalo Wing Blue Cheese
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These cracker sandwiches looked a lot like peanut butter cracker sandwiches, as they had bright orange crackers with a lighter orange/brown filling.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mild blue cheese and hot sauce smell. Nice.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: The sandwiches in this version of Lance's Bolds (introduced along with Buffalo Wing Blue Cheese and Bacon Cheddar flavors) consisted of two light orange-colored square crackers with an even-lighter-orange filling in between. The box contained six 6-packs of sandwiches.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like pizza. Nice mix of spices.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These cracker sandwich six-packs consisted of light beige toasted crackers filled with an even lighter-colored layer of cheese.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice mild cheese smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This snack broke from the usual cracker sandwich formula of having six sandwiches per pack, but otherwise it was fairly standard, with just four of the usual size sandwiches per pack. There were six packs in the package.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good fresh jalapeño smell, fairly strong.

snack_name: Lance Cheez Explosion Cheddar Charged Cheese Puffs
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are good cheese puffs, with a nice texture and noticeably more cheese on them than the comparable version of Cheetos.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good cheese smell.

snack_name: Lance Cheez Explosion Triple Cheese Twisters
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are perfectly good cheese curls, but after reading the marketing hyperbole on the bag, we were expecting a lot more.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice nice cheese and toasted corn smell, a lot like Cheetos, but maybe not as cheesy.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This box contained six individual packages, each containing two cracker sandwiches.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice, it smells like garden vegetable-flavored cream cheese.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These extra-large cracker sandwiches came two to a pack, and each consisted of two golden beige crackers with rounded ends, holding a thick filling that was close to white in color.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Pretty good. On first whiff, I wasn't sure, but after that I could definitely smell the parmesan.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These were the best hot fries I've ever had. They were perfectly crisp with a great texture and coated with a generous amount of flavor powder, tasty, hot and quite delicious. The heat level was not the hottest ever, but it was still very impressive, and the effect could easily be multiplied by eating more than one fry at a time.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice hot sauce smell. Like hot wings.

snack_name: Lance Giant Hot Sausage Texas Pete
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This sausage was just about the size of a regular hot dog, so I'm not sure where the word "giant" in the name came from.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good salami sort of smell, but not really any heat to it.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: We've eaten many kinds of bagged popcorn, but few make such an ambitious claim as this one of being like the best of all kinds of popcorn, the kind that we overpay for huge tubs of at the movie theater.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like actual movie theater popcorn. Great

snack_name: Lance Nekot S'mores Poppers Bite-Size Chocolate & Marshmallow Sandwich Cookies
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are very tasty little snacks, and they live up to their name.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice s'more smell, very marshmallowey.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are pretty much average barbecue chips.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very mild barbecue smell, nothing special.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are your standard conventional thin-sliced potato chips, with a medium level of salt, and slightly greasy.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good regular potato chips smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are very similar to Wise chips and as such were highly praised by the 12-year-old member of our tasting panel.
snack_smell_test:
From the package:  Underneath Lance logo on both front and back: “Freshness.” The
back also says: “Guaranteed Fresh...”

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This package contained six square-shaped cheese-and-crackers sandwiches.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Wow, it really does smell like Swiss cheese.

snack_name: Lance Tasty Crackers Xtra Fulls Peanut Butter
snack_taste_test: Taste test: Those box contained six separately wrapped packs, each containing six round cracker sandwiches with peanut butter filling. Obviously we've eaten peanut butter cracker sandwiches many times before, but the big draw here was the promise that the filling was going to be more than the usual thin filling. The round crackers were also a minor departure from the usual squares.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good peanut butter smell.

snack_name: Lance Toast Chee Poppers Bite-Size Peanut Butter Sandwich Crackers
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are sandwiches made from round orange crackers, with a thin layer of peanut butter in the middle.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice peanut butter and crackers smell.

snack_name: Lance Toast Chee Reduced Fat Peanut Butter
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These cracker sandwich six-packs followed the standard formula of bright orange crackers filled with peanut butter.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good peanut butter smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These cracker sandwiches had the same very bright orange crackers that are frequently used for peanut butter cookie sandwiches, with a fairly generous spicy cheddar filling that had much lighter color of orange than the crackers. The package contained six individually wrapped four-packs.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mild jalapeño smell.

snack_name: Lance Toasty Crackers Reduced Fat Peanut Butter
snack_taste_test: Taste test: The sandwiches in these 6-packs consisted of two round crackers with a thin layer of peanut butter in between.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good peanut butter smell.

snack_name: Lance Whole Grain Crackers Real Cheddar Cheese
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These cracker sandwich packs followed the usual formula of six square cracker-and-cheese sandwiches in each wrapper, but they broke the formula by using whole-wheat crackers and a very light color of cheddar rather than a glowing orange cheese.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like wheat crackers, nothing special.

snack_name: Lance Whole Grain Crackers Real Peanut Butter
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These six-packs of cracker sandwiches each contained two square wheat crackers with a pattern of 13 holes.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong peanut butter smell.

snack_name: Lance Whole Grain Crackers Real Sharp Cheddar Cheese
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These 6-packs of cracker sandwiches looked similar to Lance's Real (but not sharp) Cheddar version but was actually quite a bit better, as they did indeed have a sharper cheddar taste, and that taste was quite good.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Can smell just the wheat, not really the cheese.

snack_name: Nip Chee Poppers Bite-Size Jalapeño Cheddar Sandwich Crackers
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are sandwiches made from small round crackers, about an inch in diameter, with a spicy cheese filling in the middle.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice, fairly strong jalapeño smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This is pretty good popcorn.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Cheddary/popcorny smell

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This is an unusual snack mix, conspicuous for its lack of chips of any kind.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Sort of a bread-like aroma.

snack_name: Thunder Boomers Jumpin' Jalapeño Cheddar Kettle Cooked Potato Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are crunchy and tasty kettle-style chips with a mild jalapeño heat — just strong enough to enhance the taste and put a hot feeling your mouth, but mild enough that all except the most timid snack eaters should be able to eat handfuls of these without a desperate need to sip a beverage between chips.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good jalapeño smell, strong enough to make your mouth water.

snack_name: Thunder Boomers Quakin' Cajun Kettle Cooked Potato Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are some top-notch potato chips, with a great cajun barbecue-type taste and some good hot afterkick, on a very crunchy, crisp and delicious kettle-cooked potato chip.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice cajun barbecue smell. Wow.

snack_name: Thunder Boomers Smokin' Barbecue Kettle Cooked Potato Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are very crisp kettle-cooked chips, with a good loud crunch.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mild standard barbecue smell.

snack_name: Thunder Howlin' Hot & Spicy Texas Pete Rumble Potato Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are very good chips.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice hot sauce smell (but only slightly hot).

snack_name: Thunder Thrillin' Dill Pickle Rumble Potato Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are crunchy rippled potato chips with a strong dill pickle flavoring, and enough residue to leave some on your fingers.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: A pretty strong dill pickle aroma

snack_name: Larry the Cable Guy Bacon Ranch Tater Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips had a pale yellow color with a light smattering of red and green seasoning on the surfaces. We crunched in to find a good crispness and light crunch, with a nice bacon ranch flavor. There was a very even mix of smoky bacon and ranch, fairly strong, and neither of the two tastes dominated.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice, can smell both ranch seasoning and bacon.

snack_name: Larry the Cable Guy Barbeque Rib Tater Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips were fairly thin, came in a variety of shapes and sizes and had generally a light orange color from of the seasoning powder.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Sweet and tangy smell, not necessarily like ribs, but kind of like a rib sauce.

snack_name: Larry the Cable Guy Biscuits & Gravy Tater Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This flavor of potato chips immediately got our attention, as we've eaten many, many potato chips but never a "biscuits & gravy" flavor. (The closest was fries & gravy.) As such, we had no idea what the chips would be like, though we were optimistic, because who doesn't like a good biscuit?
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Kind of a mild ground black pepper smell.

snack_name: Larry the Cable Guy Buffalo Wing Tater Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These were very flavorful potato chips, with an initial taste that was a lot like Buffalo wing sauce, with just a bit of heat, followed by a nice kick of heat that grew stronger as we ate more chips.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells kind of like hot sauce, but not actually hot.

snack_name: Larry the Cable Guy Caramel & Peanuts Country Corn
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This bag contains contained large, round kernels with a generous coating of caramel. The picture on the bag showed peanuts stuck to the kernels, but try as we might, we could not find any actual peanuts stuck to the kernels in the bag.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like Cracker Jacks.

snack_name: Larry the Cable Guy Cheese Burger Tater Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This flavor from Larry the Cable Guy looked like ordinary potato chips, as there wasn't any seasoning powder on the surfaces, a sharp contrast to the Buffalo Wing flavor, which was overloaded with powder.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like relish and mustard.

snack_name: Larry the Cable Guy Chili Cheese Fries Tater Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This large bag of potato chips from Larry (who specializes in unusual potato chip flavors, including Fried Dill Pickle, Tater Salad, Cheeseburger and the fabulous Biscuits & Gravy!) contained mostly smallish chips, with fairly flat shapes and a nice orange glow. There was a smattering of dark seasoning powder on the surfaces, with bubbles embedded inside most chips and very little skin around the edges.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Wow, really smells like a bowl of chili. Nice!

snack_name: Larry the Cable Guy Fried Dill Pickle Tater Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips were fairly thin and had lots of green seasoning on them (kind of resembling dill).
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good strong pickle smell, much like other pickle-flavored potato chips.

snack_name: Larry the Cable Guy Hollar-Peño Popper Tater Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: Unlike most jalapeño chips with their characteristic (real or artificial) green seasoning on their surfaces, the chips in this looked like ordinary potato chips, with a pale yellow color, some areas of browning, generally smallish bubbles embedded inside, occasional bits of skin on the edges and no seasoning — green or otherwise — visible on the surfaces.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice fresh potato smell, with a hint of jalapeño.

snack_name: Larry the Cable Guy Pass the Darn Ketchup Tater Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These were some of the darkest-colored ketchup chips we've ever seen, as the surfaces were heavily covered with a very intense dark red seasoning.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Sweet ketchup smell.

snack_name: Larry the Cable Guy Tater Salad Tater Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips had a nice bright yellow/orange glow, with many of the chips fairly large, some bits of skin on the edges, and some bubbles embedded inside. These was just the slightest hint of seasoning visible, most of it consisting of very tiny dark bits.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Definitely on these sweet side, maybe remotely like potato salad. Maybe more like cole slaw.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This Lay's adaptation of the Popchips concept had round shapes with varying degrees of wiggliness and cupping, with generally a light orange color from the seasoning, plus some much darker orange spots.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong sweet barbecue smell, like a jar of barbecue sauce. Very nice.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This new line of "Air Pops" from Lay's looked to be their way of directly taking on Popchips.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Not much, but they actually smelled vaguely of a sweet pastry, not a potato crisp.

snack_name: Lay's Air Pops Sour Cream & Onion
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These crisps were Lay's attempt to take on Popchips, based on not just their similar appearance, but even their name. (Read more about the Air Pops line.) The round crisps had very light beige color and lots of green things on the surfaces. The shapes varied, with most of the pieces a bit wiggly or slightly cup-shaped, curling up around the edges, while a minority of pieces were almost completely flat. I crunched in to find that the thickness and texture also varied a lot from one piece to the next. The flat pieces were thinner and less crisp than the other ones, but even the better ones lacked the great combination of lightness, crispness and crunch that makes Popchips so appealing. Most were thinner and denser than Popchips, and the crunch was far less crisp and generally softer, resulting a noticeably weaker overall experience.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: KInd of heavy on the sour cream. Maybe a little onion too.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This new flavor adds to the existing White Cheddar, Honey BBQ and Sea Salt in the Poppables line, with the same oval shapes, hollow interiors and pattern of holes on the exterior, plus this one had a very light smattering of green bits on the light beige surfaces.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Pretty nice, I think creamy jalapeño describes it well.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This new flavor of Poppables had the same shapes (round and hollow with a geometric pattern of holes) as the original Poppables flavors, White Cheddar and Sea Salt, with two kinds of seasoning distributed unevenly on the surfaces — a fine orange powder and some larger bits of black.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong sweet barbecue smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This snack had the same oval shapes as the White Cheddar Poppables, with a pattern of holes on the outside of the hollow, potato-based shell.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Similar smell to other potato crisps, especially some of the Asian ones.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This flavor of Lay's Poppables had the same form factor as the other flavors, a round-ish, hollow potato crisp with a pattern of holes on the outer shell, with a yellowish beige color.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Wow, strong vinegar smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: For years, many snackers have lamented the demise of the Ruffles 3D's (RIP Supreme Sour Cream & Onion, BBQ Blast and Maximum Cheddar), and it seems that Frito-Lay might have finally brought back something similar, though without the Ruffles name this time.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mild cheese smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips had wide, angular ripples and a light yellow color, with occasional areas of browning along the edges, plus some bits of potato skin. There didn't appear to be any seasoning on them. The "American Classic" label was a bit confusing, as I'm an American who has eaten and reviewed over a thousand kinds of potato chips, but even I didn't know what it meant. Were they supposed to be like Lay's Classic? The ripples sure didn't make it look that way.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very strong fresh potato flavor. Nice.

snack_name: Lay's American Style Cream & Onion Flavour
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These narrow-rippled chips were an irresistible buy for me, as the whole idea of how they came to be sold where they were was just too crazy to resist.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Not much at all. Just the slightest sour cream and onion smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips from Spain were generally similar to many kinds of kettle-cooked chips, but they differed in several notable ways. Most of the chips in this bag lacked the typical wiggly shape, as these were generally flat, and in many cases, narrow and long. Many of the chips had bubbles embedded in them.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong, very nice potato smell, similar to some kettle-cooked chips but more potatoey.

snack_name: Lay's Bacon Wrapped Jalapeño Popper Duet
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This flavor had some strange origins. It showed up a week after three other musically themed Lay's flavors (Flamin' Hot Dill Pickle Remix, Classic Beer Cheese and Electric Lime & Sea Salt) and had the same music-related promotional material on the bag — but it wasn't marketed along with the other three. Plus, it wasn't even a new flavor, as Wavy Bacon Wrapped Jalapeño Popper (without the word Duet, and with ripples, but with the identical illustration on the bag) was part of last year's Tastes of America promotion.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice bacon smell initially, then a kick of heat. Nice!

snack_name: Lay's Balsamic Sweet Onion Potato Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This large bag contained mostly large chips, with a yellowish color and lots of bits of green on the surfaces.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice. Sort of like sweet onion with a bit of black pepper.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Taquitos.net has been reviewing snacks for more than 19 years, with nearly 9000 reviews, including 1896 potato chips, 469 barbecue chips and 191 Lay's — so how did we manage to miss a review of the most popular Lay's flavor (other than "Classic") for so many years?
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice, sweet but with some spicy zip to it.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips were fairly wiggly, with some folded-over chips, and they had an orange glow to them, with some bits of seasoning visible on the surfaces.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mostly the usual barbecue chips smell, but with a few extra spices.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Lay's from Taiwan had somewhat wiggly shapes and a light yellow color, appearing almost the same as Original Lay's, but a very close look revealed the very lightest smattering of dark seasoning bits.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like a beef broth.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Most years recently, Lay's has done a "Do Us A Flavor" promotion in which chip fans submit flavor ideas, then Lay's picks some, formulates flavors to match and sells them for a limited time, and finally chip fans get to vote on which one to keep as a permanent flavor. They seem to be doing things a bit differently this year. Despite the appearance of the words "Do Us A Flavor" on the bag, this apparently is not one of those flavors, but rather just a teaser flavor to entice people to submit ideas.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Definitely not like beer. Maybe remotely like bratwurst, a mild mix of nice spices.

snack_name: Lay's Bistro Gourmet Applewood BBQ & Smoked Cheddar Potato Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: I was skeptical when I first heard about these because of their association with Lay's, but the taste has proven me wrong.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: These have a good cheddary, sort of barbecuey, smell.

snack_name: Lay's Bistro Gourmet Sharp Cheddar & Jalapeño Potato Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are good chips, but I should first warn you that they're not particularly hot.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very, very nice cheese smell. No jalapeño that I could notice.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips looked fairly ordinary, with slightly curving shapes that had some small bubbles embedded inside and a light orange color generally, plus a light smattering of darker seasoning bits.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice spicy smell, like a hot soup.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This was one of four international Lay's flavors released under the "Passport to Flavor" sub-brand. Intended to emulate the taste of a Brazilian steak, the chips had a light yellow color and curvy shapes with some bubbles embedded side, plus lots of green seasoning bits on the surfaces.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong, tangy chimichurri smell. Really nice!

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips had orange surfaces, with lots of multicolored flavor powder, and a somewhat wiggly shape, with some folded-over chips. There were a couple of impressively large chips near the top of the bag.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Sweet, tangy and mildly hot. Nice.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Guest reviewer Michael B.
snack_smell_test: From the package:  “The bag you hold in your hands takes you to Southern California, the birthplace of everything cool. From jugglers and weightlifters on Venice Beach to the ultra-trendy shoppers strolling Rodeo Drive, the California lifestyle is the ultimate in cool.”

snack_taste_test: Taste test: In each of the Lay's flavor promotions, there's at least one flavor that has some snackers saying "Ick!" even before they get to taste it. In the last round, it was Chicken & Waffles. For Walkers (the British version of Lay's) it was Cajun Squirrel. Cappuccino wins the prize this time as it competes against Wasabi Ginger, Cheddar Bacon Mac & Cheese and Mango Salsa to become a permanent flavor.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mild coffee smell, but also sweet.

snack_name: Lay's Cheddar & Sour Cream Potato Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These were regular Lay's potato chips with a nuclear orange powder on them. Seriously, you might need to wear sunglasses when eating these.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like normal Lay's chips, no cheddar smell. I guess that's a good thing.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This entry in the Lay's Do Us A Flavor contest was much anticipated, as mac & cheese is a favorite comfort food for many, and everything's better with bacon! (Competing flavors in the contest are Cappuccino, Wasabi Ginger and Mango Salsa.) The chips had somewhat wiggly shapes and were light yellow with an orange glow in many areas, plus some smallish black specks scattered unevenly over the surfaces. We crunched in to find a tasty but mild cheddar taste that wasn't all that different from a lot of other cheese-flavored potato chips. There was a hint of something bacon-like, on the weak side, strong enough to alter how the cheese tasted but not nearly strong enough to really taste like someone put bacon in my mac & cheese. It was a good taste, fairly mild, but not a real close match for the highly craved flavor in the name.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mild cheddar smell, with maybe a hint of smoke but not really bacon.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: When we first spotted these in a supermarket display box proclaiming "New!" we assumed that the Lay's folks had a shorter institutional memory than Taquitos.net. But we later realized that the flavor that we reviewed back in 2007 was Jalapeño Cheddar, not Cheddar Jalapeño, so we'll go along and count this as a new flavor.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very strong tangy cheddar smell, not specifically like jalapeno, but the spices really helped to bring out the cheese.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This was a ruffled version of Lay's (but not labeled as Ruffles) from Thailand, with a mix of flavors most commonly found in Ireland. The chips were narrow-rippled and fairly pale yellow in color, but with a bit of an orange glow in the parts with cheese seasoning, plus some specks of green.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice cheddar and sweet onion smell. Great!

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips were part of a 3-flavor limited edition "Do Us A Flavor" promotion from Lay's (along with Chicken & Waffles and Sriracha). I opened the bag to find that the chips didn't have much in the way of seasoning visible on their surfaces, with a very light orange color overall and just a very few specks of black. Many of the chips had bits of skin on their edges, and some had large bubbles embedded inside the potato.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: More cheesy than garlic on the first whiff, but after that, it did smell kind of like garlic bread.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This wasn't the first crab-spiced chip that we've seen from Lay's, as we reviewed one 11 years ago labeled as Crab Spice (with no mention of the Chesapeake) and another one from Russia that did away with most of the spices and focused on the crab.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Similar to Old Bay, but pretty mild as these things go.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This was the most anticipated of the three "Do Us A Flavor" varieties from Lays (the other two were Sriracha and Cheesy Garlic Bread) and unfortunately they disappointed by not tasting much like chicken or waffles, let alone chicken and waffles.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Weird. There's kind of a hint of maple syrup in there, and maybe some fried food or even chicken-like sort of smell, but if I had taken my first whiff without knowing it was supposed to be chicken & waffles, I don't think I would have had any idea what it was.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These chips were crisp, unbroken and fairly large, and they had a decent chile and lime flavor, slightly tangy and without having too much lime.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very, very mild sort of tomato-like smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips (part of the Lay's Passport to Flavor series, along with Greek Tzatziki, Tikka Masala and Brazilian Picanha) had somewhat wiggly shapes, with many bubbles embedded inside, a dark yellow color generally, plus lots of large bits of green on the surfaces.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice mix of spices, a lot like a Chinese chicken dish.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips had a dark orange glow over most of their surfaces, plus some green and red seasoning bits. The amount of seasoning varied from chip to chip, but generally there was a lot of it.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: A hint of hot peppers, but mostly a very creamy smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips had generally a golden yellow color with a slight orange glow from seasoning powder on some of the chips, plus many specks of green and some specks of red-orange.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: On first whiff, I though, not much like a BLT, as I couldn't sense any bacon or lettuce, though maybe a hint of tomato. But as for smelling like a BLT, on second and subsequent whiffs, I thought, maybe yeah.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are the standard Lay's chips.
snack_smell_test: Online store: Buy Lay's on Amazon #ad

snack_taste_test: Taste test: I had no idea what to expect with these, figuring they could be awesome or awful.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very mild guac smell, but mostly like potato chips.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: When I first spotted this bag, I nearly fell out of my chair.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mild, sweet smell. Doesn't really remind me of Old Bay seasoning.

snack_name: Lay's Cracker Barrell Sharp Cheddar Flavor Potato Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: There's nothing really special about these chips.
snack_smell_test: Online store: Buy Lay's on Amazon #ad

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These thin crackers made from potato were rectangular and mostly pale yellow in color, with some areas a slightly less pale orange from the cheddar powder.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: There's some cheddar, but mostly a bland cracker type of smell.

snack_name: Lay's Cracker Crisps Zesty Herb & Parmesan
snack_taste_test: Taste test: In an age when Ritz is making chips, I guess we should have anticipated that Lay's would start to make crackers.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong herb and parm smell, with lots of tomato too, almost like a zesty tomato soup. Good.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips were pale yellow with many large green specks on their surfaces, plus bits of skin of the edges of some of the chips.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mild ranch smell with maybe some dill and on the creamy side.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: After reviewing the Lay's Seaweed Fries from China, we were glad to find that they also have a more conventional flavor. These fries looked generally like real fries, but they had a uniform light yellow color, with no areas of browning, nor any skin at the ends of the pieces — and no seasoning stuff. The pieces varied in length, but generally they were short, which they had to be to fit into each of the five small packets within the larger bag.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong fried potato smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This flavor from the Lay's Do Us A Flavor promotion (competing against Fried Green Tomato and Everything Bagel with Cream Cheese) had me thinking at first, "Haven't we seen this many times before?" before realizing that it's Doritos, not Lay's, that has done 12 different taco flavors. For Lay's, this was indeed the first among 147 varieties.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells mostly like taco powder.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Cucumber-flavored potato chips? This version from China looked to be a whole new thing for Lay's!
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Definitely a cucumber-like smell, maybe some other spices in there too.

snack_name: Lay's Deep Dish Pizza Flavor Inspired By Giordano's
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This flavor from the Tastes of America line wasn't the first time that Lay's did a pizza flavor — north of the border, they did a Toronto College Street Pizza flavor for the Tastes of Canada line in 2003, and in the not-really-potato-chips department, there was a Pizza-flavored Lay's Stax in 2005.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like a jar of Ragu.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips from Taiwan had deep, angular ridges and a slightly orangish yellow color, with a light smattering of green seasoning bits.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice smoky bacon smell, like bacon fresh off the grilled.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This bag contained potato chips with wide, angular ripples and kind of a light orange glow overall but not much seasoning powder visible on the surfaces.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like a garlicy fish stew.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips from Taiwan were generally small and had very deep, wide ripples with almost sawtooth-wave shapes. The chips had a strong yellow color generally and a very light smattering of dark seasoning powder. Some of the chips had areas of dark skin on the edges.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Kind of a crab-like smell, not fishy in a bad way.

snack_name: Lay's Deep Ridged Tender Chicken with Pepper
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips had wide, angular ripples and a light yellow color, with a light smattering of fine seasoning bits of various colors, plus some dark areas of skin on the edges.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice mix of intense spices, similar to the various Lay's seafood chips.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips had a light yellow color, with just a few slight bits of skin around the edges, and the bag had lots and lots of large, unbroken chips, including several that were downright huge.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice potato smell. Fresh.

snack_name: Lay's Dill Pickle Chips (Cornichons à L'aneth Croustilles)
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These have a mild pickle taste, with a good balance of spices.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like a pickle, like the ones in a McDonald's hamburger.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are good pickle chips with an excellent crispness and a good pickle taste.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very authentic pickley smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Durian snacks have achieved a legendary status here at Taquitos.net, because we've heard almost nothing but bad things about the taste and smell of this Asian fruit, and yet some people actually eat the stuff. Our encounter with wafers containing durian did not go well.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Definitely smells like durian, which is to say, just awful.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This soccer-themed bag of potato chips from Thailand contained narrow-rippled chips with gentle curves and a light orange color.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong tangy smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips had generally flat shapes, including some folded-over chips, with bubbles and embedded inside. The surfaces had a smattering of bright orange seasoning, plus some darker seasoning bits. After enjoying the fiery habanero flavor of Doritos, we were hoping that the same level of heat and flavor would be delivered in this Lay’s version. The flames depicted on the bag had us optimistic.
snack_smell_test: Smell test:  A potato smell with some sort of spices, but not specifically habanero.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These were pretty hot potato chips.
snack_smell_test: From the package:  “Get ready for a sizzle of a flavor that will set your mouth on fire. Dive into a red hot blaze of fiery crunch with LAYS® brand Flamin'® Hot Flavor Potato Chips”

snack_name: Lay's Flamin' Hot Dill Pickle Remix
snack_taste_test: Taste test: We've reviewed lots of hot pepper chips as well as a whole bunch of pickle-flavored ones, but ones that combine both flavors are pretty rare — and usually confined to Chicago-area potato chip brands such as Jays. Now Lay's has brought the idea national.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Wow, lots of intense pickle! Couldn't really notice the Flamin' Hot aspect.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This flavor joins Carnitas Street Taco, New York Pizza, Philly Cheesesteak and Nashville Hot Chicken in the Flavor Icons line, promising to deliver Cocina Azul of Albuquerque's version of the Mexican dish. (I've eaten Chile Relleno and even been to Albuquerque, but not to that restaurant.)
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mild, creamy.

snack_name: Lay's Flavor Icons Kettle Cooked New York Style Pizza
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips were based on a pizza place near the Brooklyn Bridge where I ate a few slices once, years ago. I've eaten a lot of pizza and don't remember anything specific about that one, so it didn't make any huge impression on me.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Pretty mild, like some pizza spices and maybe a bit of tomato, but not really that much like a pizza.

snack_name: Lay's Flavor Icons Nashville Hot Chicken
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This restaurant-inspired Lay's flavor is based on a chicken recipe that started in Nashville and is growing in popularity all over the place, and specifically it's based on a particular restaurant in Nashville's version of it. The chips had curvy, somewhat bubbly shapes similar to most Lay's flavors, with various shades of light orange on most of the surfaces, plus a smattering of small darker bits scattered fairly evenly throughout.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Intense and very nice, could well pass for a very heavily spiced fried chicken.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This member of the Flavor Icons line from Lay's went for the flavor of Philadelphia's favorite sandwich, available at many spots throughout the City of Brotherly Love, but the recipe was supposed to be based specifically on Geno's Steaks in South Philly. (During four years living in Philadelphia, I ate a good number of cheesesteaks from several different restaurants — the majority from Abner's at 38th and Chestnut — but never actually ate one from Geno's, nor from their famous neighbor Pat's.)
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice. Can smell the cheese, maybe a bit of onion, with maybe a meat broth thing going too, so at least in the same league as a cheesesteak.

snack_name: Lay's Flavor Icons Wavy Carnitas Street Taco
