snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips (which are joined in the Flavor Icons line by  Chile Relleno, New York Pizza, Philly Cheesesteak and Nashville Hot Chicken) had a flavor based on California Mexican restaurant chain El Torito's recipe. The chips had wide ripples and a strong yellow color, plus lots of large seasoning bits on the surfaces. I'm a big taco fan, though I've never eaten at El Torito, so I was eager to try them.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very intense on first whiff, then more like some sort of charred meat.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This flavor was released as part of the Lay's Flavor Swap promotion, which paired up four sets of two flavors, one an existing product and one a new one, for a head-to-head online competition to (supposedly) determine which one stays and which one goes. Korean Barbecue was the new one matched up against Honey Barbecue.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Definitely something there, but really mild. Kind of like a mildly fruity barbecue sauce.

snack_name: Lay's Flavor Swap Smoked Gouda & Chive
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips were part of a Lay's "Flavor Swap" promotion that matched them up against Cheddar & Sour Cream in a battle for survival on the snack shelf.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice tangy gouda smell. Mmmmm!

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This Lay's flavor was far from the first one with "Crab" in the name, as we've previously reviewed Chesapeake Bay Crab Spice, just plain Crab Spice, Deep Ridged Spicy Crab, Thai Spicy Crab and Kраб (which is Russian for crab).
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice mix of fishiness and hot spices, a little kick.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips from the Lay's Tastes of America series had a nice yellow color with some areas of browning, topped with a light smattering of green seasoning bits.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice savory smell, but I could notice neither pickles nor ranch dressing.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This new flavor from Lay's consisted of somewhat wiggly chips with a fair helping of orange-red seasoning (not quite as dark as the ones pictured on the bag) and some some specks of green.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very sweet tomato smell.

snack_name: Lay's Go Snacks Crisps Sour Cream & Onion
snack_taste_test: Taste test: Oh my God these are incredible! These are crisp-like snacks with a great Sour Cream & Onion flavor.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: A pretty good aroma that kind of smelled like sour cream.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This flavor was formerly a "Do Us A Flavor" limited edition for Canada, but now it has arrived in the USA, with no indication on the bag of being limited. (Also in Canada, Humpty Dumpty has done a Grilled Cheese & Ketchup flavor.)
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like a mild version of BBQ chips. A hint of tomato in there, but I'm not getting the cheese.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This flavor of Lay's (one of several new seafood varieties from China that we've found recently) looked like ordinary Classic Lay's with various shades of yellow, fairly flat shapes and no visible seasoning power. And yet, they promised to taste like grilled eel!
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Just slightly fishy, not really in a bad way.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips from China had wide, angular ripples and colors ranging from light yellow to light orange, with a very light smattering of darker bits.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong seasoned meat flavor, could certainly pass for pork.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips had a thick cut and wide, angular ripples, with a strong yellow color and some areas of browning, plus an uneven smattering of seasoning powder of various colors.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Kind of does smell like grilled squid.

snack_name: Lay's Half Sour Cucumber with Dill
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This bag of Lay's from Russia contained thin potato chips with a strong yellow color, some areas of skin around the edges and a light smattering of green bits of dill on the surfaces.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells exactly like a jar of half sour pickles. Great!

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips from Taiwan, themed on one of the islands of Japan, had gently curving shapes with some scattered bumps and bubbles, plus a somewhat uneven application of bright orange seasoning on the otherwise light yellow surfaces.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mild cheese smell, nice.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are good kettle chips.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good, potatoey kettle chip smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are pretty good barbecue chips.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Wow, very, very, very nice barbecue smell. It smells like really good barbecue sauce.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips had a pale yellow color, with no seasoning powder visible, plus some bits of skin at the edges.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Not very strong. Just a little mustard, and even less honey.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Lay's had a bright orange seasoning, unevenly applied, on parts of the otherwise yellow chips, with many specks of black seasoning as well. Years ago, Lay's offered a KC Masterpiece Hot 'n Spicy BBQ flavor, but this was apparently a new flavor, without the KC Masterpiece.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Not really hot, but still tangier than your typical barbecue seasoning.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are quite a bit hotter than your standard barbecue chips, and they taste pretty good.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: BBQ chip smell, but you can tell that there's some kick to it.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This bag from Thailand contained narrow-rippled potato chips with a light orange color, with just a bit of seasoning visible inside the ripples and some skin on parts of the edges. Yes, you heard that right: rippled Lay's, not Ruffles. Most of the chips were fairly small.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Kind of the fish food smell, but not that strong.

snack_name: Lay's India's Lime 'n' Masala Masti Flavour
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips looked a lot more like Ruffles than Lay's, as they had narrow ripples, but that didn't matter a whole lot, as the key thing here was the seasoning.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice mix of Indian spices. Great.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These narrow-rippled potato chips had a lot of seasoning on them, with sort of an orange-brown color, plus some specks of green. The big question when we crunched in was how the "Magic" version would differ from the Lime & Masala flavor.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice mix of Indian spices. Remotely like curry.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This Lay's flavor from China presented a somewhat mystifying flavor name in Italian Red Meat (kind of like their excellent Mexican Tomato Chicken). I just didn't know what it meant!
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice, kind of reminded me of Russet potato chips.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This special variety of Lay's came in a large bag, and upon opening it, I saw that the bag was filled nearly to the top, with some very large, unbroken chips right at the top.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice mild mix of spices.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips (not to be confused with the more recent Lay's Cheddar Jalapeño) were cut thin and had a nice orange glow from the jalapeno cheddar flavor powder. They had a pretty good crispness and a generous helping of flavor powder, with a good mix of jalapeno and cheddar, just slightly hot but still nicely tasty.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good cheddar smell, with a bit of jalapeno.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This Russian bag of Lay's contained smallish chips with a nice yellow color and without much in the way of seasoning powder that we could see. There were occasional bits of dark skin on the edges of the chips, but not a lot. Despite the bag's travels aboard some airplane flights from Moscow to Texas and then a postal voyage to Massachusetts, the chips were largely unbroken.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very mid spices. Could not smell any crab.

snack_name: Lay's KC Masterpiece Barbecue Potato Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips had a pretty good barbecue flavor. They were better than the Baked Lay's KC Masterpiece and had less kick than the KC Masterpiece Hot 'n Spicy version.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice barbecue sauce smell.

snack_name: Lay's KC Masterpiece Hot 'n Spicy BBQ Potato Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These were regular Lay's potato chips with the KC Masterpiece Hot 'n Spicy style barbecue powder on them.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Barbecue powder wafts up from the bag.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This flavor, part of the Lay's Tastes of America series, was hardly the first time that we've seen the Lay's brand on a bag of ketchup flavored snacks, as their Ketchup Potato Chips in Canada have been around forever, and they've also used the Lay's brand for these ketchup-flavored potato sticks in Poland. We even found one variation in the USA before, as six years ago we reviewed Spicy Ketchup potato chips.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice strong ketchup smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are really good ketchup chips.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like ketchup.

snack_name: Lay's Kettle Cooked 40% Less Fat Applewood Smoked BBQ
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips had wiggly, irregular shapes with some bubbles, and they were generally smallish, with a mild orange glow from the flavor seasoning.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: The usual barbecue powder smell. Nothing special.

snack_name: Lay's Kettle Cooked 40% Less Fat Cream Cheese & Chive
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips had very wiggly shapes with many bubbles embedded inside, generally a pale yellow color and lots of skin along their edges. The surfaces had a good smattering of green seasoning bits of various sizes.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mild chive and cream cheese smell.

snack_name: Lay's Kettle Cooked 40% Less Fat Jalapeño Cheddar
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips had very wiggly shapes, with many bubbles embedded inside and an overall color ranging from yellow to a fairly bright orange. There were some green bits of seasoning unevenly spread across the surfaces.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mild cheese smell. No jalapeno.

snack_name: Lay's Kettle Cooked 40% Less Fat Sun-Dried Tomato & Parmesan
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips had very wiggly shapes, with a golden yellow color, mostly green seasoning powder with some orange mixed in, and a good helping of skin around the edges.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Tangy tomato and cheese smell.

snack_name: Lay's Kettle Cooked Classic Beer Cheese
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips had wiggly shapes, many folded-over, and a nice golden yellow color, with a light smattering of small, dark seasoning bits.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice cheese smell, but not at all like beer.

snack_name: Lay's Kettle Cooked Creamy Queso & Salsa
snack_taste_test: Taste test: The potato chips had a wiggly shape, with many small pieces in the bag.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Remotely salsa-like smell. OK.

snack_name: Lay's Kettle Cooked Crinkle Cut Original
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These chips had a combination that's very rare in the snack business: they were both kettle-cooked and rippled.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: The same oily smell that's typical of kettle-cooked chips.

snack_name: Lay's Kettle Cooked Everything Bagel with Cream Cheese
snack_taste_test: Taste test: Lay's always makes some flavors you'd never expect on a potato chip for their annual "Do Us A Flavor" contest, but Everything Bagel is even farther from my expectations than usual! Luckily, I've eaten lots of everything bagels with cream cheese, so I'm in a good position to judge whether they got this flavor right. (The other two flavors in the current promotion are Fried Green Tomato and Crispy Taco.)
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mostly like potato. Couldn't really smell "everything."

snack_name: Lay's Kettle Cooked Extra Crunchy Jalapeño Potato Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are very crisp kettle-style chips with a kind of weak jalapeño flavor and minimal jalapeño heat.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good medium-strength jalapeño smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: For years, on and off, there was a Flamin' Hot version of Lay's, and now they've brought the flavor to the crunchier Kettle Cooked chips. The chips had wiggly shapes with lots of bubbles embedded inside, with various levels of reddish orange seasoning, allowing select areas of the paler yellow chip surfaces to show through.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Just mildly hot, can smell the potato too.

snack_name: Lay's Kettle Cooked Four Cheese Extra Crunchy Potato Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This bag contained generally smallish, wiggly chips, some folder over or stuck together, with lots of small green specks on them.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: More like herbs than cheese.

snack_name: Lay's Kettle Cooked Garden Tomato & Asiago
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips had a strong yellow color and wiggly shapes, including some folded-over chips, with lots of red and green seasoning on the surfaces.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong tomato smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This entry in the Lay's Do Us A Flavor promotion (released alongside Truffles Fries, New York Reuben and Southern Biscuits and Gravy) promised to taste like a sandwich stuffed with the tasty Greek meat and lots of fixin's.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Weird. Weird. Weird.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips were generally smallish and had wiggle shapes, and there appeared to be a fairly generous helping of ranch seasonong on them.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells almost like salt and pepper chips, not really ramch.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips had wiggly shapes and a light orange color, with a smattering of dark seasoning bits.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice sweet smell with some mild peppers.

snack_name: Lay's Kettle Cooked Indian Tikka Masala
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This Lay's flavor — part of the "Passport to Flavor" promotion, along with Brazilian Picanha — wasn't even the first masala-flavored Lay's, as we've eaten. However, Magic Masala and India's Lime 'n' Masala were imported from India, whereas this one was made for the American market.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Zesty mix of Indian spice. Strong.

snack_name: Lay's Kettle Cooked Lattice Cut Aged Cheddar & Black Pepper
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These cross-rippled potato chips (introduced by Lay's along with a garlic & sea salt flavor) had a middling level of bits of black pepper adhering mostly inside the ripples, with some nearly-white cheese powder on the surfaces too, for an overall color that was a fairly pale shade of yellow.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mild pepper and even milder cheddar, but pretty nice!

snack_name: Lay's Kettle Cooked Lattice Cut Roasted Garlic & Sea Salt
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This new line of potato chips from Lay's had a two-way ripple cut that followed in in the footsteps of similar chips from Herr's (who use the name waffle cut) and Cape Cod (using the same name lattice cut). The double ripples seemed a bit narrower and less deep than the Herr's and Cape Cod versions, so there were fewer and smaller holes where the opposing-angle top and bottom ripples intercepted. The chips had a light yellow color with some bits of dark skin on some of the edges.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mild, sweet garlic smell. Nice.

snack_name: Lay's Kettle Cooked Medleys Sea Salt
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These chips appeared to have the same three colors of potatoes — dark purple, light purple and yellow — as the Old Glories from Saratoga chips, but thankfully Lay's played the color combination as a "medley" rather than claiming it was red, white and blue like Saratoga did.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice rich potato smell, a lot like Kettle Chips brand.

snack_name: Lay's Kettle Cooked Olive Oil & Herbs
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This new flavor was part of the Lay's Flavor Swap promotion, pitting it against the (also kettle-cooked) Sea Salt & Cracked Pepper flavor for survival on the chip aisle shelf.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Definitely different from Salt & Pepper chips, a nice mild olive oil and herb smell.

snack_name: Lay's Kettle Cooked Olive Oil & Herbs Lightly Salted
snack_taste_test: Taste test: A year ago, Lay's introduced several pairs of "Flavor Swap" varieties — one existing flavor and a new one sold concurrently and often displayed on the same shelf — with the claim that one of each pair would stay and the other be eliminated, based on an online vote. Brand-new Olive Oil & Herbs was pitted against longtime flavor Sea Salt & Cracked Pepper. But this reappearing flavor added the large words "Lighted Salted" to the bag, so it would be a bit inconsistent for this to be the result of the flavor swap. Plus, they're still selling Sea Salt & Cracked Pepper.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice mix of herbs. Mmmm.

snack_name: Lay's Kettle Cooked Sea Salt & Cracked Pepper
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These chips were fairly pale yellow in color and very wiggly, with bits of skin around the edges and many bits of black pepper on the surfaces.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong, sharp, fresh pepper smell. Good.

snack_name: Lay's Kettle Cooked Sea Salt & Vinegar Extra Crunchy Potato Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips and had the wiggly shape typical of kettle-cooked potato chips, and upon biting in, there was a good crunch and a definite vinegar flavor, but not a very strong one.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Medium-strength vinegar smell but not a real zing. Decent.

snack_name: Lay's Kettle Cooked Spicy Cayenne & Cheese
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These chips were smallish, wiggly and had a mild orange glow, with bits of green seasoning.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mild spicy cheese smell, very good.

snack_name: Lay's Kettle Cooked Sweet Chili & Sour Cream
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These kettle-cooked potato chips had a good crunch and an excellent flavoring, as they were easily the best we've tried among the Lay's Kettle Cooked lineup.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice potato smell with some peppers. Reminds me of Kettle Chips.

snack_name: Lay's Kettle Cooked Sweet Chili & Sour Cream 40% Less Fat
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This wasn't exactly a new Lay's flavor, as we gave an extremely positive review to the Kettle Cooked Sweet Chili & Sour Cream chips almost nine years ago, but this time they brought it back in a "40% less fat" version, so we needed to see if it was as good as the "100% as much fat" version.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice, really can smell the spicy chilies and sour cream.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This bold flavor from Lay's was one of four finalists in the "Do Us A Flavor" promotion, along with Cheddar Bacon Mac & Cheese, Mango Salsa and Cappuccino.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very mild ginger smell. That's all.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This unusual flavor from Lay's came in gently curving shapes with very narrow ripples. The chips had a light orange color overall but no bits of seasoning powder visible.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Really nice, wow!

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips from Taiwan looked a lot like regular Lay's, with gently curving shapes and a nice yellow color, and it took a very close look to see the very light application of tiny seasoning powder. One of the chips was quite big, and several others were also larger than your typical American Lay's in a small bag.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice tangy smell, maybe remotely pork-like.

snack_name: Lay's Kosher for Passover Salted Potato Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: Passover is a time of year when some rarely-spotted potato chip brands such as Glicks, Manischewitz and Lieber's suddenly appear in supermarkets, but this was the first time that I found a special version of Lay's. These potato chips had a bright yellow color, with some more golden yellow spots on a few chips, and there was almost no skin around the edges. The chips had just a bit of wiggle to them.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice potato smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips had a pale yellow color and a lot of bits of green seaweed on their surfaces.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice mild mix of spices. Only vaguely seaweed-like.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: The regular variety of Lay's is a salty and somewhat greasy chip, so we were eager to try the lightly salted version.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like potato chips, but with less salt.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips had a pale yellow color, with somewhat wiggly shapes, some bubbles embedded inside and many smallish green bits scattered over the surfaces. For some reason, I was feeling lime-skepical, so I decided to check out the ingredients before opening the bag. Lime was not actually among them!
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Kind of a mild lime juice smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips from China had gently curving shapes, many of them nearly flat, with a strong yellow color and the very sparsest application of green seasoning bits, hard to notice until we looked closely. Some of the chips had areas of browning on the edges.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very slight lime smell, not sharp at all.

snack_name: Lay's Limón Tangy Lime Flavored Potato Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: Absolutely awful.
snack_smell_test: From the package:  “We've blended a unique sweet and sour seasoning combination with real tangy lime and put it on a crispy LAY'S® brand potato chip to create an irresistible snacking experience.”

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This Thailand-produced version of Lay's Potato Chips had a very light orange color, with a very, very sparse amount of flavor seasoning visible, just a few tiny dark orange specks per chip.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Kind of weird mix of spices. Not really lobstery, and not really fishy either.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Lay's consisted of narrow-rippled potato chips with a pale yellow color and what appeared to be a typical sour cream and onion seasoning, with little bits of green scattered among the ripples.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Not much, just some very mild spices.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This rippled version of Lay's from India featured deep, wide, angular ripples, with a strong orange color on the surfaces and an occasional bit of dark skin along the edges.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very tangy and sweet, maybe a bit citrusy.

snack_name: Lay's Maxx Macho Chilli Potato Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Lay's from India had ripples — and wide ones — but they were indeed labeled as Lay's, not Ruffles. The chips had a golden yellow color, without much seasoning powder visible.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Tangy, sweet barbecue smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips from India had wide, deep, angular ripples, with a light orange color on most of the surfaces, plus some darker orange spots here and there.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice strong barbecue smell. Lots of paprika.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips had a light yellow color and somewhat wiggly shapes, with just a slight smattering (lighter than pictured on the bag) of green and red seasoning bits.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: So nice! Just a perfect blend of olive oil, herbs and spices.

snack_name: Lay's Memphis Barbecue Flavored Potato Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are pretty good barbecue chips.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice sweet barbecue smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: I've enjoyed lots of Mexican food in my time, including many dishes that included tomato and chicken, but the term "Mexican Tomato Chicken" was brand new to me when I spotted this bag of Lay's from China. I opened the bag to find that the chips had somewhat wiggly shapes with lots of bubbles embedded inside, with a pale yellow color generally, plus lots of browning in various places, particularly near the edges. I had to look very closely to notice some very sparsely applied orange seasoning bits.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Kind of like a standard BBQ chip smell, maybe a hint of chicken.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These chips had a flavor based on a Thai dish called Mieng Kam Krob Ros, but when I Googled it, most things were about this very snack, so the circular reference didn't help me to understand the intended flavor. The picture on the bag provided some clues, as it showed sliced limes, green and red peppers, cheese cubes and shrimp. The chips had curvy, somewhat bumpy shapes with a bright yellow color, plus a smattering of green bits.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very mild. Could mostly smell the potato, with maybe a slight hint of something fishy.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips from China were generally roundish and large, with some bumps and bubbles on the surfaces, showing a light yellow color generally, plus a light smattering of dark seasoning bits of various colors. There was some light potato skin on many areas of the edges.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong, tangy mix of seasonings. Could pass for a heavily seasoned chicken.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This Lay's flavor from Thailand promised a Namtok flavor, which is apparently a spicy beef salad from northeastern Thailand. The chips had a a light orange/yellow color, with gently curving surfaces and not much in the way of seasoning visible.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice mix of meat and spices.

snack_name: Lay's Natural  Thick Cut Sea Salted Potato Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: You will probably find these chips in the health food section of the store, as Frito-Lay goes 'natural' with some of their famous brand names.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: A dry potato aroma.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: In name at least, this flavor was probably the most shocking to see on a potato chip out of the eight regional flavors in the Lay's Tastes of America promotion — and they just happened to send this one to my region. It promised the taste of a buttered lobster roll, but a pre-eating reading of the ingredients revealed no actual lobster inside.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice savory smell, but not particularly lobster-y.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This limited-time flavor was released along with Greektown Gyro, West Coast Truffle Fries and Southern Biscuits and Gravy as part of the 2015 edition of Lay's Do Us A Flavor promotion.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Really does smell like a Reuben — like corned beer and sauerkraut. Even a hint of pickle!

snack_name: Lay's Numb & Spicy Hot Pot Flavor
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Lay's from China jumped right out and screamed "Buy me!" as soon as I saw the "Numb & Spicy" name. What does that even mean? I had no idea, other than that I needed to eat some.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Wow, whatever peppers they used here had a different kind of zing than anything else we've tried. A real kick in the face. Impressive.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This Taiwanese version of Lay's Potato Chips looked pretty much like the American version we're accustomed to, featuring a pale yellow color with some more golden areas, a thin cut, just a few bits of skin around the edges, and no visible seasoning powder.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Fairly mild potato smell, but good.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This was the Thai version of Lay's Potato Chips, and the main difference between these and the Lay's we're accustomed to was that these were narrow-rippled instead of flat.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Regular potato chips smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Lays from Taiwan very helpfully provided a picture of the soup bowl whose taste it was trying to emulate. I opened the bag to find that the chips looked fairly ordinary, with a gently curving shapes and a pale yellow color on the potato chips' surfaces — and barely any seasoning powder visible.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Some very tangy spices with moderate heat.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips had an orange-yellow color with lots of red and green spots of seasoning.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Kind of like relish.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips looked very nice, as the large, unbroken chips had lots of reddish seasoning on their surfaces, plus some green spots.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very mild salsa smell, but nice.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This flavor from the Tastes of America series wasn't the first pimento-flavored chip we've had, as Zapp's had a really good one earlier this year.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice strong, sweet cheddar smell.

snack_name: Lay's Potato Chips Tokyo Braised Goose Meat
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips had narrow ripples and gently curving shapes, with a pale yellow color plus some areas of light red or brownish seasoning.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice tangy smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips from China had wide, angular ripples, with light orange color generally, plus some sparse dark seasoning powder. "Pure Spice" is a new phrase to us — other than the words and the chili pepper pictured on the bag, we didn't know what "Pure Spice" meant, so we were eager to give the flavor a try.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mild flavor, tangy but not much of it.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips from China had wide, angular ripples and a bit of an orange glow in places, with other areas more strictly yellow.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Slightly ketchupy tomato smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This narrow-rippled flavor of Lay's from Taiwan had chips with a light yellow color plus an orange glow in many areas. Many of the chips in the midsize bag were fairly large.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Kind of like sour cream and cheddar, fairly sharp.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This snack broke the rules of both Lay's and potato chips in general.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice spicy barbecue smell. Great.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Lay's from China had deep, wide ripples and a strong yellow color, with a good smattering of seasoning on the surfaces.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Some intense spices for this chicken. One person standing nearby thought it smelled like Indian food.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These were like the regular Lay's Potato Chips with a slathering of pepper on them (lots of black pepper flakes).
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Slight pepper aroma, but they smell more like regular Lay's chips.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are good chips.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: A nice vinegary smell.

snack_name: Lay's Salt & Vinegar Potato Chips (Sel et Vinaigre Croustilles)
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are good salt and vinegar chips.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong vinegar smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips had gently curving shapes and a slight orange glow in their yellow surfaces, with some very sparse seasoning powder. I crunched in to find a light crunch and a somewhat strange but remotely egg-like flavor, with definitely some additional spices in there too, transitioning soon into a moderately hot taste and lingering aftertaste as the peppers took over.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Wow, it does smell like egg. Nice.

snack_name: Lay's Sea Salt & Black Pepper Flavor
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips from China had gently curving shapes with some bubbles embedded inside, showing a light yellow color generally, plus a medium smattering of seasoning bits, most of which looked to be crushed black pepper.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice mix of spices, pepper among them, but definitely more.

snack_name: Lay's Sea Salt & Pepper Potato Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These salt and pepper potato chips reminded me a lot of the Utz salt & pepper chips as they had a very similar taste, bringing out not just the crushed black pepper taste, but also a hint of vinegar and a mix of other spices.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice, with black pepper, but also vinegary.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These chips had a light yellow color and gently curving surfaces, with a smattering of dark, very small seasoning bits on the surfaces.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Pretty mild as pepper chips go, and definitely some other spices in there too, but actually pretty nice.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This bag of fries was unusual in several ways, starting with the fact that they were fries at all under the Lay's brand. Next, it turned out that the bag contained five smaller bags (with similar designs to the main one), which is unusual for both fry-shapes shapes and the Lay's brand.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong seaweed smell.

snack_name: Lay's Sensations Lime & Black Pepper Kettle Cooked Potato Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These kettle-style potato chips had a lot of flavoring powder on them.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: You can smell the pepper when you open the bag. You can't smell the lime.

snack_name: Lay's Sensations Sweet Chili & Sour Cream Kettle Cooked Potato Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These chips were very crunchy with a sweet taste, more like a sweet barbecue chip than a sour cream and chili combination.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like sour cream more than chili, surprisingly.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are excellent thin potato chips with tons of bacon taste.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very good bacon aroma.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Depending on the bag you get, it can be a heavenly mixture of sour cream, onion and potato, or it can be a little too salty.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Oniony.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: When Lay's chooses flavors for their Do Us A Flavor contests, they tend to have some shock value, and they're usually flavors that haven't been tried previously on a potato chip. For example: Cappuccino. Those things were mostly the case for the four flavors this time around as well, with the other three being Greektown Gyro, West Coast Truffle Fries and  New York Reuben. To most snackers we talked to, this kind seemed as oddball as the others, but if you follow our reviews closely, you noticed that they actually missed the originality factor on this one. Larry the Cable Guy is known for his stand-up comedy and acting in some Pixar films, but he also lends his name to a line of potato chips, including a Biscuits & Gravy flavor introduced a year ago.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Kind of a like a black peppery gravy.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips had a mustardy-looking yellow color, with lots of seasoning bits of various sizes on the surfaces, most of it greenish (so the actual chips didn't much resemble the plain-looking ones shown on the front of the bag).
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong, mostly chili powder, but other stuff too.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Here we found another rippled version of Lay's (not labeled as Ruffles) from India, just like the Magic Masala flavor. She chips had narrow, shallow ripples and had a nice orange glow to them, with lots of seasoning powder all over.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice spicy tomato smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This flavor of Lay's (not to be confused with the non-spicy Ketchup flavor available in Canada) had some orange-red seasoning unevenly applied across the chips (though less of this seasoning than the picture on the bag showed), plus some green spots.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like regular ketchup, nothing particularly spicy about it.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Lay's Potato Chips from Taiwan had narrow ripples and gently curving shapes, with a light yellow color in some places and some orange seasoning powder in others.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mild pepper smell, plus a hint of potato.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Lay's from Taiwan, which we found alongside the Spicy! Sha Sha flavor, featured yellow chips with somewhat wiggly shapes and lots of large bits of green on the surfaces, along with smaller bits of other colors.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mild seaweed smell. Not spicy.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips from Taiwan looked a lot like regular Lay's, with gently curving shapes and some bubbles embedded inside, without much seasoning powder visible but with a light orange glow throughout.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very zesty, a definite kick of heat.

snack_name: Lay's Spring Limited Edition Cherry Blossom Cow Milk Flavor
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This Lay's flavor from China looked like ordinary potato chips, with somewhat wiggly shapes that included some bubbles and a light yellow color on the surfaces, with no obvious seasoning powder.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Sweet and slightly fruity, but also kind of reminded me of Frosted Flakes.

snack_name: Lay's Spring Limited Edition Vitality and White Peach Flavor
snack_taste_test: Taste test: We found this bag of Lay's from China on the shelf alongside the Cherry Cow Milk flavor, and when we opened the bag, these chips didn't look any different from those, nor really any different from Lays Classic — they looked like just plain potato chips.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Can definitely smell the peach.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These hot sauce-flavored chips from Lay's (introduced along with Cheesy Garlic Bread and Chicken & Waffles for the "Do Us A Flavor" promotion) had a nice orange glow overall, with a sparse covering of some dark bits of seasoning. Most of the chips were somewhat wiggly, with a few bits of skin on the edges.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very mild. Not any real kick of hot sauce, especially considering the garlic and hot pepper pictured on the bag.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips had wide, pointy ripples, with a strong yellow color and some areas of browning. There was hardly any seasoning powder visible, but a close look revealed a few dark bits.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Fairly strong smell of beef broth.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This bag contained some nicely crisp potato sticks — the first time we've seen the Lay's brand used for potato sticks.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice tomatoey ketchup smell.

snack_name: Lay's StrEATs of the World Taco
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These chips from Canada had somewhat wiggly shapes with lots of bubbles embedded inside, plus a strong yellow color topped with lots of smallish green seasoning bits. We've seen a number of taco-flavored snacks from Frito-Lay, but mostly within the Doritos brand — the only other Taco-flavored Lay's were Crispy Taco in 2017's Do Us A Flavor promotion in the USA.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very zesty, could easily pass for seasoned taco meat.

snack_name: Lay's Strong холодец c хреном (Holodets with Horseradish)
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This Russian flavor of Lay's tried to duplicate the flavor of holodets (which is apparently sort of like a meat broth suspended inside gelatin) with horseradish — a Russian dish that we've never eaten but we found via some googling that many visitors to Russia don't find to be so delicious.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Pretty weird. On first whiff, I thought it was like a beef broth, but when I tried again, sort of like cabbage soup.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: My expectations for this new flavor from Lay's were very, very high, because the cashier at the hospital gift shop told me (unsolicited) that these chips are really good.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Standard barbecue chips smell. Nothing like Buffalo wings.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These chips were quite tasty, but nobody could quite place what exactly the flavor was.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice mix of spices, but not particularly like Teriyaki.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These Lay's were narrow-rippled (kind of like Ruffles used to be, before they widened the ripples) unlike most Lay's, which are not rippled at all, and they had some dark green flakes scattered over their rippled surfaces. The chips varied in color from yellow to brownish yellow, with no skin around the edges.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice sharp basil smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips had a pale yellow color with lots of bits of green on them, a little bit of skin on the edges, and some folded-over chips.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice, mild sweet smell, but onions weren't the first thing that came to mind. More like garlic.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: I found these just days after discovering the Hot & Spicy Barbecue flavor from Lay's, so I was very interested to see how the two compared. These looked very much like the other kind, with a very similar orange coloration, but there were fewer tiny black specks on the Southern Heat ones.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Sweet and very tangy barbecue smell. Made my mouth water.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Full disclosure here, I'm not a big fan of Swiss cheese, so I was skepical that I'd like the flavor of this Taiwanese version of Lay's.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Not really all that cheesy, really not much aroma.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips had a golden yellow color and a fair amount of dark reddish flavor seasoning on their surfaces, with many wiggly chips and some fairly large unbroken ones.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Really nice sweet and tangy barbecue sauce smell. Quite good!

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are good chips, with a nice, mild salsa flavor.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells kind of like ketchup chips.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips were fairly large and wiggly, and they had a nice bright glow from the generous amount of orange/red seasoning on their surfaces. There wasn't any skin on the edges of the chips.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong, sweet potato/lime/hot sauce smell. Nice.

snack_name: Lay's Taro Chips with Sea Salt and Black Pepper
snack_taste_test: Taste test: The Lay's brand is pretty much synonymous with potato chips (except for that one time we found Lay's Yam Chips), but now they're using it for chips made from at least one other root vegetable, taro (which we would most closely associate with Terra Chips).
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Not at all the usual black pepper smell. Maybe the slightest hint of that mixed in with garlic and other spices.

snack_name: Lay's Tastes of America Chicago Steakhouse Loaded Baked Potato Potato Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These chips are pretty good, I expect a lot when I see "baked potato" in the flavor.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: A slight bacony aroma.

snack_name: Lay's Tastes of America Monterey Pepper Jack Potato Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: I'm not big on monterery pepper jack as a cheese gourmet, so am unclear about whether these actually taste like that flavor of cheese.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: There's an aroma there but I can't place it. Slighty cheesy?

snack_name: Lay's Tastes of America San Antonio Salsa Artificially Flavored Potato Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These have a very good but not overpowering salsa flavor, and they were quite a hit around the chip bowl.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice barbecue smell.

snack_name: Lay's Tastes of America Santa Fe Ranch
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These ranch chips were crisp and tasted quite good.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice creamy ranch smell.

snack_name: Lay's Tastes of America Southwestern Jalapeno Cheddar
snack_taste_test: Taste test: The many potato chips in this bag were generally smallish, and most of them were broken, with an unevenly applied orange seasoning and some tiny green spots.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very mild cheese smell, just the slightest hint of jalapeno.

snack_name: Lay's Tastes of America Wisconsin Cheddar Flavored Potato Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are good chips.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Sort of cheddary, not bad.

snack_name: Lay's Tastes of Canada Cape Breton Sea Salt & Pepper
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are delicious, excellent potato chips.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice black pepper smell, makes your mouth water a little.

snack_name: Lay's Tastes of Canada Toronto College Street Pizza
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are pretty good chips.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Wow, it really does smell like pizza.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips from China had a nice yellow color with areas of browning, without any visible seasoning powder. They came in gently curving shapes with occasional bumps.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mild and nice, maybe a hint of beef broth, but not a strong meat or barbecue smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips from Taiwan had generally flat shapes, with a bright yellow-orange color, some light seasoning on the surfaces and some bits of skin on the edges.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mid-strength crab smell, with some middling spices.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips from the Lay's Tastes of America series weren't the first time we've seen this flavor from Lay's, but last time they changed the order of the words and method of preparing the potato in creating a Sweet Thai Chili flavor of the Pringles-style Stax crisps. I opened the bag to find that there were lots of large, unbroken chips, with gently curving shapes, a light yellow color and a light smattering of green seasoning bits spread over the surfaces.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Wow, really smells like a sweet chili sauce!

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Lay's had narrow ripples and gently curving shapes, with a nice range of golden yellow colors, but nothing at all in terms of visible seasoning powder.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Sweet and tangy, nice, and only very remotely fishy.

snack_name: Lay's Thick Potato Chips Thai BBQ Shrimp
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Lay's from Taiwan had narrow ripples and a nice a golden yellow color, with some areas showing a bit more orange. There was barely any seasoning powder visible on the surfaces, save for some black specks that averaged about one per chip.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mildly shrimp-like, with some spices.

snack_name: Lay's Toasted Onion & Cheese Flavored Potato Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: Pretty good onion flavor, not too harsh of a cheese.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Oniony and cheesy.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These fries looked much like the original and seaweed versions from Lay's, with the short pieces looking much like actual fries, with various shades of golden yellow. The picture on the bag shows some red bits on on the surfaces, but the actual fries didn't seem to have any.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Seemed like there was something fishy in there in addition to the potato. Couldn't notice any tomato.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Turkey-flavored potato chips are a whole new concept for me, so when I was given this bag, I had no idea what to expect.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells sort of like turkey with gravy. Nice. Not bad at all.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This Russian version of Lay's potato chips had a nice yellow color with some orange accents, with just a tiny bit of seasoning powder visible, plus some small bits of skin on the edges.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Yeah, really smells like vegetable soup.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips from China promised one the most shocking Lay's flavors ever, but when I opened the bag, they looked like ordinary potato chips, with just the same range of light yellow colors that you'd expect from Lay's Classic.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very mild, maybe the slightest hint of wasabi.

snack_name: Lay's Wavy Bacon Wrapped Jalapeño Popper
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This flavor sounded like one of the boldest among the 12 Tastes of America flavors for 2018, and as an admirer of both bacon and jalapeño poppers — can't say I've ever had them combined — I was eager to try.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mild smoky baon smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These wide-rippled potato chips had fairly flat shapes and generally a bright yellow color, with some of the chips also showing some signs of orange (presumably from the cheddar) in their crevices.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice, but smells like cheddar and sour cream, not just cheddar.

snack_name: Lay's Wavy Dark Chocolate Covered Potato Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This bag marked the third variety of chocolate-covered Lay's that we've tried, following the Milk Chocolate and Milk Chocolate with Almond Bits versions.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good, strong dark chocolate smell.

snack_name: Lay's Wavy Electric Lime & Sea Salt
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips had wide, curvy ripples and a light yellow color, with lots of large green seasoning bits scattered over the surfaces. A few of the chips near the top were impressively large.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice mild lime and potato smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This new Lay's flavor, part of the "Do Us A Flavor" contest along with Everything Bagel and Crispy Taco, had wide ripples and a golden yellow color with areas of browning, plus a light smattering of dark seasoning powder.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice mild mix of spices and a hint of tomato, very nice.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This Lay's flavor was released along with Tikka Masala, Brazilian Picanha and Szechuan Chicken for the Passport to Flavor promotion. The potato chips had wide ripples and lots of specks of green on them, so they looked a whole lot like sour cream & onion chips (though Lay's does not ripple their version).
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice, it does smell like Tzatziki.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This limited-edition Lay's flavor is competing with Cheddar Bacon Mac & Cheese, Wasabi Ginger and Cappuccino in this year's "Do Us A Flavor" contest.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Not the usual salsa smell. Milder, not hot, slightly fruity.

snack_name: Lay's Wavy Milk Chocolate Covered Potato Chips with Almond Bits
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These rippled potato chips had a less-than-complete coating of a light-colored milk chocolate, so there was lots of light yellow chip surface visible in between the coated parts. They promised almond bits as well, a change from the original chocolate-coated Wavy Lay's, and there were a fair number of smallish almond fragments stuck to the chocolate (but not quite the density of almonds pictured on the bag).
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice milk chocolate smell.

snack_name: Lay's Wavy Original Potato Chips Dipped in Milk Chocolate
snack_taste_test: Taste test: Having eaten 122 varieties of Lay's and Lay's Stax, we don't get too excited about every new Lay's variety (well, sometimes we do, like with Chicken & Waffles), but the promise of chocolate-covered Lay's had our Chief Snacks Officer visiting Target stores three times over the course of a week just to track down a bag.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: More milk chocolate than potato.

snack_name: Lay's Wavy Roasted Garlic & Sea Salt
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These wide-rippled potato chips had a nice strong yellow color, with some small bits of black on the surfaces.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like corn on the cob.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These chips had wide, shallow ripples and a light yellow color on most of the surfaces, with lots of black pepper bits scattered throughout and some dark skin along parts of the edges.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Fairly mild pepper smell, but fresh and good.

snack_name: Lay's Wavy West Coast Truffle Fries
snack_taste_test: Taste test: It's that time of the year again, when Lay's rolls out limited-edition products that tempt or appall us with their bold takes on flavored potato chips, while challenging us to search every local store to find an actual bag to eat and review. This year, Truffles Fries was released along with Greektown Gyro, New York Reuben and Southern Biscuits and Gravy.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice mild spices.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: OK, we've got a weird one! These are indeed Lay's Potato Chips, made from sliced potato, but unlike just about every other flavor, they're sweet, promising to emulate the taste of a popular brand of toffee. In terms of appearance, you would never have known, as they had the light yellow color, gentle curves and occasional bumps of normal Lay's.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Definitely not your udual potato chips smell. Sweet, sugary, a bit refreshing.

snack_name: Lay's Wu Fang Zhai Salted Egg Yolk Meat Dumpling
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips promised to duplicate the taste of an egg-based meat dumpling from a restaurant chain called Wu Fang Zhai, so all in all, I had no idea what that would taste like. The chips had curvy shapes and a light yellow color, with any seasoning basically camouflaged by the chip surface, so they looked much like regular Lay's.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Kind of egg-like, along with salted potato. Good.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This was the first version of Lay's we've seen that featured yams instead of potatoes, and it came in a rather unusual bag, more resembling the "thundersticks" noise-making balloons that they sell at sports stadiums than typical potato chip bags. I opened the bag (the top sort of peeled off by pulling at a little slit) to find that it was filled a little more than halfway with small, thin pieces. Most of them were close to rectangular before the curling, but some deviated a bit. They generally measured about 7/8 inch by 1-1/4, with a light beige color, plus some small green bits.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Kind of sweet and maybe yam-like.

snack_name: Lay's Zhou Hei Ya Spicy Braised Duck Neck
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This bag of Lay's from China promised a flavor that sounded quite different from anything we've eaten on a potato chip. I opened the bag to find that the chips looked pretty ordinary, generally small, with somewhat wiggly shapes that had some bubbles embedded inside and yellow surfaces with areas of browning. There were some very sparse, fine, orange and green seasoning bits, but I had to look really closely to see them.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice tangy smell, maybe like hoisin sauce.

snack_name: Natural Lay's Sea Salt & Vinegar Kettle Cooked Potato Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These very crunchy kettle cooked potato chips reminded us of Cape Cod chips, especially their salt and vinegar chips.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Slight vinegar aroma.

snack_name: Natural Lay's Sea Salted Kettle Cooked Potato Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These kettle cooked potato chips could give Cape Cod chips a run for their money.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: A very nice potato aroma wafts up. You can tell that these are potato chips.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips had a pale yellow color generally, with gently curving shapes and some bubbles embedded inside, plus scattered dark areas and minimal skin on the edges.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong, fresh potato smell. Nice.

snack_name: Simply Lay's Barbecue Flavored Thick Cut Potato Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips had gently curving shapes with an orange glow over most of the surfaces, plus a light smattering of black seasoning bits.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong barbecue sauce smell, more spicy than sweet.

snack_name: Simply Lay's Sea Salted Thick Cut Potato Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These chips had fairly flat shapes as potato chips go, with a light yellow color and lots of skin around the edges, plus just a little browning on some chips near select areas of the edges. Many of the chips were quite big, and most were unbroken, though the bag was only filled up about halfway.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong fresh potato smell. Salty. Very good.

snack_name: Wavy Lay's Hickory BBQ Flavored Potato Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are good wide-rippled barbecue chips.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very mild barbecue chips smell. Nice.

snack_name: Wavy Lay's Hidden Valley Ranch Flavored Potato Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are good ranch chips with wide ripples.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Ranch chips smell, not bad.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are wide-rippled potato chips with some pretty good jalapeno flavor and heat.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mild jalapeno aroma, but not really hot.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are standard wide-rippled potato chips.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Regular potato chips smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: I like cake as much as the next guy, but if you were to ask me what my favorite cake is (nobody's ever actually asked), birthday cake would not even enter into consideration.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Not much.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This new flavor was released concurrently with Honey Nut and Coffee Nut to compete for a permanent spot on the shelves alongside the original Peanut M&M's. They had the same varied sizes as the Peanut M&M's but came in just three colors — orange, red and dark red.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Regular Peanut M&M's smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These special M&M's were slightly bigger than the regular ones, and they came in just three colors: white, dark brown and green.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like a Mounds bar.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: M&M's announced that they were releasing this flavor along with two other versions of Peanut M&M's — Chili Nut and Chili Nut — with an online vote to decide which one to keep. But their distribution strategy has been odd, to say the least, as despite extensive searching, we only found the first two flavors in two different stores, weeks apart, and we didn't locate this one until four months later
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mild mocha smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This special version of M&M's came in three colors, red, white and blue, with the promise of marshmallow, chocolate and a crispy center made from some sort of graham cracker substance. The shapes were different from typical M&M's, as they looked a bit lumpy, but the overall volume of each was similar.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Maybe remotely like s'mores. Not the usual M&M's smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These M&M's were released alongside two other Crunchy versions, Raspberry and Mint. They came in three colors: dark brown, medium brown and kind of a slightly brownish white.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong coffee/mocha smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of M&M's, rolled out alongside also-crunchy Espresso and Raspberry flavors, promised to bring some crunch to a candy brand not usually associated with crunch. They came in three colors: bright green, very light green and brown. Many of the pieces looked lumpier than your typical M&M's.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good chocolate mint smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These M&M's promised the same crunchy feel as the mint version. They came with brown, red and white candy coatings, with a chocolate interior within those shells and then a crunchy center that was white.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong raspberry and chocolate smell. Me no like.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Peanut M&M's (competing against (Thai Coconut and Mexican Jalapeño in a flavor contest) came in two different shades of mustard yellow (let's call them yellow and brown mustard), plus a very dark brown.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice, can definitely smell the toffee, and it's stronger than the peanut or chocolate.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of M&M's came in a fairly standard color assortment of brown, blue, yellow, green and red (but no orange, despite what was pictured on the wrapper). The pieces varied in size, though all were larger than standard M&M's, and they had irregular shapes. I bit in to find a soft feel inside the thin, crunchy shell, with a taste that definitely hit the brownie flavor spot-on.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong chocolate smell, similar to regular M&M's, but a bit of a brownie twist to it too.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Another new M&M's flavor, and I took the "Hazelnut Spread" name to mean that it was supposed to taste like Nutella, without officially licensing the name. The color assortment was fairly standard M&M's, with yellow, blue, orange, brown and green.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Maybe a hint of hazelnut, but mostly chocolate.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These large M&M's, part of a series of three new peanut M&M's flavors vying for votes online (with this, Chili Nut and Coffee Nut competing against regular Peanut M&M's), came with coatings of dark brown, light yellow and mustard yellow.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Regular Peanut M&M's smell. Couldn't really notice any honey.

snack_name: Hostess Brownies made with Milk Chocolate M&M's
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This box contained six brownies, each individually wrapped in a typical Hostess white wrapper with red logo. When I opened my first one, I was quite surprised to see mini M&M's rather than full-size ones — the pictures on the box really had me expecting that. There appeared to be a chocolate frosting on the top.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Pretty good chocolate smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This small snack bar consisted mostly of crisp rice and mini-M&M's.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like M&M's

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This M-Azing chocolate bar is definitely one of the cooler-looking candy bars to come along in a while (as is its similar-looking peanut butter cousin).
snack_smell_test: Smell test: An OK chocolate smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: The weird thing about this is that it's a chocolate candy bar with peanut butter-flavored M&M's inside it. Peanut butter M&M's? I thought that M&M's were by definition made from chocolate. (They also make a chocolate-in-chocolate version that uses conventional M&M's.)
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice chocolate smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This seasonal version of M&M's came in three different colors shells — yellow, tan and a very slightly pinkish off-white — with gray M's on all three kinds. Many of the recent limited-edition M&M's were build around the original Milk Chocolate formula, with in most cases subtle changes in flavor from there, but they were more ambitious here, promising a white chocolate base.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Wow, really smells like butterscotch!

snack_name: M&M's Bar Milk Chocolate with Minis & Peanuts
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This bar had the same impressive section design as the Crisp Rice and original versions, this time with peanuts within the chocolate in addition to miniature versions of M&M's. As with the others, there were some of the colorful M&M's showing through the top, but not a lot of them. There were some peanuts showing through the bottom of the bar, but again, not a lot.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells a like like Peanut M&M's.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These M&M's came in just green and red, and with the promise of mocha flavor, we were eager to try them. However, there was some disappointment when we did, as they tasted a whole lot like regular Milk Chocolate M&M's. We shared them with lots of snackers, and people generally noticed just a hint of coffee amid the chocolate, if any. No major complaints, as they still satisfied the chocolate craving, but we would hope that a mocha flavor would have a more even mix of coffee and chocolate.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very much like standard Milk Chocolate M&M's but maybe hint of coffee.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These M&M's came in standard M&M's colors — orange, yellow, brown, green, blue and red — but the pieces were noticeably larger than the originals. Many of the M's inked onto the surfaces seemed to be a bit off center. I carefully bit off half of my first piece to get a look at the cross-section. The vast majority of the interior consisted of caramel, with a thin chocolate layer between that and the colored shell. The caramel part had a chewy feel that was quite unusual for M&M's. That chewiness made the light crunch of the shell more noticeable. The mix of chocolate and caramel was good.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good caramel and chocolate smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Some years back, M&M's sold the M-Azing Bar in peanut butter and crunchy versions. Neither was much of a standout in terms of taste, but they both looked really nice, as the glow of the colored mini-M&M's inside a chocolate bar was visually stunning. So of course, they stopped selling those. We recently spotted this, which looked to be a revival of the same concept, though in this case they didn't promise peanut butter or crunches, just milk chocolate.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mild milk chocolate smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These M&M's had textured patterns on their surfaces unlike any we've seen on M&M's since the demise of the Premiums M&M's sub-brand. They didn't glow quite the way the Premiums did, but they did have an impressive look. Some of the pieces did, anyway — the texture was very pronounced on about half of them and subtle on the others. Those with lots of texture had lots of smattered light spots or even a domination of light spots on the generally dark surfaces, not quite a black-and-white look as pictured on the bag, as the tints of the light areas varied from one piece to the next. Those with less texture had minimal, smaller light spots.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mostly dark chocolate, but probably some white mixed in too. Nice.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These were the same size as regular M&M's and came in maroon, gray, dark blue, light purple and black colors.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Rich chocolatey smell, a little different from regular M&M's, but you can still tell it's M&M's.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These M&M's came in white, green and red colors, with gray M's on all three kinds. The sizes of the pieces varied more than I've generally seen with M&M's. Was this really a new "Holiday Mint" flavor, or the same as the ones previously labeled Mint Chocolate with a new name and bag design? It's hard to say for sure, as there were similarities and difference — same three colors of the pieces, but a different color for the M's.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Sharp mint and chocolate smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This Pirates of the Caribbean movie tie-in version of M&M's contained standard M&M's in lavender, green, dark blue and red, with pirate-related icons printed on some of the pieces, along with smaller versions of the usual M.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: The usual M&M's chocolate smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This new version of M&M's didn't attempt to stand out with a new flavor or special color, but instead it boasted increased size, claiming that each piece had three times as much chocolate as your usual M&M's. We ripped open the bag to find that they were indeed bigger. Each piece had about the same diameter as a nickel. But that's still not a particularly big snack, so Mega sounded a bit overstated. The M's printed on the surfaces were the same size as the ones on regular M's. That seemed like a poor choice. A larger M, proportional to the larger M&M — like the one in the Mega logo on the bag — might have reinforced the Mega look. Instead, the small M looked lost amid the large surface.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Regular M&M's smell.

snack_name: M&M's Milk Chocolate Bar with Minis
snack_taste_test: Taste test: I was a big fan of the M-Azing Bar, more for how it looked than how it tasted, and I've long lamented the fact that it got discontinued. So it was exciting to see that M&M's is giving candy bars another try.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good creamy milk chocolate smell.

snack_name: M&M's Milk Chocolate Bar with Minis & Crisp Rice
snack_taste_test: Taste test: The bar had the same clever design as the M&M's Milk Chocolate Bar with Minis one, with 20 regular sections bearing a round M&M's logo, plus an M&M's character spanning all four rows and three virtual columns of extra-wide sections — the only difference being that this time, they added Rice Krispies in addition to mini M&M's within the chocolate.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice creamy milk chocolate smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: The weird thing about this M&M's bag is that it was Jedi Mix and promoted Star Wars Episode III, yet it had a picture of Han Solo, who is not a Jedi and does not appear in Episode III.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: The usual M&M's smell. Nice.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of M&M's came in very light brown (you could say off-white), light brown and dark brown exterior colors.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Not particularly like pecan pie, but not like chocolate either.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These M&M's came in Christmas colors, with just green, red and white ones in the bag, with green M's on the white and red ones and white M's on the green ones. The pieces seemed to be larger than the standard M&M's, and some of the had more of a spherical shape.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very minty, reminded me of those Andes chocolate mints.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This new M&M's flavor promised orange-flavored white chocolate, and it was far from the first candy to try to taste like a Creamsicle.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like a Creamsicle

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of M&M's was a bit bigger than the regular M&Ms and came in a subset of the original set of colors, with just blue, orange, green, yellow and red represented in this bag.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like regular M&M's.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This was a dark chocolate version of the standard Peanut M&M's, with mostly (but not exclusively) dark colors.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice peanuuty dark chocolate smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This M&M's assortment had just five colors: light green, light blue, mustard yellow, beige and white.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong peanutty chocolate smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This fancy-priced version of M&M's certainly looked fancy, as they had a metallic, marble-like surface that mixed varying amounts of green and black for a very cool look. Each piece was just slightly bigger than a standard M&M.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good mint chocolate smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of M&M's came in a clear bag inside a funky-shaped box, and the pieces were roughly the size of regular M&M's but had a marble-like finish with a copper overall color.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Great mocha smell. Really nice.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: The first question upon encountering this oddly shaped cardboard box was how to open it. One of the concave sides sort of folded out after ripping some glue, revealing a clear plastic bag that held the M&M's. (I later discovered that if I had first slid the inner box out of its slip case, a pull tab near the top provided easy access to the interior.) The M&M's looked quite a bit different than conventional M&M's. They were bigger, and each piece did not have a uniform color, both rather a marble-like mix of colors, with sort of a metallic glow. The overall color of each piece was generally a dark purple, but the brightness and shade varied from one piece to the next.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice. Initially, I got the regular M&M's smell, but after that I could definitely smell a mix of different chocolates.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This special flavor of M&M's came in the yupical M&M's size, with just three different colors: white, orange and brown. Somewhat confusingly, it said "Milk Chocolate" on the bag in addition to the "Pumpkin Spice Latte" designation, in the same "Milk Chocolate" design used on the original M&M's since they were rebranded.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Yes, some pumpkin spice mixed in with the chocolate.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This special version of M&M's promised a shimmery appearance and a white chocolate interior. The pieces came in three colors — white, green and kind of a brownish red. The picture on the package showed all three kinds being quite shimmery, even a bit metallic in the case of green and red/brown. But really, the white ones weren't shimmery at all, the green ones had just a slight texture on the surfaces and weren't metallic, and the brown/red ones were shimmery and metallic, though less metallic than the picture showed.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Not much.

snack_name: M&M's Special Edition Strawberried Peanut Butter
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of M&M's had pieces somewhat bigger than the regular M&M's though still quite a bit smaller than Peanut M&M's, with somewhat irregular shapes and some size variation.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like those assortments of chocolate with various jellies inside (in other words, nothing great).

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This large bag of M&M's was not the first triple-chocolate M&M's, as we reviewed one in the M&M's Premiums line back in 2009 that was also Triple Chocolate. Both kinds offered a dark chocolate layer surrounding a while chocolate layer surrounding a milk chocolate center, but this was a much different product than the Premiums, proving to be far less impressive.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice chocolate smell, even better than regular M&M's.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: As someone who is not a huge fan of candy corn (but loves M&M's), yet can't resist eating some when it's made available to me, I of course jumped at the chance to see what the M&M's take on candy corn would be.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Definitely not the standard M&M's smell. Sort of like a Creamsicle.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of M&M's came with the same color assortment as the milk chocolate peanut version, with blue, green, orange, yellow and brown candy coatings.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Not much! Couldn't notice any white chocolate or peanuts.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of M&M's wasn't labeled as a limited edition, but we bought it at a post-Christmas closeout and haven't seen it before or since, so it may have been limited.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like a candy cane.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These M&M's were a bit bigger than standard ones and came in three colors — orange, light brown and a very, very light orange that almost looked white — with the M's in the same gray on all three kinds. I grabbed a handful and bit in to find the usual M&M's texture and a flavor that was very much like the taste of a pumpkin pie. The interiors had an off-white color. It was definitely denser and sweeter, but both the taste and aftertaste definitely said "pumpkin pie" to me. And I love pumpkin pie, so that's a good thing!
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Wow, smells just like a pumpkin pie. Great!

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These M&M's (part of a flavor contest also involving Thai Coconut and Toffee versions) looked mostly like regular Peanut M&M's, with a subset of the usual colors — green, yellow and red — that gave them a Mexican theme.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Definitely different than regular peanut M&M's, but not really a strong hit of jalapeno.

snack_name: Mint Crisp M&M's Adventures of Indiana Jones
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These M&M's were a bit larger and more irregularly shaped than regular M&M's, and they came in three colors: white, light green and green.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Excellent chocolate mint smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These M&M's (not to be confused with the Mint Chocolate, Mint Crisp or Premium Mint versions) were slightly larger than standard M&M's, and they came in just two colors, green and light green.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good chocolate mint smell. Strong.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Putting pretzels inside M&M's is a big change from the ordinary, so I was very excited when I heard about these. The art on the bag depicted an orange M&M holding up an x-ray showing that there was a knotted pretzel inside. I had no idea how they managed to fit any sort of knotted pretzel inside an M&M, so the anticipation grew as I opened the bag. It turned out that these M&M's had a much different shape than your typical M&M's, as they were roughly spherical (though a bit irregular as spheres go). Colors included blue, orange, brown and sort of a reddish light brown.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Regular M&M's smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This special edition of M&M's came in green, red and pink, and the pieces generally looked smaller in size than regular Peanut M&M's. I bit in to find that whatever they did to add strawberry to Peanut M&M's really altered the whole flavor of everything, and not in good way at all. Internally, they looked like peanut M&M's, with a peanut center, but everything tasted overly sweet and berry-ish. Some kind of berry, anyway — I couldn't really specifically taste strawberry. Not good at all.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Definitely some strawberry and peanut mixed in with the chocolate.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This special edition of M&M's, released alongside Jalapeño and Toffee versions, came with blue, pinkish off-white and dull green pieces that were comparable in size to standard Peanut M&M's.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like regular Peanut M&M's.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This bag included white, light beige, pale yellow and light blue M&M's.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Something about the smell reminded me of regular M&M's, but it was different.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These M&M's were slightly larger than the standard M&M's, but nowhere near as big as Peanut M&M's.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like chocolate cherry candies. More cherry than chocolate. Strong.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Mike and Ike had the usual shapes, with a pale yellow color.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Kind of smells like a movie theater. But not that strongly of buttered popcorn.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This seasonal flavor from Mike and Ike had two different kinds of pieces pieces in the usual shapes — light green apple ones and light brown caramel ones.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Not much.

snack_name: Mike and Ike Chewy Cotton Candy Flavored Candies
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This box contained two different colors of Mike and Ikes, matching two of the most common cotton candy colors, pink and blue. The pink ones looked much like the illustration on the front of the package, but the blue ones were quite bit darker than the powder blue ones pictured, as they were almost teal blue.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Not much, but remotely like cotton candy.
