snack_taste_test: Taste test: This bag promised to deliver the taste of Mike and Ike candy in the delightful form of cotton candy, with anywhere from one to three flavors in the bag. The really crazy thing here is that we previously reviewed a flavor of Mike and Ike (as in the actual capsule-shaped candies) that tried to perform the very opposite trick — bring the cotton candy taste to that form.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: A nice change from the usual cotton candy smell, as we could actually smell the sugary fruit flavors.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This grape-flavored version of Mike and Ike (sold years ago under the separate brand of Jolly Joes) is the only Mike and Ike flavor that we know of that puts just one flavor into the box, rather than a mix of different kinds.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like grape candy.

snack_name: Mike and Ike Root Beer Float
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This special flavor of Mike and Ike turned a lot of heads when we offered it to potential snack tasters during a musical performance at a brewery. People just could not resist the temptation of a root beer float encapsulated in a candy.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Yes, smells like a root beer float. Great!

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Mike and Ike had five different flavors, each a different color, according to the back of the package: Kiwi-Banana (green), Caribbean Punch (blue), Strawberry-Banana (red), Paradise Punch (pink) and Mango (orange). The front also had a nice picture key to translate flavor names into fruits (though translation was only needed for two of the five flavors; the others were self-explanatory). But it was odd that you needed to consult two different keys that couldn't be viewed simultaneously to figure out the name and intended fruit composition of any given color. I opened the package to find that the distinction between pink and red wasn't quite so clear; it turned out that the Strawberry-Banana ones were more of a dark pink, and the Paradise Punch ones light pink.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Not much, just a slight fruit juice smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This large chocolate bar had the same 5x3 grid as the Oreo Milka, with a filling that in this case tried to bring the taste of a Chips Ahoy cookie in between the milk chocolate top and bottom. The center looked kind of like cookie dough, with some cookie bits or chocolate chips visible, but not a lot of them.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: There is a hint of chocolate chip cookie amid the milk chocolate smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This candy bar's announcement made a big splash in the news — apparently putting Oreo into a candy bar is newsworthy, which kind of baffled me because Cadbury had already done the same thing. Then it took some months for me to find one to eat.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: It does smell like a mix of milk chocolate and Oreos.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This large candy bar had a 6x4 grid of small sections, each bearing the Milka logo.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good milk chocolate smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This bar from Poland was Milka's entry into the field of aerated chocolate, already populated by bars that include Cadbury Wispa, Hershey Air Delight, Nestle Areo and Cadbury Dairy Milk Bubbly (which uses the same "Bubbly" brand as this one, but also now falls under the same Mondelez corporate umbrella).
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good creamy, sweet milk chocolate smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This large chocolate bar had a 4x6 grid of rectangular sections. From the picture on front, I was expecting M&M's-like candies to be embedded inside, and could see hints of just that through the outside of the bar, I, but the effect was nowhere near as impressive as the beautiful (and long-gone) M-Azing bars from M&M's. Each section had the Milka logo on top.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mild creamy milk chocolate smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These wafers were much different from most things that we consider wafers, as they were round, individually foil wrapped and had a thick chocolate coating. There were three wafer layers within each piece, separated by chocolate, with an even thicker coating of chocolate for the whole exterior. Each one was pretty big, a half inch thick and 2-1/2 inches in diameter. The package contained just five of them, stacked at an angle, overlapping on a plastic tray.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice chocolate smell.

snack_name: Milka Double Chocolate Oreo Chocolate Candy Bar
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This bar followed a similar formula to the Milka & Oreo bar, with a 5x3 section grid, a milk chocolate exterior and an interior consisting of Oreo creme and bits of Oreo cookie. The "Double Chocolate" difference was that the creme was chocolate-flavored instead of the conventional white creme. Each section had the Milka logo, and from the outside, there was no sign of the cookie bits or creme.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Creamy milk chocolate smell. Nice.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This bar from Milka was clearly a knockoff of Kit Kat, as it had a suspiciously similar detachable four-finger structure, with wafers embedded inside each one. The four bars had a pattern of waves running across their tops (with no Leo logo as it showed in on the wrapper).
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good rich milk chocolate smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This cardboard wrapper contained contained eight small, individually foiler-wrapped bars, each roughly the size of a single Kit Kat finger, except about half as thick. Dimensions aside, they were quite unlike Kit Kat bars, as there was no wafer interior, and instead there was a white cream interior. The exteriors were all milk chocolate, with each bar divided into four sections and a cow atop each one.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Creamy, sweet milk chocolate smell.

snack_name: Milka Mint Oreo Chocolate Candy Bar
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This narrow bar had the same shape and six-section design as the non-mint version, and it's now one of four different versions of the Milk Oreo bar (the other two being Big Crunch and the original Milka & Oreo).
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Great mint chocolate smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This was the eighth kind of Oreo-themed Milka chocolate bar that we've reviewed, but it was the first to embed entire Oreo cookies (albeit miniature ones) into the bar. The bar had 10 sections, lined up in two rows of five, with the round Mini Oreo cookies and a layer of creme rising up from the top and just the cookies jutting out of the bottom. Each section was rounded on the outer edge, following the contour of the cookie inside.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mild, creamy chocolate smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This bar was by far the largest of the three new Oreo-themed candy bars released by Milka, weighing in at 10.5 ounces and containing 36 sections in a 9x4 grid. After finding the other two (the small Oreo Chocolate Candy Bar and midsize Milka & Oreo) had far more creme than cookie, with bits of Oreo cookie within a white creme center — and not even the real Oreo creme filling, at that — I was excited to see that this one showed a solid cookie layer in between creme layers. It took some serious muscle to break the bar into sections — this was one very structurally sound bar.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good mild chocolate smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of the collaborative Milka/Oreo bar had a 5x3 section grid, with the Milka logo atop each section and some occasional darkish stuff (that I assumed to be the Oreo material within) showing through the otherwise light milk chocolate color.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice creamy milk chocolate smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This mix promised two kind of Mini Oreos — regular chocolate ones and Golden ones — along with Milka's version of M&M's (called "candy coated chocolate pieces"), which were previously seen embedded in a Milka bar, plus some larger chocolate buttons.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Sweet, but not the typical Oreos smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This narrow bar, one of three new Oreo-themed candy bars, had six dome-shaped sections (basically six big bumps) with a design that was sort of like the Coca Cola dynamic ribbon running across the tops of all the sections. The whole exterior had a light milk chocolate color.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice creamy milk chocolate smell.

snack_name: Hostess Brownies made with Milky Way
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This box promised some sort of mix-up between a Milky Way bar and a brownie, and that was an unusual combination, so we figured it was worth a shot. There were six individually wrapped square brownies. The top of each one had a chocolate coating  topped with an irregular layer that looked like the stuff inside a Milky Way.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good chocolate smell, but not that much like a brownie, nor a Milky Way bar.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This small candy bar had a whipped white chocolate inside, with a milk chocolate outer coating.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very creamy chocolate smell. Reminded me of Elite chocolates from Israel.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This limited-edition version of the Milky Way bar promised the taste of a caramel apple, as they replaced the original Milky Way's chocolate nougat with an apple-flavored nougat and left the caramel layer and milk chocolate exterior as is.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Not really like a caramel apple, but there was lots of caramel and a hint of apple.

snack_name: Milky Way French Vanilla and Caramel
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of the Milky Way bar looked like a regular Milky Way from the outside, with the same overall shape and a smooth milk chocolate exterior featuring some subtle ripples on top.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good caramel and chocolate smell. Maybe a hint of vanilla.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This variation on the standard Milky Way bar kept two of the three elements in place, with the same milk chocolate coating and caramel layer near the top, while swapping out the Milky Way's nougat layer for a darker, fudge-flavored nougat.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good caramel and chocolate smell, not that different from a regular Milky Way.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This bag contained smallish five-poined stars made from milk chocolate, with various different faces in the center of each ones.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good milk chocolate smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: We discovered this version of Milky Way in a six-bar Fun Size multipack, before ever seeing a full-size bar to review, so we'll go against our general practice of reviewing the full-size versions.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Great mix of caramel and milk chocolate.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of the Milky Way bar did away with the chocolate nougat part of the interior and expanded the caramel to compensate, while retaining the milk chocolate coating.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mild caramel smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This bag contained small, roughly cube-shaped versions of the Milk Way bar, indeed unwrapped as the name said, with milk chocolate exteriors just like full Milky Way bars.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Just like a Milky Way bar — mild caramel and milk chocolate. Great.

snack_name: Miss Vickie's Farmhouse White Cheddar Kettle Cooked Potato Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips had wiggly shapes and a nice light yellow color, with lots of bubbles embedded inside. Picking up a chips, I could feel a lot of cheese seasoning powder on my fingertips.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice cheddar smell, fairly strong.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Yeah, there's a jalepeño taste, but it's not particularly hot.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mild jalapeno smell without the burning sensation.

snack_name: Miss Vickie's Lime & Black Pepper Potato Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These kettle-cooked potato chips were fairly thin, crunchy and very crisp.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good peppery smell. No lime that I could discern.

snack_name: Miss Vickie's Mesquite BBQ Potato Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These kettle-cooked potato chips were OK.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: An pretty good mesquite smell.

snack_name: Miss Vickie's Original Recipe Potato Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are kettle-style chips, with less salty flavor than a Cape Cod, and about the same amount of oil.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: A slight potato-like aroma.

snack_name: Miss Vickie's Roasted Garlic & Herb Potato Chips (Ail Grillé et Fines Herbes Croustilles)
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are very good chips, with lots of nice garlic and herb flavor.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Garlicy smell.

snack_name: Miss Vickie's Sea Salt & Malt Vinegar Potato Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are good vinegar chips.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Fairly strong vinegar smell.

snack_name: Miss Vickie's Sweet Chili & Sour Cream
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These wigglly, bubble chips had a bit of an orange glow to them, with irregular shapes, some folded-over chips and bit of skin around the edges.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice mild chili and sour cream smell. Great!

snack_name: Kraft Handi-Snacks Dunk 'ems Mister Salty Nacho Fiesta Cheesy
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This box contained six individual packages similar to the cheese-and-crackers except with mini-pretzel rods instead of crackers.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Ordinary pretzel smell, fairly weak nacho cheese smell.

snack_name: Kraft Handi-Snacks Mister Salty Pretzels 'n Cheez
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This box contained six individual packages, each with eight pretzel sticks and a tub of cheese for dipping.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: On the cheese side, a strong but unimpressive cheese smell. Not a very good pretzel smell on the pretzels side.

snack_name: Mister Salty Milk Chocolate Covered Pretzels 100 Calorie Packs
snack_taste_test: Taste test: I'm increasingly baffled by the Mister Salty brand.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice slightly salty milk chocolate smell. Good.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These were pretty much your average miniature knotted pretzels, in a potentially convenient can.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Regular pretzels smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These corn (maize) snacks, molded into the shape of a monster's foot, had a pickle flavor with some spicy heat.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Sort of a pickled onion smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These really do taste like pickled onion.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Kind of pickley, not too bad.

snack_name: Monster Munch Spicy Flavour Baked Corn Snacks
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These footprint-shaped snacks made from corn meal have the pickled onion taste of other Monster Munch flavors, but with sort of a ketchupy/barbecuey taste mixed in.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Sort of pickley, maybe slightly barbecuey.

snack_name: Frito-Lay Munchies Mini Sandwich Crackers Cheddar Cheese Flavored Filling on Golden Toast Crackers Flavor by Cheetos
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These round cracker sandwiches had a medium-orange cheese filling, not nearly as bright of an orange as I would expect, given their association with the Cheetos brand. The amount of cheese varied a lot from one sandwich to the next. The crackers were light in color, just your standard light beige cracker color, with a hexagonal pattern of seven holes in each one.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very mild cheddar smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are all mini versions of a party mix favorite, including mini Cheetos, Funyuns, Doritos and Pretzels.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like Doritos.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Frito-Lay scores a big hit with this mix of snacks.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like Cheetos.

snack_name: Munchies Baked Snack Crackers Cheddar Cheese
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These cheese crackers had the same three odd shapes as the other two Munchies crackers flavors, Nacho Cheese and Flamin' Hot, with a light orange color similar to Cheez-Its.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mild cheese smell. Despite the "flavored by Cheetos" claim, they didn't really smell like cheese puffs.

snack_name: Munchies Baked Snack Crackers Flamin' Hot
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This flavor of the Munchies crackers had the same odd shapes as the two other flavors (one sort of triangular and two not quite rectangular) with what looked like a light coating of Frito-Lay's standard dark red Flamin' Hot seasoning. The crackers weren't as red as they looked in the picture, as there was more of a mix of light orange from the cracker and red from the seasoning.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Kind of a hot sauce-like smell, but not actually hot.

snack_name: Munchies Baked Snack Crackers Nacho Cheese
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These cheese crackers appeared at first to be Frito-Lay's answer to Cheez-Its, but as soon as we opened the bag, we found one major difference: variety of shapes. Whereas the standard Cheez-Its are all squares, this bag contained no squares, instead providing orange-colored crackers in three unusual shapes. If not unusual, at least difficult to describe: sort-of triangles, with curved edges bulging outward instead of just flat sides, plus three holes; not-quite rectangles, with two straight edges, but curved, bulging-outward edges on the two shorts sides, plus two holes; and a third shape that's even harder to describe, sort of like a rectangle, with rounded corned and the edges curving inward, plus five holes. According to the bag, the flavor was supposed to be based on Doritos, presumably Nacho Cheese Doritos.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Sort of like a nacho cheese dip.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of the Munchies mix combined midsize knotted Rold Gold pretzels, Nacho Cheese Doritos, Harvest Cheddar Sun Chips and Crunchy Cheetos.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Pretty good cheese smell. The Cheetos and pretzels seemed to dominate.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This was a good snack mix with four different Frito-Lay snacks mixed together.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Slight ranch aroma.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This snack was similar in concept to Chili Nutterz, with peanuts covered by a crunchy coating (made from wheat flour and corn starch in this case) and seasoned with a mix of spices.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good honey-roasted peanut type of smell.

snack_name: Munchies Crunchy Coated Peanuts Sweet & Spicy
snack_taste_test: Taste test: Having reviewed several kinds of coated peanuts over the years, I thought I knew what to expect when I opened this narrow bag, but I ended up being quite surprised upon opening it. Generally, these snacks consist of nuts coated in a crunchy starch of some kind, with an outer flavoring layer. A look inside revealed some coated nuts that were a bit smaller than most other kinds, and some much smaller. I poured them onto a plate to find that only about half of the nuts had the starch coating, so in many cases, the flavor was applied directly to the peanuts.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Same smell as honey-roasted peanuts.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This mix combined four different Frito-Lay snacks (Mini Doritos, Cheetos, Rold Gold pretzels and Sun Chips) with various hot seasonings, and the result was quite good.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: A good hot sauce smell, makes your mouth water.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This snack mix consisted of Rold Gold Tiny Twists knotted pretzels, Crunchy Jalapeño Cheddar Cheetos, miniaturized Poppin' Jalapeno Doritos and a smallish version of Garden Salsa Sun Chips.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mostly smells like Doritos, with a hint of jalapeño.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This is an interesting mixture of sweet and salty snacks.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like cheddar popcorn.

snack_name: Munchies Sandwich Crackers Jalapeño Cheddar Doritos
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These crackers followed the standard formula for six square cracker sandwiches in a cellophane wrapper. The crackers had a very pale beige color, and the filling looked like Cheese Whiz, with a very strong orange color.
snack_smell_test: Smell test:  Can smell a bit of the zesty cheddar.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This snack mix includes miniature Smokey Red BBQ Doritos, plus Bar-B-Q Fritos, Cheetos and Rold Gold pretzels.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like corn chips.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This is like traditional Chex Mix, with pieces of other snacks and a light Worcestershire powder coating on all the snacks.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like Worcestershire sauce, kind of.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This is a really good snack mix, with the added bonus of having a cheese flavor to it.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: At first it smelled like an old shoe, but then a sweeter aroma came up, so it wasn't that bad.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Munchos have a unique taste.
snack_smell_test: From the package:  “A light tasting crispy snack!” ... “Munchos are an irresistible light tasting delicate snack!”

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Munchos are a rarity among Frito-Lay's vast array of snack brands and flavors, in that while the others brands have exploded over the years in the variety of flavors offered, there's always been just the plain Munchos. That finally ended during a recent chip-hunting trip to Canada, as we found this bag — just the second kind of Munchos ever.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Sweet, tangy barbecue smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Nestle used to sell Buncha Crunch in bags back in the early 90s, and I enjoyed quite a few bags of it back then.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good Nestle Crunch smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: I've long been a fan of Buncha Crunch, and indeed some years ago, I might have suffered from a mild addiction. There's something about the smallish, irregularly shaped lumps of Nestle chocolate that just makes it hard to stop popping handful after handful into the mouth.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like peanuts with chocolate.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This box contained six individually wrapped wafer sticks. Each one had a tubular cookie base, with a Crunch milk chocolate coating the outside and coffee creme filling the inside.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good mocha smell, more chocolate than coffee.

snack_name: Nestle Crunch Creme Egg with Caramel
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This chocolate egg had a milk chocolate outer shell, with a layer of chocolate creme inside the shell, some thick, chewy caramel inside that, and a hollow area in the center.
snack_smell_test: From the package:  “Chocolate Creme with Crisped Rice and a Smooth Caramel Layer in a Milk Chocolate Shell”

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This wide candy bar had seven layers.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good creamy chocolate smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This variation on the Nestle Crunch was all one section, like the original, with the tilted CRUNCH logo stretching the length of the bar.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Regular dark chocolate smell. Good.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This Nestle creation took those deliciously addictive chocolate wafer sticks stuffed with creamy dark chocolate, and then coated them with a dark version of the Nestle Crunch chocolate.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mild dark chooclate smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This bar consisted of three detachable square sections, each about an inch and a quarter per side. The "Crunch" part of the bar with the embedded Rice Krispies was entirely on the bottom, constituting about half of the overall thickness. Above that was a liquidy caramel layer, with a thin non-Crunch chocolate layer on top, sealing in the caramel.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good chocolate smell, almost more like milk chocolate than dark.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These heart-shaped chocolates had Nestle Crunch chocolate with embedded Rice Krispies inside.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like chocolate even through the colored foil.

snack_name: Nestle Crunch Limited Edition Cookie Flavors Girl Scouts Peanut Butter Crème
snack_taste_test: Taste test: The two small candy bars in this wrapper were arranged end-to-end, and each consisted of alternating layers of wafers and peanut butter crème.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice peanut butter and chocolate smell, like those "Buddy Bars."

snack_name: Nestle Crunch Limited Edition Cookie Flavors Girl Scouts Thin Mints
snack_taste_test: Taste test: Nestle has done the world a great favor by offering the great taste of Girl Scout cookies in candy bar form, and even better, you can get these in ordinary stores without having to place your order weeks in advance from Girl Scouts (or more accurately, their parents) and then have nothing but cookies on your mind until they arrive.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice mint chocolate smell. Just like the corresponding cookies.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of the Nestle Crunch bar was a mystery until I unwrapped it, as I couldn't read any of the Turkish on the wrapper. The most striking thing was the bits of crisp rice jutting out of the top and sides, within a chocolate coating, a big change from the usual sectioned top of a Crunch bar.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good chocolate smell, like a regular Crunch bar.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This candy bar was oval shaped, except for Peter's ears jutting out of one end of the oval.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: The usual Nestle Crunch smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This excellent snack took those crispy chocolate-filled wafer sticks and coated them Nestle Crunch chocolate, resulting in a high level of deliciousness.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good chocolate smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This candy bar was pretty good, with lots of chocolate and a medium helping of thick liquid caramel.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice chocolatey caramel smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of the Nestle Crunch bar had three detachable sections, a much different setup than the regular Crunch, which is all just one section.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good milk chocolate smell, with maybe a little coconut.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: For some reason, Nestle decided to try putting peanuts into their very successful Crunch bar.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Not very strong, but I think I could smell peanuts in addition to the chocolate.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: When I heard that there were going to be fudge-coated Nutter Butters, it sounded great, but when I found a box of them, I was a bit disappointed to find that the sandwiches were round, rather than peanut-shaped. So really, they looked very much the same from the outside as the concurrently released Fudge Covered Oreos. The coating was less smooth and less shiny than it showed in the picture.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mostly like regular Nutter Butters, couldn't really smell the chocolate.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Unlike regular Nutter Butters, which are shaped kind of like peanuts, these smaller cookie sandwiches were round.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells just like regular Nutter Butters. Great!

snack_name: Nutter Butter Chewy Granola Bars 100 Calorie Packs
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This small granola bar looked like it contained mostly oats and crisp rice, but one side of the bar did have a wiggle of peanut butter shaped like the design on Charlie Brown's shirt.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Kind of peanut buttery and sweet.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: As a major fan of Nutter Butters, classic the peanut butter sandwich cookies shaped like peanuts, I couldn't have been much more excited than I was when I noticed that there's a double-stuffed version!
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong, sweet peanut butter smell. Nice/

snack_name: Pure Milk Chocolate Covered Nutter Butter Peanut Butter Sandwich Cookie
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This box contained twelve round cookies spaced very widely apart in a plastic tray.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very mild peanut butter and chocolate smell.

snack_name: Off the Eaten Path Chickpea Veggie Crisps Rice, Chickpeas, Peas, Black Beans
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These crisps has shapes similar to Popchips, but they were much more colorful than any kind of Popchips, combining many different vegetables to bring in green and purple bits, along with some more conventional off-white.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Kind of weird mix of veggies, but I could smell the peas among whatever else it was.

snack_name: Off the Eaten Path Hummus Crisps Feta & Herb
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These chickpea-based crisps had the same Popchips-like shapes as the Garlic Tomato Basil version, with yellowish surfaces that had lots of bits of seasoning, most of them green, in various sizes.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong mix of herbs, nice.

snack_name: Off the Eaten Path Hummus Crisps Garlic Tomato Basil
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These round crisps looked similar to Popchips, with bumpy, somewhat wiggly surfaces, though the surfaces were generally smoother than Popchips, and the chips were thinner. They had light beige surfaces with varying levels of red and green seasoning.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice tomato and basil smell, not particularly garlicy.

snack_name: Off the Eaten Path Hummus Crisps Rosemary & Olive Oil
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These hummus crisps came in a different shape than Odd the Eaten Path's Feta & Herb and Garlic Tomato Basil versions, ditching the PopChips-like round forms for triangles while keeping the same wiggly surfaces. The surfaces had a light smattering of grayish green seasoning bits (not nearly as green as the ones pictured on the bag).
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong rosemary and olive oil smell.

snack_name: Off the Eaten Path Kettlecorn Cranberry Granola
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This bag was filled a bit over halfway with large round kernels that had lots of golden caramel coating, plus some bits of dark red that were presumably the cranberry. There was so much caramel coating that I couldn't really tell of it was really kettle corn or just plain popcorn under the coating.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice mildly fruity caramel smell, not too sweet.

snack_name: Off the Eaten Path Sweet Potato Crisps
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These round crisps had a light orange color and somewhat wiggly shapes, so they looked a bit like PopChips, but they were thinner than Popchips. We crunched in to find a very crisp, light crunch and an excellent taste that was both sweet and savory, including a hint of sweet potato. The feel was lighter and crispier than PopChips, quite a nice texture.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mild sweet potato smell.

snack_name: Off the Eaten Path Veggie Crisps Rice, Peas, Black Beans
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These snacks took the same basic form as Popchips, but thanks to the inclusion of peas and beans, they were the most colorful snacks of this type that we've seen. The thin, round crisps looked really good, as the base was rice-based and off-white, but there were lots of green and yellow peas embedded inside, plus some darker spots from the beans.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells mostly like peas, maybe a hint of beans.

snack_name: Off the Eaten Path Veggie Puffs Sour Cream & Onion
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These puffs had the same stubby and somewhat wiggly shapes, with a base of peas and chickpeas, as the Spicy Cheddar flavor but these looked different, with just a light yellow color. There wasn't any of the green stuff that is typical of sour cream and onion snacks.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Some mild sour cream and onion, and I could also smell the peas.

snack_name: Off the Eaten Path Veggie Puffs Spicy Cheddar
snack_taste_test: Taste test: When Off the Eaten Path took on the challenge of making a different kind of cheese puff, they shook things up by changing the very base of the puffs — out with the usual Corn Meal and in with Chickpea Flour and Yellow Pea Flour.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice, like a spicy queso dip.

snack_name: 100 Calorie Packs Oreo Dipped Delight Bars
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This latest in the ever-expanding array of Oreo products was a small bar consisting of a thick layer that appeared to be made from Oreo cookie material, topped with a thin layer of Oreo creme, and then coated with a very thin layer of milk chocolate.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good creme and chocolate smell, but not the same as Oreos.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are hexagon-shaped crackers that have white specks on them.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like Oreos.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This latest limited-edition Oreo flavor promised a taste as American as apple pie. In fact, it actually promised the taste of apple pie! The cookies had a color similar to Golden Oreos, though the package said they were graham-flavored, and the filling wasn't too far off from the cookies in color, but it kind of looked like peanut butter.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Reminds me of some apple snacks, but very graham cracker-like, so not a real match for apple pie.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: When I was in school, it always annoyed me to see all sorts of "Back to School" sales during the summer, long before school was really going to start. Can't they just let us enjoy our summer without reminding us about school? But I guess if you're going to remind me about school, it might as well be on the outside of an Oreo that I'm eating.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: The usual Oreos smell. Nice.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This ice cream shop-themed version of Oreos, based on my favorite flavor, had the usual Oreo chocolate cookies enclosing a two-tone creme filling — one layer green with tiny brown spots, the other all brown. The alignment of the two layers varied a bit from one cookie to the next, as both colors didn't consistently extend all the way to the edge (as was pictured on the wrapper), leaving some parts of the exposed filling all-green or all-brown.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Really good, like a lot of other chocolate and mint cookies.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Based on the package graphics, this Oreo flavor seemed to promise a filling that combined both raspberry and strawberry. However, neither berry was named anywhere on the wrapper, as the actual words said only "Berry" and we couldn't find any kind of berry at all listed in the ingredients. We opened the package to find kind of a pink/light purple filling in between the chocolate cookies, about the same as the color shown on the package.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells just like Mixed Berry yogurt. Like the yogurt, not awful or anything, but nothing great either.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This isn't really a new kind of Oreo, but after reviewing the Mickey Mouse 90th Birthday Oreos, we realized we'd missed out on the non-limited-edition of the same flavor.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like birthday cake frosting, very sweet.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This highly anticipated version of Oreos used the same graham cracker-flavored cookies as the S'mores and Key Lime Pie ones while adding a lavender-colored filling to bring on the blueberry.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mostly smells like graham crackers, but also a hint of blueberry on the second whiff.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This limited edition of Oreos was dark. Very dark. The picture on the wrapper showed a dark brown filling between the nearly-black Oreo cookies, but when I opened the package, the brownie batter filling looked actually just about equally as dark as the cookies. The lack of contrast between the cookies and the filling gave them kind of a strange, un-Oreo-like look.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very intense chocolate smell. Just smelling the package made we want some cold milk.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This chocolate bar had seven domed sections with a nice curvy appearance. Atop each section was neither a Cadbury logo nor an Oreo one, but instead some squiggly lines that vaguely resembled the "Dynamic Ribbon" from Coke's logo. From the outside, the surface looked mostly like milk chocolate, but there were a few darker areas that we figured came from the Oreo bits within.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good chocolate smell, but couldn't really notice any Oreo.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This special version of Oreos consisted of light yellow/beige cookies with the same surface design as regular Oreos and a filling that was a 50/50 split of bright orange and yellow.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Not like Oreos. Not like candy corn either. Kind of like very sweet cookies.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This limited edition of Oreos took two Golden Oreo cookies for the exterior and then split the filling between a green apple half and a light brownish caramel. We offered these with lots of snackers, and most were eager to try them. Those who did were about equally split between fans who thought the combination tasted just like a caramel apple and detractors who though that the apple tasted fake, the caramel tasted fake, and the combination tasted bad. This was a sharp contrast to the universally praise that folks had for the Pumpkin Spice Oreos.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like fake caramel and fake apple, but not really like a caramel apple.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: We've reviewed several coconut-flavored Oreos — Fudge Cremes Coconut Delight, Coconut Thins and Thins Bites Fudge Dipped Coconut Creme — and one thing they all had in common was that none of them contained any actual coconut (another thing being that that all all really did taste like coconut). That isn't necessarily a bad thing, since I find the texture of coconut to be the worst aspect of it.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: More caramel than coconut. Really, barely any coconut.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This striking flavor of Oreo was labeled as "New!" but the package didn't mention anything about being a limited edition. However, considering how long some of the Limited Editions stick around and how flavors generally come and go, maybe it's not a meaningful distinction.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Yeah, it really smells like carrot cake.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This limited-edition Oreo, created to celebrate 90 years of Mickey Mouse, featured a rotation of three Mickey-related designs on one face of each sandwich, with the other side bearing the standard Oreo markings.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like birthday cake frosting.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Even with lots of new limited Oreo flavors hitting the market over the past year (including Kettle Corn), this one was far more ambitious than most — attempting not just the taste of cola, but cherry cola, and not just that flavor, but also incorporating the popping sensations that first came to the Oreo line with Firework Oreo. Like many other Oreo products, they didn't license the famous Cherry Coke name here, just going with a generic version.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like cola.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This special flavor of Oreos came in the same small 10.7-oz. package as other recent limited editions, but there was something brand new about this one — the cookies. Rather than reusing an existing cookie and just making a new filling, it looked like they started with Golden Oreo cookies and added small bits/streaks of chocolate within them. It didn't give the appearance of chocolate chip cookies, but rather it was an odd, irregular look. The creme filling had a slightly brownish off-white color, plus there were small bits of chocolate in the creme.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Kind of Oreo like, but not entirely, as there is a strong hint of chocolate chip cookie.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: When we reviewed the new Dark Chocolate Oreos, it seemed appropriate to compare them against this longtime flavor — until we realized we'd neglected to actually review these. So it's time to formally do that.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: A lot like original Oreos, as you can still smell the creme and not just the chocolate, but probably a bit more chocolatey.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These limited-edition Oreos put a Nutella-like filling in between two Golden Oreo cookies, but the Oreo folks conspicuously avoided using the word Nutella anywhere on the package. This is consistent with the past tendency of Oreo not to license well-known brands when incorporating their flavors into limited-edition Oreos — witness the "Not Rice Krispies Treats" Marshmallow Crispy Oreo, "Not Fruity Pebbles" Fruity-Crisp Oreo, "Not Red Hots" Hot & Spicy Cinnamon and "Not Cinnabon" Cinnamon Bun. (Three notable exceptions were Dunkin' Donuts, Swedish Fish and DQ Blizzard flavors.)
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very mild, but kind of like Nutella.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: For years, we've documented the ever-smaller package sizes for limited-edition Oreos, but it seems that the new decade has brought real change to the Oreo brand, as this one was not only not smaller than a regular Oreos package — it was actually bigger, upping the weight from the standard 15.25 ounces to the family-size 17 oz. (It actually wasn't described on the package as a limited edition, a label that Oreo seems to be moving away from, as they simply proclaimed "New!" on this one.)
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Kind of marshmallowy, definitely different from standard Oreos.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This wasn't the first time we've seen both chocolate and peanut butter in an Oreo, nor even the second for that matter, as we've reviewed both the Peanut Butter and Reese's versions. However, there was one very essential difference with this one, as the sandwich was enclosed in graham cracker-flavored cookies instead of chocolate ones — and the result was extremely tasty. The filling was split down the middle between chocolate and peanut butter (just like the Reese's version), and the combination of those fillings and the cookies was pretty awesome, a great match for the taste of a peanut butter pie. It was even better with some cold milk.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Way more PB than chocolate, and really good.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These special Oreos kept the conventional chocolate cookies while replacing the white creme with a mix of chocolate creme (around the edges) and strawberry creme (in the center). The chocolate creme had a fairly light brown color, or at least it looked light against the nearly black cookies. The pink strawberry creme wasn't visible without biting into or peeling open a sandwich.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: More chocolate than strawberry, but a very nice mix.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This special version of Oreos had a white filling and beige color to the cookies, but the beige was not a consistent color, as there were darker spots here and there.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Kind of a vanilla-heavy cinnamon smell. Pretty good.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: I first encountered the concept of Cookie Butter at Trader Joe's when they started selling Speculoos Cookie Butter. I had no idea what it was, but I had to try, and when I did, I ended up eating quite a few spoonfuls of it straight from the jar. It had a texture similar to peanut butter, and was just as spreadable and came in both crunchy and smooth versions. I don't think I ever actually spread it onto anything — right off the spoon with milk worked great. When TJ's introduced a sandwich cookie filled with their cookie butter, I liked it just as much.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong sweet smell, with lots of vanilla and maybe a hint of cinnamon.

snack_name: Cookie Crusted Almonds made with Oreo
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These coated almonds had almond-like shapes, except bigger, thanks to a two-layer coating, with Oreo creme immediately coating the almond, then a finely crushed Oreo cookie coating over that. The outside was a dark grayish color.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mild Oreo cookie smell, with definitely the creme part noticeable.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Oreos had the standard designs for the round cookies enclosing the sandwich, but in between there was a light brown filling, supplied a bit more generously than the standard white, though the filling thickness varied from sandwich to sandwich. The filling was darker in color than it showed in the illustration on the package, as it was more of a light brown than a beige. At first it looked like the filling was uniform in color, but when I pulled open a few sandwiches, I found that there were some darker areas of the filling (presumably representing the "chocolatey chips" promised on the package, but really they were not chips).
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells kind of like Oreos, but not quite, probably because of the different filling, but not really much like cookie dough.

snack_name: Cookies & Creme Oreo Chocolate Candy Bar
snack_taste_test: Taste test: When the Oreo candy bars were first released a few years back, they were branded as Milka Oreo bars. That was followed up with several more variations, including the wide Oreo Big Crunch and Double Chocolate Oreo Bar, narrow Oreo Chocolate Candy Bar (plus a similar mint one) and also an Oreo snack mix bag — all branded as Milka.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong white chocolate smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: It's our policy at Taquitos.net not to review as snacks anything that requires refrigeration, and exceptions to this are extremely rare. This is the exception, for a couple of reasons: 1) We consider it part of our effort to document Oreo's gradual takeover of the entire grocery store. 2) It's freaking Oreo-flavored Cool Whip!
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very mild, just a hint of Oreo.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: When we reviewed the Red Velvet Oreos, we were quite disappointed by the decision to shrink the package to just 10.7 ounces. Well, 10.7 oz. is apparently now a thing, as this limited edition flavor weighed in at the exact same number. It look quite a bit smaller on the shelf than all of the other flavors, and indeed it was.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Kind of like cotton candy.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This new Oreo flavor promised a dark chocolate flavor creme in between the usual non-dark chocolate cookies. Visually, it all looked quite dark, and a close look revealed that that filling was indeed a bit darker than the cookies.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Definitely different from regular Oreos, with a lot of chocolate, but not particularly dark chocolate-like.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Oreos from Indonesia initially looked to be the limited-edition Reese's ones with a different package and name, but there were quite a few surprises to come.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Sweet peanut butter and chocolate smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This isn't a new product by any stretch, but it's one that we're way overdue in reviewing. We did our due diligence in reviewing the even-more-than-Double-Stuf Mega Stuf Oreo a few years back, as well as the Mint Creme version of the Double, but this one existed many years earlier. In fact, long before the days of countless varieties of Oreos, I believe the Double Stuf was the first-ever addition to the Oreo product line. Back when Oreos were persistently advertised with the Ice cold milk and an Oreo cookie jingle — which included the words "The one and only, creamy, crunchy, chocolate O-R-E-O" — they eventually had to add an extra (extremely self-contradictory) verse at the end, noting that "Oreo and Oreo with Double Stuf, it really is the one and only!"
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice! Maybe even better than regular Oreos.

snack_name: Double Stuf Oreo Cool Mint Creme
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Oreos had the usual chocolate cookies with their usual markings, with a light green filling.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Extremely nice mint chocolate smell. Reminds me of those Keebler Grasshopper cookies, or a bowl of mint chocolate chip ice cream. Mmmm.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Not long after Pop-Tarts rolled out two Dunkin' Donuts flavors (Frosted Chocolate Mocha and Vanilla Latte), these coffee-themed Oreos promised to deliver the flavor of a mocha beverage from Dunkin' Donuts in Oreo form. Each sandwich appeared to have the same chocolate cookies as the regular Oreos, but their filling was a very light brown rather than the usual white. The cookies had standard Oreo markings — no Dunkin' Donuts logo or anything.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like regular Oreos. Couldn't notice any coffee.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: After offering up two Peeps-themed Oreos for Easter in the last two years (with golden cookies in 2017 and chocolate ones in 2018), the Nabisco folks really cranked up their efforts this time!
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Standard Oreo chocolate smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: For the fourth year in a row, there's a special Easter version of Oreo, this time borrowing the flavor of Golden cookies from the 2017 Peeps Oreo, except coloring them pink, while taking the egg-like shape and smaller size of the chocolate-cookied 2019 Easter Egg Oreo and using the original white Oreo creme. One face of each sandwich had a fairly typical Oreo design, except modified for the not-round shape, while the opposite side rotated among four different Easter designs, the same ones used in 2019.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Fairly sweet, just like Golden Oreos.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This new flavor generated a lot of excitement, as the promise seemed to be that they would taste like a Hostess Cupcake. They used the usual chocolate Oreo cookies with standard markings, and the outwardly visible filling was a medium brown, dark but quite a bit lighter than the cookies. The center of the filling was promised to be white, with the admonition, "Twist & lick!" to access it.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: It really smells like cupcake frosting! Not the standard Oreos smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: We've eaten a lot of buzzworthy limited-edition Oreo flavors, but this one seemed to generate even more interest than most, promising to include Pop Rocks-like exploding candies within the chocolate-and-creme cookie sandwiches. They looked like regular Oreos, except that the white creme filling included some small red and blue bits, presumably the source of the fireworks.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Just like regular Oreos.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: For this version of Oreos, Nabisco rotated through four designs (a football, a quarterback throwing a football, a helmet and an X's and O's diagram) for one cookie in each sandwich and used the standard Oreo markings on the other one. They also doubled the creme filling — an extra bonus not mentioned on the package.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Regular Oreo smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: A few years back, Nabisco brought us the original Football Oreos as round Oreos with football-related designs on one cookie out of each sandwich. This product had the same "Football Oreo" name on the package, but it wasn't the same, as they went one better and made the cookies in the shape of a football.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Normal Oreos smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: The limited-edition Oreos keep getting weirder, and this one certainly followed that trend. It essentially promised a creme filling with bits of colorful Fruity Pebbles cereal in between two Golden Oreo cookies. Although everything on the package closely resembled Fruity Pebbles, it appears that the folks at Oreo/Nabisco/Mondelez didn't want to pony up the dough to use the actual trademark, hence the odd "Fruity Crisp" name. (This is much like the lack of the Rice Krispies Treats name for the Marshmallow Crispy Oreos.)
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very sweet and fruity, a lot like Fruity Pebbles.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: If not for the word "New!" on the box, we would have assumed that this was among the many coated Oreos we've already reviewed, but we checked and found that Fudge Mint Covered, Milk Chocolate Covered, Milk Chocolate Covered Mint, White Fudge Covered, Fudge Cremes, Mint Fudge Cremes, Golden Fudge Cremes with Birthday Cake Filling, Coconut Fudge Cremes and Fudge Dipped Thin Bites were indeed different than this!
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mild fudge smell, but good.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This box contained 12 sandwiches, similar in concept to the Fudge Covered Oreo and Fudge Covered Oreo Mint Creme, but in this case, they changed both the creme and coating to be dark chocolate-flavored. The coating didn't look super dark, maybe a hint darker than the non-dark chocolate ones.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very mild, not really like dark chocolate.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: When I spotted this in the cookie aisle, it looked on first glance like just a mint variation of the Fudge Covered Oreo that we reviewed four months earlier. But after noticing some odd fine print on the box — specifically: "enlarged to show details, serving size 1 cookie" — I became curious. The part before the comma is fairly standard stuff on all food packaging, and the last part is nothing unusual in these days of portion sizing. But combining them together, separated by a comma, was downright weird. Are they required to have a disclaimer simply for having pictured two cookies on the box? Is this about preempting frivolous lawsuits? I don't know!
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good chocolate mint smell, but not the amazing sensation that combinations like this usually provide.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These Oreos were dipped in a thin layer of minty fudge, with a flat bottom and a smooth fudge covering on all other sides.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Excellent minty chocolate smell. Great.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This limited-edition Oreo (available only at Target as far as we know) used the lightly colored Golden Oreo cookies to enclose a filling with a color closer to Ginger Snaps.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong gingerbread smell.

snack_name: Golden Oreo Fudge Cremes with Birthday Cake Creme
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These cookies followed the same basic formula as the other Oreo Fudge Cremes (original, Peanut Butter and Mint): a single cookie with creme on one side, covered in fudge.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Wow, they really do smell like a birthday cake.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Much like the non-golden Oreo Mega Stuff, this beige-and-white version had more "stuf" between the two cookies than a double-stuf Oreo, but really not that much more, and not nearly enough to justify the use of the word Mega. We've reviewed lots of variations of the Oreo cookie, including a Golden version of the Fudge Cremes with birthday cake filling and chocolate fudge coating, but until this, we'd so far avoided the plain, chocolate-free Golden ones.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong, sweet vanilla smell. Nice.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: So many variations of Oreos! We've already reviewed the Mega Stuf Golden ones, Golden Thins and Golden Fudge Cremes with Birthday Cake Creme, but this simpler Golden Mini was a new one. The bag said "Big Bag" but really it wasn't that big and was filled less than halfway. Since it cost just $1, no major complaint about that.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Kind of remind me of Vienna Fingers. Nice.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This limited-edition Oreo was based on the popular ice cream bar, delivering a strawberry filling between two specially modified Golden Oreo cookies (more on those later). This marked the second time we're aware of that Oreo attempted to match a particular ice cream treat, the previous being a DQ Blizzard version.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong sweet strawberry smell, a good match for the Good Humor bar.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This very orange-looking version of Oreos replaced the normal filling with an orange-colored filling.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Same as non-orange

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Each part of this five-pack contained eight chocolate cookie sticks and a "creme" dipping area.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: The chocolate part smells like Oreos.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These Oreos looked much like the Winter Oreos, with the same red-colored filling (but without the winter-themed cookie designs), yet this one promised to bring a spicy cinnamon flavor along with the red, rather than Winter Oreo's "same great taste." The package showed what appeared to be a bunch of Red Hots, arranged into the shape of a heart. As a fan of spicy cinnamon things, especially Hot Tamales, this sounded great to me, and I was eager to see how the spicy cinnamon taste would combine with chocolate.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good cinnamon candy smell, but you really have to hold the cookies close to your nose to notice it.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These Oreos used a noticeably different formula than some other limited editions that split a single filling layer into two types (like Candy Corn Oreo, PB&J Oreo or Jelly Donut Oreo), as this one instead had two thinner layers stacked on top of each other. Depending on which way you hold the cookie, it was a white layer over a brown layer, or the other way around.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Definitely different from regular Oreos, and probably because of the inclusion of chocolate creme, but it didn't really smell like hot chocolate.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These limited-edition Oreo sandwiches promised to taste like jelly donuts, and the creme filling was even designed to look like them. From the outside, each one looked like a Golden Oreo, but within the white-edged filling was a dark purplish center.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Not really like a donut, but could definitely smell some jelly fruitiness in addition to the Golden Oreo aroma.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These Oreos were released alongside two other surprising flavors, Cherry Cola and Piña Colada, for the first Oreo flavor contest that we're aware of. The sandwiches had the same beige cookies as Golden Oreos, with a filling that was off-white. I crunched in to find a nice sweet flavor, vaguely maple-like, but not anything like kettle corn. For a good kettle corn, I expect a light sweetness along with some saltiness. I liked the taste and level of sweetness here, but it was too sweet for kettle corn, and the saltiness was absent.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mostly like Golden Oreos, but sweetened with some maple, but really not anything like popcorn or kettle corn.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Oreo has been cranking out limited editions in rapid succession lately, with some big hits like S'more and major misses like Lemon Twist.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good sugary lime smell. Strong.

snack_name: Kraft Handi-Snacks Oreo Cookie Sticks 'n Creme Dip
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This adaptation of the Oreo cookie followed the Cheese 'n Crackers concept, with a similar split package offering dipping sauce on one end and dippable cookies on the other.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like like Oreos

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These Oreo-themed wafer bars broke most of the rules of wafer bars, as the pieces were individually wrapped rather than detachable pieces of a brick, and they were smaller than your typical wafer bars. The package contained 16 bars, arranged in two layers of eight, with each blue wrapper bearing the Bis logo and some illustrations of Oreo cookies (but not the Oreo logo).
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice creamy chocolate smell, similar to Oreos, but creamier.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This large bar from Brazil had a 5x4 section grid, with an off-white color generally, plus bits of Oreo cookie showing through the surfaces in various places. It had a pretty typical cookies-and-creme taste, with some nice light crunch from the cookie bits.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good white chocolate smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: When we tried the limited-edition Lemon Twist version of Oreos, the results were bad, very bad. The obvious conclusion was that lemon and Oreos don't mix. However, we had never tried this non-limited edition flavor (does that make it an unlimited edition?), and we got a tip from a snacking friend that these were really good.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong sweet lemon smell, like a lemon pie.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This limited edition Oreo flavor came in the same tiny 10.7-oz. container that they've used for the last two limited editions that we found (Red Velvet and Cotton Candy). That was disappointing, because it was quite a bit smaller than the standard-size package that they used to have for special flavors. If they're so special, why can't Oreo give us the normal amount?
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smelled like Oreos at first, but then I noticed the lemon.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This new limited-edition Oreos package included some changes that are typical of limited editions — a flavored filling and special cookie designs — along with one new innovation we haven't seen from Oreo before: stickers!
snack_smell_test: Smell test: A sweet kind of fruity smell, maybe remotely like cherries, but not really.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This special flavor of Oreos used the cookies from Golden Oreos, with a maple filling that was very close to the same color as the cookies.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Couldn't smell much maple. Very similar to the regular Golden Oreos.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: There were a few very odd things about this limited-edition flavor of Oreos. First was their announcement/release schedule. In January 2014, the Oreo folks got a lot of buzz when they announced two special flavors, this one and Cookie Dough. We managed to get the Cookie Dough Oreos the next month, but these have been nowhere to be found during a year and half of searching (and we do look in many cookie aisles — often — for new versions of Oreos). That's very odd. (In fact, it was such a long gap of time that Oreo had shrunk the standard size of their limited-edition packaging from 12.2 oz. for Cookie Dough to 10.7 oz. for these, so the two flavors announced together didn't even match.)
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Not exactly like Rice Krispies Treats, but somewhat close.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: We bought this unusually named variation on Oreos, made in Indonesia, alongside a much less unusual one that was also made there but was labeled as Original Oreo. One odd thing about the other was that the wrapper inside the box appeared to meet all of the requirements to be the outer packaging, but in three different languages than the box) It wasn't that way for this one — the inner foil tube wrapper had a whole bunch of Oreo logos (just "Oreo" — not "Mildly Sweet Oreo") and nothing else, so it probably wouldn't meet labeling requirements in the absence of the box.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Definitely less intense than the standard Oreos, but not qualitatively different.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This candy bar's announcement made a big splash in the news — apparently putting Oreo into a candy bar is newsworthy, which kind of baffled me because Cadbury had already done the same thing. Then it took some months for me to find one to eat.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: It does smell like a mix of milk chocolate and Oreos.

snack_name: Milka Double Chocolate Oreo Chocolate Candy Bar
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This bar followed a similar formula to the Milka & Oreo bar, with a 5x3 section grid, a milk chocolate exterior and an interior consisting of Oreo creme and bits of Oreo cookie. The "Double Chocolate" difference was that the creme was chocolate-flavored instead of the conventional white creme. Each section had the Milka logo, and from the outside, there was no sign of the cookie bits or creme.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Creamy milk chocolate smell. Nice.

snack_name: Milka Mint Oreo Chocolate Candy Bar
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This narrow bar had the same shape and six-section design as the non-mint version, and it's now one of four different versions of the Milk Oreo bar (the other two being Big Crunch and the original Milka & Oreo).
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Great mint chocolate smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This was the eighth kind of Oreo-themed Milka chocolate bar that we've reviewed, but it was the first to embed entire Oreo cookies (albeit miniature ones) into the bar. The bar had 10 sections, lined up in two rows of five, with the round Mini Oreo cookies and a layer of creme rising up from the top and just the cookies jutting out of the bottom. Each section was rounded on the outer edge, following the contour of the cookie inside.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mild, creamy chocolate smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This bar was by far the largest of the three new Oreo-themed candy bars released by Milka, weighing in at 10.5 ounces and containing 36 sections in a 9x4 grid. After finding the other two (the small Oreo Chocolate Candy Bar and midsize Milka & Oreo) had far more creme than cookie, with bits of Oreo cookie within a white creme center — and not even the real Oreo creme filling, at that — I was excited to see that this one showed a solid cookie layer in between creme layers. It took some serious muscle to break the bar into sections — this was one very structurally sound bar.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good mild chocolate smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of the collaborative Milka/Oreo bar had a 5x3 section grid, with the Milka logo atop each section and some occasional darkish stuff (that I assumed to be the Oreo material within) showing through the otherwise light milk chocolate color.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice creamy milk chocolate smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This mix promised two kind of Mini Oreos — regular chocolate ones and Golden ones — along with Milka's version of M&M's (called "candy coated chocolate pieces"), which were previously seen embedded in a Milka bar, plus some larger chocolate buttons.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Sweet, but not the typical Oreos smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This narrow bar, one of three new Oreo-themed candy bars, had six dome-shaped sections (basically six big bumps) with a design that was sort of like the Coca Cola dynamic ribbon running across the tops of all the sections. The whole exterior had a light milk chocolate color.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice creamy milk chocolate smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Oreos had the usual decorative patterns on the cookies enclosing the sandwich, with a light green-colored filling instead of the original white. We crunched in to find a nice crunch (the cookies seemed a bit crisper than the usual Oreos) and lots of chocolate and lots of mint — a great combination!
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Great chocolate mint smell! Just as good as the chocolate-coated mint ones.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These cookies followed generally the same formula as the non-mint Oreo Fudge Cremes, with a single non-Oreo cookie, coated on one side with non-Oreo creme, then coated in fudge.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Wow, that mix of milk chocolate and mint is about as good as it gets.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This large, thick, rectangular brownie had a bumpy-looking top that was presumably the promised Oreo bits, including some subtle white areas that were presumably from the creme filling.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Definitely some hints of Oreo amid this good brownie smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Unlike some of the limited-edition Oreos that get lots of prerelease buzz before we can find any, this one just popped up out nowhere. And oh, boy did it pop up! Lots of stores suddenly had huge, not-so-limited supplies. And they even packaged them in the same 15.25-oz. packages as original Oreos, rather than the 10.7-oz. ones that have been used lately for limited editions.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very sweet, like Fruity Pebbles.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This mysterious new flavor came in a package that looked fairly similar to 2017's Mystery Oreo, but honey, they shrunk the package — bringing the weight down from 15.25 oz. to just 12.2 oz.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Maybe like carrot cake?

snack_taste_test: Taste test: With Halloween fast approaching, it's important to start thinking about what cookies you'll be eating on that scary night.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Regular Oreos smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: The Oreo Brownie is back for a second try, but unlike the first one we reviewed, which was a licensed product made by Mrs. Freshley's, this one appeared to be genuine Mondelez. Since the other one was mostly just a brownie, with no actual Oreo taste or texture, we were hoping for a more Oreo-like experience this time. Even before opening it the wrapper, we could see white creme showing through one end of the brownie, plus there was a pattern of white frosting on top, so I had reason for optimism.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Not much at all, but if I really tried, maybe a weak chocolate cake smell. Not like Oreos or brownies.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These snack cakes had the appearance of giganticized Oreos, with two round devil's food type of cakes surrounding a creme filling.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Kind of like Ring Dings.

snack_name: Oreo Candy Cane Creme with Crunchy Sprinkles
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This Christmas version of Oreos had the same general structure as a regular Oreo, but they replaced with white filling with a half-red/half-white filling, and one of the two cookies in each sandwich had Christmas tree-like designs on its outer surface.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Really nice peppermint and chocolate smell. Great!

snack_name: Oreo Chewy Granola Bars 100 Calorie Packs
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These granola bars were made mostly of oats and Rice Krispies, but they sure didn't look that I first open up a bar, as the dark Oreo material covered just about everything.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Not really like an Oreo.

snack_name: Oreo Chocolate Bar Mini Macadamia Nuts
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These Oreos from Japan broke the Oreos formula pretty much entirely, as they were neither sandwiches nor even round. They promised a flavor that I haven't seen in any of the round Oreo sandwiches, so I won't dwell any more on whether they should be sold as Oreos. Each one was individually wrapped in blue foil, about an inch and half long, three-quarters of an inch thick and wide, with a flat bottom and lumpy sides and top. The exteriors were coated in milk chocolate.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: The smell reminds me of a Twix bar.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These Oreos from Japan took the same form factor as the Macadamia Nuts ones, with a small, dome-profile bar shape, rather than anything remotely round or sandwich-like. Don't confuse them with the Berry Oreos, which had the conventional Oreo shape (and kind of passively disassociated themselves with any specific berries, despite the picture of strawberry).
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mild, strawberry-like smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This thin candy bar had a 3x10 grid of squares on top, with a single Oreo logo sprawled across many of the squares near the middle.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good chocolate smell, like M&M's.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: When I found this box with the words "Oreo Chocolate Pie" on it, I really had no idea what to expect. Based on the size of the box (about the same as your average cookie box) and the use of "Pie" in the singular, I kind of figured it might contain a single pie that resembled a much-oversized Oreo. But when I opened the box, I found that there were six individual packets — not one giant pie. The "pie" in each one was a bit bigger than a conventional Oreo, but still quite small by pie standards: 2-1/4 inches in diameter (vs. 1-3/4 inches for an Oreo cookie) and 5/8-inch thick. The top had an enlarged version of the typical Oreo design, and the bottom was flat and smooth, with a pattern of Nabisco logos embossed into it.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong chocolate and strawberry smell. OK.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: The ChocoStix lived up to their name, with a mix of Oreo cookie with the crunchy consistency of those Sugar Wafer cookies you find at Grandma's.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Chocolatey.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This bag contained crushed Oreo sandwiches, with not just the cookies but also the creme broken into fine bits. The intention here was to aid in using Oreos as part of a recipe. Having twice made the same Oreo Cookie Balls recipe provided on the back of the bag, I can attest that it's quite labor-intensive to crush Oreos into bits as small as the ones in this bag. So taking advantage of whatever industrial machinery Oreo uses to crush them in bulk is a big help.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Regular Oreos smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This box from Japan contained three separate foil packets, each containing eight sandwiches constructed much like Oreo Thins, with thinner-than-normal Oreo cookies enclosing a creme filling, which was brownie-flavored in this case. The filling had a light brown color, a bit darker than the chocolate creme Oreos but still quite a bit lighter than the cookies surrounding it.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mid chocolate smell, but not specifically like brownies.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This is the first "Crispy" version of Oreos that we've reviewed, but Crispy appears to be the Japanese branding for the same thinner-cookie version of Oreos sold in the USA as Oreo Thins, which we've reviewed in several flavors. One of those flavors was Lemon, but it was not the same as this, since that one used the Golden Oreo cookies, while this one went with the chocolate ones. We've also reviewed a standard full-thickness chocolate Oreo with a lemon filling, a limited edition known as Lemon Twist, which was terrible.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong lemon smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Oreos from Japan followed the ultra-thin shape of the American Oreos branded as Thins, using the standard black cookies, though in a flavor that we've not seen in Thins or any other kind of Oreo before, with a light brown-colored filling.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong sweet coffee smell.

snack_name: Oreo Delce de Leche Caramel Creme
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These Oreos had a caramel creme filling instead of the standard white Oreo filling.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Standard Oreo smell with a bit of caramel.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: The Oreos in this package looked quite a bit different from regular Oreos, as they had much more creme filling, and the creme appeared to have tiny bits of Oreo embedded inside.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Pretty much the regular Oreos smell, but maybe a bit like ice cream too.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: The Oreo brand is all over Easter all of a sudden, with this year's new egg-shaped Oreo sandwiches, last year's chocolate Peeps Oreos and 2017's golden Peeps Oreos. Now they've followed the lead of most of the candy brands and introduced their own chocolate egg!
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Creamy milk chocolate smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: On first glance, this new version of Oreos just looked like a repeat of Chocolate Covered Oreos or Fudge Covered Oreos, but that turned out not to be the case.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like those Keebler Fudge Grahams. Very good.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Like the other varieties of Oreo Fudge Cremes that we've reviewed (mint, peanut butter, birthday cake and original), each of these cookies consisted of a single Oreo cookie rather than a sandwich, with creme filing on on side, all coated in fudge. The package contained a tray that left a large gap between cookies, but they still managed to fit 28 of them inside, so that was OK. From the outside, the cookies looked the same as the other kinds.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Fairly strong coconut smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: The box contained eight two-packs of wafer cookie sticks similar to the delicate, fancy ones that everyone likes so much.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like Oreos.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This seasonal version of Oreos featured two changes from the standard ones, with a dark red filling replacing the white (but no change in flavor), plus special designs replacing the standard Oreo marking on one cookie face for each sandwich.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Regular Oreo smell.

snack_name: Oreo Limited Edition Game of Thrones
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This special edition of Oreos was the first among the many special editions to re-do the Oreo logo in a themed style, though they did have the regular Oreo logo on one side of the package. Each sandwich had the standard Oreo markings on one face, with the other side alternating among designs based on White Walkers, House Lannister, House Targaryen and House Stark.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: The usual Oreos.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: "Landing a man on the Moon and returning him safely to the Earth," as described by President Kennedy in May of 1961, was a pretty big deal, and it was completed successfully just over eight years later, in July of 1969. Despite making a cookie that has the same shape as a full moon, it took far longer for Oreos to commemorate the moon landing, but now they've done it with this limited edition package, just under 50 years later.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: A little different from the usual — I could smell some marshmallow.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: We reviewed Double Stuf Oreos (actually a mint version) in the past and were disappointed to find that there wasn't really double the creme of regular Oreos, so when we discovered this Mega Stuff version, it seem like a chance for Oreo to stand up and deliver. We were not expecting to take "Mega" literally here — meaning 1 million times as much creme — but we did expect to find noticeably more creme than regular Oreos and Double Stuf Oreos. We peeled open the top of the package to find just that. The filling thickness varied, but on average, there was probably four times as much as regular Oreos. The cookies looked kind of messy, with inconsistent fillings and creme spilling out in various places.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like Oreos, very nice, maybe ever creamier.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This packet contained four Oreos, with the conventional size of cookies and a pale pink filling that seemed to be thinner than the standard single-stuff filling that we're accustomed to.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Wow, really does smell like a strawberry milkshake or Strawberry Nesquik.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This cup contained a miniaturized version of Oreos that was quite a bit smaller than regular Oreos, at about 15/16 inch in diameter, just slightly more than half that of a full-size Oreo sandwich.
