Only the diameter was different, as the thickness of the two cookies and the filling didn't change during the miniaturization process. The sandwiches fell within the same range of thickness (with a similar amount variation in the volume of creme filling).
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Same as regular-sized Oreos. Nice.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Oreos promised three layers of creme filling, with the all-American colors. The sandwich pictured on the package set an expectation of how that should look — smooth, perfectly even layers, each full visible across the profile of the sandwich. But when we opened the package, the look was quite different. In most cases, the layers were quite uneven, and you had to look very closely to see all three colors. The blue layer was darker than shown, as it was almost a navy blue.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Regular Oreos smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: With the rapid acceleration in the number of limited-edition Oreos recently, we've seen lots of new flavors but precious few changes in cookie design. That drought has finally ended, as this package featured Oreos with the standard markings on one side of each sandwich and an assortment of five Olympic-themed designs on the other. Designs included a cross-country skier; a figure skater; a ski jumper; the American flag and the Olympic rings; and a crest surrounding the words "Team USA."
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Same as non-Olympic Oreos.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Much as scientists have observed that the expansion of the universe is accelerating, we at Taquitos.net have observed that the expansion of the Stuf inside Oreo sandwiches is accelerating.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mostly the standard Oreo smell, but it seemed like the creme part was stronger than usual.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: We've seen a proliferation of new varieties of Oreos since we started reviewing them, mostly in terms of new flavors, so it was surprising to spot this change of form. Unlike the previous shape change, Fudge Cremes, which did away with one of the two cookies before applying the fudge coating, this one stayed true to the sandwich cookie concept, promising only thinness.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: The usual Oreos smell. Nice.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This thinner version of Oreos was introduced alongside mint chocolate and regular chocolate versions. Like those, each sandwich featured cookies that were about half as thin as regular Oreos, with about the same thickness of filling.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Verrrrry nice! Just line Vienna Fingers.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Oreos stood apart from the other three "Thins Bites" products in lacking a fudge coating. So it was just a reduced-thickness, reduced-diameter Oreo with no change in flavor or extra coating. Thanks to the lack of a coating, I was able to measure the size of the cookies (15/16-inch in diameter), plus I could see the cookies' surface pattern (a downscaled and slightly modified version of the standard Oreo markings).
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Regular Oreos smell.

snack_name: Oreo Thins Bites Fudge Dipped Coconut Creme
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Thins Bites followed the same formula as the other fudge-coated ones, with two small-diameter, extra-thin cookies surrounding a creme filling, and then the whole thing was coated in fudge.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mild coconut smell.

snack_name: Oreo Thins Bites Fudge Dipped Latte
snack_taste_test: Taste test: The new Oreo variety brought together the small diameter, thin cookies and fudge coating of the Thins Bites with the latte-flavored filling first seen in the (not-fudge-covered, regular-diameter) Latte Thins.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong coffee smell.

snack_name: Oreo Thins Bites Fudge Dipped Mint Creme
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Oreos had a long and complicated name, and they needed it to explain all of the steps removed it was from the original Oreos.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Excellent chocolate mint smell, just like all of the other kinds of mint Oreos.

snack_name: Oreo Thins Bites Fudge Dipped Original
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These Oreos followed a similar formula to the coconut and mint flavors of the Fudge Dipped Thins Bites, applying a fudge coating to an Oreo sandwich made with extra-thin, reduced-diameter Oreo cookies.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Surprisingly, much weaker chocolate smell than just regular Oreos.

snack_name: Oreo Thins Bites White Fudge Dipped Original
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Oreos followed the lead of the Fudge Dipped Thin Bites, with thinner, smaller-diameter Oreo sandwiches coated in fudge, but this time it was white fudge.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice white chocolate smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: We're taking it as a sign that the first three flavors of Oreo Thins — original, Mint and Golden — were a big success when we discovered that they've added yet two more flavors, this chocolate creme-filled one, plus a lemon-filled Golden Oreo.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Regular Oreos smell. Nice.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These cookies looked just like the original Oreo Thins, as the coconut filling that replaced the regular Oreo filling looked just as white.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Middling strength coconut smell mix with chocolate.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This package was labeled as Family Size, and it sure contained a lot of sandwiches, thanks to both the larger size of the package and the thinness of the Thins. I didn't have the patience to count them, but I did have the patience to do math, so multiplying the serving size from the Nutrition Facts by the number of servings meant 52 Oreo sandwiches.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: More intense chocolate smell than regular Oreos.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This coffee-themed version of Oreo Thins had the usual two thin dark cookies enclosing each sandwich, with a layer of light beige-colored creme filling in between. (It wasn't the first coffee-flavored Oreo, as we previously reviewed their Dunkin' Donuts Mocha and Tiramisu flavors.)
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice mocha-like smell, mild on the coffee part.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This latest addition to the Oreo Thins line (along with founding members original, Mint and Golden, and newcomer chocolate filled) had round sandwiches looked like Oreos, except with thinner cookies, so Thins was a very fitting name.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Kind of like a lemon meringue smell, but mild.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: When the Oreo folks rolled out a thinner version of their flagship cookie, they weren't so shy as to limit the thin to just one flavor for launch. We discovered this Mint version, as well as a Golden one, on the very same visit to the supermarket.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: A mix of chocolate and a mild mint. Very nice!

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These Oreos had the same extra-thin black cookies as the other Thins, with a light green filling that looked much like the mint version. I bit in to find a chocolate-and-creme taste on the first bite that didn't seen pistachio-like at all. But shortly after that, when filling reached my tongue, the taste was very strongly like pistachio ice cream.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Just the regular chocolate Oreo smell. No pistachio that I could notice.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Oreo Thins had the same slim form factor as the other varieties (now totaling six) and used the same cookies as the Golden and Lemon ones. The difference here was the filling, which had kind of a dull caramel color.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice caramel smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Oreos broke the mold quite a bit, as the most basic characteristics of an Oreo — two cookies with a creme filling — were thrown out in favor of a whopping three cookies and two creme fillings. So it was sort of like a Big Mac ... without beef patties or buns, of course! As if two layers of filling were not enough, they were two different fillings: one the standard Oreo white creme, and the other a chocolate creme. All of those dramatic changes aside, the most obvious change upon grabbing my first Triple Double out of the tray was how thick the extra cookie and creme layer made it — it was impressively different than a regular Oreo.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like regular Oreos, which is to say, very good.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: We discovered this box of Indonesia-made Oreos alongside another dubbed Mildly Sweet Oreo. This one itself didn't seem all that notable on its face, but a direct comparison against the Mildly Sweet ones seemed in order, and while we're at it, we might as well see if there's a difference between the North American-made original Oreos and this Asian version.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Regular Oreos smell, nice.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These limited-edition Oreos are evidently a Kroger exclusive, and they mark a return to the Oreo practice of splitting the filling between two different flavor/colors, as we've previously seen in Cotton Candy, Candy Corn, Caramel Apple and Watermelon. The cookies were of the Golden Oreo variety. The peanut butter filling was almost the same color as the cookie, and the jelly was kind of dark purplish.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like peanut butter cookies with jelly, but not quite like a PB&J sandwich.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: After being overwhelmed by the addictiveness and deliciousness of the limited-edition Reese's Oreos, we decided to finally buy a package of these, which aren't marked as having limited availability. They sounded like they should be substantially similar to the Reese's ones, as they too combined peanut butter and chocolate.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: It does smell like a jar of peanut butter, though milder.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These cookies were a lot like the original and mint versions of Fudge Cremes (neither of which have much similarity to actual Oreo sandwich cookies) but substituted a peanut butter creme for the Oreo-like creme filling in the others, while retaining the fudge coating.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Great peanut butter and chocolate smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Oreos was rather shocking, based on the looks of the package alone — it pushed the design envelope far more than the other Oreo limited editions, so much so that when I first saw it online, I assumed it was just another fake Internet Oreo flavor. But oh, it was for real.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very sweet, but not particularly marshmallow-like.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This follow-up to last year's original Peeps Oreo gets more effort points than the original, as they didn't use just the standard Oreo cookie designs, instead presenting a new Peeps-themed design for one side of each sandwich while keeping the standard Oreo markings on the other. The package showed a sandwich with a chicken-shaped Peeps design, but there were actually two different designs inside, as half the cookies depicted a Peeps bunny surrounded by butterflies.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice, a hint of fruitiness added to the original Oreo smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This limited flavor from Oreo — not to be confused with the previous limited edition Peppermint from four years ago — looked mostly like regular Oreos, with the standard markings on the two cookies and a white filling, but they did add a fairly sparse collection of red specks inside the filling. The description on the package gave it away that the creme itself was actually peppermint flavored and that the red stuff was really crunchy bits of sugar, rather than bits of crushed candy cane like some other Peppermint Bark-themed snacks.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like all of the other mint Oreos. Very nice!

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This limited-edition flavor of Oreos put a mint filling between two Oreo chocolate cookies with the usual design, and when we offered them to some snackers, everyone was thrilled to grab one to try. The Oreo folks didn't attempt to create the red-and-white stripes that many peppermint snacks have, nor did they do a filling split between red and white (which would similar to other split-filling Oreo flavors such as Candy Corn, Caramel Apple and Reese's), opting instead for just a uniform pinkish filling.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good chocolate mint smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This new Oreo flavor, part of a three-way contest with Cherry Cola and Kettle Corn, promised both coconut and pineapple in the creme of what looked like Golden Oreo Thins. We've already reviewed a a coconut version of Oreo Thins, but this was more different than just the pineapple, since the other coconut ones used chocolate cookies.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: I could make out lots of things — the regular Golden Oreo smell, some coconut and pineapple.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Here at Taquitos.net, we review many kinds of snacks, including snacks containing cereal, but we've chosen not to go on a quest to try every possible box of cereal. Because of our hunger to try every Oreo, this box of cereal seemed worth making an exception.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Maybe sort of a hint of the Oreo creme, but all in all not like Oreos at all.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This special version of Oreos had two blonde Oreo cookies enclosing a dark orange filling, with the standard Oreo markings on the outsides of the sandwich. We crunched in to find that they were really good, with the standard Oreo texture and a great pumpkin pie taste. The feel of the creme was slightly gritty, but not really in a bad way — it wasn't anything like a smooth pumpkin pie filling, but it was about as gritty as your normal Oreo creme. Every one of our snackers who tried these loved them. Oreo folks, please don't make these just a limited-time flavor!
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like pumpkin pie.

snack_name: Pure Milk Chocolate Covered Mint Oreo
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These cookies were a lot like the chocolate mint Girl Scout cookies.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice mint and chocolate smell. Same as the Girl Scouts coolikes.

snack_name: Pure Milk Chocolate Covered Oreo Sandwich Cookies
snack_taste_test: Taste test: The tray in this box contained 12 cookies, following Nabisco's recent formula of placing large spaces between the cookies to keep the box large while minimizing the number of cookies.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good milk chocolate smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This limited-edition version of Oreos broke the usual Oreo formula in several ways, the most of significant of which was that the cookies were not the nearly-black regular Oreo ones, nor the beige Golden Oreo ones. You'd expect them to be red then, right? Well, they only very slightly red, if at all — they were basically brown, and a fairly dark brown at that. Whether I could see any red at all seemed to depend on the lighting. I probably wouldn't have noticed the red if I weren't actively looking for it.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Yeah, it really smells like cake.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: I don't usually seek out reduced-fat snacks, but lately I've been keeping close track of the Oreos shelf for new flavors, and after years of simply ignoring this variety, I decided it warranted a review.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Seems slightly different than the regular Oreos smell. but not bd

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This special edition of Oreos had the standard two chocolate cookies with the usual markings, but the creme filling in between was split 50/50 between a light chocolate color and a peanut butter color.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells just like a real Reese's. Great!

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Continuing a year of unprecedented growth in new flavors, Oreo has unleashed this ice cream-themed flavor right on the heels of one based on the Good Humor Strawberry Shortcake bar. In this case, they've modified the standard Oreo by putting tiny marshmallows within the chocolate cookie (visible as white spots from the outside) and replacing the white creme with a chocolate creme that also featured some bits of soy nuts.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mostly marshmallow, overpowering the chocolate.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: It looked like this Oreo flavor got some extra attention from the Oreos product development folks, as there were several innovations beyond the usual for special-edition Oreos.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Not really like s'mores. Can smell the graham cracker, but not any marshmallow or chocolate.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Oreo flavors just keep getting weirder! (We're talking Fruity Pebbles, Blueberry Pie and Pumpkin Spice weird.) But when we heard about this one based on Swedish Fish, we expected one of the weirdest.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like Swedish Fish (the gummy, not the fish)! Apparently the filling was strong enough that we couldn't smell the chocolate cookies at all.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This limited-edition Oreo wasn't the first tiramisu-flavored one we found, as there was a Tiramisu flavor from Japan two years ago. But this was really a much different product, with full-thickness cookies instead of Thins and two layers of creme — one white, one beige — instead of just a beige layer.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Sweet coffee and chocolate smell.

snack_name: Trolls World Tour Oreo Green with Glitter and Popping Candy
snack_taste_test: Taste test: The first that I heard of this Trolls movie was from a Lay's Poppables promotion a week ago, and now two kinds of Trolls Oreos have appeared. Trolls World Tour is apparently a sequel to a first Trolls movie that escaped my radar entirely. And it's evidently a big enough deal that Oreo was willing to change their logo (which we previously saw changed only for Game of Thrones Oreos).
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Regular Oreo smell.

snack_name: Trolls World Tour Oreo Pink Colored Creme with Glitter
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This movie-themed special edition of Oreos had a lot in common with the green version associated with the same movie, sporting an altered Oreo logo, colored filling, "glitter" in the filling that didn't actually glitter and Trolls World Tour-related designs on one of the two cookie faces. The differences started with the filling, which was bright purplish pink instead of green, but the change of the cookies from chocolate to Golden Oreo was far more significant from a snacking perspective. Some of the face designs were different ("Music is Life" stayed, but headphones and some other musical design that didn't ring any bells for me replaced the cassette and CD). This time, there were no Pop Rocks in the filling.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Same as Golden Oreos

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These Oreo sandwiches looked from the outside like Golden Oreos, with their beige cookies and white filing, but the picture on the front revealed that the center of the filling was yellowish. I pulled open a sandwich to find that the filling looked like a sunny-side-up egg.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like buttery syrup with waffles. But not like maple.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This odd flavor of Oreos consisted of blonde-colored cookies with the standard Oreo designs on the exteriors, separated by a filling that was split between green and red. The green was a bit dull compared to a bright watermelon exterior, while the red was a closer match the the inside of a watermelon, but still somewhat dull. When it's a hot summer day and you're thirsty, there are few things better than a cold juicy slice of watermelon, right? That's why we all crave watermelon, and that's probably why the Oreo folks decided to make this flavor.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Not much like watermelon. But not much like anything else either, very weak aroma.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This box came with just 16 white-coated Oreos, with a thick coating on the top of each, so that we could not see the cookies through the coating, but a thinner one on the bottom, allowing sort of a ghostly view of the markings on the bottom cookie.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mild white chocolate smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: The very day before we heard the first of the hype surrounding the upcoming Red Velvet version of Oreos, we spotted this red-filled version at our local supermarket. The package promised that same taste as original Oreos, and there was no mention of velvet of any kind. Instead, it promised five different winter-themed designs.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Standard Oreos smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of O'Boisies has the same great texture that all of the other flavors have, with a thin cut, bubbly surface, excellent crispness and good crunch.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice intense jalapeno smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of O'Boisies had the same good crunch that O'Boisies is known for, with a really nice texture, but our tasters were mixed when it came to the taste.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Kind of intense, but a bit chemically and not that much like cheddar or sour cream.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato crisps had a thin cut and a very bubbly appearance.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Sort of remotely potatoey, but not really that fgood.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These thin, oddly shaped potato crisps had a beige color, with small bits of black pepper visible on the surface.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like a baked potato with black pepper.

snack_name: Marshmallow Peeps Inside a Crispy Milk Chocolate Egg
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This package contained a large chocolate egg with the Peeps logo engraved into it in several places, with a flat area at the bottom of the egg so that it could stand up (prior to being broken open).
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Regular milk chocolate smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: It too me a minute to figure out that this version of Peeps was supposed to look like the head of a reindeer, because the shape was pretty obscure (it could have been a rabbit head or any number of things) but I guess the green eyes and red nose should have given it away.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Slight but very nice chocolate smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These chicken-shaped candies had a bright green color with brown eyes.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: None.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Peeps had the usual chick shape, with a chocolate coating over the whole exterior.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice marshmallow and chocolate smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: I was expecting these cheese puffs to be a direct clone of Pirate's Booty, and though the snacks in the bag were somewhat similar, there were quite a few differences. The pale yellow puffs were irregularly shaped and smallish, with a much different shape than Pirate's Booty, sort of a wiggly mini-curl shape with numerous variations in shape and size.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: An OK cheese smell. Nothing great.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: With a name that was such an obvious knockoff of Pirate's Booty, we were expecting this snack to be a close imitation. But the snacks in this bag looked like mini, stubby cheese curls, rather than the more oddly shaped pieces that Pirate's Booty offers. Lengths ranged from half an inch to a full inch.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mild cheese smell. Not much.

snack_name: Buckaneer Joe's Unburied Treasure White Cheddar Corn Puffs
snack_taste_test: Taste test: From the looks of the bag, I thought these were going to be a Trader Joe's private-label knockoff of the extremely popular Pirate's Booty cheese puffs.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very cheesy smell, just on the edge of too cheesy.

snack_taste_test: Note: This snack has been discontinued by the manufacturer.
snack_smell_test: Shop: Buy Pirate's Booty on Amazon #ad

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These store-brand snacks were clearly a knockoff of Pirate's Booty, and they were far from the first. The name didn't follow the formula quite as much as Miner's Gold, Sailor's Loot or Bandit's Bounty, but like the others, this one had a mascot, who seemed to be mining gold nuggets. (I loved the way the donkey on the bag announced, "They're Gluten Free!")
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mild cheese smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This booty rocks.
snack_smell_test: From the package:  “Pirate's Booty is a great tasting snack made from rice and corn with the finest ingredients in the world. Fans are called Booty Heads, eat 'em and you'll get hooked.”

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Pirate's Booty had the same shape as the original white cheddar version but the pieces looked much different, with a light orange color and some tiny bits of green.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Sort of a mild cheese and tomato smell, but not really like a pizza.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Pirate's Booty had a pale yellow color, with some areas a bit less pale, plus some dark green seasoning bits scattered over the surfaces. The shapes varied a lot, with some C-shaped, some almost like spirals and lots of other random shapes as well.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: A bit different from the usual ranch smell, but still ranch-like.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Pirate's Booty consisted of smallish curls with a whitish color, with some green seasoning visible on the surfaces.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mild but very nice sweet onion smell.

snack_name: Pirate's Booty Veggie Sticks Sea Salt
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This snack seemed a bit odd to be bearing the Pirate's Booty brand, as it appeared to be much like lots of other veggie sticks that we've reviewed; they typically come in three colors, with tomato and spinach seasoning bringing red and green colors to the beige potato base. But Pirate's Booty did bring their own new twists to the humble veggie stick.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mild veggie smell.

snack_name: Pirate's Booty Wild Tings Sour Cream & Onion
snack_taste_test: Taste test: Much like the Lotso Nacho of "Pirate's Booty Wild Tings," this snack was actually flavored crunchy cheese curls, not any direct match for Pirate's Booty in shape or texture, but for whatever reason, the folks at Pirate Brands decided to attach the Pirate's Booty brand to it. The pieces had a bright yellow color with many smallish green seasoning bits on the surfaces, and their shapes were typical of crunchy cheese curls.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very much like sour cream and onion potato chips.

snack_taste_test: Note: This snack has been discontinued by the manufacturer.
snack_smell_test: Shop: Buy Pirate's Booty on Amazon #ad

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This is another obvious Pirate's Booty knockoff, through the puffs didn't quite follow the Pirate's Booty shape. They were more like short, stubby, curly puffs, though with irregular, somewhat wiggly sides. The pale yellow color did closely resemble Pirate's Booty.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mid-strength cheese smell, not one I liked, but thankfully it wasn't stronger.

snack_name: Sensible Portions Miner's Gold White Cheddar Puffs
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These puffs were yet another obvious attempt to duplicate the formula of Pirate's Booty, with weird-shaped puffs lightly covered with white cheddar cheese.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mild cheese smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: When these first came out, we loved the name and thought they were unique — but now you can find these chips in almost any "health food store" like Trader Joe's.
snack_smell_test: From the package:  “Veggie Booty is a snack made from organic rice & corn, with a phytonutrient blend of Spinach, Kale, and other Veggies. Phytonutrients are naturally occuring constituents found in fruits and vegetables. Veggie Booty will change the way you eat and provide you with the vitamins and minerals needed for maximum nutrition, while enjoying the finest snack on the planet.”

snack_name: Pejoy Chocolate Cream Filled Biscuit Sticks
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This snack, billed as "Pocky's friend," reversed the well-established Pocky formula of chocolate-coated cookie stick by providing a slightly thicker but hollow stick and putting the Pocky coating inside the hollow tube instead. The overall thickness was about the same as Pocky. The major advantage over Pocky was that instead of skipping the sweet stuff on one end the tube to allow a clean handle, the tube was filled all the way with chocolate — and the entire outside was safe to hold.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good creamy chocolate smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This snack was made by the same company as Pocky, but it reversed the Pocky formula by putting turning the solid cookie stick into a hollow tube and changing the sweet coating into a sweet filling. This flavor tried to be like Oreos, with a chocolate cookie and a vanilla cream filling.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Kind of like Oreos.

snack_name: Pocky Biscuit Sticks Covered With White Fudge
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are sticks that taste like graham crackers, dipped in white fudge.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like white chocolate.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This box of Pocky featured an adorable cartoon monkey on the front, so that was a nice start.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mild banana candy smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This box contained two foil packets with 10 mint-coated sticks in each. The 5-inch-long sticks had fairly thick, light green coating, while the underlying sticks had a nice brown chocolate color.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: That great chocolate mint smell, so nice!

snack_name: Pocky Chocolate Cream Covered Biscuit Sticks
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This box contained a white foil bag holding 20 cracker sticks, each a bit over 5 inches long, with a chocolate coating that covered all but one inch of each stick.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good chocolate smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Pocky had shorter, thicker sticks than the regular Pocky, with a much thicker chocolate coating. The box contained three separately wrapped, blue-tinted clear bags, each holding four sticks. Each stick was about three and a half inches long, and much like the regular Pocky, about three-quarters inch at the end of each stick was not coated, serving as a holding spot.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice fudge-like chocolate smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This box contained two plastic bags, each holding 10 chocolate mint-coated cracker sticks.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice mint chocolate smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Pocky looked a lot different than typical Pocky, as the sticks were quite a bit shorter at about 3-1/2 inches long, and rather than being light in color, they were brown with an even darker brown coating over most of their lengths. We looked up the meaning of "Demitasse" and found that it might mean that there was some coffee mixed in with the chocolate — it means a small coffee cup.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice chocolate smell.

snack_name: Poore Brothers BBQ Ranch Kettle Cooked Potato Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato chips were quite tasty, as the flavor really did combine the taste of barbecue with ranch, a combination of tastes that we hadn't tried before.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice barbecue smell.

snack_name: Poore Brothers Desert Mesquite Bar-B-Que Potato Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: Tastes smoky, moreso than other barbecue chips we've had.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: They smell like an open can of barbecue sauce or like a barbecue brush after you've basted the chicken.

snack_name: Poore Brothers Habanero Intensely Hot Potato Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: Kettle-flavor style chip, looks like a barbecue chip.
snack_smell_test: From the package:  “Poore Brothers Habanero Intensely Hot Potato Chips are a real kick in the pants! Made with fiery habanero peppers, these chips are not for wimps. Tear into a bag today, but be careful, these chips BITE BACK!”

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These kettle-cooked potato chips were really good.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: "Oh man alive!" They smell like fresh jalapenos.

snack_name: Poore Brothers Olde English Salt & Vinegar Potato Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are about medium in their vinegariness.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong vinegar smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Thick and crunchy, but not that spectacular.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Oily bad potato chips smell.

snack_name: Poore Brothers Parmesan & Garlic Potato Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: They taste like parmesan and garlic, also very potato-y.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: It smells like a mixture of peanut shells dipped in paint.

snack_name: Poore Brothers Pepper Jack Cheese Kettle Cooked Potato Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: It was easy to tell that these were kettle-cooked chips, because the potato flavor dominated more than any of the powder that they put on the chips.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells a little like jalapeno chips.

snack_name: Poore Brothers Salt & Cracked Pepper Kettle Cooked Potato Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These just might be the best salt and pepper chips ever.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice black peppery smell, like fresh ground pepper.

snack_name: Poore Brothers Steak & Onion Potato Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These crunchy, large (and unbroken) kettle-style chips have a nice steak flavor.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very mild steak aroma.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Pop-Tarts had a promotional tie-in to the popular movie "Cars" from Disney/Pixar.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Wow, quite nice. They smelled like Pop-Tarts with a mixed berry filling, but somehow that turned out to be a very good smell.

snack_name: Pop-Tarts Birthday Edition Milk Chocolate Graham
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Pop-Tarts had an unusual exterior, with a soft, crumbly texture and no frosting. I took the two Pop-Tarts from one packet and toasted one, then placed both on a plate. When I ate the toasted one, it had the feel of a graham cracker with a filling of fudge. That surprised me, as just expected a graham type of flavor on a Pop-Tart, and it never occurred to me that it was supposed to feel like an actual graham cracker. That they pulled this off was impressive.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mild chocolate smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These limited-edition Pop-Tarts had a light chocolate-colored pastry base, with light pink frosting on top that had some dark pink (or even purple) bits of something (not sprinkles, but much smaller and in random tiny shapes) stuck to the top.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very sweet chocolate and strawberry smell, OK.

snack_name: Pop-Tarts Crisps Frosted Brown Sugar Cinnamazing
snack_taste_test: Taste test: As with regular Pop-Tarts, this Crisps version came with two pieces per individual wrapper. The two bar-shaped Crisps combined to be quite a bit less Pop Tart than just one of the standard-size ones. Several years ago, Pop-Tarts had a product called Mini Crisps (in Strawberry and Chocolate versions), which came with many pieces per wrapper, each considerably smaller than this new (non-mini) Crisps kind.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mild cinnamon toast smell.

snack_name: Pop-Tarts Dunkin' Donuts Frosted Chocolate Mocha
snack_taste_test: Taste test: I'm reviewing this Dunkin' Donuts co-branded version of Pop-Tarts (as well as the Vanilla Latte flavor) from the point of view of someone who loves the smell of coffee and enjoys various coffee-related foods such as coffee ice cream — but doesn't actually drink coffee. For the review, I tried one Pop-Tart right out of the package, then a second one toasted.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Fairly mild mocha smell.

snack_name: Pop-Tarts Dunkin' Donuts Frosted Vanilla Latte
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This Dunkin' Donuts-themed version of Pop-Tarts was released alongside a Chocolate Mocha one. Keep in mind when reading this review, I don't drink coffee, but I do like the taste of many coffee-flavored non-coffee things.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good coffee smell, slightly creamy.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These's something about the taste of Froot Loops that has always been irresistible to me. I don't stock much cereal in my kitchen, but on the rare occasions when I buy some Froot Loops, the box gets emptied very quickly, with bowls consumed at many meals that aren't breakfast (not to mention snacktime). Thus, I couldn't resist trying a Froot Loops-flavored Pop-Tart.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Yes, smells like Froot Loops! (But mild.)

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These Pop-Tarts had a caramel and chocolate filling, a chocolate frosting with some caramel stripes in it, and chocolate pastry holding it all together.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Awesome chocolatey caramel smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This flavor of Pop-Tarts had a very light brown color overall, with a somewhat darker color of brown frosting, including some bits of white.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice. Sweet, chocolatey and fudgey.

snack_taste_test:
Taste test: The debate about whether Pop-Tarts qualify as a snack is over, especially since Kellogg's has come out with Pop-Tart flavors such as Hot Fudge Sundae, Chocolate Chip Cookie Dough, Cookies 'n' Creme and Strawberry Milkshake (we'll try to get to all of those flavors eventually).

One of the original flavors that led Pop-Tarts down the path from somewhat nutritious breakfast complement (part of a complete breakfast) into sugar-laden anytime snack was Chocolate Vanilla Creme.   Similar snacksThis version is basically a chocolate Pop-Tart with a vanilla creme (not cream) filling. In this case, eating the tart cooked or uncooked is just as good, depending on whether you want melted filling or not.

Trying to find this flavor is sometimes difficult, it's not as popular as the frosted strawberry, frosted chocolate or (ugh) S'mores flavors. If you find them, buy them, because we want Kellogg's to keep making this flavor. At first we thought that they had replaced this flavor with the Cookies 'n' Creme variety, but this is definitely a different flavor, and the much superior one. Shop: Buy chocolate on Amazon #ad Smell test: Smells like a chocolate Pop-Tart. From the package:  “Due to possible risk of fire, never leave your toasting appliance or microwave unattended. If Pastry is overheated, frosting/filling can beome extremely hot and could cause burns.” Online store: Buy chocolate on Amazon #ad Company: Kellogg'sCategories for this snack: All Pop-Tarts (28 snacks)Chocolate (1759 snacks)Bars (937 snacks)Breakfast snacks (68 snacks)Vanilla Snacks (29 snacks)This snack was discovered  by Keith at Shaw's in Worcester, Massachusetts. Review published .
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like a chocolate Pop-Tart.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Pop-Tarts had a crumblier look than normal Pop-Tarts, with sort of a cross-hatch pattern of white frosting on the top of each one. The picture on the box made it look like there was sort of a spiral (or at least series of round indentations) in the center of the Pop-Tart, in tribute to the actual cinnamon roll shown next it it, but in actuality the spiral was much more subtle. The frosting pattern was also different than what was shown on the box.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice cinnamon roll smell initially (before toasting). Even better during and after toasting!

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This special seasonal flavor from Pop-Tarts had white frosting on the outside, covered with sprinkles colored red, orange, yellow and brown, like fall foliage (or, as Marge Simpson would say, foilage).
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like pumpkin pie!

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This tempting flavor of Pop-Tarts had a beige-colored frosting on the exterior (presumably this was the graham cracker element of the s'mores) and inside, alternating stripes of marshmallow and chocolate filling.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Pretty good, I could actually smell some marshmallow and a bit of chocolate.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This was one of the crazier Pop-Tarts flavors we've heard of, so it definitely seemed worth a try. Most of the top surface of each piece was covered with a pink frosting, a good match for watermelon's inside color, with some squiggles of green frosting that were a good match for the outside. The filling was redder than the frosting, but still well within the watermelon range of color.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: It first, it smelled mostly like the Pop-Tarts dough, but on third whiff, I could detect an actual watermelon smell.

snack_name: Pop-Tarts Gone Nutty! Frosted Chocolate & Peanut Butter
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These Pop-Tarts had a light chocolate colored exterior with a darker chocolate frosting covering most of the top.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good mild chocolate smell, just a hint of peanut butter.

snack_name: Pop-Tarts Gone Nutty! Frosted PB & J Strawberry
snack_taste_test: Taste test: When Pop-Tarts introduced its first two peanut butter varieties, it was a pretty huge deal, and I was very impressed by the plain peanut butter version and somewhat impressed by the chocolate & peanut butter ones. The idea of a PB&J one seemed like it could take this concept to a whole new level, combining the deliciousness of a peanut butter and jelly sandwich with the simplicity of a Pop-Tart.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mild peanut butter smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This Pop-Tarts variety was introduced along with a Chocolate and Peanut Butter version, and I figured that aside from the presence or lack of chocolate, they'd be pretty similar. That turned out to be quite wrong; this was very different from the other one, and it was also very different from all other Pop-Tarts. The most striking change was the lack of any sort of frosting on the top surface, replaced by a thin coating of sugar granules. Beyond that, the whole thing felt less solid than I've come to expect. It felt like the pastry dough that formed the main structure of the Pop-Tart was softer, but the lack of frosting to provide some structural reinforcement may have contributed as well. For the review, I toasted one piece and ate the other one raw, right out of the packet.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Sweet peanut butter smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These Pop-Tarts had a light brown color on the outside and a white frosting on one side, with two intersecting sets of brown frosting squiggles on top of the white, and then some multicolored sprinkles on top of the frosting.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Like chocolate cookies or cake, but not really like a hot fudge sundae.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This was a strange new take on Pop-Tarts, as Kellogg's is apparently OK with using the Pop-Tarts brand to sell something that really is nothing like Pop-Tarts. Well, almost nothing: They did look sort of like ultra-miniaturized Pop-Tarts. Each piece had a rectangular shape, about a half inch by three-quarters of an inch and very thin, and they were frosted. But otherwise, they were nothing like Pop-Tarts, as they were made from a different material (crunchier and more cereal-like), had no filling, and definitely can't be toasted.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good, sort of fudge-like smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This fairly large box contained just six fairly small bags filled with small pieces that looked like miniaturized Pop-Tarts, as featured in the movie, "Honey, I Shrunk the Pop-Tarts." Unlike real Pop-Tarts, they had no filling, but they still did taste a lot like strawberry Pop-Tarts.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like strawberry Pop-Tarts.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These Pop-Tarts were brown with white frosting on one side, a squiggle of green frosting on top of the white frosting, and brown sprinkles (or, as we say in Boston, jimmies) on top of the frosting.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good mint chocolate smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Pop-Tarts come in a whole lot of different types and flavors, but introducing a pretzel version was quite a big change from the usual, probably the most significant development since they started making peanut butter-filled ones a few years back.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Slight pretzel smell, couldn't notice any chocolate.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This flavor of Pop-Tarts landed on shelves alongside a Chocolate Pretzel version, and it had the same pretzel-looking top, with white bits of sugar scattered over the surface. This time, they had white wiggles of frosting stretching across.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: A sugary cinnamon sugar smell, definitely heavy on the frosting.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This special version of Pop-Tarts featured art on the surfaces depicting gingerbread men involved in various winter activities, including skiing, skating, hockey and snow shoveling. The art was nicely done and fun.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice gingerbread smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This box said that the two flavors (Chocolate and Strawberry) were on opposite sides of these Pop-Tarts, but really they were on opposite ends, with a split of flavor going along the length of the pop-tart.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: More strawberry than chocolate.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This new type of Pop-tart combined two different flavors, each occupying half the real estate of the Pop-Tart, with a border down the middle extending the length of the Pop-Tart.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good sweet strawberry or blueberry smell for each particular side. The combined aroma down the middle was not particularly good.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These Pop-Tarts had a white frosting on the outside with some wiggles of pink, and a creamy light pink filling.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like a strawberry milkshake with lots of sugar and whipped cream.

snack_name: Printed Fun Pop-Tarts Major League Baseball Frosted Strawberry
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This box contained eight Pop-Tarts bearing a Major League Baseball team logo on each, packaged in four twin packs. From the outside of any given foil wrapper, there was no indication of which two teams were inside. (So in a way, they were kind of like packs of baseball cards!)
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good strawberry smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These round, irregularly shaped potato crisps (not actually chips) had a look similar to many of the soy crisps and other potato crisps, but these were fairly thin and had lots of seasoning powder on them.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Not much. Not like barbecue.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Popchips promised a sweet-and-salty kettle corn taste, but with the familiar shape of Popchips. It wasn't the first time that Popchips attempted the taste of kettle corn, as there was previously a Katy Perry-endorsed triangular version.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Sweet, but not really like kettle corn or popcorn.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: When Popchips first burst onto the snacking scene, they made quite a splash by offering chips that were ostensibly healthier, and yet unlike others who had tried that before, Popchips had a great texture and were quite flavorful. Part of the success was driven by the fact that they offered varieties that mirrored popular potato chip flavors such as sour cream & onion and barbecue — and although they didn't taste quite the same as potato chips, they actually tasted good and had a great texture.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Definitely different than any other PopChips

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These round, wiggly chips had a soft, somewhat stryrofoam-like crunch and were covered with lots of seasoning.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong cheddar smell, good at first, then chemically.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These roundish, wiggly potato crisps (not chips) were fairly thick and had a good crispness and crunch.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong cheddar-like smell, but kind of chemically.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: When we search for snacks, it sometimes seems like there's a contest going on for which snack company can promise the hottest chips. Not necessarily make the hottest ones, but at least claim they're hot. We're pretty sure that "Crazy Hot" meant a promise of some very serious heat. Did Popchips deliver?
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good spicy cheese and potato smell.

snack_name: Popchips Galaxy Puffs Aged White Cheddar
snack_taste_test: Taste test: During my 51-day George Lucus Diet in 2015, Popchips played a big role, as their marketing agreements with Disney produced several different Star Wars-branded bags, supplying me with snacks for three of the 51 days. Although the bag designs were nice, the snacks inside were just regular Popchips, without any Star Wars shapes. They've corrected that deficiency with this new snack, as Galaxy Puffs included five different Star Wars shapes.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong white cheddar smell.

snack_name: Popchips Hint of Butter Corn Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: The round chips were very wiggly, with a look similar to many of the soy chips.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very buttery, but kind of like fake butter.

snack_name: Popchips Hint of Olive Oil Veggie Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: We've reviewed quite a few kinds of "veggie chips" that were potato-based but delivered multiple vegetable tastes with a variety of colors of chips (usually three colors). Most of them were perfectly OK but nothing special.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice mix of veggies.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This new addition to the Popchips line was definitely the boldest of their flavors, as they were fairly generous in spicing up the basic potato-based Popchip.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good strong jalapeno-like smell, mixed with strong potato smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This triangular version of Popchips had the expected wiggly surfaces, with generally a light yellow to golden yellow color, plus some brown areas.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Barely any, just the slightest corn chips smell. Definitely not like popcorn or kettle corn.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: After years of offering round Popchips that defined their own new category (and have seen quite a few imitators), the Popchips folks have made a turn in the Doritos direction. These Popchips-inspired, triangular, corn-based chips had a nacho cheese flavor — and lots of it. The chips were light orange-colored equilateral triangles, with generally flat surfaces and just some minor wiggle.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Kind of weird, but not bad.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These round, wiggly potato crisps (not really chips) had a generally yellow color, with areas of scattered browness. The taste was sort of like Pringles, but the texture was different, as these were crunchier and thicker, though less dense, as there were lots of tiny bubbles embedded inside.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Kind of a fried potato smell, but not like potato chips.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Popchips was by far the best among the Popchips varieties we tasted.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong smell, kind of like toasted garlic

snack_name: Popchips Potato Ridges Cheddar & Sour Cream
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Popchips broke with their traditional shape by adding some wide ripples to the still-disc-shaped crisps. The size was about the same, but the surfaces were still wiggly like original Popchips, so the ripples gave them just a slightly different look — they really didn't resemble the chips pictured on the bag. The surfaces had a bright orange color, but not quite a fluorescent one.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good sour cream and cheddar smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These crisps shared the same shape and texture as the excellent Tangy Barbecue flavor, with wiggles shapes and parallel ridges, bringing a nice substantial crunch to the already excellent Popchips crispness.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice chili powder smell. Made my mouth water!

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This rippled version of Popchips didn't looked entirely different from the original, as the shapes were generally still round and the surfaces wiggly, but one or both sides of each chip had a series of parallel ridges. Some pieces did stray a bit from being round.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very mild sweet barbecue smell. OK.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These triangular chips had a light beige color with a light sprinkling of mostly green seasoning, so from a distance their overall look wasn't all that different than Cool Ranch Doritos, but on close examination the surface looked quite different, with less texture and less stuff on it.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Kind of weird. Not that bad, but not like ranch at all.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These thin, round, wiggly chips had a light feel and a decent crunch, but the best part was definitely the flavor, as it really did taste like salsa, with some zing and quite a nice mix of spices, so it was like a gourmet salsa, rather than just the standard salsas.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Tangy and sort of salsa-like.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These round, wiggly crisps were beige in color with some sparse bits of ground black pepper visible on the surface.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Just very mildly peppery.

snack_name: Popchips Sea Salt & Vinegar Potato Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These round, wiggly crisps weren't really potato chips as it said on the bag (they were actually potato crisps), but the "salt and vinegar" description on the bag was spot-on, as they had an intense vinegar seasoning.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Wow, a seriously sharp kick of vinegar. Ouch. Clear my sinuses instantly.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These wiggly, round chips tasted kind of like salted popcorn, but the sea salt definitely tasted different than regular salt, a pretty good taste.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Kind of like popcorn.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: I bought this bag not because it stood out as a new flavor, but because Chewbacca was on the front of the bag, making it a necessary purchase as part of The George Lucas Diet. But on closer examination, it turned out that it was a new flavor — Taquitos.net hadn't reviewed a Sea Salt version of the potato-based Popchips.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good potato smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These round, wiggly chips had a surprising amount of flavor for rice chips, as the sea salt really added quite a bit of taste.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Kind of weird, maybe a bit like seaweed, not sea salt.

snack_name: Popchips Sour Cream & Onion Potato Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These roughly round, irregularly shaped potato crisps (they were not really potato chips as it said on the bag) had a good crunch and a strong sour cream and onion flavor.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good fresh sour cream and onion smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These round crisps had kind of a brownish orange color, with some bits of sugar visible on the somewhat wiggly surfaces. They were a bit thinner than the potato-based versions Popchips.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Kind of mildly like fried dough.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These round, wiggly, irregularly shaped crisps generally had a fairly sparse coating of green seasoning.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like rice cakes. Little or no wasabi smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These chips sure didn't look anything like popcorn, with their triangular shapes and wiggly surfaces, and they definitely didn't feel anything like popcorn, with a chip-like crunch.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like slightly burnt popcorn.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These triangular, corn-based chips had very wiggly surfaces in various shades of beige, with some darker spots.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like buttery caramel corn.

snack_name: PopCorners Cheesy Jalapeño Popped Corn Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of PopCorners looked very similar to the White Cheddar flavor, with the same wiggly surface and a thin coating of white cheddar powder, though this kind also had just a few spots of green on each piece.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Sort of a hint of hot pepper, but not really in a hot way.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These triangular chips had a light yellow color and the same wiggly surfaces as the the other PopCorners varieties.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Not much, just a slight tortilla chips smell. Not like kettle corn.

snack_name: PopCorners Memphis BBQ Popped Whole Grain Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This was part of a new series of PopCorners flavors (which also included Sweet Cinnamon and Twisted Salt) featuring a hexagonal shape, rather than the triangular shape seen in the first six flavors of PopCorners. Besides the altered shape, these also were made from a whole different base material, as Whole Grain Sorghum replaced corn. We opened the bag to find that the chips were hexagonal, thin and very wiggly, kind of like the ones pictured on the bag, except even wigglier in many cases, with a mix of light and dark colors, much darker than shown on the bag.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: A bit of the sweet barbecue seasoning.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These smallish triangular chips had very wiggly surfaces (like the regular PopCorners) with sort of a cinnamon-looking powder on the surfaces, plus some chocolate drizzle on one side of the chips. The lines of drizzle weren't as organized as it showed in the picture on the package, but there was still a good amount of chocolate.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mild chocolate smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These small trinagular chips had wiggly surfaces with a light yellow color and some cinnamon-looking stuff on it, plus some drizzles of a white frosting on one side.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice sweet smell, a mix of cinnamon and vanilla.

snack_name: PopCorners Sea Salt Popped Corn Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These triangular chips had a strange wiggly surface (kind of a brain-like texture) with a mix of white and yellow colors.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Kind of remotely like popcorn.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These chips had the same shapes and wiggly surfaces as the various other triangular PopCorners flavors, with some light red seasoning, a lighter color than the chips pictured on the bag.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice mix of corn and tangy chili. Mmmm.

snack_name: PopCorners Sweet Cinnamon Popped Whole Grain Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These chips were cut into hexagonal shapes, just like the Memphis BBQ flavor from PopCorners, but unlike most of the other PopCorners, which are triangles. The surfaces were very wiggly, with mostly an off-white color, except for dark brown seasoning confined mostly to the many crevices.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mostly like cinnamon toast, but also a little of something else not quite so sweet.

snack_name: PopCorners Twisted Salt Popped Whole Grain Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These hexagonal chips had very wiggly surfaces and didn't closely resemble the chips pictured on the front of the bag, because in addition to the off-white areas of the surface shown, there were many parts that were various shades of brown.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Salty, corn-like smell.

snack_name: PopCorners White Cheddar Popped Corn Chips
snack_taste_test: Taste test: The triangular chips had the same shape as the Corners from Medora Snacks that we previously tried, with a wiggly, irregular surface, but with a more popcorn-like flavor in this case.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like white cheddar popcorn,  on the mild side as far as the cheddar goes.

snack_name: Tayto PopCorners Chili & Lime Popcorn Snacks
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of PopChips had the familiar triangular shapes and wiggly surfaces, with an orange/yellow color overall but also some dark spots (which were not present in the ones pictured on the bag).
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very mild lime and even milder chili smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This Irish version of PopCorners kept the original triangular shape and wiggly surface but switched out flavors. The actual chips didn't have the yellow color of the ones pictured on the bag, but more of a light orange instead.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Spicy, tangy cheese smell. Tomato too.

snack_name: Poppycock Butter Almond Pecan Popcorn Clusters
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This is OK and will satisfy your sweet tooth, but we've had better when it comes to the various kinds of sugar-coated popcorn.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nothing out of the ordinary.

snack_name: Poppycock Cashew Lovers Butter Cashew Popcorn Clusters
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are good.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Sweet and sort of popcorn-like. Nice.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This popcorn had lots of peanut butter stuck to it, with an irregular and uneven drizzle of chocolate on some of the pieces.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice, like peanut butter, caramel and chocolate, very sweet.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This is excellent caramel-covered popcorn with pecans.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: You can smell the pecans and the caramel.  Pretty good.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This new flavor the the flattened Pretzel Crisps had the usual shapes and colors, with a fairly lightly seasoning on the surface that didn't add much color to the surfaces.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Some sort of seasoning, similar to other Pretzel Crisps flavors, but neither bacon nor habanero.

snack_name: Pretzel Crisps Buffalo Wing Deli Style
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These knotted, flattened pretzels looked like pretzels that somebody stepped on before baking, and they were mostly the color of your standard pretzels. There appeared to be a bottom and top to them, as one side was flatter and a bit darker, and most of the orange Buffalo Wing powder was on the top.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Just much. Just the slightest hint of hot sauce.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These knotted, flattened, caramel-coated pretzels didn't look much much like the ones pictured on the bag, with their smooth caramel surfaces and large bits of toffee, as the actual top surfaces were bumpy and scuffed, with much smaller toffee pieces. The bottoms of the pretzels looked somewhat closer to the picture, as they had smoother (though still not smooth) surfaces without the extra bits stuck to them. On closer analysis, it seemed that what looked like scuff marks were really tiny, almost microscopic bits of toffee, as those bits were absent from the bottom. Even the larger ones of the bits on top were much smaller than the ones in the picture, and there weren't that many of them.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very strong sweet caramel and toffee smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of the flattened, knotted Pretzel crisps had some salt bumps and orange seasoning on the otherwise flat surfaces, and the actual pretzels had a darker color than the ones pictured on the bag.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Not really like cheddar or horseradish. Well, maybe a little.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This flavor of the flattened Pretzel Crisps featured some orange seasoning on top, along with large salt crystals, and on the bottom, a bit of very dark-colored seasoning (along with more of the orange stuff).
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice tangy, sharp cheddar smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These flattened knotted pretzels had lots of cinnamon sugar visible on their golden-colored surfaces.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mild cinnamon toast smell. Not strong.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These looked like small knotted pretzels that somebody had stepped on or driven a car over, as they had the same general pretzel shape but were considerably thinner and flatter.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Not much.

snack_name: Pretzel Crisps Dark Chocolate & Mediterranean Sea Salt Crunch
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These thin, knotted pretzels had a generous coating of dark chocolate, plus a similarly generous sprinkling of sea salt, with crystals visible all over the top and bottom surfaces.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good dark chocolate smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This sweet-and-salty version of Pretzel Crisps took a standard salted, flattened Pretzel Crisp, then coated about 90% of the exterior in dark chocolate and stuck bits of broken-up peppermint hard candy on one side.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Just mildly minty.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: After finding that the delicious Mint Chocolate Crunch flavor of Pretzel Crisps had a huge disconnect between the actual appearance of the pretzels and the picture on the package, we were eager to see how this kind would look.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong dark chocolate smell. Intense.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These looked like pretzels that somebody had stepped on to flatten them, and they tasted like bagels loaded with poppy seeds, sesame seeds, rye and salt.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like sesame and onions.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These flattened knotted pretzels had the usual pretzel color, with a bit of light-colored seasoning on the surfaces.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Really mild. Just slightly parmesan-y and not garlicy at all.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These flattened, knotted pretzels had a fairly thick off-white coating that promised not just yogurt — something we've seen on pretzels before — but Greek yogurt, which we haven't.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like regular yogurt (with lots of sweetness), not Greek.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of the flattened Pretzel Crisps looked much like the other kinds of Pretzel Crisps, with some light seasoning on the surfaces of the knotted shapes. The surprise here was that unlike most of the other Pretzel Crisps varieties, which boasted fairly original flavors, the promised flavor was quite familiar from the pre-Pretzel Crisps world of pretzels, having been done before by Bachman, Snyder's of Hanover, Rold Gold (twice!), Utz (again, twice!),  and Cumby's.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Not much. Certainly not honey, mustard and onion.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of the flattened pretzel had a nice pretzel color with lots of white seasoning on the surfaces, plus some bits of green.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Sharp jalapeño smell on first whiff, not so much after that.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: We've tried quite a few variations of Snack Factory's Pretzel Crisps, as they've varied the seasonings in many ways and even coated them in various kinds of chocolate. But this was the first time they altered the flattened pretzels themselves, as the ones in this bag were quite a bit smaller than all of the others.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Not much, just the slightest cheddar smell.

snack_name: Pretzel Crisps Minis Gluten Free Dark Chocolate
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of pretzel Crisps promised a few changes from the usual, using the smaller shape that we've seen recently in some non-coated versions, plus a different base for the underlying pretzel, with no gluten. The pieces were fairly small and very dark, with a very thorough dark chocolate coating and just two holes per pseudo-knotted pretzel.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Not much. Not really like dark chocolate or pretzels.

snack_name: Pretzel Crisps Minis Gluten Free Original
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This wheat-free version of Pretzel Crisps looked much like the wheat-containing original Minis, very small flattened pretzels with a pretzel color and sort-of-knotted shapes with two holes instead of three. They were very crunchy, a crunch that was solid and loud without being too hard — notably crunchier than regular pretzels and regular (gluten-rich) Pretzel Crisps. They tasted remotely like pretzels, but also like various other things, like maybe Ritz Crackers. There was kind of greasy aftertaste/afterfeel on the tongue.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like cake.

snack_name: Pretzel Crisps Minis Gluten Free Salted Caramel
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This bag of gluten-free pretzels took the original flavor of mini, knotted, flattened, wheat-free pretzels in a sweet direction, promising the increasingly popular salted caramel flavor.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good caramel smell.

snack_name: Pretzel Crisps Minis Gluten Free Vanilla Yogurt
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These small, sort-of-knotted pretzels had a white coating of varying thickness, particularly on the bottoms, so the pretzel showed through the coating to varying degrees, which looked kind of cool.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong yogurt smell, more yogurt than sugar.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Much like the Cheddar Minis from Pretzel Crisp, these flattened pretzels were quite a bit smaller than the original size, with a modified knot shape and just two holes instead of three.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong pretzel smell. Nice.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: As a mint chocolate addict who likes pretzels too, it took me approximately no time flat to decide to buy this bag after I spotted it on the shelf.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Great mint smell, like minty, chocolate-dipped Oreos! Mmmm!

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These flat, knotted pretzels had a thick coating of peanut butter, plus thin parallel chocolate stripes running at different angles across each pretzel.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong peanut butter smell. Not like candy, almost like real peanut butter.

snack_name: Pretzel Crisps Sea Salt & Cracked Pepper
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These flattened knotted pretzels had a pretty good helping of tiny bits of black pepper visible on the surfaces, along with some larger bits of salt — just like the ones pictured on the bag.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice freshly ground black pepper smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These flattened knotted pretzels had a pretty good density of sesame seeds on their surfaces (about the same as shown on the bag) along with some salt.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good milk sesame smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This bold-sounding flavor from Pretzel Crisps looked fairly ordinary when I opened the bag, as the flattened knotted pretzels looked mostly like the plain salted flavor, save for the slightest bit of orange seasoning in a few spots.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Some lime and a hint of peppers but not really hot or like sriracha.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These flattened knotted pretzels had a fairly typical pretzel color, with lots of seasoning visible on the surfaces.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Really nice, great mix of spices and cheeses.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This bag was filled less than halfway with flattened pretzels coated with a thin layer of white chocolate and then covered in bits of peppermint candy. They looked just about exactly the way they were shown in the picture on the bag.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice nice mild peppermint and white chocolate smell. Great!

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These snacks were the same general concept as the normal Pringles, except smaller, and yet they seemed completely different, with little resemblance of any kind to the snacking experience of Pringles.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: The usual Pringles aroma.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This "new product" containing six single-serving packs of Pringles was purely a marketing ploy, as Pringles already made individual serving size packages in little plastic containers.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like Pringles.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: For years, we've seen Pringles dance around a simple Bacon flavor, with Bacon Ranch, Bacon & Cheese Potato, Jalapeño Bacon, Smoky Bacon and even a Loaded Baked Potato that included a good share of bacon. But this this was the first time we saw the famous maker of identically shaped potato crisps in a can put out a flavor that promised nothing but bacon.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Pretty good bacon smell. Not really like you're cooking bacon, but it did have some bacon hints.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These Pringles seemed a little less crisp than other varieties of Pringles, and they had a remotely bacony taste, not really a good taste.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like Pringles.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This new variety of Pringles was horrible.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells mostly like ranch dressing.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: The box included a generous 10 individual packages, and each of those had an impressive dozen Pringles sticks.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong cheese smell.

snack_name: Pringles Baked Wheat Stix Honey Butter
snack_taste_test: Taste test: Most of our tasters were very skeptical of this Honey Butter flavor, as several people just didn't think that those were two flavors that belong together.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Can definitely smell the butter. Not particularly any honey.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These thin sticks came a dozen to a pack (with 10 packs in the box) and looked sort of like extra-long pretzel sticks.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Just slightly like pizza, more like parmesan cheese and a bit of tomato.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This new Pringles flavor looked just like ordinary Pringles, with no special coloring resulting from the unusual flavor pairing of blueberry and hazelnut.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mild blueberry smell. Very nice.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This limited-edition Pringles flavor had a smattering of mostly light reddish seasoning on the surfaces, unevenly applied.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice sweet barbecue smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These generally looked like standard Pringles, but most of the crisps had a noticeable orange hue on one end of the them, visible from both top and bottom.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good tomatoey smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These Pringles looked mostly like the original ones, with a pale color and just the slightest hint of orange seasoning.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Some hot zing with a definite ranch smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This limited-edition version of Pringles had just the slightest bit of dark orange seasoning visible on the surfaces, mostly around the edges, so the actual crisps were much less orange than the football-themed can.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Wow, intense. Strong Buffalo sauce smell, cleared the sinuses instantly.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: When I spotted this Pringles flavor at my local chain discount store, it seemed like a new one based on my memory, but there was a voice in the back of my head saying, "Maybe not!" I bought it anyway and checked the list of all Pringles when I got home to find that there was no flavor with this exact name, but there was a Cheddar & Sour Cream sold under the "Cheez-Ummms" sub-brand (along with Mild Jalapeño Cheddar and 4 Cheese).
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mostly like plain Pringles.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Pringles was billed having half as much salt as the regularly salted Cheddar flavor, claiming "great taste, less sodium" on the can. They did not go so far as to say that it was "as great" as anything else.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mild cheese and potato smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This flavor (not to be confused with the Restaurant Cravers Cheeseburger version) looked like regular Pringles, but with an orange stripe of powder and brownish flecks of flavor powder, mostly on one side of each crisp.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like pickles and onions.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These Pringles had very little flavor powder on them, despite the words "Flavor Fest" printed on the can.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: No particular aroma,  nothing too smelly.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Pringles had an orange seasoning distributed unevenly on both sides of the crisp, and our tasters like the taste a lot, as the crisps had a fairly mild but very tasty tangy cheese flavor.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Wow, nice mix of cheese and hot peppers, you can really smell some hot jalapeno peppers.

snack_name: Pringles Cheez Ummms Cheddar & Sour Cream
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Pringles Cheez Ummms didn't have much in the way of seasoning visible on the uniformly shaped crisps, as they looked pretty much like regular Pringles.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like regular Pringles, not any sour cream or cheddar that I could notice.

snack_name: Pringles Cheez Ummms Mild Jalapeño Cheddar
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This new Pringles flavor, part of a line of three "Cheez-Ummms" flavors, shouldn't be confused with the original Cheez Ums.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice, smells like a jalapeño cheese sauce.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Like most Pringles, it’s hard to avoid eating lots and lots of these.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like Cheez Whiz

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These Pringles had the usual Pringles color over most of the crisps, with some additional bright orange seasoning on some areas of each crisp.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong cheese smell. Could very well be four of them.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: When we spotted this flavor on the chips aisle shelf at Wal-Mart, we weren't sure whether it was a new flavor or one we'd eaten previously. So we checked the archives and found our review of Pringles Game Time Zesty Queso, which said the flavor wasn't all that zesty.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Spicy cheese smell of middling strength.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This limited-edition Pringles flavor had a fairly light seasoning on one of its surfaces, with the typical Pringles flavor.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Not much chile or lime, mostly just the standard Pringles potato smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: It's truly an exciting day when Pringles comes out with a new flavor, because you know they're going to do the flavor right.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Like many chili cheese snacks, it smells like taco mix powder.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This limited-edition flavor was released in tandem with White Chocolate Peppermint as one of the first-ever sweet Pringles flavors. The crisps had just a bit of brownish cinnamon sugar visible on the surfaces, mostly near the edges.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like cinnamon toast, but not a strong aroma.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These Pringles crisps had a lot of dill pickle flavor powder.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like a fresh dill pickle. Very good job on the aroma.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are decent curry chips.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like curry.
