snack_taste_test: Taste test: We've seen quite a few flavors of Pringles promise some sort of heat, but they rarely delivered. This time, the promise was not just heat, but extra heat. We were hopeful. The crisps had a lot of red seasoning on their surfaces, mostly on the convex side.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Just a hint of lime, nothing in the way of heat.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: When I popped open this can of Pringles, there was no seasoning that I could see on the crisps, even when I checked both sides, so I was wondering whether there would really be any Buffalo wing seasoning.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mildly vinegary, but not like Buffalo wings.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: For this new "extreme" flavor of Pringles, you could see a bright orange flavor seasoning, but it was only on very select areas of each crisp.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good fresh jalapeno smell, strong enough on first whiff to make my mouth water. Weaker after that.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These crisps had the typical Pringles shape and even the typical Pringles pale yellow color, with no green seasoning of any kind visible.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice, smells like taking a whiff from a pickle jar.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This new variety of Pringles was marketed as part of the Extreme line, but there wasn't much about the crisps that was particularly extreme.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Not much.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Pringles came in a bag (rather than a can) and each piece was less than half the size of a normal Pringle, thicker, and strangest of all, they were not uniformly shaped.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mild tangy flavor, similar to other Pringles varieties.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This new Pringles flavor had some orange-red seasoning applied unevenly from one chip to the next, with most of the seasoning on the convex side of the crisps.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice kick of cheddar and tangy sweet barbecue sauce.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Pringles had some fairly dark flavor powder sprinkled unevenly across the crisps.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like taco powder. Strong.

snack_name: Pringles Family Faves White Cheddar Pop
snack_taste_test: Taste test: So the idea here was that these Pringles were supposed to taste like white cheddar popcorn — one type of snack trying to taste like a different snack category entirely.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: On first whiff, smelled like normal Pringles with no cheese. After that, I could smell some of the white cheddar.

snack_name: Pringles Fat Free Barbecue Potato Crisps
snack_taste_test: Taste test: Normally, I won't eat food made with Olestra, but I made an exception and tried one (and only one) of these crisps.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very mild barbecue sauce type of smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Pringles are generally tasty, sort of bland, but oddly addictive.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like tomato soup.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Cheeseburger flavoring is back in Pringles cans, but apparently they were not content to revive Limited Edition Cheeseburger or Restaurant Cravers Cheeseburger and instead brought this one as part of a new food truck theme. Why? If you're craving a cheeseburger, would you be particularly craving one from a truck? Is there a particular taste that unites all food truck cheeseburgers and distinguishes them from burgers that are grilled, broiled or steamed without being on wheels? Not in any obvious way that we can think of.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mild, but kind of like a McDonald's cheeseburger.

snack_name: Pringles Food Truck Flavors Kickin' Chicken Taco
snack_taste_test: Taste test: The food truck keeps rolling! What started as as single Pringles flavor with the "Food Truck" label, Cheeseburger, has now officially turned into a series with the arrival of this Chicken Taco version. It's not the first Taco flavor for Pringles that we've tried, but it is just the second, a follow-up to Family Faves Taco Night.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Wow, really does smell like a spicy chicken taco. Nice!

snack_name: Pringles Frank's Red Hot Chile 'n Lime
snack_taste_test: Taste test: This limited-edition Pringles flavor had some orange seasoning on the surfaces, with the usual uniformly shaped Pringles crisps in a particularly large can.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mild chili and lime smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These potato crisps had some bright red seasoning on them, and they were loaded up fairly strongly with a tasty hot sauce that mixed well with the potato.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good hot sauce-like smell.

snack_name: Pringles Frank's Red Hot Wing Buffalo
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These Pringles had some bright orange/red seasoning on their surfaces, unevenly applied, and the bright color looked quite nice on the light yellow crisps.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice. Not that strong, but tangy in just the right way to say "wing sauce."

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This new flavor of Pringles didn't have any seasoning visible on the surfaces, so it was just the pale yellow/beige Pringles color.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good sweet onion smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These Pringles didn't appear to have much flavor seasoning on them, just a very light amount of orange powder, and when we crunched in, the "Philly Cheesesteak" flavor tasted like neither steak nor cheese.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mild tangy smell, but nothing like a cheesesteak.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Based on the fancy packaging, Spicy Queso flavor and "Game Time" sub-branding, we were expecting a lot of flavor from these Pringles.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Tangy smell, not really a queso or spicy cheese smell at all.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This flavor of Pringles was a shockingly bright shade of pink, in fact just about the same shade of pink as the can.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like shrimp soup.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These limited-edition Pringles had just a slight orange tint on one side and were very tasty, with a fairly mild but sweet honey mustard seasoning, more honey than mustard and a very nice flavor.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very nice honey mustard smell, with an emphasis on the honey.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This Chinese version of Pringles (not to be confused with Smokin' Hot Ranch, Fiery Hot or Hot & Spicy Wonton) had just a light coating of orange seasoning, mostly on one side of the crisps.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Kind of weird. Not really hot or spicy, but sort of tangy.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This was one of the strangest-sounding Pringles flavors we've ever tried.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Unlike the taste, the smell really was like wontons.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These crisps had a moderately hot level of jalapeno seasoning and a good taste, and they were popular around the chip bowl.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: A remotely jalapeno-like smell, it did make my mouth water.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This Pringles flavor had me sold as soon as I spotted the words "Jalapeño Bacon" on the can! We've reviewed many snacks with one of those flavors or the other, but rarely both.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good mid-strength jalapeño smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: I was surprised to see this flavor, because it came just a few months after Pringles first started pushing a jalapeno (without cheddar) flavor.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good jalapeno smell. Made my mouth water.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This flavor of Pringles promised a spicy Jamaican Jerk flavor, but the appearance of the uniformly shaped crisps surprised me by having just about no seasoning visible on the surfaces. Both sides were about as pale as any flavor of Pringles.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Just about nothing, surprisingly.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Pringles had a lot of dark orange-red seasoning, unevenly applied on both sides of the crisps. There was a good level of tomatoey flavoring overall, but it didn't taste all that ketchupy to me. It was more of a pizza sauce sort of taste, without any of the little kick of vinegar that usually comes along with ketchup.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good sweet tomatoey smell, a bit vinegary too.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These Pringles had a light orange powder that basically tasted like cheese, but there was also a hint of bacon, like you're eating a baked potato with cheese and bacon.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Sort of a potato-type smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These "Loud" Pringles surprised me a bit when I opened the can, because unlike the large crisp pictured on the front, the actual ones inside were green. Not bright green, not Loud green, really more of a dull green typical of veggie chips, but still, green. They were indeed veggie chips, described on the can as "Grain and Vegetable Crisps" with many vegetables, including Carrots, Spinach and Peas plus a whole variety of grains, among the ingredients (in addition to the first ingredient, Degermed Corn Meal). The veggie emphasis might have been more obvious to me if the picture had shown green. There was also stuff of various colors embedded inside the crisps, plus some reddish seasoning (though a lot less of it than pictured).
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good tomato and cheese smell, with minimal spices.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of the Loud Pringles had the same yellow, corn-based crisps as the Spicy Queso flavor but instead of an unevenly distributed bright orange seasoning concentrated on one side of the crisps, there was a reddish orange powder that was similarly uneven.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Good spicy salsa smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This new variety of Pringles was one of three boasting the word LOUD on the can, much bigger than the reduced-size Pringles logo above it. In this case, the Pringles were primarily corn-based, with generally a yellow color, but much like most tortilla chips, the surface color was uneven, with some much darker spots. There was also some bright orange seasoning, primarily on the convex side of the crisps.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice spicy cheese smell, like a queso dip.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This flavor from Pringles' Loud line stood out from the other two for the different materials in the underlying chip; while the Spicy Queso and  Salsa Fiesta flavors were primarily corn and were labeled "Corn Crisps," this one was dubbed "Grain and Vegetable Crisps." The composition wasn't entirely different, as the first ingredient was still corn, but this also included a "Grain and Vegetable Blend" that included carrots, rice, barley, oats, spinach, peas and wheat, plus farther down in the ingredients there were potatoes and more rice.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Kind of a typical veggie chips smell, but with some cheese too. Pretty good.

snack_name: Pringles Loud Zesty Ranch Corn Crisps
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These chips had the standard Pringles shapes, with a light yellowish beige color generally, plus a smattering of lighter and darker spots on the surfaces. Unlike most Pringles, they were corn-based.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Very mild ranch smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This flavor of Pringles generated a lot of interest, as many snackers apparently have quite a taste for mangoes (though personally I don't like them). It came about a year after the limited-edition Lay's Mango Salsa chip. There was just a bit of orange seasoning on most of the pieces, so not a lot of color.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Tangy salsa smell, with some mango.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This Pringles flavor — the 11th version of BBQ from Pringles that we've found! — had generally a pale yellow color, with a very sparse application of dark orange flavor powder.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice sweet barbecue smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These Pringles were made from rice, potato, corn and wheat, much like the ranch version of Pringles Multi Grain that we previously tried, but obviously in this case there was cheese flavoring instead.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like Cheez Whiz.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This new version of Pringles had the same size and shape that we've come to expect from Pringles, but the surface looked quite different, with coloration similar to the typical white corn tortilla chip.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Intense creamy ranch and veggies smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Pringles had the usual shape but a much different appearance, as the surface had an overall beige look made from a mix of different colors, similar to the look of a tortilla chip.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Kind of like Wheatables or Wheat Thins.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: I was surprised to find this flavor on the shelf at Dollar General, as I hadn't heard any advance buzz about it, but I was even more surprised when I opened the can to find that the stack of Pringles fell about 3 inches short of the top of the can! I've come to expect less-than-full cans from some of the store-brand Pringles knockoffs recently, but it was astonishing to see the same from the original.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mild hot sauce smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These much-anticipated, limited-edition Pringles had pale yellow surfaces generally, with some brighter yellow areas, plus an uneven, very light smattering of tiny bits of dark seasoning. The seasoning bits were so small that from a distance, I didn't even notice them.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Smells like the chicken powder that comes with ramen, but pretty mild.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This flavor of Pringles from Japan had the usual appearance of Pringles, with just a bit of dark seasoning powder on both sides.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Sort of like a sweet onion smell, maybe even remotely onion soup-like.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These chips were a very bright orange in color, perfectly stacked in the can and unbroken.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Regular Pringles smell.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Pringles were the pioneer in the world of snacks made from potatoes, shaped like potato chips, that aren't actually potato chips.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: A good, salty potatoey smell.

snack_name: Pringles Original Colored Crisps Blue Summer 2004
snack_taste_test: Taste test: The picture on the package shows these crisps as being a uniform dark blue, almost a navy blue.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Regular Pringles smell.

snack_name: Pringles Original Colored Crisps Red Summer 2004
snack_taste_test: Taste test: These were just like regular Pringles, except they were a bright, bright red in color.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: The same as non-red Pringles.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: These are pretty good crisps.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Not much aroma, but they do kind of smell like Paprika

snack_taste_test: Taste test: Having reviewed 145 kinds of Pringles, it was a bit surprising to see this one show up as a new flavor — parm & garlic is a pretty common combination found in lots of snacks. But we checked and found that although this is indeed a new product, is was actually not the first time Pringles attempted the flavor combination. Over a decade ago, there was a Parmesan Garlic version of the bagged Pringles Select.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Mild but nice, just slightly garlicy.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: After introducing two head-turning sweet flavors (White Chocolate Peppermint and Cinnamon & Sugar) a year ago, Pringles really surprised us with this one.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Not much, but very slightly like maple syrup.

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Pringles — themed on some animated TV show that I've never seen — didn't look particularly pickle-y, as the crisps were largely just the standard pale beige color, but a very close look revealed some very sparse, tiny green bits.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Strong dill pickle smell. Nice. Cleared my sinuses a bit!

snack_taste_test: Taste test: This version of Pringles, purchased in England but made in Belgium, had an elaborate Christmas-themed illustration on the can, apparently depicting Santa as a Pringle (wearing a winter hat) with two bacon-wrapped sausages as the rails of his sleigh.
snack_smell_test: Smell test: Nice mild sausage smell.
